{"type":"text","timestamp":1778725093734,"sessionID":"ses_1dbbd8624ffegC9E6f6kSZD0gl","part":{"id":"prt_e2446eef1001mxBkL7dFsST6Y5","messageID":"msg_e2446dc6400177cqgvV36js0P5","sessionID":"ses_1dbbd8624ffegC9E6f6kSZD0gl","type":"text","text":"I have written the hypothesis file to:\n\n`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r2s0.yaml`\n\n### Summary of the hypothesis\n\n**Category:** `micro_opt`  \n**Title:** MEM-to-EX load bypass to eliminate load-use stalls\n\n**Core idea:**  \nThe bench core currently inserts a 1-cycle bubble whenever a LOAD is immediately followed by an instruction that consumes its result, because loaded data can only be forwarded from the MEM/WB register. I propose adding a combinational bypass from the MEM stage's `load_data` back to the EX-stage operand muxes. The forwarding unit will be extended to select this bypass (encoding `2'b11`) when the instruction in EX/MEM is a load with a matching destination register. With the bypass in place, the load-use stall logic in the hazard unit can be removed entirely.\n\n**Expected impact:**  \n- **Fitness delta:** +7%  \n- **Confidence:** high\n\nThis should improve CoreMark IPC (loop bodies and pointer/array code are rich in load-use patterns) with minimal LUT/FF overhead and only a modest combinational-path lengthening.","time":{"start":1778725089009,"end":1778725093732}}}
