{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1778726985019,"sessionID":"ses_1db9e25c4ffeWL056lNnlwtuko","part":{"id":"prt_e2463dd390010Qbxnzf9ls80hH","messageID":"msg_e2463ca98001qozxVgqjuKB7aW","sessionID":"ses_1db9e25c4ffeWL056lNnlwtuko","snapshot":"7099bcb3618112f5884ba57b957b0567b045f052","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778726991618,"sessionID":"ses_1db9e25c4ffeWL056lNnlwtuko","part":{"id":"prt_e2463e78c001Ld43i7WAZexgTU","messageID":"msg_e2463ca98001qozxVgqjuKB7aW","sessionID":"ses_1db9e25c4ffeWL056lNnlwtuko","type":"text","text":"Done. Wrote hypothesis file to:\n\n`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r3s0.yaml`\n\n**Summary:** Proposed an opcode-aware hazard-unit fix that eliminates **false load-use stalls**. The current design conservatively stalls whenever `instr[19:15]` or `instr[24:20]` matches a LOAD's `rd`, even for instruction types where those bits are immediates (I-type, U-type, J-type). CoreMark uses small immediates heavily, so imm[4:0] frequently collides with common register numbers (x1–x5), causing spurious 1-cycle stalls. By decoding the opcode in `hazard_unit` and only checking `rs1`/`rs2` when the instruction actually reads registers, we improve IPC with negligible LUT/Fmax impact.","time":{"start":1778726987660,"end":1778726991616}}}
