{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778725428928,"sessionID":"ses_1dbbd8558ffeBxliGckE4NqTl7","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"bash:3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls -la cores/","description":"List available cores"},"output":"total 0\ndrwxr-xr-x   9 bonetto  staff  288 May 13 22:32 .\ndrwxr-xr-x  20 bonetto  staff  640 May 13 22:32 ..\ndrwxr-xr-x   6 bonetto  staff  192 May 13 22:32 baseline\ndrwxr-xr-x  12 bonetto  staff  384 May 13 23:11 bench\ndrwxr-xr-x   6 bonetto  staff  192 May 13 22:32 ibex\ndrwxr-xr-x   6 bonetto  staff  192 May 13 22:32 neorv32\ndrwxr-xr-x   6 bonetto  staff  192 May 13 22:32 picorv32\ndrwxr-xr-x   7 bonetto  staff  224 May 13 22:32 v1\ndrwxr-xr-x   6 bonetto  staff  192 May 13 22:32 vexriscv\n","metadata":{"output":"total 0\ndrwxr-xr-x   9 bonetto  staff  288 May 13 22:32 .\ndrwxr-xr-x  20 bonetto  staff  640 May 13 22:32 ..\ndrwxr-xr-x   6 bonetto  staff  192 May 13 22:32 baseline\ndrwxr-xr-x  12 bonetto  staff  384 May 13 23:11 bench\ndrwxr-xr-x   6 bonetto  staff  192 May 13 22:32 ibex\ndrwxr-xr-x   6 bonetto  staff  192 May 13 22:32 neorv32\ndrwxr-xr-x   6 bonetto  staff  192 May 13 22:32 picorv32\ndrwxr-xr-x   7 bonetto  staff  224 May 13 22:32 v1\ndrwxr-xr-x   6 bonetto  staff  192 May 13 22:32 vexriscv\n","exit":0,"description":"List available cores","truncated":false},"title":"List available cores","time":{"start":1778725428923,"end":1778725428927}},"id":"prt_e244c1cab001uNXa8OcvlpUPEa","sessionID":"ses_1dbbd8558ffeBxliGckE4NqTl7","messageID":"msg_e2442b8c2001Q8UAS1v97AogsO"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778725430245,"sessionID":"ses_1dbbd8558ffeBxliGckE4NqTl7","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"bash:4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -h '\"category\": \"structural\"' cores/*/experiments/log.jsonl 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"Find prior structural hypotheses across cores"},"output":"...output truncated...\n\nFull output saved to: /Users/bonetto/.local/share/opencode/tool-output/tool_e244c23e1001G4lj5N1aMdsaDN\n\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-035-r14s1\", \"title\": \"Registered MEM Load-Replay Candidate\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core gets its largest IPC gain from registered lookahead\\ninstruction replay: repeated hot instructions can be supplied during random\\nimem stalls without putting a same-cycle replay-table lookup on the IF\\ndecision path. The analogous remaining structural loss is on the data side.\\nLoads still freeze the whole in-order pipeline whenever io_dmemReady is low,\\neven when the same normal-RAM word was recently returned by dmem.\\n\\nThe earlier MEM-stage load replay experiment showed the opportunity: it cut\\nCoreMark cycles, but the combinational replay-table lookup, tag compare, and\\nstore merge logic in MEM lowered Fmax enough to miss the current best. The\\npromising structural angle is to keep the replay behavior while moving the\\nlookup off the MEM critical path, just as the successful IF replay predictor\\ndid for instruction stalls.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core gets its largest IPC gain from registered lookahead\\ninstruction replay: repeated hot instructions can be supplied during random\\nimem stalls without putting a same-cycle replay-table lookup on the IF\\ndecision path. The analogous remaining structural loss is on the data side.\\nLoads still freeze the whole in-order pipeline whenever io_dmemReady is low,\\neven when the same normal-RAM word was recently returned by dmem.\\n\\nThe earlier MEM-stage load replay experiment showed the opportunity: it cut\\nCoreMark cycles, but the combinational replay-table lookup, tag compare, and\\nstore merge logic in MEM lowered Fmax enough to miss the current best. The\\npromising structural angle is to keep the replay behavior while moving the\\nlookup off the MEM critical path, just as the successful IF replay predictor\\ndid for instruction stalls.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small normal-RAM load replay table with a registered candidate for the\\ninstruction entering MEM. When EX computes an effective address for a legal\\nload, use that address to look up the replay table one cycle early and latch a\\ncandidate {hit, raw_word, tag/address} alongside the EX/MEM payload. In the\\nfollowing MEM cycle, if io_dmemReady is low and the candidate still matches a\\nvalid non-trapping normal-RAM load, complete the load from the registered raw\\nword: suppress the live dmem read, use the cached word for sign/zero\\nextension and RVFI mem_rdata, and do not assert mem_wait. If the candidate\\nmisses, or if dmem is ready, preserve the current live-memory behavior.\\n\\nReplay remains conservative. It is disabled while the pending store slot is\\nvalid, for MMIO/marker/UART addresses, for misaligned or trapping memory\\noperations, and for stores. Accepted normal-RAM loads refresh the replay\\ntable from live io_dmemRData. Normal-RAM stores either byte-merge-update or\\ninvalidate a matching replay entry before the store retires or enqueues into\\nthe pending store slot, so a replayed load cannot observe stale bytes.\\n\\nThis is a structural latency-hiding change, not a load-to-EX bypass: cached\\ndata is used only at the MEM retirement boundary, and dependent younger\\ninstructions still rely on the existing in-order load-use behavior. The\\ntop-level IO, RVFI NRET=2 contract, channel-0-only retirement convention,\\nstrict rvfi_order sequence, registered IF replay predictor, divider\\ninterlock, branch prediction, and pending-store ordering all remain\\nunchanged. The expected win is to recover much of the prior load-replay cycle\\nreduction with less Fmax loss because MEM sees only a registered hit/data\\ncandidate instead of a same-cycle table read.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/load_replay.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a small direct-mapped normal-RAM replay table with valid, tag, and\\nraw-word data state. Provide a one-cycle-early lookup interface that\\nlatches a replay candidate for the load entering MEM, refresh entries\\nfrom accepted live dmem load responses, and invalidate or byte-merge\\nmatching entries on legal normal-RAM stores. Reset clears only valid and\\ncandidate-valid state.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Expose the effective address and replay-eligible metadata for the\\ninstruction being launched into EX/MEM so the load replay table can\\nregister its lookup candidate one cycle before MEM uses it. Do not change\\nALU results, forwarding, branch/JAL prediction repair, divider launch,\\nor RVFI operand metadata.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Consume the registered replay candidate during load handling. Select\\ncached raw word data only when dmem_ready is low, the current access is a\\nvalid legal normal-RAM load, no pending store slot owns the port, and the\\nregistered candidate matches. On a hit, gate off dmem_ren, clear\\nmem_wait, and drive load extraction plus RVFI mem_rdata from the cached\\nword. Keep replay misses and all nonbufferable accesses on the existing\\nwait path, and update or invalidate replay entries for stores.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the one-cycle-early replay lookup sideband from EX to the replay\\ntable and the registered replay candidate into MEM, while preserving the\\nexisting registered IF replay wiring, pending-store-slot dmem arbitration,\\ntop-level core IO shape, RVFI channel layout, and channel-1 tie-off.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add only compact helper typedefs or comments if useful for carrying the\\nregistered load-replay candidate and eligibility metadata. Do not change\\narchitectural state semantics, decoder legality defaults, RVFI field\\nwidths, or the NRET=2 contract.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/load_replay.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a small direct-mapped normal-RAM replay table with valid, tag, and\\nraw-word data state. Provide a one-cycle-early lookup interface that\\nlatches a replay candidate for the load entering MEM, refresh entries\\nfrom accepted live dmem load responses, and invalidate or byte-merge\\nmatching entries on legal normal-RAM stores. Reset clears only valid and\\ncandidate-valid state.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Expose the effective address and replay-eligible metadata for the\\ninstruction being launched into EX/MEM so the load replay table can\\nregister its lookup candidate one cycle before MEM uses it. Do not change\\nALU results, forwarding, branch/JAL prediction repair, divider launch,\\nor RVFI operand metadata.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Consume the registered replay candidate during load handling. Select\\ncached raw word data only when dmem_ready is low, the current access is a\\nvalid legal normal-RAM load, no pending store slot owns the port, and the\\nregistered candidate matches. On a hit, gate off dmem_ren, clear\\nmem_wait, and drive load extraction plus RVFI mem_rdata from the cached\\nword. Keep replay misses and all nonbufferable accesses on the existing\\nwait path, and update or invalidate replay entries for stores.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the one-cycle-early replay lookup sideband from EX to the replay\\ntable and the registered replay candidate into MEM, while preserving the\\nexisting registered IF replay wiring, pending-store-slot dmem arbitration,\\ntop-level core IO shape, RVFI channel layout, and channel-1 tie-off.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add only compact helper typedefs or comments if useful for carrying the\\nregistered load-replay candidate and eligibility metadata. Do not change\\narchitectural state semantics, decoder legality defaults, RVFI field\\nwidths, or the NRET=2 contract.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 380.74, \"delta_pct\": -24.7, \"vs_baseline\": 26.47, \"fmax_mhz\": 130.14, \"ipc_coremark\": 3e-06, \"cycles\": 3418106, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5928, \"ff\": 2237, \"seeds\": [140.23, 129.57, 130.14], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"# Implementation Notes\\n\\n## What Changed\\n\\n- Added `rtl/load_replay.sv`, a 16-entry direct-mapped normal-RAM load replay table with reset-cleared valid state and a registered MEM-stage replay candidate.\\n- Added `load_replay_cand_t` in `rtl/core_pkg.sv` to carry `{valid, word-aligned address, raw word}` from the replay table to MEM.\\n- Extended `rtl/ex_stage.sv` to expose a one-cycle-early effective-address lookup sideband for valid, legal, aligned normal-RAM loads.\\n- Extended `rtl/mem_stage.sv` to consume the registered candidate only when `io_dmemReady` is low, the current instruction is still a valid legal normal-RAM load, and the pending store slot is not valid. Replay hits suppress the live dmem read, clear `mem_wait`, and drive both load extraction and RVFI `mem_rdata` from the cached raw word.\\n- Wired the replay table through `rtl/core.sv` while leaving top-level IO, RVFI channel layout, channel-1 tie-off, IF replay, divider interlock, branch prediction, and store-slot dmem arbitration unchanged.\\n\\n## Deviations\\n\\n- Store handling invalidates a matching replay entry instead of byte-merge-updating it. This is conservative and prevents stale replayed bytes while keeping the store-side replay-table update path smaller.\\n- The exact in-tree `bash formal/run_all.sh` command could not stage files because `formal/riscv-formal` is a symlink to a sandbox-protected directory; it failed immediately with `Operation not permitted` while removing staged `.sv` files. I mirrored `rtl/` and `formal/` into `/tmp/codex-formal-load-replay-36775` with a writable `riscv-formal/cores` directory and ran the same script there.\\n\\n## Concerns\\n\\n- The replay table is intentionally small and direct-mapped; it may recover less IPC than a larger or merge-updating table.\\n- The lookup is off the MEM wait path, but it still adds an EX effective-address-to-candidate-register setup path. The FPGA fitness run will decide whether that is cheaper than the old same-cycle MEM replay lookup.\\n\\n## Local Verification\\n\\n- `verilator --lint-only -Wall -Wno-MULTITOP -sv rtl/*.sv`: pass.\\n- `bash formal/run_all.sh`: in-place run blocked by sandbox permissions before proofs began.\\n- `/tmp` mirror `bash formal/run_all.sh`: pass, `Formal: 105 passed, 0 failed`.\\n\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-04-28T06:42:55.474038\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 14}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-038-r15s1\", \"title\": \"Two-Entry Pending Store Slot\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core combines the proven structural pieces: cold DIV/REM is\\nout of the universal EX path, the one-deep pending-store slot hides some\\nnormal-RAM store backpressure, and the registered instruction replay table\\nremoves most random iStall loss. The remaining structural stalls are now\\nconcentrated on the data side. A single pending-store entry lets one stalled\\nRAM store retire, but the next store still freezes the whole pipeline while\\nthe older slot drains, even though both stores already have their address,\\nreplicated write data, byte mask, and RVFI memory metadata available in MEM.\\n\\nA two-entry store buffer was attempted before the large post-DIV and replay\\ntiming wins and failed placement on a much larger design. The current RTL is\\nsubstantially smaller and already has the timing-local one-entry direct fast\\npath, so revisiting only a second pending-store slot is the cleanest\\nstructural bet: it targets store bursts under the 22% random dStall model\\nwithout adding load data to EX, changing the branch predictor, widening\\nretirement, or touching the IF replay timing path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core combines the proven structural pieces: cold DIV/REM is\\nout of the universal EX path, the one-deep pending-store slot hides some\\nnormal-RAM store backpressure, and the registered instruction replay table\\nremoves most random iStall loss. The remaining structural stalls are now\\nconcentrated on the data side. A single pending-store entry lets one stalled\\nRAM store retire, but the next store still freezes the whole pipeline while\\nthe older slot drains, even though both stores already have their address,\\nreplicated write data, byte mask, and RVFI memory metadata available in MEM.\\n\\nA two-entry store buffer was attempted before the large post-DIV and replay\\ntiming wins and failed placement on a much larger design. The current RTL is\\nsubstantially smaller and already has the timing-local one-entry direct fast\\npath, so revisiting only a second pending-store slot is the cleanest\\nstructural bet: it targets store bursts under the 22% random dStall model\\nwithout adding load data to EX, changing the branch predictor, widening\\nretirement, or touching the IF replay timing path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extend the pending-store retirement slot into a two-entry oldest-first FIFO\\nfor legal, aligned normal-RAM stores only. When the FIFO is empty and\\n`io_dmemReady` is high, keep the existing direct ready-store path unchanged:\\nthe live MEM-stage store drives the external dmem port and retires normally.\\nWhen a bufferable store cannot use the port because `io_dmemReady` is low or\\nbecause an older pending store already owns the port, enqueue the store into\\nany free FIFO entry, retire it once through MEM/WB with its RVFI memory\\nfields, and allow younger non-memory instructions to continue.\\n\\nThe FIFO drains oldest-first onto the single external dmem port. While any\\npending store is valid, younger loads, younger stores that cannot enqueue,\\nand all MMIO/marker/UART stores must wait behind the buffered store stream.\\nThis preserves in-order memory visibility and keeps start/stop marker timing\\nexact. Misaligned, illegal, trapping, or non-normal-RAM stores never enter the\\nFIFO and keep the current wait-for-handshake behavior. If both entries are\\nfull, the MEM stage asserts the existing precise `mem_wait` interlock.\\n\\nThis should recover store-burst stall cycles that the one-entry slot cannot\\nabsorb while keeping the hot zero-wait memory path close to the current best\\nRTL. The top-level core IO, RVFI NRET=2 port set, channel-0-only single\\nretirement convention, strict `rvfi_order` sequence, divider interlock,\\nregistered IF replay predictor, and decoder legality invariants remain\\nunchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/store_slot.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the one-entry pending-store slot with a two-entry oldest-first\\nFIFO. Expose valid/nonempty, full, enqueue-ready, and oldest drain\\nsignals. Support simultaneous drain and enqueue so a ready drain can\\nfree capacity for a younger store in the same cycle. Each entry holds\\nonly the byte address, replicated write data, and byte mask; RVFI\\nmetadata still retires through the normal MEM/WB path on enqueue.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Treat legal aligned normal-RAM stores as bufferable whenever the FIFO has\\nspace and the live dmem port is unavailable because `io_dmemReady` is low\\nor an older pending store is draining. Keep the direct ready-store path\\nunchanged when the FIFO is empty and `io_dmemReady` is high. Assert\\n`mem_wait` for loads and nonbufferable/MMIO stores behind any valid\\npending store, and for bufferable stores only when the FIFO is full.\\nPreserve misalignment traps, dmem gating, RVFI `mem_addr`, `mem_wmask`,\\nand `mem_wdata` semantics.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the two-entry store FIFO into the existing top-level dmem\\narbitration. Give the FIFO's oldest entry priority on the external port\\nwhile valid, route live MEM-stage requests directly only when the FIFO is\\nempty, and pass FIFO fullness/capacity back to MEM. Preserve the core\\nmodule IO shape, registered IF replay wiring, RVFI channel layout, strict\\nchannel-0 order counter behavior, and tied-off channel 1.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Keep consuming the MEM-stage `mem_wait` interlock, but update comments\\nand any naming if needed to reflect that a store can retire into either\\npending-store FIFO entry while younger non-memory work continues. Do not\\nchange load-use, imem replay readiness, EX long-operation, redirect, or\\nMEM/WB hold semantics.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/store_slot.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the one-entry pending-store slot with a two-entry oldest-first\\nFIFO. Expose valid/nonempty, full, enqueue-ready, and oldest drain\\nsignals. Support simultaneous drain and enqueue so a ready drain can\\nfree capacity for a younger store in the same cycle. Each entry holds\\nonly the byte address, replicated write data, and byte mask; RVFI\\nmetadata still retires through the normal MEM/WB path on enqueue.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Treat legal aligned normal-RAM stores as bufferable whenever the FIFO has\\nspace and the live dmem port is unavailable because `io_dmemReady` is low\\nor an older pending store is draining. Keep the direct ready-store path\\nunchanged when the FIFO is empty and `io_dmemReady` is high. Assert\\n`mem_wait` for loads and nonbufferable/MMIO stores behind any valid\\npending store, and for bufferable stores only when the FIFO is full.\\nPreserve misalignment traps, dmem gating, RVFI `mem_addr`, `mem_wmask`,\\nand `mem_wdata` semantics.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the two-entry store FIFO into the existing top-level dmem\\narbitration. Give the FIFO's oldest entry priority on the external port\\nwhile valid, route live MEM-stage requests directly only when the FIFO is\\nempty, and pass FIFO fullness/capacity back to MEM. Preserve the core\\nmodule IO shape, registered IF replay wiring, RVFI channel layout, strict\\nchannel-0 order counter behavior, and tied-off channel 1.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Keep consuming the MEM-stage `mem_wait` interlock, but update comments\\nand any naming if needed to reflect that a store can retire into either\\npending-store FIFO entry while younger non-memory work continues. Do not\\nchange load-use, imem replay readiness, EX long-operation, redirect, or\\nMEM/WB hold semantics.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"placement_failed\", \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": \"placement_failed\", \"seeds\": [null, null, null], \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 15}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-041-r16s1\", \"title\": \"Same-Cycle Store Slot Refill\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already has the two structural wins that matter most:\\nregistered instruction replay hides many random iStall cycles, and the\\none-deep pending-store slot lets a stalled normal-RAM store retire before\\nthe external dmem write is accepted. The remaining store-side bottleneck is\\nnarrower than a full second buffer entry. When the pending slot is valid, the\\nMEM stage currently treats every younger memory operation as blocked even on\\nthe exact cycle where `io_dmemReady` will drain the older buffered store.\\n\\nThat leaves a small but avoidable bubble for bursts of normal-RAM stores:\\nthe older store uses the physical dmem port, while the younger store already\\nhas its address, replicated data, byte mask, and RVFI-visible memory fields\\navailable in MEM and could refill the just-drained slot. A previous\\ntwo-entry FIFO targeted the same store-burst pressure but failed placement.\\nThe existing `store_slot` state machine already supports simultaneous drain\\nand enqueue, so the lower-risk structural angle is to expose that fast refill\\ncase without adding another entry or touching the IF replay path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already has the two structural wins that matter most:\\nregistered instruction replay hides many random iStall cycles, and the\\none-deep pending-store slot lets a stalled normal-RAM store retire before\\nthe external dmem write is accepted. The remaining store-side bottleneck is\\nnarrower than a full second buffer entry. When the pending slot is valid, the\\nMEM stage currently treats every younger memory operation as blocked even on\\nthe exact cycle where `io_dmemReady` will drain the older buffered store.\\n\\nThat leaves a small but avoidable bubble for bursts of normal-RAM stores:\\nthe older store uses the physical dmem port, while the younger store already\\nhas its address, replicated data, byte mask, and RVFI-visible memory fields\\navailable in MEM and could refill the just-drained slot. A previous\\ntwo-entry FIFO targeted the same store-burst pressure but failed placement.\\nThe existing `store_slot` state machine already supports simultaneous drain\\nand enqueue, so the lower-risk structural angle is to expose that fast refill\\ncase without adding another entry or touching the IF replay path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Allow a legal, aligned normal-RAM store in MEM to enqueue into the pending\\nstore slot on the same cycle that an older slot entry drains\\n(`store_slot_valid && io_dmemReady`). The top-level dmem port still gives the\\nolder slot entry priority for that cycle. The younger store retires once\\nthrough MEM/WB with its normal RVFI `mem_addr`, `mem_wmask`, and `mem_wdata`,\\nand the slot remains valid with the younger store's physical drain fields for\\na later external write.\\n\\nKeep all existing ordering constraints. If the slot is valid and the port is\\nnot ready, younger memory operations still wait. Loads, MMIO/marker/UART\\nstores, misaligned stores, illegal/trapping accesses, and any non-normal-RAM\\nstore still wait behind the slot and never enter it. If the slot is empty,\\nthe current direct ready-store path and low-ready enqueue path remain\\nunchanged. Younger non-memory instructions continue to pass while a buffered\\nstore drains, as they do today.\\n\\nThis should recover part of the store-burst stall cycles that motivated the\\nfailed two-entry FIFO, but with almost no additional placement pressure:\\nonly the MEM-stage enqueue/wait predicate changes, and the existing one-entry\\nslot already implements the simultaneous drain-plus-enqueue update. The\\ntop-level IO, RVFI NRET=2 channel layout, strict channel-0 order sequence,\\ntied-off channel 1, registered IF replay predictor, divider interlock, branch\\nprediction, and decoder legality invariants remain unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Refine pending-store backpressure so a bufferable normal-RAM store can\\nenqueue when the existing slot is valid and `dmem_ready` is high, because\\nthe older slot entry is draining on that same cycle. Preserve the direct\\nready-store path when the slot is empty, the existing low-ready enqueue\\npath when the slot is empty and the port stalls, and full waits for\\nloads, nonbufferable stores, MMIO/marker/UART stores, traps, and memory\\noperations behind a non-draining valid slot.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/store_slot.sv\", \"description\": \"Keep the one-entry slot state machine, but document and, if needed,\\ntighten the simultaneous drain-plus-enqueue behavior so a draining older\\nstore can be replaced by a younger bufferable store in the same clock\\nedge. The slot still holds only physical drain fields; RVFI metadata\\nremains retired through MEM/WB on the enqueue cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Preserve the current top-level dmem arbitration with pending-slot\\npriority while valid. Update comments or local naming only if needed to\\nmake clear that `store_slot_valid && io_dmemReady` represents available\\nenqueue capacity after the older store drains, without changing the core\\nmodule IO, RVFI ports, IF replay wiring, or channel-1 tie-off.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Refine pending-store backpressure so a bufferable normal-RAM store can\\nenqueue when the existing slot is valid and `dmem_ready` is high, because\\nthe older slot entry is draining on that same cycle. Preserve the direct\\nready-store path when the slot is empty, the existing low-ready enqueue\\npath when the slot is empty and the port stalls, and full waits for\\nloads, nonbufferable stores, MMIO/marker/UART stores, traps, and memory\\noperations behind a non-draining valid slot.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/store_slot.sv\", \"description\": \"Keep the one-entry slot state machine, but document and, if needed,\\ntighten the simultaneous drain-plus-enqueue behavior so a draining older\\nstore can be replaced by a younger bufferable store in the same clock\\nedge. The slot still holds only physical drain fields; RVFI metadata\\nremains retired through MEM/WB on the enqueue cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Preserve the current top-level dmem arbitration with pending-slot\\npriority while valid. Update comments or local naming only if needed to\\nmake clear that `store_slot_valid && io_dmemReady` represents available\\nenqueue capacity after the older store drains, without changing the core\\nmodule IO, RVFI ports, IF replay wiring, or channel-1 tie-off.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"placement_failed\", \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": \"placement_failed\", \"seeds\": [null, null, null], \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 16}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-044-r17s1\", \"title\": \"Tiny MRU Load Replay Latch\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already uses the two structural ideas that have paid\\nclearly: a one-deep pending-store slot for store-only dmem backpressure and\\na registered instruction replay table for random iStall. The remaining\\nstructural stalls are concentrated on normal-RAM loads. A load still freezes\\nthe whole in-order pipeline whenever io_dmemReady is low, even if the same\\naligned word was returned recently.\\n\\nThe prior 16-entry MEM-stage load replay buffer showed that this stall source\\nis real: it reduced CoreMark cycles on top of the instruction replay design.\\nIt missed the current best because the same-cycle table lookup, tag compare,\\nand store-update logic dropped Fmax too much. A much smaller MRU replay latch\\ntargets the same dmem-stall opportunity while keeping the MEM path close to\\nthe current best design.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already uses the two structural ideas that have paid\\nclearly: a one-deep pending-store slot for store-only dmem backpressure and\\na registered instruction replay table for random iStall. The remaining\\nstructural stalls are concentrated on normal-RAM loads. A load still freezes\\nthe whole in-order pipeline whenever io_dmemReady is low, even if the same\\naligned word was returned recently.\\n\\nThe prior 16-entry MEM-stage load replay buffer showed that this stall source\\nis real: it reduced CoreMark cycles on top of the instruction replay design.\\nIt missed the current best because the same-cycle table lookup, tag compare,\\nand store-update logic dropped Fmax too much. A much smaller MRU replay latch\\ntargets the same dmem-stall opportunity while keeping the MEM path close to\\nthe current best design.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a two-entry most-recently-used normal-RAM load replay latch in MEM. Each\\nentry stores a valid bit, an aligned word address tag, and the raw 32-bit word\\nreturned by a previously accepted legal normal-RAM load. On io_dmemReady=1,\\nloads keep using live io_dmemRData exactly as today and update the MRU latch\\nwith the aligned word and raw data. On io_dmemReady=0, a valid legal\\nnormal-RAM load may complete from the latch if either entry matches the\\naligned word address: suppress dmem_ren, use the cached raw word for\\nsign/zero extension and RVFI mem_rdata, and do not assert mem_wait.\\n\\nReplay remains conservative. It is disabled while the pending store slot is\\nvalid, for MMIO/marker/UART addresses, for misaligned or trapping accesses,\\nand for stores. Normal-RAM stores byte-merge any matching replay entry before\\nthey retire or enqueue into the pending-store slot; if a simple merge is not\\navailable for a corner case, invalidating the matching entry is acceptable.\\nReplay misses preserve the current dmem wait behavior exactly.\\n\\nThis is a structural latency-hiding change, not a MEM-to-EX bypass. Cached\\ndata is consumed only at the MEM retirement boundary, dependent younger\\ninstructions still use the existing load-use discipline, and the top-level IO,\\nRVFI NRET=2 channel layout, channel-0-only retirement order, divider\\ninterlock, registered IF replay predictor, branch prediction, pending-store\\nordering, and decoder legality invariants remain unchanged. The expected win\\nis a small cycle reduction from repeated normal-RAM loads during random\\ndmem stalls with much less Fmax cost than the earlier 16-entry load replay\\ntable.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/load_mru_replay.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a tiny two-entry MRU replay latch for normal-RAM load words. Entries\\nhold valid, aligned word address tag, and raw 32-bit data. Provide lookup\\nhit/data for the current MEM load, update from accepted live load\\nresponses, and byte-merge or invalidate matching entries on legal\\nnormal-RAM stores. Reset clears only valid bits.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Integrate the MRU replay lookup into load handling. Select cached raw word\\ndata only when dmem_ready is low, the current access is a valid legal\\nnormal-RAM load, no pending store slot is valid, and the latch hits. On a\\nhit, gate off dmem_ren, clear mem_wait, and drive load extraction plus\\nRVFI mem_rdata from the cached word. Keep replay misses and all\\nnonbufferable accesses on the existing wait path.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add only comments or compact helper typedefs if useful to document the\\nMRU load replay eligibility and raw-word metadata. Do not change\\narchitectural state semantics, decoder legality defaults, RVFI field\\nwidths, or the NRET=2 contract.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/load_mru_replay.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a tiny two-entry MRU replay latch for normal-RAM load words. Entries\\nhold valid, aligned word address tag, and raw 32-bit data. Provide lookup\\nhit/data for the current MEM load, update from accepted live load\\nresponses, and byte-merge or invalidate matching entries on legal\\nnormal-RAM stores. Reset clears only valid bits.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Integrate the MRU replay lookup into load handling. Select cached raw word\\ndata only when dmem_ready is low, the current access is a valid legal\\nnormal-RAM load, no pending store slot is valid, and the latch hits. On a\\nhit, gate off dmem_ren, clear mem_wait, and drive load extraction plus\\nRVFI mem_rdata from the cached word. Keep replay misses and all\\nnonbufferable accesses on the existing wait path.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add only comments or compact helper typedefs if useful to document the\\nMRU load replay eligibility and raw-word metadata. Do not change\\narchitectural state semantics, decoder legality defaults, RVFI field\\nwidths, or the NRET=2 contract.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 404.58, \"delta_pct\": -19.99, \"vs_baseline\": 34.39, \"fmax_mhz\": 139.0, \"ipc_coremark\": 3e-06, \"cycles\": 3435657, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5909, \"ff\": 2224, \"seeds\": [139.0, 142.94, 131.86], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"# Implementation Notes\\n\\n## What changed\\n\\n- Added `rtl/load_mru_replay.sv`, a two-entry MRU latch for legal normal-RAM load words. Each entry tracks a valid bit, aligned word address tag, and raw 32-bit word data.\\n- Integrated the latch in `rtl/mem_stage.sv`.\\n  - Ready normal-RAM loads still use live `dmem_rdata` and fill the latch.\\n  - Stalled legal normal-RAM load hits suppress `dmem_ren`, clear `mem_wait`, and use cached raw data for load extraction and RVFI `mem_rdata`.\\n  - Replay is disabled while the pending-store slot is valid, and for stores, MMIO/marker/UART/OOB addresses, illegal accesses, and misaligned accesses.\\n  - Legal normal-RAM stores byte-merge matching latch entries when they retire or enqueue into the pending-store slot.\\n\\n## Deviations\\n\\n- No `core_pkg.sv` changes were needed; the replay eligibility stayed local to MEM.\\n- The implementation promotes an entry-1 replay hit to entry 0 so the two entries behave as a true MRU pair. This is a small sequential state update and does not add another table.\\n\\n## Concerns\\n\\n- No known functional concerns from lint or formal. The latch intentionally resets only valid bits; tags and data are ignored until valid.\\n- This still adds two 32-bit tag compares in the MEM decision path, so the final FPGA result will determine whether the small cycle win outweighs timing cost.\\n\\n## Local verification\\n\\n- `verilator --lint-only -Wall -Wno-MULTITOP -sv rtl/*.sv`: pass.\\n- `bash formal/run_all.sh`: blocked before solver startup in this sandbox because `formal/riscv-formal` is a symlink to a shared checkout outside the writable worktree, and the script's staging cleanup could not remove stale files there (`Operation not permitted`).\\n- Equivalent local formal flow from a temporary writable mirror under `/tmp`, using the same `checks.cfg`, `wrapper.sv`, current `rtl/*.sv`, and riscv-formal framework files: pass, `105 passed, 0 failed`.\\n\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-04-28T07:35:07.182987\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 17}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-047-r18s1\", \"title\": \"Decode-Exact Load-Use Interlock\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core has strong timing wins from the registered instruction\\nreplay predictor, segmented RVFI order counter, pending-store slot, and\\nhot/cold ALU split. The remaining structural improvement should therefore\\navoid another cache, queue, predictor table, or load-data forwarding path that\\ncould disturb Fmax.\\n\\nThe load-use interlock is still structurally conservative. It stalls whenever\\na load in ID/EX has a nonzero destination matching either raw rs1 or raw rs2\\nbitfield of the IF/ID instruction. That is correct for true consumers, but it\\ncreates false bubbles for instructions where one or both fields are not\\nsource operands: OP-IMM and LOAD do not read rs2, JAL/LUI/AUIPC read neither,\\nFENCE/EBREAK read neither, and JALR reads only rs1. CoreMark's optimized code\\nhas dense immediate arithmetic, address-generation loads, calls, and loop\\ncontrol, so these false one-cycle bubbles are a plausible remaining IPC loss.\\n\\nA prior operand-aware interlock attempt broke selftest, so this hypothesis is\\ndeliberately conservative: decode source-use exactly for known legal\\ninstruction classes, keep reserved or unknown encodings on the current\\nboth-source stall policy, and do not add any MEM-to-EX load-data path. The\\ngoal is to recover only provably false load-use stalls while leaving all true\\nload consumers, dmem waits, branch recovery, divider interlocks, and RVFI\\nordering unchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core has strong timing wins from the registered instruction\\nreplay predictor, segmented RVFI order counter, pending-store slot, and\\nhot/cold ALU split. The remaining structural improvement should therefore\\navoid another cache, queue, predictor table, or load-data forwarding path that\\ncould disturb Fmax.\\n\\nThe load-use interlock is still structurally conservative. It stalls whenever\\na load in ID/EX has a nonzero destination matching either raw rs1 or raw rs2\\nbitfield of the IF/ID instruction. That is correct for true consumers, but it\\ncreates false bubbles for instructions where one or both fields are not\\nsource operands: OP-IMM and LOAD do not read rs2, JAL/LUI/AUIPC read neither,\\nFENCE/EBREAK read neither, and JALR reads only rs1. CoreMark's optimized code\\nhas dense immediate arithmetic, address-generation loads, calls, and loop\\ncontrol, so these false one-cycle bubbles are a plausible remaining IPC loss.\\n\\nA prior operand-aware interlock attempt broke selftest, so this hypothesis is\\ndeliberately conservative: decode source-use exactly for known legal\\ninstruction classes, keep reserved or unknown encodings on the current\\nboth-source stall policy, and do not add any MEM-to-EX load-data path. The\\ngoal is to recover only provably false load-use stalls while leaving all true\\nload consumers, dmem waits, branch recovery, divider interlocks, and RVFI\\nordering unchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small decode-light source-use classifier for the IF/ID instruction and\\nuse it in the load-use hazard predicate. A load in ID/EX should stall the next\\ninstruction only when the next instruction is valid and actually reads the\\nmatching source:\\n\\n- rs1 is used by OP, OP-IMM, LOAD, STORE, BRANCH, and legal JALR.\\n- rs2 is used by OP, STORE, and BRANCH.\\n- JAL, LUI, AUIPC, FENCE/FENCE.I, and EBREAK use no integer source register.\\n- Reserved funct3/funct7 combinations and unknown opcodes remain\\n  conservative by treating both rs fields as possible sources.\\n\\nThe existing one-cycle bubble remains for every true load-use dependency,\\nincluding store address dependencies, branch compares, JALR bases, ALU\\nconsumers, and any conservative illegal/unknown instruction class. The change\\nshould not forward load data, alter the MEM stage, widen retirement, or\\nchange the top-level IO. It only refines when the frontend and ID/EX register\\nare stalled for a load in EX.\\n\\nThis preserves the hard invariants: decoder legality still defaults illegal,\\nRVFI traps and order remain generated at MEM/WB, channel 1 stays tied off, and\\nall memory and timing-marker behavior remains unchanged. The expected benefit\\nis a small CoreMark cycle reduction with minimal Fmax risk because the added\\nlogic is opcode/funct predecode on the existing hazard path, not a new data\\npath or stateful predictor.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 1, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the raw load-use comparison against both IF/ID register fields\\nwith a source-use-aware predicate. Add conservative decode-light logic for\\nknown legal RV32IM instruction classes, defaulting unknown or reserved\\nencodings to uses_rs1=1 and uses_rs2=1. Gate the rs1 comparison with\\nuses_rs1 and the rs2 comparison with uses_rs2, while preserving the\\nexisting redirect, imem replay readiness, MEM wait, and EX long-operation\\nstall behavior.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Pass any additional IF/ID instruction validity or predecoded source-use\\nsideband needed by the hazard unit. Keep the core module IO unchanged,\\npreserve the registered IF replay wiring, pending-store-slot arbitration,\\ndivider interlock, RVFI NRET=2 field set, strict channel-0 order sequence,\\nand tied-off channel 1.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"If useful, add compact comments or bundle fields documenting IF/ID\\nsource-use metadata for hazard detection. Do not change RVFI fields,\\narchitectural state semantics, decoder legality defaults, ALU op\\nencodings, or the NRET=2 contract.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 1, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the raw load-use comparison against both IF/ID register fields\\nwith a source-use-aware predicate. Add conservative decode-light logic for\\nknown legal RV32IM instruction classes, defaulting unknown or reserved\\nencodings to uses_rs1=1 and uses_rs2=1. Gate the rs1 comparison with\\nuses_rs1 and the rs2 comparison with uses_rs2, while preserving the\\nexisting redirect, imem replay readiness, MEM wait, and EX long-operation\\nstall behavior.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Pass any additional IF/ID instruction validity or predecoded source-use\\nsideband needed by the hazard unit. Keep the core module IO unchanged,\\npreserve the registered IF replay wiring, pending-store-slot arbitration,\\ndivider interlock, RVFI NRET=2 field set, strict channel-0 order sequence,\\nand tied-off channel 1.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"If useful, add compact comments or bundle fields documenting IF/ID\\nsource-use metadata for hazard detection. Do not change RVFI fields,\\narchitectural state semantics, decoder legality defaults, ALU op\\nencodings, or the NRET=2 contract.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"cosim_failed: selftest.elf\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 18}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-050-r19s1\", \"title\": \"Backend-Stall Shadow I-Fetch Prefetcher\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core gets its largest cycle-count win from the registered\\nlookahead instruction replay table: hot instructions can be supplied during\\nrandom imem stalls without a same-cycle replay lookup on the IF critical\\npath. The remaining structural stalls are now mostly backend stalls from\\ndmem waits and long operations. During those cycles the frontend PC is held,\\ndecode is not accepting a new instruction, and the independent imem port is\\nusually wasted refreshing the same held PC or sitting idle.\\n\\nPrior fetch queues tried to decouple fetch and decode directly, but they put\\nqueue control on the normal zero-wait frontend path and lost Fmax. A more\\ntargeted structural angle is to use backend-stall cycles only as replay-table\\nwarmup time. The architectural fetch/decode stream remains held exactly as it\\nis today, while a shadow prefetch PC walks ahead through the existing static\\nbranch/direct-JAL prediction policy and fills the replay table with future\\ninstruction words. When the backend releases, later external imem stalls are\\nmore likely to hit in the already-proven registered replay structure.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core gets its largest cycle-count win from the registered\\nlookahead instruction replay table: hot instructions can be supplied during\\nrandom imem stalls without a same-cycle replay lookup on the IF critical\\npath. The remaining structural stalls are now mostly backend stalls from\\ndmem waits and long operations. During those cycles the frontend PC is held,\\ndecode is not accepting a new instruction, and the independent imem port is\\nusually wasted refreshing the same held PC or sitting idle.\\n\\nPrior fetch queues tried to decouple fetch and decode directly, but they put\\nqueue control on the normal zero-wait frontend path and lost Fmax. A more\\ntargeted structural angle is to use backend-stall cycles only as replay-table\\nwarmup time. The architectural fetch/decode stream remains held exactly as it\\nis today, while a shadow prefetch PC walks ahead through the existing static\\nbranch/direct-JAL prediction policy and fills the replay table with future\\ninstruction words. When the backend releases, later external imem stalls are\\nmore likely to hit in the already-proven registered replay structure.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a shadow instruction prefetch mode inside IF that activates only while a\\nbackend stall is holding the architectural frontend and the current IF/ID\\ninstruction is already safely held or replayable. On entry, capture the\\ncurrent architectural IF/ID metadata into a tiny hold register so the hazard\\nunit and decode-facing output continue to see the same instruction while\\nthe external imem address is repurposed for prefetch. The architectural PC\\nand pipeline-visible IF/ID payload remain frozen until the backend accepts\\nthem; only the replay table is updated by shadow fetches.\\n\\nWhile shadow prefetch is active, drive `io_imemAddr` from a `prefetch_pc`\\nrather than the architectural PC. On each `io_imemReady` prefetch response,\\nfill or refresh the existing 256-entry compressed-tag replay entry for\\n`prefetch_pc`, then advance `prefetch_pc` using the same zero-state static\\nnext-PC rule already used for normal fetch: backward conditional branches\\npredict taken, direct aligned JAL predicts its target, and JALR remains\\nunpredicted. Redirects, reset, and frontend flushes cancel shadow prefetch\\nimmediately and resume normal fetch at the resolved architectural target.\\n\\nThis is not a fetch queue and it does not let prefetched instructions enter\\ndecode early. It only converts cycles where the backend cannot accept an\\ninstruction into useful instruction replay-table fills. Live architectural\\nfetches still have priority when the backend is ready, replay hits still use\\nthe registered lookahead candidate, replay misses still hold the PC and\\ninject the existing IF bubble, and EX still repairs branch/JAL prediction\\nmistakes through resolved-next-PC mismatch recovery. The top-level IO, RVFI\\nNRET=2 port set, channel-0-only retirement convention, strict `rvfi_order`\\nsequence, pending-store slot, divider interlock, memory ordering, and decoder\\nlegality rules remain unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a backend-stall-only shadow prefetch mode. Capture the current\\narchitectural IF/ID metadata into a hold register before repurposing\\n`io_imemAddr`, keep the decode-facing output stable from that hold\\nregister while the backend is stalled, and use a separate `prefetch_pc`\\nto fill the existing compressed-tag replay table. Advance the shadow PC\\nwith the existing static branch/direct-JAL prediction rule, cancel it on\\nreset, flush, or EX redirect, and preserve live-imem priority plus the\\nregistered replay-hit `fetch_ready` contract for architectural fetches.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire a backend-prefetch-eligible signal into IF, derived from precise\\nbackend holds such as MEM wait and EX long-operation stalls rather than\\nraw imem misses. Keep the core module IO, RVFI channel layout, pending\\nstore-slot arbitration, hot/cold ALU wiring, divider interlock, and\\nchannel-1 tie-off unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"If needed, expose or document the distinction between frontend imem\\nunavailability and backend holds so IF only enters shadow prefetch when\\ndecode is blocked by the backend and the architectural IF/ID instruction\\nmust remain stable. Preserve existing load-use, redirect, MEM wait,\\nEX-long-operation, EX/MEM hold, and MEM/WB hold behavior.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Clarify IF/ID comments to document that during backend-stall shadow\\nprefetch the pipeline-visible IF/ID metadata remains held while the imem\\nport may be used only to warm the replay table. Do not change bundle\\nwidths, architectural state semantics, decoder legality defaults, RVFI\\nfields, or the NRET=2 contract.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a backend-stall-only shadow prefetch mode. Capture the current\\narchitectural IF/ID metadata into a hold register before repurposing\\n`io_imemAddr`, keep the decode-facing output stable from that hold\\nregister while the backend is stalled, and use a separate `prefetch_pc`\\nto fill the existing compressed-tag replay table. Advance the shadow PC\\nwith the existing static branch/direct-JAL prediction rule, cancel it on\\nreset, flush, or EX redirect, and preserve live-imem priority plus the\\nregistered replay-hit `fetch_ready` contract for architectural fetches.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire a backend-prefetch-eligible signal into IF, derived from precise\\nbackend holds such as MEM wait and EX long-operation stalls rather than\\nraw imem misses. Keep the core module IO, RVFI channel layout, pending\\nstore-slot arbitration, hot/cold ALU wiring, divider interlock, and\\nchannel-1 tie-off unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"If needed, expose or document the distinction between frontend imem\\nunavailability and backend holds so IF only enters shadow prefetch when\\ndecode is blocked by the backend and the architectural IF/ID instruction\\nmust remain stable. Preserve existing load-use, redirect, MEM wait,\\nEX-long-operation, EX/MEM hold, and MEM/WB hold behavior.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Clarify IF/ID comments to document that during backend-stall shadow\\nprefetch the pipeline-visible IF/ID metadata remains held while the imem\\nport may be used only to warm the replay table. Do not change bundle\\nwidths, architectural state semantics, decoder legality defaults, RVFI\\nfields, or the NRET=2 contract.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"cosim_failed: coremark.elf\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 19}\n","metadata":{"output":"...\n\ns a stalled normal-RAM store retire before\\nthe external dmem write is accepted. The remaining store-side bottleneck is\\nnarrower than a full second buffer entry. When the pending slot is valid, the\\nMEM stage currently treats every younger memory operation as blocked even on\\nthe exact cycle where `io_dmemReady` will drain the older buffered store.\\n\\nThat leaves a small but avoidable bubble for bursts of normal-RAM stores:\\nthe older store uses the physical dmem port, while the younger store already\\nhas its address, replicated data, byte mask, and RVFI-visible memory fields\\navailable in MEM and could refill the just-drained slot. A previous\\ntwo-entry FIFO targeted the same store-burst pressure but failed placement.\\nThe existing `store_slot` state machine already supports simultaneous drain\\nand enqueue, so the lower-risk structural angle is to expose that fast refill\\ncase without adding another entry or touching the IF replay path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already has the two structural wins that matter most:\\nregistered instruction replay hides many random iStall cycles, and the\\none-deep pending-store slot lets a stalled normal-RAM store retire before\\nthe external dmem write is accepted. The remaining store-side bottleneck is\\nnarrower than a full second buffer entry. When the pending slot is valid, the\\nMEM stage currently treats every younger memory operation as blocked even on\\nthe exact cycle where `io_dmemReady` will drain the older buffered store.\\n\\nThat leaves a small but avoidable bubble for bursts of normal-RAM stores:\\nthe older store uses the physical dmem port, while the younger store already\\nhas its address, replicated data, byte mask, and RVFI-visible memory fields\\navailable in MEM and could refill the just-drained slot. A previous\\ntwo-entry FIFO targeted the same store-burst pressure but failed placement.\\nThe existing `store_slot` state machine already supports simultaneous drain\\nand enqueue, so the lower-risk structural angle is to expose that fast refill\\ncase without adding another entry or touching the IF replay path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Allow a legal, aligned normal-RAM store in MEM to enqueue into the pending\\nstore slot on the same cycle that an older slot entry drains\\n(`store_slot_valid && io_dmemReady`). The top-level dmem port still gives the\\nolder slot entry priority for that cycle. The younger store retires once\\nthrough MEM/WB with its normal RVFI `mem_addr`, `mem_wmask`, and `mem_wdata`,\\nand the slot remains valid with the younger store's physical drain fields for\\na later external write.\\n\\nKeep all existing ordering constraints. If the slot is valid and the port is\\nnot ready, younger memory operations still wait. Loads, MMIO/marker/UART\\nstores, misaligned stores, illegal/trapping accesses, and any non-normal-RAM\\nstore still wait behind the slot and never enter it. If the slot is empty,\\nthe current direct ready-store path and low-ready enqueue path remain\\nunchanged. Younger non-memory instructions continue to pass while a buffered\\nstore drains, as they do today.\\n\\nThis should recover part of the store-burst stall cycles that motivated the\\nfailed two-entry FIFO, but with almost no additional placement pressure:\\nonly the MEM-stage enqueue/wait predicate changes, and the existing one-entry\\nslot already implements the simultaneous drain-plus-enqueue update. The\\ntop-level IO, RVFI NRET=2 channel layout, strict channel-0 order sequence,\\ntied-off channel 1, registered IF replay predictor, divider interlock, branch\\nprediction, and decoder legality invariants remain unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Refine pending-store backpressure so a bufferable normal-RAM store can\\nenqueue when the existing slot is valid and `dmem_ready` is high, because\\nthe older slot entry is draining on that same cycle. Preserve the direct\\nready-store path when the slot is empty, the existing low-ready enqueue\\npath when the slot is empty and the port stalls, and full waits for\\nloads, nonbufferable stores, MMIO/marker/UART stores, traps, and memory\\noperations behind a non-draining valid slot.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/store_slot.sv\", \"description\": \"Keep the one-entry slot state machine, but document and, if needed,\\ntighten the simultaneous drain-plus-enqueue behavior so a draining older\\nstore can be replaced by a younger bufferable store in the same clock\\nedge. The slot still holds only physical drain fields; RVFI metadata\\nremains retired through MEM/WB on the enqueue cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Preserve the current top-level dmem arbitration with pending-slot\\npriority while valid. Update comments or local naming only if needed to\\nmake clear that `store_slot_valid && io_dmemReady` represents available\\nenqueue capacity after the older store drains, without changing the core\\nmodule IO, RVFI ports, IF replay wiring, or channel-1 tie-off.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Refine pending-store backpressure so a bufferable normal-RAM store can\\nenqueue when the existing slot is valid and `dmem_ready` is high, because\\nthe older slot entry is draining on that same cycle. Preserve the direct\\nready-store path when the slot is empty, the existing low-ready enqueue\\npath when the slot is empty and the port stalls, and full waits for\\nloads, nonbufferable stores, MMIO/marker/UART stores, traps, and memory\\noperations behind a non-draining valid slot.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/store_slot.sv\", \"description\": \"Keep the one-entry slot state machine, but document and, if needed,\\ntighten the simultaneous drain-plus-enqueue behavior so a draining older\\nstore can be replaced by a younger bufferable store in the same clock\\nedge. The slot still holds only physical drain fields; RVFI metadata\\nremains retired through MEM/WB on the enqueue cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Preserve the current top-level dmem arbitration with pending-slot\\npriority while valid. Update comments or local naming only if needed to\\nmake clear that `store_slot_valid && io_dmemReady` represents available\\nenqueue capacity after the older store drains, without changing the core\\nmodule IO, RVFI ports, IF replay wiring, or channel-1 tie-off.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"placement_failed\", \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": \"placement_failed\", \"seeds\": [null, null, null], \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 16}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-044-r17s1\", \"title\": \"Tiny MRU Load Replay Latch\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already uses the two structural ideas that have paid\\nclearly: a one-deep pending-store slot for store-only dmem backpressure and\\na registered instruction replay table for random iStall. The remaining\\nstructural stalls are concentrated on normal-RAM loads. A load still freezes\\nthe whole in-order pipeline whenever io_dmemReady is low, even if the same\\naligned word was returned recently.\\n\\nThe prior 16-entry MEM-stage load replay buffer showed that this stall source\\nis real: it reduced CoreMark cycles on top of the instruction replay design.\\nIt missed the current best because the same-cycle table lookup, tag compare,\\nand store-update logic dropped Fmax too much. A much smaller MRU replay latch\\ntargets the same dmem-stall opportunity while keeping the MEM path close to\\nthe current best design.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already uses the two structural ideas that have paid\\nclearly: a one-deep pending-store slot for store-only dmem backpressure and\\na registered instruction replay table for random iStall. The remaining\\nstructural stalls are concentrated on normal-RAM loads. A load still freezes\\nthe whole in-order pipeline whenever io_dmemReady is low, even if the same\\naligned word was returned recently.\\n\\nThe prior 16-entry MEM-stage load replay buffer showed that this stall source\\nis real: it reduced CoreMark cycles on top of the instruction replay design.\\nIt missed the current best because the same-cycle table lookup, tag compare,\\nand store-update logic dropped Fmax too much. A much smaller MRU replay latch\\ntargets the same dmem-stall opportunity while keeping the MEM path close to\\nthe current best design.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a two-entry most-recently-used normal-RAM load replay latch in MEM. Each\\nentry stores a valid bit, an aligned word address tag, and the raw 32-bit word\\nreturned by a previously accepted legal normal-RAM load. On io_dmemReady=1,\\nloads keep using live io_dmemRData exactly as today and update the MRU latch\\nwith the aligned word and raw data. On io_dmemReady=0, a valid legal\\nnormal-RAM load may complete from the latch if either entry matches the\\naligned word address: suppress dmem_ren, use the cached raw word for\\nsign/zero extension and RVFI mem_rdata, and do not assert mem_wait.\\n\\nReplay remains conservative. It is disabled while the pending store slot is\\nvalid, for MMIO/marker/UART addresses, for misaligned or trapping accesses,\\nand for stores. Normal-RAM stores byte-merge any matching replay entry before\\nthey retire or enqueue into the pending-store slot; if a simple merge is not\\navailable for a corner case, invalidating the matching entry is acceptable.\\nReplay misses preserve the current dmem wait behavior exactly.\\n\\nThis is a structural latency-hiding change, not a MEM-to-EX bypass. Cached\\ndata is consumed only at the MEM retirement boundary, dependent younger\\ninstructions still use the existing load-use discipline, and the top-level IO,\\nRVFI NRET=2 channel layout, channel-0-only retirement order, divider\\ninterlock, registered IF replay predictor, branch prediction, pending-store\\nordering, and decoder legality invariants remain unchanged. The expected win\\nis a small cycle reduction from repeated normal-RAM loads during random\\ndmem stalls with much less Fmax cost than the earlier 16-entry load replay\\ntable.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/load_mru_replay.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a tiny two-entry MRU replay latch for normal-RAM load words. Entries\\nhold valid, aligned word address tag, and raw 32-bit data. Provide lookup\\nhit/data for the current MEM load, update from accepted live load\\nresponses, and byte-merge or invalidate matching entries on legal\\nnormal-RAM stores. Reset clears only valid bits.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Integrate the MRU replay lookup into load handling. Select cached raw word\\ndata only when dmem_ready is low, the current access is a valid legal\\nnormal-RAM load, no pending store slot is valid, and the latch hits. On a\\nhit, gate off dmem_ren, clear mem_wait, and drive load extraction plus\\nRVFI mem_rdata from the cached word. Keep replay misses and all\\nnonbufferable accesses on the existing wait path.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add only comments or compact helper typedefs if useful to document the\\nMRU load replay eligibility and raw-word metadata. Do not change\\narchitectural state semantics, decoder legality defaults, RVFI field\\nwidths, or the NRET=2 contract.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/load_mru_replay.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a tiny two-entry MRU replay latch for normal-RAM load words. Entries\\nhold valid, aligned word address tag, and raw 32-bit data. Provide lookup\\nhit/data for the current MEM load, update from accepted live load\\nresponses, and byte-merge or invalidate matching entries on legal\\nnormal-RAM stores. Reset clears only valid bits.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Integrate the MRU replay lookup into load handling. Select cached raw word\\ndata only when dmem_ready is low, the current access is a valid legal\\nnormal-RAM load, no pending store slot is valid, and the latch hits. On a\\nhit, gate off dmem_ren, clear mem_wait, and drive load extraction plus\\nRVFI mem_rdata from the cached word. Keep replay misses and all\\nnonbufferable accesses on the existing wait path.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add only comments or compact helper typedefs if useful to document the\\nMRU load replay eligibility and raw-word metadata. Do not change\\narchitectural state semantics, decoder legality defaults, RVFI field\\nwidths, or the NRET=2 contract.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 404.58, \"delta_pct\": -19.99, \"vs_baseline\": 34.39, \"fmax_mhz\": 139.0, \"ipc_coremark\": 3e-06, \"cycles\": 3435657, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5909, \"ff\": 2224, \"seeds\": [139.0, 142.94, 131.86], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"# Implementation Notes\\n\\n## What changed\\n\\n- Added `rtl/load_mru_replay.sv`, a two-entry MRU latch for legal normal-RAM load words. Each entry tracks a valid bit, aligned word address tag, and raw 32-bit word data.\\n- Integrated the latch in `rtl/mem_stage.sv`.\\n  - Ready normal-RAM loads still use live `dmem_rdata` and fill the latch.\\n  - Stalled legal normal-RAM load hits suppress `dmem_ren`, clear `mem_wait`, and use cached raw data for load extraction and RVFI `mem_rdata`.\\n  - Replay is disabled while the pending-store slot is valid, and for stores, MMIO/marker/UART/OOB addresses, illegal accesses, and misaligned accesses.\\n  - Legal normal-RAM stores byte-merge matching latch entries when they retire or enqueue into the pending-store slot.\\n\\n## Deviations\\n\\n- No `core_pkg.sv` changes were needed; the replay eligibility stayed local to MEM.\\n- The implementation promotes an entry-1 replay hit to entry 0 so the two entries behave as a true MRU pair. This is a small sequential state update and does not add another table.\\n\\n## Concerns\\n\\n- No known functional concerns from lint or formal. The latch intentionally resets only valid bits; tags and data are ignored until valid.\\n- This still adds two 32-bit tag compares in the MEM decision path, so the final FPGA result will determine whether the small cycle win outweighs timing cost.\\n\\n## Local verification\\n\\n- `verilator --lint-only -Wall -Wno-MULTITOP -sv rtl/*.sv`: pass.\\n- `bash formal/run_all.sh`: blocked before solver startup in this sandbox because `formal/riscv-formal` is a symlink to a shared checkout outside the writable worktree, and the script's staging cleanup could not remove stale files there (`Operation not permitted`).\\n- Equivalent local formal flow from a temporary writable mirror under `/tmp`, using the same `checks.cfg`, `wrapper.sv`, current `rtl/*.sv`, and riscv-formal framework files: pass, `105 passed, 0 failed`.\\n\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-04-28T07:35:07.182987\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 17}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-047-r18s1\", \"title\": \"Decode-Exact Load-Use Interlock\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core has strong timing wins from the registered instruction\\nreplay predictor, segmented RVFI order counter, pending-store slot, and\\nhot/cold ALU split. The remaining structural improvement should therefore\\navoid another cache, queue, predictor table, or load-data forwarding path that\\ncould disturb Fmax.\\n\\nThe load-use interlock is still structurally conservative. It stalls whenever\\na load in ID/EX has a nonzero destination matching either raw rs1 or raw rs2\\nbitfield of the IF/ID instruction. That is correct for true consumers, but it\\ncreates false bubbles for instructions where one or both fields are not\\nsource operands: OP-IMM and LOAD do not read rs2, JAL/LUI/AUIPC read neither,\\nFENCE/EBREAK read neither, and JALR reads only rs1. CoreMark's optimized code\\nhas dense immediate arithmetic, address-generation loads, calls, and loop\\ncontrol, so these false one-cycle bubbles are a plausible remaining IPC loss.\\n\\nA prior operand-aware interlock attempt broke selftest, so this hypothesis is\\ndeliberately conservative: decode source-use exactly for known legal\\ninstruction classes, keep reserved or unknown encodings on the current\\nboth-source stall policy, and do not add any MEM-to-EX load-data path. The\\ngoal is to recover only provably false load-use stalls while leaving all true\\nload consumers, dmem waits, branch recovery, divider interlocks, and RVFI\\nordering unchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core has strong timing wins from the registered instruction\\nreplay predictor, segmented RVFI order counter, pending-store slot, and\\nhot/cold ALU split. The remaining structural improvement should therefore\\navoid another cache, queue, predictor table, or load-data forwarding path that\\ncould disturb Fmax.\\n\\nThe load-use interlock is still structurally conservative. It stalls whenever\\na load in ID/EX has a nonzero destination matching either raw rs1 or raw rs2\\nbitfield of the IF/ID instruction. That is correct for true consumers, but it\\ncreates false bubbles for instructions where one or both fields are not\\nsource operands: OP-IMM and LOAD do not read rs2, JAL/LUI/AUIPC read neither,\\nFENCE/EBREAK read neither, and JALR reads only rs1. CoreMark's optimized code\\nhas dense immediate arithmetic, address-generation loads, calls, and loop\\ncontrol, so these false one-cycle bubbles are a plausible remaining IPC loss.\\n\\nA prior operand-aware interlock attempt broke selftest, so this hypothesis is\\ndeliberately conservative: decode source-use exactly for known legal\\ninstruction classes, keep reserved or unknown encodings on the current\\nboth-source stall policy, and do not add any MEM-to-EX load-data path. The\\ngoal is to recover only provably false load-use stalls while leaving all true\\nload consumers, dmem waits, branch recovery, divider interlocks, and RVFI\\nordering unchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small decode-light source-use classifier for the IF/ID instruction and\\nuse it in the load-use hazard predicate. A load in ID/EX should stall the next\\ninstruction only when the next instruction is valid and actually reads the\\nmatching source:\\n\\n- rs1 is used by OP, OP-IMM, LOAD, STORE, BRANCH, and legal JALR.\\n- rs2 is used by OP, STORE, and BRANCH.\\n- JAL, LUI, AUIPC, FENCE/FENCE.I, and EBREAK use no integer source register.\\n- Reserved funct3/funct7 combinations and unknown opcodes remain\\n  conservative by treating both rs fields as possible sources.\\n\\nThe existing one-cycle bubble remains for every true load-use dependency,\\nincluding store address dependencies, branch compares, JALR bases, ALU\\nconsumers, and any conservative illegal/unknown instruction class. The change\\nshould not forward load data, alter the MEM stage, widen retirement, or\\nchange the top-level IO. It only refines when the frontend and ID/EX register\\nare stalled for a load in EX.\\n\\nThis preserves the hard invariants: decoder legality still defaults illegal,\\nRVFI traps and order remain generated at MEM/WB, channel 1 stays tied off, and\\nall memory and timing-marker behavior remains unchanged. The expected benefit\\nis a small CoreMark cycle reduction with minimal Fmax risk because the added\\nlogic is opcode/funct predecode on the existing hazard path, not a new data\\npath or stateful predictor.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 1, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the raw load-use comparison against both IF/ID register fields\\nwith a source-use-aware predicate. Add conservative decode-light logic for\\nknown legal RV32IM instruction classes, defaulting unknown or reserved\\nencodings to uses_rs1=1 and uses_rs2=1. Gate the rs1 comparison with\\nuses_rs1 and the rs2 comparison with uses_rs2, while preserving the\\nexisting redirect, imem replay readiness, MEM wait, and EX long-operation\\nstall behavior.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Pass any additional IF/ID instruction validity or predecoded source-use\\nsideband needed by the hazard unit. Keep the core module IO unchanged,\\npreserve the registered IF replay wiring, pending-store-slot arbitration,\\ndivider interlock, RVFI NRET=2 field set, strict channel-0 order sequence,\\nand tied-off channel 1.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"If useful, add compact comments or bundle fields documenting IF/ID\\nsource-use metadata for hazard detection. Do not change RVFI fields,\\narchitectural state semantics, decoder legality defaults, ALU op\\nencodings, or the NRET=2 contract.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 1, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the raw load-use comparison against both IF/ID register fields\\nwith a source-use-aware predicate. Add conservative decode-light logic for\\nknown legal RV32IM instruction classes, defaulting unknown or reserved\\nencodings to uses_rs1=1 and uses_rs2=1. Gate the rs1 comparison with\\nuses_rs1 and the rs2 comparison with uses_rs2, while preserving the\\nexisting redirect, imem replay readiness, MEM wait, and EX long-operation\\nstall behavior.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Pass any additional IF/ID instruction validity or predecoded source-use\\nsideband needed by the hazard unit. Keep the core module IO unchanged,\\npreserve the registered IF replay wiring, pending-store-slot arbitration,\\ndivider interlock, RVFI NRET=2 field set, strict channel-0 order sequence,\\nand tied-off channel 1.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"If useful, add compact comments or bundle fields documenting IF/ID\\nsource-use metadata for hazard detection. Do not change RVFI fields,\\narchitectural state semantics, decoder legality defaults, ALU op\\nencodings, or the NRET=2 contract.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"cosim_failed: selftest.elf\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 18}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-050-r19s1\", \"title\": \"Backend-Stall Shadow I-Fetch Prefetcher\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core gets its largest cycle-count win from the registered\\nlookahead instruction replay table: hot instructions can be supplied during\\nrandom imem stalls without a same-cycle replay lookup on the IF critical\\npath. The remaining structural stalls are now mostly backend stalls from\\ndmem waits and long operations. During those cycles the frontend PC is held,\\ndecode is not accepting a new instruction, and the independent imem port is\\nusually wasted refreshing the same held PC or sitting idle.\\n\\nPrior fetch queues tried to decouple fetch and decode directly, but they put\\nqueue control on the normal zero-wait frontend path and lost Fmax. A more\\ntargeted structural angle is to use backend-stall cycles only as replay-table\\nwarmup time. The architectural fetch/decode stream remains held exactly as it\\nis today, while a shadow prefetch PC walks ahead through the existing static\\nbranch/direct-JAL prediction policy and fills the replay table with future\\ninstruction words. When the backend releases, later external imem stalls are\\nmore likely to hit in the already-proven registered replay structure.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core gets its largest cycle-count win from the registered\\nlookahead instruction replay table: hot instructions can be supplied during\\nrandom imem stalls without a same-cycle replay lookup on the IF critical\\npath. The remaining structural stalls are now mostly backend stalls from\\ndmem waits and long operations. During those cycles the frontend PC is held,\\ndecode is not accepting a new instruction, and the independent imem port is\\nusually wasted refreshing the same held PC or sitting idle.\\n\\nPrior fetch queues tried to decouple fetch and decode directly, but they put\\nqueue control on the normal zero-wait frontend path and lost Fmax. A more\\ntargeted structural angle is to use backend-stall cycles only as replay-table\\nwarmup time. The architectural fetch/decode stream remains held exactly as it\\nis today, while a shadow prefetch PC walks ahead through the existing static\\nbranch/direct-JAL prediction policy and fills the replay table with future\\ninstruction words. When the backend releases, later external imem stalls are\\nmore likely to hit in the already-proven registered replay structure.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a shadow instruction prefetch mode inside IF that activates only while a\\nbackend stall is holding the architectural frontend and the current IF/ID\\ninstruction is already safely held or replayable. On entry, capture the\\ncurrent architectural IF/ID metadata into a tiny hold register so the hazard\\nunit and decode-facing output continue to see the same instruction while\\nthe external imem address is repurposed for prefetch. The architectural PC\\nand pipeline-visible IF/ID payload remain frozen until the backend accepts\\nthem; only the replay table is updated by shadow fetches.\\n\\nWhile shadow prefetch is active, drive `io_imemAddr` from a `prefetch_pc`\\nrather than the architectural PC. On each `io_imemReady` prefetch response,\\nfill or refresh the existing 256-entry compressed-tag replay entry for\\n`prefetch_pc`, then advance `prefetch_pc` using the same zero-state static\\nnext-PC rule already used for normal fetch: backward conditional branches\\npredict taken, direct aligned JAL predicts its target, and JALR remains\\nunpredicted. Redirects, reset, and frontend flushes cancel shadow prefetch\\nimmediately and resume normal fetch at the resolved architectural target.\\n\\nThis is not a fetch queue and it does not let prefetched instructions enter\\ndecode early. It only converts cycles where the backend cannot accept an\\ninstruction into useful instruction replay-table fills. Live architectural\\nfetches still have priority when the backend is ready, replay hits still use\\nthe registered lookahead candidate, replay misses still hold the PC and\\ninject the existing IF bubble, and EX still repairs branch/JAL prediction\\nmistakes through resolved-next-PC mismatch recovery. The top-level IO, RVFI\\nNRET=2 port set, channel-0-only retirement convention, strict `rvfi_order`\\nsequence, pending-store slot, divider interlock, memory ordering, and decoder\\nlegality rules remain unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a backend-stall-only shadow prefetch mode. Capture the current\\narchitectural IF/ID metadata into a hold register before repurposing\\n`io_imemAddr`, keep the decode-facing output stable from that hold\\nregister while the backend is stalled, and use a separate `prefetch_pc`\\nto fill the existing compressed-tag replay table. Advance the shadow PC\\nwith the existing static branch/direct-JAL prediction rule, cancel it on\\nreset, flush, or EX redirect, and preserve live-imem priority plus the\\nregistered replay-hit `fetch_ready` contract for architectural fetches.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire a backend-prefetch-eligible signal into IF, derived from precise\\nbackend holds such as MEM wait and EX long-operation stalls rather than\\nraw imem misses. Keep the core module IO, RVFI channel layout, pending\\nstore-slot arbitration, hot/cold ALU wiring, divider interlock, and\\nchannel-1 tie-off unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"If needed, expose or document the distinction between frontend imem\\nunavailability and backend holds so IF only enters shadow prefetch when\\ndecode is blocked by the backend and the architectural IF/ID instruction\\nmust remain stable. Preserve existing load-use, redirect, MEM wait,\\nEX-long-operation, EX/MEM hold, and MEM/WB hold behavior.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Clarify IF/ID comments to document that during backend-stall shadow\\nprefetch the pipeline-visible IF/ID metadata remains held while the imem\\nport may be used only to warm the replay table. Do not change bundle\\nwidths, architectural state semantics, decoder legality defaults, RVFI\\nfields, or the NRET=2 contract.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a backend-stall-only shadow prefetch mode. Capture the current\\narchitectural IF/ID metadata into a hold register before repurposing\\n`io_imemAddr`, keep the decode-facing output stable from that hold\\nregister while the backend is stalled, and use a separate `prefetch_pc`\\nto fill the existing compressed-tag replay table. Advance the shadow PC\\nwith the existing static branch/direct-JAL prediction rule, cancel it on\\nreset, flush, or EX redirect, and preserve live-imem priority plus the\\nregistered replay-hit `fetch_ready` contract for architectural fetches.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire a backend-prefetch-eligible signal into IF, derived from precise\\nbackend holds such as MEM wait and EX long-operation stalls rather than\\nraw imem misses. Keep the core module IO, RVFI channel layout, pending\\nstore-slot arbitration, hot/cold ALU wiring, divider interlock, and\\nchannel-1 tie-off unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"If needed, expose or document the distinction between frontend imem\\nunavailability and backend holds so IF only enters shadow prefetch when\\ndecode is blocked by the backend and the architectural IF/ID instruction\\nmust remain stable. Preserve existing load-use, redirect, MEM wait,\\nEX-long-operation, EX/MEM hold, and MEM/WB hold behavior.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Clarify IF/ID comments to document that during backend-stall shadow\\nprefetch the pipeline-visible IF/ID metadata remains held while the imem\\nport may be used only to warm the replay table. Do not change bundle\\nwidths, architectural state semantics, decoder legality defaults, RVFI\\nfields, or the NRET=2 contract.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"cosim_failed: coremark.elf\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 19}\n","exit":0,"description":"Find prior structural hypotheses across cores","truncated":true,"outputPath":"/Users/bonetto/.local/share/opencode/tool-output/tool_e244c23e1001G4lj5N1aMdsaDN"},"title":"Find prior structural hypotheses across cores","time":{"start":1778725430220,"end":1778725430243}},"id":"prt_e244c1eaa0016NIyWKlFfYIu5V","sessionID":"ses_1dbbd8558ffeBxliGckE4NqTl7","messageID":"msg_e2442b8c2001Q8UAS1v97AogsO"}}
