{"type":"text","timestamp":1778727428717,"sessionID":"ses_1db9e262bffeuwRtxhKH1fPme3","part":{"id":"prt_e246a8957001K5oVZ22UDzP5oX","messageID":"msg_e246a6d8d001g1KVGiHDk24FNx","sessionID":"ses_1db9e262bffeuwRtxhKH1fPme3","type":"text","text":"Done. I've written the hypothesis YAML to:\n\n`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r3s2.yaml`\n\nThe hypothesis proposes adding a **32-entry tagged Branch Target Buffer with 2-bit saturating counters** to the existing static predictor. The key ideas:\n\n1. **Timing benefit:** BTB hits bypass the combinational immediate-decode + PC-adder path in IF, potentially shortening the critical path.\n2. **IPC benefit:** The 2-bit counters learn taken forward branches that the static BTFN predictor currently mispredicts, while backward branches and JAL continue to be predicted correctly by the static base.\n3. **Low area cost:** ~1.2 kbits of state (32 × 38-bit entries), trivial on the Tang Nano 20K.\n4. **Safe fallback:** BTB can only override to *predict taken*, never to predict not-taken, so backward branches are never harmed.","time":{"start":1778727422295,"end":1778727428715}}}
