ent 5-stage pipeline stalls for one cycle on every load-use hazard\\nbecause it can only forward loaded data from MEM/WB, not from the MEM stage\\nitself.  CoreMark pointer-chasing and array-index patterns frequently emit a\\nLOAD followed immediately by a dependent ALU or STORE.  Eliminating the\\nload-use bubble improves IPC with no extra pipeline stages or tables.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline stalls for one cycle on every load-use hazard\\nbecause it can only forward loaded data from MEM/WB, not from the MEM stage\\nitself.  CoreMark pointer-chasing and array-index patterns frequently emit a\\nLOAD followed immediately by a dependent ALU or STORE.  Eliminating the\\nload-use bubble improves IPC with no extra pipeline stages or tables.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a combinational bypass from mem_stage's load_data output back to the\\nEX-stage operand muxes.  Extend the forwarding_unit so that when EX/MEM\\ncontains a LOAD whose rd matches an EX-stage rs, it selects the new bypass\\npath (encoding 2'b11).  Remove the load_use_hazard stall from hazard_unit;\\nthe bypass makes it unnecessary.  All other stalls (imem/dmem backpressure,\\nredirect flush) remain unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 7, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the load_use_hazard term from stall_if, stall_id, and flush_id. The MEM\\u2192EX bypass eliminates the need to stall the pipeline for load-use.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_mem_mem_read input.  When EX/MEM has a matching rd and ex_mem_mem_read is high, drive fwd_rs1/fwd_rs2 = 2'b11 to select the MEM-stage load bypass instead of the ALU-result path.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_mem_load [31:0] input.  Extend the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes to select fwd_mem_load ...\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Eliminate false load-use stalls via opcode-aware hazard detection\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current hazard_unit conservatively checks both rs1 (instr[19:15]) and rs2\\n(instr[24:20]) of the instruction in ID against the LOAD's rd in EX,\\nregardless of whether the instruction actually reads those fields as registers.\\nFor I-type (OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR), U-type, and J-type instructions, the rs2\\nfield is an immediate/shamt, not a register address. A LOAD followed by an\\nADDI where imm[4:0] happens to match the LOAD's rd currently triggers a\\nspurious one-cycle stall. CoreMark uses small immediate values extensively,\\nso false stalls on common x1-x5 register numbers are likely frequent.\\nEliminating these false stalls improves IPC with negligible LUT/Fmax cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current hazard_unit conservatively checks both rs1 (instr[19:15]) and rs2\\n(instr[24:20]) of the instruction in ID against the LOAD's rd in EX,\\nregardless of whether the instruction actually reads those fields as registers.\\nFor I-type (OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR), U-type, and J-type instructions, the rs2\\nfield is an immediate/shamt, not a register address. A LOAD followed by an\\nADDI where imm[4:0] happens to match the LOAD's rd currently triggers a\\nspurious one-cycle stall. CoreMark uses small immediate values extensively,\\nso false stalls on common x1-x5 register numbers are likely frequent.\\nEliminating these false stalls improves IPC with negligible LUT/Fmax cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add opcode decoding to hazard_unit so load-use detection only fires when\\nthe instruction in ID actually reads rs1/rs2 as registers. R-type, I-type\\n(OP-IMM/LOAD/JALR), S-type, and B-type use rs1; R-type, S-type, and B-type\\nuse rs2. U-type and J-type use neither. This removes false stalls without\\naltering pipeline structure or lengthening critical paths.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": ...\n  Line 11: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r4s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r4s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r4s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r4s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r4s2'])\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 4}\n\n  Line 14: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Eliminate false load-use stalls via opcode-aware hazard detection\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit conservatively stalls on any LOAD-to-use sequence where the\\nLOAD's rd matches either rs1 or rs2 of the next instruction, regardless of\\nwhether those fields are actually register reads. For I-type instructions\\n(OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR) the rs2 field encodes an immediate or shamt; for U-type\\n(LUI, AUIPC), J-type (JAL), and SYSTEM/FENCE instructions neither field is a\\nregister read. These false stalls waste cycles\\u2014especially on CoreMark's heavy\\nuse of ADDI, LUI, and JAL immediately after pointer loads\\u2014with negligible\\nLUT cost and no impact on Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit conservatively stalls on any LOAD-to-use sequence where the\\nLOAD's rd matches either rs1 or rs2 of the next instruction, regardless of\\nwhether those fields are actually register reads. For I-type instructions\\n(OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR) the rs2 field encodes an immediate or shamt; for U-type\\n(LUI, AUIPC), J-type (JAL), and SYSTEM/FENCE instructions neither field is a\\nregister read. These false stalls waste cycles\\u2014especially on CoreMark's heavy\\nuse of ADDI, LUI, and JAL immediately after pointer loads\\u2014with negligible\\nLUT cost and no impact on Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add opcode decoding to hazard_unit so the load_use_hazard term only fires\\nwhen the instruction in ID genuinely reads rs1 or rs2. R-type, BRANCH, and\\nSTORE read both; I-type reads only rs1; U/J/FENCE/SYSTEM read neither. The\\nstall_if / stall_id / flush_id logic otherwise stays identical, so no other\\npipeline behavior changes. This removes spurious one-cycle bubbles without\\nlengthening any critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a new 7-bit `if_id_opcode` input. Inside the module compute\\n`uses_rs1` and `uses_rs2` fla...\n  Line 17: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Fold WB mux into MEM stage and remove dead EX/MEM fields\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move the write-back data selection into the MEM stage so that the MEM/WB\\nregister stores only the final rd_wdata (already muxed between load_data and\\nalu_result).  The WB stage then becomes a pure passthrough.  This removes one\\n32-bit mux from the MEM/WB->EX forwarding critical path.  At the same time,\\ndelete the unused branch_taken and branch_target fields from ex_mem_t to\\nreduce area and routing congestion.  No pipeline behaviour changes; IPC stays\\nidentical and Fmax should improve slightly.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove branch_taken ...\n  Line 20: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Precompute forwarding selects in ID stage to shorten EX critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The EX-stage critical path currently includes the forward_unit's 5-bit\\naddress comparison, priority encoder, and operand forwarding mux before the\\nALU.  On a LUT-based FPGA these extra logic levels consume precious\\nnanoseconds.  By shifting the forwarding decision into the ID stage\\u2014where\\nthe same comparison is performed against the instructions currently in EX\\nand MEM\\u2014we register the 2-bit select signals into the ID/EX pipeline\\nregister.  This removes the comparison and control generation from the\\nEX-stage datapath without changing pipeline behaviour or IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX-stage critical path currently includes the forward_unit's 5-bit\\naddress comparison, priority encoder, and operand forwarding mux before the\\nALU.  On a LUT-based FPGA these extra logic levels consume precious\\nnanoseconds.  By shifting the forwarding decision into the ID stage\\u2014where\\nthe same comparison is performed against the instructions currently in EX\\nand MEM\\u2014we register the 2-bit select signals into the ID/EX pipeline\\nregister.  This removes the comparison and control generation from the\\nEX-stage datapath without changing pipeline behaviour or IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add fwd_rs1_sel and fwd_rs2_sel (2 bits each) to the id_ex_t bundle.\\nIn id_stage, compute the forwarding selects combinationally by comparing\\nthe current IF/ID instruction's rs1_addr/rs2_addr against the rd and\\nreg_write flags of the instruction currently in EX (the ID/EX register)\\nand the instruction currently in MEM (ex_mem_w), preserving the same\\nEX/MEM-over-MEM/WB priority and x0 guard that forward_unit uses today.\\nRegister these selects into the ID/EX payload.  In ex_stage, remove the\\nforward_unit input ports and use the precomputed in.fwd_rs1_sel /\\nin.fwd_rs2_sel directly in the operand forwarding muxes.  In...\n  Line 23: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Consolidate ALU multipliers to reduce routing congestion and improve Fmax\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU unconditionally computes three separate 64-bit products\\n(mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) on every cycle even though only one multiply\\nop is ever active.  On FPGA this causes the synthesis tool to infer\\nmultiple wide multipliers and large cross-products that consume DSP\\nblocks and routing resources around the EX stage.  CoreMark is\\nmultiply-heavy (matrix operations), so the ALU multiplier path is\\nlikely on or near the critical path.  By sharing a single 64-bit\\nmultiplier and selecting the signedness mode per-op, we cut the\\nmultiplier area by roughly two thirds and relieve routing\\ncongestion, which should raise median Fmax with zero IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU unconditionally computes three separate 64-bit products\\n(mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) on every cycle even though only one multiply\\nop is ever active.  On FPGA this causes the synthesis tool to infer\\nmultiple wide multipliers and large cross-products that consume DSP\\nblocks and routing resources around the EX stage.  CoreMark is\\nmultiply-heavy (matrix operations), so the ALU multiplier path is\\nlikely on or near the critical path.  By sharing a single 64-bit\\nmultiplier and selecting the signedness mode per-op, we cut the\\nmultiplier area by roughly two thirds and relieve routing\\ncongestion, which should raise median Fmax with zero IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the three always-computed 64-bit products in alu.sv with one\\nshared 64-bit multiplier whose operands are muxed per the active ALU\\nop: unsigned*unsigned for MUL/MULHU, signed*signed for MULH, and\\nsigned*unsigned for MULHSU.  Add a small case block before the\\nmultiplication that selects the correctly-extended a and b inputs.\\nThe DIV/REM family remains combinational (unchanged); only the MUL\\nfamily is touched.  This reduces inferred multi...\n  Line 26: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r9s0\", \"title\": \"Word-load bypass from MEM to EX stage\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Prior MEM-to-EX load bypass failed because the critical path through\\nvariable-shift + sign-extend degraded Fmax enough to cancel IPC gains.\\nWord loads (LW) are the dominant load type in CoreMark pointer chasing\\nand need no byte-alignment or sign-extension. A bypass that forwards\\nraw dmem_rdata straight from MEM to EX for LW-only dependencies keeps\\nthe bypass wire path very short, potentially recovering the IPC gain\\nwithout the Fmax loss that killed the full-width bypass.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior MEM-to-EX load bypass failed because the critical path through\\nvariable-shift + sign-extend degraded Fmax enough to cancel IPC gains.\\nWord loads (LW) are the dominant load type in CoreMark pointer chasing\\nand need no byte-alignment or sign-extension. A bypass that forwards\\nraw dmem_rdata straight from MEM to EX for LW-only dependencies keeps\\nthe bypass wire path very short, potentially recovering the IPC gain\\nwithout the Fmax loss that killed the full-width bypass.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a fast MEM-to-EX forwarding path for word loads only: when a LW is\\nin MEM and the instruction in EX reads its rd, forward io_dmemRData\\ndirectly into the EX operand muxes (encoding 2'd3). Suppress the\\nload-use stall in hazard_unit when the load in EX is a word load\\n(mem_width == 2'd2), so the dependent instruction reaches EX in the\\ncycle the LW is in MEM. Keep the existing 1-cycle stall for byte and\\nhalfword loads. Extend forward_unit to prioritise the new dmem bypass\\nover EX/MEM forwarding when active.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Route io_dmemRData into ex_stage as fwd_dmem_rdata. Compute fwd_dmem_en from ex_mem_w (mem_read && mem_width==word && rd!=0) and feed it to both forward_unit and ex_stage.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"descript...\n  Line 29: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r10s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r10s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r10s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r10s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r10s2'])\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 10}\n\n  Line 32: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r11s0\", \"title\": \"Replace mem_stage barrel shifter with explicit byte-lane selects\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The failed MEM-to-EX load bypass hypothesis identified the variable\\nbarrel shifter (dmem_rdata >> (addr*8)) as part of the critical path\\nthat degraded Fmax enough to cancel IPC gains.  The current mem_stage\\ncomputes this 32-bit shift for every memory operation, even though\\nCoreMark is dominated by word loads (LW) which need no shifting.\\nYosys often infers a full barrel-shifter network for the variable\\nshift pattern, adding unnecessary LUT depth on the dmem read path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The failed MEM-to-EX load bypass hypothesis identified the variable\\nbarrel shifter (dmem_rdata >> (addr*8)) as part of the critical path\\nthat degraded Fmax enough to cancel IPC gains.  The current mem_stage\\ncomputes this 32-bit shift for every memory operation, even though\\nCoreMark is dominated by word loads (LW) which need no shifting.\\nYosys often infers a full barrel-shifter network for the variable\\nshift pattern, adding unnecessary LUT depth on the dmem read path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure mem_stage load-data extraction to eliminate the variable\\nbarrel shifter.  Word loads bypass all formatting (load_data = dmem_rdata).\\nByte loads use an explicit 4:1 byte-select mux on dmem_rdata driven by\\naddr[1:0].  Halfword loads use an explicit 2:1 halfword select.\\nGuard the shift/sign-extend logic behind in.ctrl.mem_read so it is\\ncompletely elided for stores.  This shortens the dmem_rdata-to-MEM/WB\\npath for the dominant LW case and reduces overall LUT depth for\\nbyte/halfword accesses, improving median Fmax with zero IPC impact.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the unconditional 'shifted = dmem_rdata >> (alu_result[1:0]*8)'\\npattern with explicit case-based byte and halfword lane extraction.\\nWord loads by...","metadata":{"matches":12,"truncated":false},"title":"\"category\": \"micro_opt\"","time":{"start":1778747727244,"end":1778747727267}},"id":"prt_e25a05a26001LOcL38NQtjBbPL","sessionID":"ses_1da61a4deffelP4f1gmLU9rBUa","messageID":"msg_e259e5b57001mfG0TaT9u9yU1q"}}
