{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778753868981,"sessionID":"ses_1da08a8d9ffeonKd7w6wlMvkY9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"read:1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","limit":50,"offset":33},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n33: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Add 1-entry non-blocking store buffer to hide dmem backpressure on stores\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit currently stalls the entire pipeline on every !dmem_ready cycle\\nwhenever any memory operation is in MEM. Stores are roughly 20-25% of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream and the cosim model injects ~22% random dmem stalls, so about\\n5% of total cycles are wasted waiting for the store bus. Because stores do not\\nproduce register results, the instructions behind them are almost always\\nindependent and could continue executing if the store were decoupled. A 1-entry\\nstore buffer captures a stalled store and lets the pipeline advance while the\\nbuffer drains asynchronously, converting store-bus stalls into useful execution\\ncycles with minimal area and no new long combinational paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit currently stalls the entire pipeline on every !dmem_ready cycle\\nwhenever any memory operation is in MEM. Stores are roughly 20-25% of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream and the cosim model injects ~22% random dmem stalls, so about\\n5% of total cycles are wasted waiting for the store bus. Because stores do not\\nproduce register results, the instructions behind them are almost always\\nindependent and could continue executing if the store were decoupled. A 1-entry\\nstore buffer captures a stalled store and lets the pipeline advance while the\\nbuffer drains asynchronously, converting store-bus stalls into useful execution\\ncycles with minimal area and no new long combinational paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a 1-entry store buffer between the MEM stage and the external dmem interface.\\nWhen a store reaches MEM and dmem_ready is low, the buffer captures the address,\\ndata, and byte mask instead of asserting a global stall. The buffer continuously\\nretries the write whenever dmem_ready is high. The top-level dmem outputs are\\nmuxed between the buffer (when valid) and the live M... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n34: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"Add 8-entry loop predictor for backward branch exits\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit BHT already captures forward branch directions and\\nbackward-taken bias, but it cannot avoid mispredicting the final iteration\\nof every loop (predicted taken, actually not-taken). CoreMark contains\\nmany small inner loops (list traversal, matrix rows, CRC updates) where\\nthis exit misprediction wastes cycles. A dedicated loop predictor learns\\nthe trip count of individual backward branches and predicts not-taken on\\nthe last iteration, removing the only remaining systematic direction\\nmispredictions with only ~100 flops and no wider BHT mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit BHT already captures forward branch directions and\\nbackward-taken bias, but it cannot avoid mispredicting the final iteration\\nof every loop (predicted taken, actually not-taken). CoreMark contains\\nmany small inner loops (list traversal, matrix rows, CRC updates) where\\nthis exit misprediction wastes cycles. A dedicated loop predictor learns\\nthe trip count of individual backward branches and predicts not-taken on\\nthe last iteration, removing the only remaining systematic direction\\nmispredictions with only ~100 flops and no wider BHT mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an 8-entry direct-mapped loop predictor table to the IF stage.\\nEach entry stores a tag, a trained iteration length, a speculative\\ndown-counter, and a 1-bit confidence flag.\\nWhen a backward branch is fetched, if the entry is valid, tag matches,\\nand confidence is high, the predictor overrides the BHT:\\n  - down-counter > 0  \\u2192 predict taken and decrement the counter.\\n  - down-counter == 0 \\u2192 predict not-taken.\\nIn EX, resolved backward branches update the table:\\n  - During training (confidence low) the table counts taken outcomes;\\n    the first not-taken exit stores the count as the trained length\\n    and sets confidence high.\\n  - On a correct ex... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n35: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r12s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core_pkg.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/id_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/if_stage.sv']\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 12}\n36: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r12s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-002-r12s1 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r12s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r12s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r12s2'])\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 12}\n37: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r12s2\", \"title\": \"Add 4-entry return-address stack for JALR prediction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current predictor correctly handles conditional branches (32-entry BHT)\\nand JAL (always-taken), but JALR is never predicted. Every function return\\ncauses a 2-cycle redirect bubble in EX. CoreMark contains many small function\\ncalls; a return-address stack predicts return targets with near-perfect\\naccuracy for a tiny area cost (~130 flops), improving IPC without degrading\\nFmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current predictor correctly handles conditional branches (32-entry BHT)\\nand JAL (always-taken), but JALR is never predicted. Every function return\\ncauses a 2-cycle redirect bubble in EX. CoreMark contains many small function\\ncalls; a return-address stack predicts return targets with near-perfect\\naccuracy for a tiny area cost (~130 flops), improving IPC without degrading\\nFmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 4-entry return-address stack (RAS) to the IF stage. Push PC+4 on\\nany JAL or JALR call (rd = x1/x5). Pop the RAS and predict taken on any\\nJALR return (rd = x0, rs1 = x1/x5). Thread the predicted target through a\\nnew `pred_target` field in the IF/ID and ID/EX bundles. In EX stage,\\ncompare the actual JALR target with `pred_target`; only redirect on\\nmispredict or when JALR was not predicted. This eliminates the redirect\\nbubble on correct function returns.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `pred_target` field to `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t` structs.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 4-entry RAS with push/pop control; use RAS top as predicted target for JALR returns; drive `out.pred_target`.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Thread `in.pred_target` into the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace unconditional JALR redirect with mispredict detection using `in.... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n38: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r13s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r13s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r13s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r13s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r13s2'])\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 13}\n39: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r13s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-002-r13s1 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r13s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r13s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r13s2'])\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 13}\n40: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r13s2\", \"title\": \"Hash-mix higher PC bits into 32-entry BHT index to reduce aliasing\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter BHT is the proven sweet spot for\\nthis core, delivering a +7.3% fitness gain. A follow-up attempt to grow\\nthe table to 128 entries regressed -3% because the wider read mux hurt\\nFmax, while gshare global-history variants regressed due to history\\nstaleness. The remaining occasional forward-branch mispredictions may\\nstem from destructive aliasing among branches that share the low five\\nPC bits. A zero-cost hash that XORs higher PC bits into the index\\nscatters colliding branches without enlarging the array or adding any\\nnew state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter BHT is the proven sweet spot for\\nthis core, delivering a +7.3% fitness gain. A follow-up attempt to grow\\nthe table to 128 entries regressed -3% because the wider read mux hurt\\nFmax, while gshare global-history variants regressed due to history\\nstaleness. The remaining occasional forward-branch mispredictions may\\nstem from destructive aliasing among branches that share the low five\\nPC bits. A zero-cost hash that XORs higher PC bits into the index\\nscatters colliding branches without enlarging the array or adding any\\nnew state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the proven 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter table unchanged, but\\nchange both the read index and the write-back index from pc[6:2] to\\npc[6:2] ^ pc[11:7]. In the IF stage this mixes bits 7-11 of the PC\\ninto the existing 5-bit index, reducing the chance that two branches\\nwhose lower five bits collide map to the same counter. In the EX stage\\nthe update index uses in.pc[6:2] ^ in.pc[11:7] so the counter write\\nhits exactly the entry that was read during fetch. The combinational\\ncost is a single 5-bit XOR, which Yosys will absorb into the existing\\nLUT fabric with negligible Fmax impact. No new flops, pipeline bundles,\\nor cont... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n41: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r14s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r14s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r14s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r14s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r14s2'])\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 14}\n42: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r14s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-002-r14s1 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r14s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r14s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r14s2'])\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 14}\n43: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r14s2\", \"title\": \"Add single global loop-exit predictor to eliminate BHT loop-exit mispredictions\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit BHT saturates to strongly-taken for backward branches,\\nso it mispredicts the final iteration of every inner loop. CoreMark is\\nloop-heavy (list traversal, matrix rows, CRC) and these exit mispredictions\\nare the last systematic control bubble. A prior 8-entry tagged loop\\npredictor regressed because its tag-CAM and per-entry state machines\\nhurt Fmax. A single global loop counter needs only ~45 flops and one\\n32-bit PC comparator, giving loop-exit prediction with negligible\\ncombinational overhead.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit BHT saturates to strongly-taken for backward branches,\\nso it mispredicts the final iteration of every inner loop. CoreMark is\\nloop-heavy (list traversal, matrix rows, CRC) and these exit mispredictions\\nare the last systematic control bubble. A prior 8-entry tagged loop\\npredictor regressed because its tag-CAM and per-entry state machines\\nhurt Fmax. A single global loop counter needs only ~45 flops and one\\n32-bit PC comparator, giving loop-exit prediction with negligible\\ncombinational overhead.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single global loop-exit predictor to the IF stage. It keeps one\\nloop_pc (32-bit), one loop_len (8-bit), one loop_cnt (8-bit), and a\\nvalid bit. When the fetched PC matches loop_pc and the branch is backward,\\nthe predictor overrides the BHT: loop_cnt>0 predicts taken (and decrements),\\nloop_cnt==0 predicts not-taken. In EX, training is automatic: on every\\nbackward branch that matches loop_pc, increment a training counter while\\ntaken; on the first not-taken exit capture the count as loop_len and\\nreload loop_cnt. A new backward-branch mispredict in EX clears valid so\\nthe predictor retrains safely. For all other branches the existing BHT\\nand JAL logic remain unchanged. This removes the 2-cycle bubble on every\\ncorre... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(End of file - total 43 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Add 1-entry non-blocking store buffer to hide dmem backpressure on stores\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit currently stalls the entire pipeline on every !dmem_ready cycle\\nwhenever any memory operation is in MEM. Stores are roughly 20-25% of 