{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778754084742,"sessionID":"ses_1da08a8d9ffeonKd7w6wlMvkY9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"bash:8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -A5 '\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r7s0\"' /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","description":"Check broken reason for forwarding precompute"},"output":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Precompute forwarding selects in ID stage to shorten EX critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The EX-stage critical path currently includes the forward_unit's 5-bit\\naddress comparison, priority encoder, and operand forwarding mux before the\\nALU.  On a LUT-based FPGA these extra logic levels consume precious\\nnanoseconds.  By shifting the forwarding decision into the ID stage\\u2014where\\nthe same comparison is performed against the instructions currently in EX\\nand MEM\\u2014we register the 2-bit select signals into the ID/EX pipeline\\nregister.  This removes the comparison and control generation from the\\nEX-stage datapath without changing pipeline behaviour or IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX-stage critical path currently includes the forward_unit's 5-bit\\naddress comparison, priority encoder, and operand forwarding mux before the\\nALU.  On a LUT-based FPGA these extra logic levels consume precious\\nnanoseconds.  By shifting the forwarding decision into the ID stage\\u2014where\\nthe same comparison is performed against the instructions currently in EX\\nand MEM\\u2014we register the 2-bit select signals into the ID/EX pipeline\\nregister.  This removes the comparison and control generation from the\\nEX-stage datapath without changing pipeline behaviour or IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add fwd_rs1_sel and fwd_rs2_sel (2 bits each) to the id_ex_t bundle.\\nIn id_stage, compute the forwarding selects combinationally by comparing\\nthe current IF/ID instruction's rs1_addr/rs2_addr against the rd and\\nreg_write flags of the instruction currently in EX (the ID/EX register)\\nand the instruction currently in MEM (ex_mem_w), preserving the same\\nEX/MEM-over-MEM/WB priority and x0 guard that forward_unit uses today.\\nRegister these selects into the ID/EX payload.  In ex_stage, remove the\\nforward_unit input ports and use the precomputed in.fwd_rs1_sel /\\nin.fwd_rs2_sel directly in the operand forwarding muxes.  In core.sv,\\nwire ex_mem_w.rd and ex_mem_w.ctrl.reg_write into id_stage for the\\nprecomputation, remove the forward_unit instantiation, and connect the\\nprecomputed selects straight through to ex_stage.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_rs1_sel [1:0] and fwd_rs2_sel [1:0] fields to the id_ex_t struct.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add inputs ex_mem_rd [4:0] and ex_mem_reg_write. Compute next_fwd_rs1/next_fwd_rs2 combinationally by comparing in.instr[19:15] and in.instr[24:20] against reg_q.rd and ex_mem_rd with the same write-enable / x0 guards used by forward_unit. Register the resulting 2-bit values into the ID/EX payload.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the fwd_rs1_sel and fwd_rs2_sel input ports. Use in.fwd_rs1_sel and in.fwd_rs2_sel directly in the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes instead of the former forward_unit-driven selects.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire ex_mem_w.rd and ex_mem_w.ctrl.reg_write into the id_stage instance for precomputation.  Remove the forward_unit instantiation and its wires.  Connect id_ex_w.fwd_rs1_sel and id_ex_w.fwd_rs2_sel directly to ex_stage.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_rs1_sel [1:0] and fwd_rs2_sel [1:0] fields to the id_ex_t struct.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add inputs ex_mem_rd [4:0] and ex_mem_reg_write. Compute next_fwd_rs1/next_fwd_rs2 combinationally by comparing in.instr[19:15] and in.instr[24:20] against reg_q.rd and ex_mem_rd with the same write-enable / x0 guards used by forward_unit. Register the resulting 2-bit values into the ID/EX payload.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the fwd_rs1_sel and fwd_rs2_sel input ports. Use in.fwd_rs1_sel and in.fwd_rs2_sel directly in the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes instead of the former forward_unit-driven selects.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire ex_mem_w.rd and ex_mem_w.ctrl.reg_write into the id_stage instance for precomputation.  Remove the forward_unit instantiation and its wires.  Connect id_ex_w.fwd_rs1_sel and id_ex_w.fwd_rs2_sel directly to ex_stage.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"formal_failed: reg_ch0\\n: pass\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_sw_ch0] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_sw_ch0] summary: Elapsed process time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_sw_ch0] summary: engine_0 (smtbmc bitwuzla) returned pass\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_sw_ch0] summary: engine_0 did not produce any traces\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_sw_ch0] DONE (PASS, rc=0)\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_xori_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Checking assertions in step 20..\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_xori_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Status: passed\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_xori_ch0] engine_0: finished (returncode=0)\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_xori_ch0] engine_0: Status returned by engine: pass\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_xori_ch0] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:00 (0)\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_xori_ch0] summary: Elapsed process time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_xori_ch0] summary: engine_0 (smtbmc bitwuzla) returned pass\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_xori_ch0] summary: engine_0 did not produce any traces\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_xori_ch0] DONE (PASS, rc=0)\\n\\nFormal: 52 passed, 1 failed\\nFailed: reg_ch0\\n\\n--- reg_ch0/logfile.txt (last 30 lines) ---\\nSBY  2:57:53 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 9..\\nSBY  2:57:53 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 10..\\nSBY  2:57:53 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 11..\\nSBY  2:57:53 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 12..\\nSBY  2:57:53 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 13..\\nSBY  2:57:53 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 14..\\nSBY  2:57:53 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 15..\\nSBY  2:57:53 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 16..\\nSBY  2:57:53 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 17..\\nSBY  2:57:53 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 18..\\nSBY  2:57:53 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 19..\\nSBY  2:57:53 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Checking assumptions in step 20..\\nSBY  2:57:54 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:01  Checking assertions in step 20..\\nSBY  2:58:03 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:10  BMC failed!\\nSBY  2:58:03 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:10  Value for anyconst rvfi_testbench.insn_order (rvfi_reg_check.sv:19.24-19.34): 15\\nSBY  2:58:03 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:10  Value for anyconst rvfi_testbench.register_index (rvfi_reg_check.sv:20.23-20.37): 28\\nSBY  2:58:03 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:10  Assert failed in rvfi_testbench: rvfi_reg_check.sv:44.6-44.59 (_witness_.check_flatten_checker_inst__assert_rvfi_reg_check_sv_44_62)\\nSBY  2:58:03 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:10  Writing trace to VCD file: engine_0/trace.vcd\\nSBY  2:58:03 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:10  Writing trace to Verilog testbench: engine_0/trace_tb.v\\nSBY  2:58:03 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:10  Writing trace to constraints file: engine_0/trace.smtc\\nSBY  2:58:03 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:10  Writing trace to Yosys witness file: engine_0/trace.yw\\nSBY  2:58:03 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:10  Status: failed\\nSBY  2:58:03 [reg_ch0] engine_0: finished (returncode=1)\\nSBY  2:58:03 [reg_ch0] engine_0: Status returned by engine: FAIL\\nSBY  2:58:03 [reg_ch0] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:11 (11)\\nSBY  2:58:03 [reg_ch0] summary: Elapsed process time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:08 (8)\\nSBY  2:58:03 [reg_ch0] summary: engine_0 (smtbmc bitwuzla) returned FAIL\\nSBY  2:58:03 [reg_ch0] summary: counterexample trace: reg_ch0/engine_0/trace.vcd\\nSBY  2:58:03 [reg_ch0] summary:   failed assertion rvfi_testbench._witness_.check_flatten_checker_inst__assert_rvfi_reg_check_sv_44_62 at rvfi_reg_check.sv:44.6-44.59 step 20\\nSBY  2:58:03 [reg_ch0] DONE (FAIL, rc=0)\\n\\nFull run log: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260514-001-r7s0/formal/last_run-63200.log\\nPer-check logs in: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260514-001-r7s0/formal/riscv-formal/cores/bench-63200/checks/<check>/logfile.txt\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 7, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the\\nSystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX\\nstage alone consumes over 6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is\\ndominated by arithmetic primitives. Division is essentially unused in\\nCoreMark, yet the combinational divider consumes massive area and\\nrouting resources that congest the fabric around the critical ALU adder\\npath, limiting Fmax. A prior attempt at this change failed because the\\ndivider state machine lacked a proper IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM with a\\n'started' bit, causing deadlock. With a correct FSM implementation,\\nremoving the combinational divider should relieve routing congestion\\nand raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the\\nSystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX\\nstage alone consumes over 6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is\\ndominated by arithmetic primitives. Division is essentially unused in\\nCoreMark, yet the combinational divider consumes massive area and\\nrouting resources that congest the fabric around the critical ALU adder\\npath, limiting Fmax. A prior attempt at this change failed because the\\ndivider state machine lacked a proper IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM with a\\n'started' bit, causing deadlock. With a correct FSM implementation,\\nremoving the combinational divider should relieve routing congestion\\nand raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extract DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of the combinational ALU into a new\\n`divider.sv` module that performs restoring division in 33 cycles.\\nThe divider MUST use a proper 3-state FSM (IDLE, RUNNING, DONE) with\\na registered 'started' bit:\\n  - IDLE:  waiting for start pulse. busy=0, done=0.\\n  - RUNNING: counting down 32 bits. busy=1, done=0.\\n  - DONE: result valid for one cycle. busy=0, done=1. Next clock\\n    returns to IDLE automatically.\\nIn `ex_stage`, detect divide ops and assert `div_start` for exactly\\none cycle when the divider is in IDLE. The hazard unit stalls IF,\\nID, and EX/MEM while `div_busy` (= RUNNING) is high. Because `busy`\\nis LOW in the DONE state, the EX/MEM register naturally captures the\\ndivider result on the done cycle and the next instruction can enter\\nEX on the following cycle. The main ALU keeps all I-type ops and the\\nmultiplier path. This structural change shrinks the EX stage\\nsignificantly, frees routing capacity on the critical path, and\\nshould improve median Fmax without hurting CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and all combinational divide/rem\\nlogic. Keep the multiplier paths and the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS\\nbranch unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative restoring divider with IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM.\\nInputs: clock, reset, start, dividend[31:0], divisor[31:0],\\nop[3:0] selecting DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU. Outputs: result[31:0],\\nbusy, done. 33-cycle latency. busy is high only in RUNNING.\\ndone is high for one cycle in DONE. Returns to IDLE on next\\nclock edge. Handles all RV32M corner cases (divide by zero,\\nINT_MIN/-1).\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide ops from in.ctrl.alu_op. Route operands to the\\ndivider and assert div_start when the divider is idle.\\nCapture divider result into ex_mem_w.alu_result when div_done\\nis high. Stall EX/MEM via hazard_unit during div_busy.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add div_busy input. Extend stall_if, stall_id, and stall_ex_mem\\nto freeze the entire pipeline while div_busy is high. Do not\\nassert flush_id during div_busy; hold the pipeline state.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate divider module. Wire div_busy into hazard_unit.\\nConnect divider inputs from id_ex_w operands. No top-level IO\\nchanges.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and all combinational divide/rem\\nlogic. Keep the multiplier paths and the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS\\nbranch unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative restoring divider with IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM.\\nInputs: clock, reset, start, dividend[31:0], divisor[31:0],\\nop[3:0] selecting DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU. Outputs: result[31:0],\\nbusy, done. 33-cycle latency. busy is high only in RUNNING.\\ndone is high for one cycle in DONE. Returns to IDLE on next\\nclock edge. Handles all RV32M corner cases (divide by zero,\\nINT_MIN/-1).\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide ops from in.ctrl.alu_op. Route operands to the\\ndivider and assert div_start when the divider is idle.\\nCapture divider result into ex_mem_w.alu_result when div_done\\nis high. Stall EX/MEM via hazard_unit during div_busy.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add div_busy input. Extend stall_if, stall_id, and stall_ex_mem\\nto freeze the entire pipeline while div_busy is high. Do not\\nassert flush_id during div_busy; hold the pipeline state.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate divider module. Wire div_busy into hazard_unit.\\nConnect divider inputs from id_ex_w operands. No top-level IO\\nchanges.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T06:07:59.336648Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 7, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/alu.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/test/test_alu.py', 'cores/bench/test/test_pipeline.py', 'cores/bench/rtl/divider.sv', 'cores/bench/test/test_divider.py']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r7s2.yaml\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": fals