a larger array, and fixes the staleness that broke the first gshare.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr_snapshot field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0. Compute BHT read index as pc[6:2] ^ ghr. Drive the current ghr value into out.ghr_snapshot. On non-stalled, non-flushed cycles where the fetched instruction is a conditional branch, speculatively update ghr <= {ghr[3:0], predict_taken}. Add a new input port ghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en; when restore_en is asserted on redirect from EX, reload ghr with ghr_restore.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr_snapshot into the ID/EX register so it reaches EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr_snapshot so the counter update writes the exact entry that was read during fetch. Add output ports ghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en. Drive ghr_restore = {in.ghr_snapshot[3:0], branch_taken} and assert ghr_restore_en whenever redirect is asserted for a conditional branch (in.ctrl.is_branch). JAL/JALR redirects must not assert restore_en.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new ghr_restore/ghr_restore_en signals from ex_stage back to if_stage.\"}]}}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Consolidate ALU multipliers to reduce routing congestion and improve Fmax\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU unconditionally computes three separate 64-bit products\\n(mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) on every cycle even though only one multiply\\nop is ever active.  On FPGA this causes the synthesis tool to infer\\nmultiple wide multipliers and large cross-products that consume DSP\\nblocks and routing resources around the EX stage.  CoreMark is\\nmultiply-heavy (matrix operations), so the ALU multiplier path is\\nlikely on or near the critical path.  By sharing a single 64-bit\\nmultiplier and selecting the signedness mode per-op, we cut the\\nmultiplier area by roughly two thirds and relieve routing\\ncongestion, which should raise median Fmax with zero IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU unconditionally computes three separate 64-bit products\\n(mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) on every cycle even though only one multiply\\nop is ever active.  On FPGA this causes the synthesis tool to infer\\nmultiple wide multipliers and large cross-products that consume DSP\\nblocks and routing resources around the EX stage.  CoreMark is\\nmultiply-heavy (matrix operations), so the ALU multiplier path is\\nlikely on or near the critical path.  By sharing a single 64-bit\\nmultiplier and selecting the signedness mode per-op, we cut the\\nmultiplier area by roughly two thirds and relieve routing\\ncongestion, which should raise median Fmax with zero IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the three always-computed 64-bit products in alu.sv with one\\nshared 64-bit multiplier whose operands are muxed per the active ALU\\nop: unsigned*unsigned for MUL/MULHU, signed*signed for MULH, and\\nsigned*unsigned for MULHSU.  Add a small case block before the\\nmultiplication that selects the correctly-extended a and b inputs.\\nThe DIV/REM family remains combinational (unchanged); only the MUL\\nfamily is touched.  This reduces inferred multiplier count from three\\nto one, shrinking EX-stage area and easing nextpnr placement.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the three always-on 64-bit product wires (mul_ss, mul_uu,\\nmul_su).  Add a shared 64-bit `mul_result` wire.  Precede the\\nmultiply with a combinational mux that selects the sign-extended\\noperands based on the current ALU op, then assign mul_result once.\\nUpdate the MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU case arms to pick the correct\\nhigh or low half of mul_result.  Keep the ALTOPS branch intact.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the three always-on 64-bit product wires (mul_ss, mul_uu,\\nmul_su).  Add a shared 64-bit `mul_result` wire.  Precede the\\nmultiply with a combinational mux that selects the sign-extended\\noperands based on the current ALU op, then assign mul_result once.\\nUpdate the MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU case arms to pick the correct\\nhigh or low half of mul_result.  Keep the ALTOPS branch intact.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T06:38:10.504767Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 8}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/alu.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 8}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r8s2\", \"title\": \"(slot 2 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-003-r8s2 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r8s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r8s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r8s2'])\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 8}\n","metadata":{"output":"...\n\nn EX\\nand MEM\\u2014we register the 2-bit select signals into the ID/EX pipeline\\nregister.  This removes the comparison and control generation from the\\nEX-stage datapath without changing pipeline behaviour or IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX-stage critical path currently includes the forward_unit's 5-bit\\naddress comparison, priority encoder, and operand forwarding mux before the\\nALU.  On a LUT-based FPGA these extra logic levels consume precious\\nnanoseconds.  By shifting the forwarding decision into the ID stage\\u2014where\\nthe same comparison is performed against the instructions currently in EX\\nand MEM\\u2014we register the 2-bit select signals into the ID/EX pipeline\\nregister.  This removes the comparison and control generation from the\\nEX-stage datapath without changing pipeline behaviour or IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add fwd_rs1_sel and fwd_rs2_sel (2 bits each) to the id_ex_t bundle.\\nIn id_stage, compute the forwarding selects combinationally by comparing\\nthe current IF/ID instruction's rs1_addr/rs2_addr against the rd and\\nreg_write flags of the instruction currently in EX (the ID/EX register)\\nand the instruction currently in MEM (ex_mem_w), preserving the same\\nEX/MEM-over-MEM/WB priority and x0 guard that forward_unit uses today.\\nRegister these selects into the ID/EX payload.  In ex_stage, remove the\\nforward_unit input ports and use the precomputed in.fwd_rs1_sel /\\nin.fwd_rs2_sel directly in the operand forwarding muxes.  In core.sv,\\nwire ex_mem_w.rd and ex_mem_w.ctrl.reg_write into id_stage for the\\nprecomputation, remove the forward_unit instantiation, and connect the\\nprecomputed selects straight through to ex_stage.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_rs1_sel [1:0] and fwd_rs2_sel [1:0] fields to the id_ex_t struct.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add inputs ex_mem_rd [4:0] and ex_mem_reg_write. Compute next_fwd_rs1/next_fwd_r