{"type":"text","timestamp":1778732107948,"sessionID":"ses_1db556a4affe7hShpYdghPERa0","part":{"id":"prt_e24b1fce1002J1gYhInse1su6J","messageID":"msg_e24b1eceb001UdzFr4zZt1RGCB","sessionID":"ses_1db556a4affe7hShpYdghPERa0","type":"text","text":"Done. Wrote the `micro_opt` hypothesis to:\n\n`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-001-r5s0.yaml`\n\n**Summary:** Opcode-aware hazard detection. The current hazard unit stalls the pipeline whenever a LOAD’s `rd` matches the next instruction’s `instr[19:15]` or `instr[24:20]`, even when those bits encode immediates (I‑type) or destination registers (U/J types) rather than source registers. By decoding the opcode in `hazard_unit.sv` and qualifying the load‑use check with per‑opcode `uses_rs1` / `uses_rs2` flags, we remove spurious one‑cycle stalls on ADDI, LUI, JAL, etc. This is a pure IPC win with negligible area and no Fmax risk.","time":{"start":1778732104929,"end":1778732107947}}}
