|\n27:       Remove branch_taken and branch_target from ex_mem_t (dead fields).\n28:       Replace alu_result and read_data in mem_wb_t with a single rd_wdata\n29:       field that holds the final register write data.\n30:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n31:     description: |\n32:       Stop writing branch_taken and branch_target into the EX/MEM register.\n33:       All other fields remain unchanged.\n34:   - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n35:     description: |\n36:       Compute rd_wdata = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? load_data : in.alu_result\n37:       combinationally and store it in the MEM/WB register as reg_q.rd_wdata.\n38:       Remove the now-redundant alu_result and read_data assignments.\n39:   - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n40:     description: |\n41:       Replace the mem_to_reg mux with a passthrough: w_data = in.rd_wdata.\n42:       w_en and w_addr logic stays identical.\n\n(End of file - total 42 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260514-001-r6s0\ntitle: Fold WB mux into MEM stage and remove dead EX/MEM fields\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\n  mux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\n  wb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\n  32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\n  EX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\n  between timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\n  branch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\n  downstream, wasting ~33 flops.\nhypothesis: |\n  Move the write-back data selection into the MEM stage so that the MEM/WB\n  register stores only the final rd_wdata (already muxed between load_data and\n  alu_result).  The WB stage then becomes a pure passthrough.  This removes one\n  32-bit mux from the MEM/WB->EX forwarding critical path.  At the same time,\n  delete the unused branch_taken and branch_target fields from ex_mem_t to\n  reduce area and routing congestion.  No pipeline behaviour changes; IPC stays\n  identical and Fmax should improve slightly.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-001-r6s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778733660410,"end":1778733660418}},"id":"prt_e24c9b5ca001goDN8LUaMCPziJ","sessionID":"ses_1db419843ffeQUi9B9VyBNpPkX","messageID":"msg_e24c98fcf001Qsx4dxNdNijV0X"}}
