{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778736011676,"sessionID":"ses_1db13f4edffe6UBI9bfWCBljE1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"bash:2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep '\"category\": \"micro_opt\"' /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | head -n 20","description":"Grep micro_opt entries in log"},"output":"{\"id\": \"baseline-bench-4217612\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 282.82, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9563, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [128.72, 127.03, 123.02], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T01:36:12.712654Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r1s0.yaml\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"schema_error: while scanning a simple key\\n  in \\\"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r1s0.yaml\\\", line 6, column 1\\ncould not find expected ':'\\n  in \\\"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r1s0.yaml\\\", line 7, column 1\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 1}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"MEM-to-EX load bypass to eliminate load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline stalls for one cycle on every load-use hazard\\nbecause it can only forward loaded data from MEM/WB, not from the MEM stage\\nitself.  CoreMark pointer-chasing and array-index patterns frequently emit a\\nLOAD followed immediately by a dependent ALU or STORE.  Eliminating the\\nload-use bubble improves IPC with no extra pipeline stages or tables.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline stalls for one cycle on every load-use hazard\\nbecause it can only forward loaded data from MEM/WB, not from the MEM stage\\nitself.  CoreMark pointer-chasing and array-index patterns frequently emit a\\nLOAD followed immediately by a dependent ALU or STORE.  Eliminating the\\nload-use bubble improves IPC with no extra pipeline stages or tables.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a combinational bypass from mem_stage's load_data output back to the\\nEX-stage operand muxes.  Extend the forwarding_unit so that when EX/MEM\\ncontains a LOAD whose rd matches an EX-stage rs, it selects the new bypass\\npath (encoding 2'b11).  Remove the load_use_hazard stall from hazard_unit;\\nthe bypass makes it unnecessary.  All other stalls (imem/dmem backpressure,\\nredirect flush) remain unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 7, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the load_use_hazard term from stall_if, stall_id, and flush_id. The MEM\\u2192EX bypass eliminates the need to stall the pipeline for load-use.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_mem_mem_read input.  When EX/MEM has a matching rd and ex_mem_mem_read is high, drive fwd_rs1/fwd_rs2 = 2'b11 to select the MEM-stage load bypass instead of the ALU-result path.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_mem_load [31:0] input.  Extend the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes to select fwd_mem_load when the forwarding select is 2'b11.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Expose the combinational load_data signal as a new output port load_data_fwd [31:0] so core.sv can route it back to ex_stage.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire mem_stage.load_data_fwd to ex_stage.fwd_mem_load.  Connect ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read to forward_unit.ex_mem_mem_read.  Update the hazard_unit instantiation to reflect removed load-use stall logic.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 7, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the load_use_hazard term from stall_if, stall_id, and flush_id. The MEM\\u2192EX bypass eliminates the need to stall the pipeline for load-use.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_mem_mem_read input.  When EX/MEM has a matching rd and ex_mem_mem_read is high, drive fwd_rs1/fwd_rs2 = 2'b11 to select the MEM-stage load bypass instead of the ALU-result path.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_mem_load [31:0] input.  Extend the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes to select fwd_mem_load when the forwarding select is 2'b11.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Expose the combinational load_data signal as a new output port load_data_fwd [31:0] so core.sv can route it back to ex_stage.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire mem_stage.load_data_fwd to ex_stage.fwd_mem_load.  Connect ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read to forward_unit.ex_mem_mem_read.  Update the hazard_unit instantiation to reflect removed load-use stall logic.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 324.08, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 14.59, \"fmax_mhz\": 138.05, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4259699, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10189, \"ff\": 1874, \"seeds\": [133.46, 138.05, 148.35], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T02:41:03.769480Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 2, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/test/test_pipeline.py']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Eliminate false load-use stalls via opcode-aware hazard detection\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current hazard_unit conservatively checks both rs1 (instr[19:15]) and rs2\\n(instr[24:20]) of the instruction in ID against the LOAD's rd in EX,\\nregardless of whether the instruction actually reads those fields as registers.\\nFor I-type (OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR), U-type, and J-type instructions, the rs2\\nfield is an immediate/shamt, not a register address. A LOAD followed by an\\nADDI where imm[4:0] happens to match the LOAD's rd currently triggers a\\nspurious one-cycle stall. CoreMark uses small immediate values extensively,\\nso false stalls on common x1-x5 register numbers are likely frequent.\\nEliminating these false stalls improves IPC with negligible LUT/Fmax cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current hazard_unit conservatively checks both rs1 (instr[19:15]) and rs2\\n(instr[24:20]) of the instruction in ID against the LOAD's rd in EX,\\nregardless of whether the instruction actually reads those fields as registers.\\nFor I-type (OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR), U-type, and J-type instructions, the rs2\\nfield is an immediate/shamt, not a register address. A LOAD followed by an\\nADDI where imm[4:0] happens to match the LOAD's rd currently triggers a\\nspurious one-cycle stall. CoreMark uses small immediate values extensively,\\nso false stalls on common x1-x5 register numbers are likely frequent.\\nEliminating these false stalls improves IPC with negligible LUT/Fmax cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add opcode decoding to hazard_unit so load-use detection only fires when\\nthe instruction in ID actually reads rs1/rs2 as registers. R-type, I-type\\n(OP-IMM/LOAD/JALR), S-type, and B-type use rs1; R-type, S-type, and B-type\\nuse rs2. U-type and J-type use neither. This removes false stalls without\\naltering pipeline structure or lengthening critical paths.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add opcode input and uses_rs1/uses_rs2 qualification to the load_use_hazard check.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire if_id_w.instr[6:0] to the hazard_unit's new opcode input.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add opcode input and uses_rs1/uses_rs2 qualification to the load_use_hazard check.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire if_id_w.instr[6:0] to the hazard_unit's new opcode input.\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"cosim_failed: selftest.elf\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 3, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r4s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r4s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r4s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r4s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r4s2'])\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 4}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Eliminate false load-use stalls via opcode-aware hazard detection\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit conservatively stalls on any LOAD-to-use sequence where the\\nLOAD's rd matches either rs1 or rs2 of the next instruction, regardless of\\nwhether those fields are actually register reads. For I-type instructions\\n(OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR) the rs2 field encodes an immediate or shamt; for U-type\\n(LUI, AUIPC), J-type (JAL), and SYSTEM/FENCE instructions neither field is a\\nregister read. These false stalls waste cycles\\u2014especially on CoreMark's heavy\\nuse of ADDI, LUI, and JAL immediately after pointer loads\\u2014with negligible\\nLUT cost and no impact on Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit conservatively stalls on any LOAD-to-use sequence where the\\nLOAD's rd matches either rs1 or rs2 of the next instruction, regardless of\\nwhether those fields are actually register reads. For I-type instructions\\n(OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR) the rs2 field encodes an immediate or shamt; for U-type\\n(LUI, AUIPC), J-type (JAL), and SYSTEM/FENCE instructions neither field is a\\nregister read. These false stalls waste cycles\\u2014especially on CoreMark's heavy\\nuse of ADDI, LUI, and JAL immediately after pointer loads\\u2014with negligible\\nLUT cost and no impact on Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add opcode decoding to hazard_unit so the load_use_hazard term only fires\\nwhen the instruction in ID genuinely reads rs1 or rs2. R-type, BRANCH, and\\nSTORE read both; I-type reads only rs1; U/J/FENCE/SYSTEM read neither. The\\nstall_if / stall_id / flush_id logic otherwise stays identical, so no other\\npipeline behavior changes. This removes spurious one-cycle bubbles without\\nlengthening any critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a new 7-bit `if_id_opcode` input. Inside the module compute\\n`uses_rs1` and `uses_rs2` flags from the opcode (R/BRANCH/STORE = both;\\nI-type = rs1 only; U/J/FENCE/SYSTEM = neither). Qualify the\\n`load_use_hazard` expression with these flags so that matches on\\nimmediate fields no longer stall the pipeline.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire `if_id_w.instr[6:0]` into the new `if_id_opcode` port of the\\n`hazard_unit` instance. No other top-level signals are modified.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a new 7-bit `if_id_opcode` input. Inside the module compute\\n`uses_rs1` and `uses_rs2` flags from the opcode (R/BRANCH/STORE = both;\\nI-type = rs1 only; U/J/FENCE/SYSTEM = neither). Qualify the\\n`load_use_hazard` expression with these flags so that matches on\\nimmediate fields no longer stall the pipeline.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire `if_id_w.instr[6:0]` into the new `if_id_opcode` port of the\\n`hazard_unit` instance. No other top-level signals are modified.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:24:18.728881Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 5, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/test/test_pipeline.py']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Fold WB mux into MEM stage and remove dead EX/MEM fields\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move the write-back data selection into the MEM stage so that the MEM/WB\\nregister stores only the final rd_wdata (already muxed between load_data and\\nalu_result).  The WB stage then becomes a pure passthrough.  This removes one\\n32-bit mux from the MEM/WB->EX forwarding critical path.  At the same time,\\ndelete the unused branch_taken and branch_target fields from ex_mem_t to\\nreduce area and routing congestion.  No pipeline behaviour changes; IPC stays\\nidentical and Fmax should improve slightly.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove branch_taken and branch_target from ex_mem_t (dead fields).\\nReplace alu_result and read_data in mem_wb_t with a single rd_wdata\\nfield that holds the final register write data.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Stop writing branch_taken and branch_target into the EX/MEM register.\\nAll other fields remain unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute rd_wdata = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? load_data : in.alu_result\\ncombinationally and store it in the MEM/WB register as reg_q.rd_wdata.\\nRemove the now-redundant alu_result and read_data assignments.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/wb_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the mem_to_reg mux with a passthrough: w_data = in.rd_wdata.\\nw_en and w_addr logic stays identical.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove branch_taken and branch_target from ex_mem_t (dead fields).\\nReplace alu_result and read_data in mem_wb_t with a single rd_wdata\\nfield that holds the final register write data.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Stop writing branch_taken and branch_target into the EX/MEM register.\\nAll other fields remain unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute rd_wdata = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? load_data : in.alu_result\\ncombinationally and store it in the MEM/WB register as reg_q.rd_wdata.\\nRemove the now-redundant alu_result and read_data assignments.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/wb_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the mem_to_reg mux with a passthrough: w_data = in.rd_wdata.\\nw_en and w_addr logic stays identical.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 229.88, \"delta_pct\": -33.9, \"vs_baseline\": -18.72, \"fmax_mhz\": 96.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10222, \"ff\": 1915, \"seeds\": [99.71, 96.63, 92.38], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:50:14.606389Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 6, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n","metadata":{"output":"{\"id\": \"baseline-bench-4217612\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 282.82, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9563, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [128.72, 127.03, 123.02], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T01:36:12.712654Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r1s0.yaml\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"schema_error: while scanning a simple key\\n  in \\\"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r1s0.yaml\\\", line 6, column 1\\ncould not find expected ':'\\n  in \\\"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r1s0.yaml\\\", line 7, column 1\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 1}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"MEM-to-EX load bypass to eliminate load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline stalls for one cycle on every load-use hazard\\nbecause it can only forward loaded data from MEM/WB, not from the MEM stage\\nitself.  CoreMark pointer-chasing and array-index patterns frequently emit a\\nLOAD followed immediately by a dependent ALU or STORE.  Eliminating the\\nload-use bubble improves IPC with no extra pipeline stages or tables.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline stalls for one cycle on every load-use hazard\\nbecause it can only forward loaded data from MEM/WB, not from the MEM stage\\nitself.  CoreMark pointer-chasing and array-index patterns frequently emit a\\nLOAD followed immediately by a dependent ALU or STORE.  Eliminating the\\nload-use bubble improves IPC with no extra pipeline stages or tables.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a combinational bypass from mem_stage's load_data output back to the\\nEX-stage operand muxes.  Extend the forwarding_unit so that when EX/MEM\\ncontains a LOAD whose rd matches an EX-stage rs, it selects the new bypass\\npath (encoding 2'b11).  Remove the load_use_hazard stall from hazard_unit;\\nthe bypass makes it unnecessary.  All other stalls (imem/dmem backpressure,\\nredirect flush) remain unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 7, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the load_use_hazard term from stall_if, stall_id, and flush_id. The MEM\\u2192EX bypass eliminates the need to stall the pipeline for load-use.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_mem_mem_read input.  When EX/MEM has a matching rd and ex_mem_mem_read is high, drive fwd_rs1/fwd_rs2 = 2'b11 to select the MEM-stage load bypass instead of the ALU-result path.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_mem_load [31:0] input.  Extend the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes to select fwd_mem_load when the forwarding select is 2'b11.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Expose the combinational load_data signal as a new output port load_data_fwd [31:0] so core.sv can route it back to ex_stage.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire mem_stage.load_data_fwd to ex_stage.fwd_mem_load.  Connect ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read to forward_unit.ex_mem_mem_read.  Update the hazard_unit instantiation to reflect removed load-use stall logic.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 7, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the load_use_hazard term from stall_if, stall_id, and flush_id. The MEM\\u2192EX bypass eliminates the need to stall the pipeline for load-use.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_mem_mem_read input.  When EX/MEM has a matching rd and ex_mem_mem_read is high, drive fwd_rs1/fwd_rs2 = 2'b11 to select the MEM-stage load bypass instead of the ALU-result path.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_mem_load [31:0] input.  Extend the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes to select fwd_mem_load when the forwarding select is 2'b11.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Expose the combinational load_data signal as a new output port load_data_fwd [31:0] so core.sv can route it back to ex_stage.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire mem_stage.load_data_fwd to ex_stage.fwd_mem_load.  Connect ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read to forward_unit.ex_mem_mem_read.  Update the hazard_unit instantiation to reflect removed load-use stall logic.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 324.08, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 14.59, \"fmax_mhz\": 138.05, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4259699, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10189, \"ff\": 1874, \"seeds\": [133.46, 138.05, 148.35], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T02:41:03.769480Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 2, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/test/test_pipeline.py']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Eliminate false load-use stalls via opcode-aware hazard detection\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current hazard_unit conservatively checks both rs1 (instr[19:15]) and rs2\\n(instr[24:20]) of the instruction in ID against the LOAD's rd in EX,\\nregardless of whether the instruction actually reads those fields as registers.\\nFor I-type (OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR), U-type, and J-type instructions, the rs2\\nfield is an immediate/shamt, not a register address. A LOAD followed by an\\nADDI where imm[4:0] happens to match the LOAD's rd currently triggers a\\nspurious one-cycle stall. CoreMark uses small immediate values extensively,\\nso false stalls on common x1-x5 register numbers are likely frequent.\\nEliminating these false stalls improves IPC with negligible LUT/Fmax cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current hazard_unit conservatively checks both rs1 (instr[19:15]) and rs2\\n(instr[24:20]) of the instruction in ID against the LOAD's rd in EX,\\nregardless of whether the instruction actually reads those fields as registers.\\nFor I-type (OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR), U-type, and J-type instructions, the rs2\\nfield is an immediate/shamt, not a register address. A LOAD followed by an\\nADDI where imm[4:0] happens to match the LOAD's rd currently triggers a\\nspurious one-cycle stall. CoreMark uses small immediate values extensively,\\nso false stalls on common x1-x5 register numbers are likely frequent.\\nEliminating these false stalls improves IPC with negligible LUT/Fmax cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add opcode decoding to hazard_unit so load-use detection only fires when\\nthe instruction in ID actually reads rs1/rs2 as registers. R-type, I-type\\n(OP-IMM/LOAD/JALR), S-type, and B-type use rs1; R-type, S-type, and B-type\\nuse rs2. U-type and J-type use neither. This removes false stalls without\\naltering pipeline structure or lengthening critical paths.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add opcode input and uses_rs1/uses_rs2 qualification to the load_use_hazard check.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire if_id_w.instr[6:0] to the hazard_unit's new opcode input.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add opcode input and uses_rs1/uses_rs2 qualification to the load_use_hazard check.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire if_id_w.instr[6:0] to the hazard_unit's new opcode input.\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"cosim_failed: selftest.elf\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 3, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r4s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r4s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r4s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r4s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r4s2'])\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 4}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Eliminate false load-use stalls via opcode-aware hazard detection\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit conservatively stalls on any LOAD-to-use sequence where the\\nLOAD's rd matches either rs1 or rs2 of the next instruction, regardless of\\nwhether those fields are actually register reads. For I-type instructions\\n(OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR) the rs2 field encodes an immediate or shamt; for U-type\\n(LUI, AUIPC), J-type (JAL), and SYSTEM/FENCE instructions neither field is a\\nregister read. These false stalls waste cycles\\u2014especially on CoreMark's heavy\\nuse of ADDI, LUI, and JAL immediately after pointer loads\\u2014with negligible\\nLUT cost and no impact on Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit conservatively stalls on any LOAD-to-use sequence where the\\nLOAD's rd matches either rs1 or rs2 of the next instruction, regardless of\\nwhether those fields are actually register reads. For I-type instructions\\n(OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR) the rs2 field encodes an immediate or shamt; for U-type\\n(LUI, AUIPC), J-type (JAL), and SYSTEM/FENCE instructions neither field is a\\nregister read. These false stalls waste cycles\\u2014especially on CoreMark's heavy\\nuse of ADDI, LUI, and JAL immediately after pointer loads\\u2014with negligible\\nLUT cost and no impact on Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add opcode decoding to hazard_unit so the load_use_hazard term only fires\\nwhen the instruction in ID genuinely reads rs1 or rs2. R-type, BRANCH, and\\nSTORE read both; I-type reads only rs1; U/J/FENCE/SYSTEM read neither. The\\nstall_if / stall_id / flush_id logic otherwise stays identical, so no other\\npipeline behavior changes. This removes spurious one-cycle bubbles without\\nlengthening any critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a new 7-bit `if_id_opcode` input. Inside the module compute\\n`uses_rs1` and `uses_rs2` flags from the opcode (R/BRANCH/STORE = both;\\nI-type = rs1 only; U/J/FENCE/SYSTEM = neither). Qualify the\\n`load_use_hazard` expression with these flags so that matches on\\nimmediate fields no longer stall the pipeline.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire `if_id_w.instr[6:0]` into the new `if_id_opcode` port of the\\n`hazard_unit` instance. No other top-level signals are modified.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a new 7-bit `if_id_opcode` input. Inside the module compute\\n`uses_rs1` and `uses_rs2` flags from the opcode (R/BRANCH/STORE = both;\\nI-type = rs1 only; U/J/FENCE/SYSTEM = neither). Qualify the\\n`load_use_hazard` expression with these flags so that matches on\\nimmediate fields no longer stall the pipeline.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire `if_id_w.instr[6:0]` into the new `if_id_opcode` port of the\\n`hazard_unit` instance. No other top-level signals are modified.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:24:18.728881Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 5, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/test/test_pipeline.py']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Fold WB mux into MEM stage and remove dead EX/MEM fields\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move the write-back data selection into the MEM stage so that the MEM/WB\\nregister stores only the final rd_wdata (already muxed between load_data and\\nalu_result).  The WB stage then becomes a pure passthrough.  This removes one\\n32-bit mux from the MEM/WB->EX forwarding critical path.  At the same time,\\ndelete the unused branch_taken and branch_target fields from ex_mem_t to\\nreduce area and routing congestion.  No pipeline behaviour changes; IPC stays\\nidentical and Fmax should improve slightly.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove branch_taken and branch_target from ex_mem_t (dead fields).\\nReplace alu_result and read_data in mem_wb_t with a single rd_wdata\\nfield that holds the final register write data.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Stop writing branch_taken and branch_target into the EX/MEM register.\\nAll other fields remain unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute rd_wdata = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? load_data : in.alu_result\\ncombinationally and store it in the MEM/WB register as reg_q.rd_wdata.\\nRemove the now-redundant alu_result and read_data assignments.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/wb_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the mem_to_reg mux with a passthrough: w_data = in.rd_wdata.\\nw_en and w_addr logic stays identical.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove branch_taken and branch_target from ex_mem_t (dead fields).\\nReplace alu_result and read_data in mem_wb_t with a single rd_wdata\\nfield that holds the final register write data.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Stop writing branch_taken and branch_target into the EX/MEM register.\\nAll other fields remain unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute rd_wdata = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? load_data : in.alu_result\\ncombinationally and store it in the MEM/WB register as reg_q.rd_wdata.\\nRemove the now-redundant alu_result and read_data assignments.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/wb_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the mem_to_reg mux with a passthrough: w_data = in.rd_wdata.\\nw_en and w_addr logic stays identical.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 229.88, \"delta_pct\": -33.9, \"vs_baseline\": -18.72, \"fmax_mhz\": 96.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10222, \"ff\": 1915, \"seeds\": [99.71, 96.63, 92.38], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implem