{"type":"text","timestamp":1778743452034,"sessionID":"ses_1daaccaa2ffe5OUTFCUmOyCNDo","part":{"id":"prt_e255f01bc001ZaI8JufqSX4aeL","messageID":"msg_e255ee9af001bIMaQWt8CRbzuE","sessionID":"ses_1daaccaa2ffe5OUTFCUmOyCNDo","type":"text","text":"Done. Wrote the hypothesis file to:\n\n`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-002-r10s1.yaml`\n\n**Hypothesis summary**: Add a **1-entry instruction skid buffer** in the IF stage to decouple fetch from issue.  \n- **Why**: The cosim model injects ~22% random imem stalls; currently every `!imem_ready` cycle asserts a global stall/flush that wastes the fetch slot. During load-use or dmem stalls, valid instructions arriving on the bus are also discarded because the PC freezes.  \n- **What changes**:  \n  - `rtl/if_stage.sv` — 1-entry buffer (`buf_pc`, `buf_instr`, `buf_pred_taken`, `buf_valid`) with a prefetch/consume FSM. PC advances whenever `imem_ready` is high and there is room (direct issue or buffer empty).  \n  - `rtl/hazard_unit.sv` — remove `imem_ready` from `stall_if` and `flush_if`; stalls now only for load-use / dmem, letting IF prefetch while the pipeline is stalled downstream.  \n  - `rtl/core.sv` — wire `io_imemReady` into `if_stage` and wire `flush_if = redirect`.  \n- **Expected impact**: ~6% fitness improvement (medium confidence). The buffer hides single-cycle imem bubbles and recovers otherwise-wasted fetches during downstream stalls, with only ~66 flops and no new long combinational paths.","time":{"start":1778743443900,"end":1778743452032}}}
