{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778749217352,"sessionID":"ses_1da496f0affe1xo1ihroyY0XWo","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"functions.read:2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","offset":33},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n33: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Add 1-entry non-blocking store buffer to hide dmem backpressure on stores\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit currently stalls the entire pipeline on every !dmem_ready cycle\\nwhenever any memory operation is in MEM. Stores are roughly 20-25% of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream and the cosim model injects ~22% random dmem stalls, so about\\n5% of total cycles are wasted waiting for the store bus. Because stores do not\\nproduce register results, the instructions behind them are almost always\\nindependent and could continue executing if the store were decoupled. A 1-entry\\nstore buffer captures a stalled store and lets the pipeline advance while the\\nbuffer drains asynchronously, converting store-bus stalls into useful execution\\ncycles with minimal area and no new long combinational paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit currently stalls the entire pipeline on every !dmem_ready cycle\\nwhenever any memory operation is in MEM. Stores are roughly 20-25% of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream and the cosim model injects ~22% random dmem stalls, so about\\n5% of total cycles are wasted waiting for the store bus. Because stores do not\\nproduce register results, the instructions behind them are almost always\\nindependent and could continue executing if the store were decoupled. A 1-entry\\nstore buffer captures a stalled store and lets the pipeline advance while the\\nbuffer drains asynchronously, converting store-bus stalls into useful execution\\ncycles with minimal area and no new long combinational paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a 1-entry store buffer between the MEM stage and the external dmem interface.\\nWhen a store reaches MEM and dmem_ready is low, the buffer captures the address,\\ndata, and byte mask instead of asserting a global stall. The buffer continuously\\nretries the write whenever dmem_ready is high. The top-level dmem outputs are\\nmuxed between the buffer (when valid) and the live M... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n34: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"Add 8-entry loop predictor for backward branch exits\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit BHT already captures forward branch directions and\\nbackward-taken bias, but it cannot avoid mispredicting the final iteration\\nof every loop (predicted taken, actually not-taken). CoreMark contains\\nmany small inner loops (list traversal, matrix rows, CRC updates) where\\nthis exit misprediction wastes cycles. A dedicated loop predictor learns\\nthe trip count of individual backward branches and predicts not-taken on\\nthe last iteration, removing the only remaining systematic direction\\nmispredictions with only ~100 flops and no wider BHT mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit BHT already captures forward branch directions and\\nbackward-taken bias, but it cannot avoid mispredicting the final iteration\\nof every loop (predicted taken, actually not-taken). CoreMark contains\\nmany small inner loops (list traversal, matrix rows, CRC updates) where\\nthis exit misprediction wastes cycles. A dedicated loop predictor learns\\nthe trip count of individual backward branches and predicts not-taken on\\nthe last iteration, removing the only remaining systematic direction\\nmispredictions with only ~100 flops and no wider BHT mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an 8-entry direct-mapped loop predictor 