{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778751320418,"sessionID":"ses_1da325275ffethxWFZGYDI5HFe","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"bash:3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"rg -i \"forward|pre-compute|precompute\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | head -30","description":"Search log for forward-related hypotheses"},"output":"...output truncated...\n\nFull output saved to: /Users/bonetto/.local/share/opencode/tool-output/tool_e25d73160002gQ8dxOaETvV7CA\n\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"MEM-to-EX load bypass to eliminate load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline stalls for one cycle on every load-use hazard\\nbecause it can only forward loaded data from MEM/WB, not from the MEM stage\\nitself.  CoreMark pointer-chasing and array-index patterns frequently emit a\\nLOAD followed immediately by a dependent ALU or STORE.  Eliminating the\\nload-use bubble improves IPC with no extra pipeline stages or tables.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline stalls for one cycle on every load-use hazard\\nbecause it can only forward loaded data from MEM/WB, not from the MEM stage\\nitself.  CoreMark pointer-chasing and array-index patterns frequently emit a\\nLOAD followed immediately by a dependent ALU or STORE.  Eliminating the\\nload-use bubble improves IPC with no extra pipeline stages or tables.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a combinational bypass from mem_stage's load_data output back to the\\nEX-stage operand muxes.  Extend the forwarding_unit so that when EX/MEM\\ncontains a LOAD whose rd matches an EX-stage rs, it selects the new bypass\\npath (encoding 2'b11).  Remove the load_use_hazard stall from hazard_unit;\\nthe bypass makes it unnecessary.  All other stalls (imem/dmem backpressure,\\nredirect flush) remain unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 7, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the load_use_hazard term from stall_if, stall_id, and flush_id. The MEM\\u2192EX bypass eliminates the need to stall the pipeline for load-use.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_mem_mem_read input.  When EX/MEM has a matching rd and ex_mem_mem_read is high, drive fwd_rs1/fwd_rs2 = 2'b11 to select the MEM-stage load bypass instead of the ALU-result path.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_mem_load [31:0] input.  Extend the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes to select fwd_mem_load when the forwarding select is 2'b11.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Expose the combinational load_data signal as a new output port load_data_fwd [31:0] so core.sv can route it back to ex_stage.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire mem_stage.load_data_fwd to ex_stage.fwd_mem_load.  Connect ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read to forward_unit.ex_mem_mem_read.  Update the hazard_unit instantiation to reflect removed load-use stall logic.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 7, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the load_use_hazard term from stall_if, stall_id, and flush_id. The MEM\\u2192EX bypass eliminates the need to stall the pipeline for load-use.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_mem_mem_read input.  When EX/MEM has a matching rd and ex_mem_mem_read is high, drive fwd_rs1/fwd_rs2 = 2'b11 to select the MEM-stage load bypass instead of the ALU-result path.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_mem_load [31:0] input.  Extend the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes to select fwd_mem_load when the forwarding select is 2'b11.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Expose the combinational load_data signal as a new output port load_data_fwd [31:0] so core.sv can route it back to ex_stage.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire mem_stage.load_data_fwd to ex_stage.fwd_mem_load.  Connect ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read to forward_unit.ex_mem_mem_read.  Update the hazard_unit instantiation to reflect removed load-use stall logic.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 324.08, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 14.59, \"fmax_mhz\": 138.05, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4259699, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10189, \"ff\": 1874, \"seeds\": [133.46, 138.05, 148.35], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T02:41:03.769480Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 2, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/test/test_pipeline.py']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/forward_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/mem_stage.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 2}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"Add 32-entry tagged BTB with 2-bit saturating counters for branch target caching and forward-branch learning\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor correctly predicts backward branches and JAL,\\nbut forward branches that are frequently taken are always mispredicted.\\nAdditionally, the combinational branch-target computation in the IF stage\\n(opcode decode \\u2192 immediate extraction \\u2192 sign-extension \\u2192 PC adder) may\\ncontribute to the critical path. A small Branch Target Buffer can learn\\ntaken forward branches, cache targets to shorten the IF-stage path, and\\ncoexist safely with the existing static BTFN predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor correctly predicts backward branches and JAL,\\nbut forward branches that are frequently taken are always mispredicted.\\nAdditionally, the combinational branch-target computation in the IF stage\\n(opcode decode \\u2192 immediate extraction \\u2192 sign-extension \\u2192 PC adder) may\\ncontribute to the critical path. A small Branch Target Buffer can learn\\ntaken forward branches, cache targets to shorten the IF-stage path, and\\ncoexist safely with the existing static BTFN predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped Branch Target Buffer in the IF stage.\\nEach entry stores a valid bit, a 5-bit tag (PC[11:7]), a 30-bit\\nword-aligned target, and a 2-bit saturating counter.  In IF, a BTB\\nhit on a branch or JAL supplies the target directly from a register\\nread, bypassing the combinational immediate+adder path.  Direction\\nprediction remains static-taken for backward branches and JAL, but\\nthe BTB can additionally predict taken for forward branches once\\ntheir counter reaches 2.  In EX, every resolved branch/JAL writes\\nits outcome and target back into the BTB.  JALR is excluded from\\nBTB usage to avoid aliasing noise.  This should improve IPC on\\ntaken forward branches and may raise Fmax by reducing IF-stage\\ncombinational delay.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a packed `btb_entry_t` struct (valid, tag[4:0], target[29:0],\\ncounter[1:0]) for the 32-entry Branch Target Buffer.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add the 32-entry BTB array and combinational read logic.  Use the\\nBTB target on hit for branches/JAL, falling back to the existing\\ncombinational immediate+adder path on miss.  Add `btb_update_en`,\\n`btb_update_idx`, and `btb_update_entry` input ports so EX can\\nwrite resolved outcomes back.  Keep the static backward-taken/JAL\\nprediction as a base; allow BTB to override only to predict taken\\nfor forward branches when the counter is saturated.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add combinational BTB update logic that drives `btb_update_en`,\\n`btb_update_idx` (from `in.pc[6:2]`), and `btb_update_entry`\\n(valid=1, tag=PC[11:7], target=resolved target, counter updated\\nby the 2-bit saturating counter rule) on every resolved branch\\nor jump.  Gate the update on `!stall && in.valid`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires `btb_update_en`, `btb_update_idx[4:0]`, and\\n`btb_update_entry` and route them from `ex_stage` outputs to\\n`if_stage` inputs so the BTB can be updated from EX.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a packed `btb_entry_t` struct (valid, tag[4:0], target[29:0],\\ncounter[1:0]) for the 32-entry Branch Target Buffer.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add the 32-entry BTB array and combinational read logic.  Use the\\nBTB target on hit for branches/JAL, falling back to the existing\\ncombinational immediate+adder path on miss.  Add `btb_update_en`,\\n`btb_update_idx`, and `btb_update_entry` input ports so EX can\\nwrite resolved outcomes back.  Keep the static backward-taken/JAL\\nprediction as a base; allow BTB to override only to predict taken\\nfor forward branches when the counter is saturated.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add combinational BTB update logic that drives `btb_update_en`,\\n`btb_update_idx` (from `in.pc[6:2]`), and `btb_update_entry`\\n(valid=1, tag=PC[11:7], target=resolved target, counter updated\\nby the 2-bit saturating counter rule) on every resolved branch\\nor jump.  Gate the update on `!stall && in.valid`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires `btb_update_en`, `btb_update_idx[4:0]`, and\\n`btb_update_entry` and route them from `ex_stage` outputs to\\n`if_stage` inputs so the BTB can be updated from EX.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"cosim_failed: coremark.elf\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 3, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Move JALR target resolution to ID stage to cut penalty from 2 to 1 cycle\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"JALR is currently unpredicted in IF and resolved in EX, incurring a 2-cycle\\nmisprediction bubble on every function return and indirect call. CoreMark's\\nlist benchmark makes frequent function calls through pointers, so JALR\\nbubbles are a real IPC limiter.  Because the return address register (x1)\\nis almost always in the regfile when the JALR reaches ID (no forwarding\\nneeded), we can compute the target address in ID stage and redirect IF one\\ncycle earlier, shrinking the penalty to a single flushed fetch slot.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"JALR is currently unpredicted in IF and resolved in EX, incurring a 2-cycle\\nmisprediction bubble on every function return and indirect call. CoreMark's\\nlist benchmark makes frequent function calls through pointers, so JALR\\nbubbles are a real IPC limiter.  Because the return address register (x1)\\nis almost always in the regfile when the JALR reaches ID (no forwarding\\nneeded), we can compute the target address in ID stage and redirect IF one\\ncycle earlier, shrinking the penalty to a single flushed fetch slot.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a JALR target adder in the ID stage: when the decoded instruction is\\nJALR and its rs1 is not the subject of an in-flight load-use hazard, compute\\njalr_target = (rs1_data + imm) & ~1 and assert a new id_redirect signal.\\nThread a jalr_redirected flag through the id_ex_t bundle so the EX stage\\nsuppresses its own redirect for JALRs that were already handled in ID.\\nAt the top level, OR the new id_redirect with the existing ex_redirect to\\ndrive the PC, and adjust flush_if/flush_id so that a JALR in ID is allowed\\nto advance into EX while the speculative fetch in IF is killed.\\nThis structural change shortens the JALR resolution loop by one full stage\\nwithout touching any other instruction type.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add jalr_redirected bit to id_ex_t bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute JALR target from regfile rs1 + imm. Assert id_redirect when JALR has no load-use hazard on rs1. Set jalr_redirected flag in the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Suppress redirect for JALR instructions when jalr_redirected is set; otherwise keep existing redirect logic unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add id_redirect input to flush_if logic. Ensure load-use hazard on JALR rs1 stalls ID (do not assert id_redirect until hazard clears).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new id_redirect from id_stage to hazard_unit and PC logic. Combine id_redirect with ex_redirect for top-level redirect and flush control.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add jalr_redirected bit to id_ex_t bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute JALR target from regfile rs1 + imm. Assert id_redirect when JALR has no load-use hazard on rs1. Set jalr_redirected flag in the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Suppress redirect for JALR instructions when jalr_redirected is set; otherwise keep existing redirect logic unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add id_redirect input to flush_if logic. Ensure load-use hazard on JALR rs1 stalls ID (do not assert id_redirect until hazard clears).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new id_redirect from id_stage to hazard_unit and PC logic. Combine id_redirect with ex_redirect for top-level redirect and flush control.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 324.08, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 14.59, \"fmax_mhz\": 138.05, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4259699, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10189, \"ff\": 1874, \"seeds\": [133.46, 138.05, 148.35], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:05:58.810116Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 4}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"Add 32-entry 2-bit BHT for forward branch direction prediction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped Branch History Table with 2-bit saturating\\ncounters to the IF stage. The table is indexed by PC[6:2] and initialized to\\nstrongly-taken (2'b11) so backward loops are correct immediately without any\\ntraining cost. For every conditional branch, the BHT entry MSB drives\\npredict_taken; unconditional JAL continues to be always predicted taken. In\\nEX stage, each resolved branch writes its actual outcome back to the entry\\nindexed by the branch PC using a standard saturating update rule. This adds\\nonly 64 flops and a few LUTs of combinational logic, does not widen any\\npipeline register, and the BHT read is off the critical instruction-fetch path\\nbecause the PC is known at the start of the cycle while the opcode decode\\n(which selects the BHT result) happens later in parallel.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 32-entry x 2-bit BHT array inside the IF stage.  Combinational read uses pc[6:2] to select the counter; the MSB becomes the direction prediction for conditional branches.  Add three new input ports (bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], bht_update_taken) and a saturating update rule that increments on taken and decrements on not-taken.  Modify predict_taken so that conditional branches use the BHT MSB while JAL remains unconditionally taken.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add output ports bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken.  Drive bht_update_en high on every cycle a conditional branch is resolved (!stall && in.valid && in.ctrl.is_branch). bht_update_idx is in.pc[6:2] and bht_update_taken is the combinational branch_taken signal.  No other EX-stage logic is changed.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken and route them from ex_stage outputs to if_stage inputs. No top-level IO or RVFI changes.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 32-entry x 2-bit BHT array inside the IF stage.  Combinational read uses pc[6:2] to select the counter; the MSB becomes the direction prediction for conditional branches.  Add three new input ports (bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], bht_update_taken) and a saturating update rule that increments on taken and decrements on not-taken.  Modify predict_taken so that conditional branches use the BHT MSB while JAL remains unconditionally taken.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add output ports bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken.  Drive bht_update_en high on every cycle a conditional branch is resolved (!stall && in.valid && in.ctrl.is_branch). bht_update_idx is in.pc[6:2] and bht_update_taken is the combinational branch_taken signal.  No other EX-stage logic is changed.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken and route them from ex_stage outputs to if_stage inputs. No top-level IO or RVFI changes.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 7.31, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T03:44:01.694682Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 4, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r4s2 (improvement, +7.31%): After a static backward-taken baseline captures the easy loop gains, a minimal 32-entry 2-bit BHT (64 flops) still recovers +7.3% fitness by predicting forward conditional branches; forward-branch direction is the largest remaining dynamic bubble source in CoreMark.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"Expand BHT to 128 entries to reduce aliasing among forward branches\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the 32-entry BHT in if_stage with a 128-entry direct-mapped BHT.\\nChange the index from pc[6:2] to pc[8:2] (7 bits) and widen the\\nbht_update_idx port from 5 to 7 bits so EX can write back using in.pc[8:2].\\nThe counter update rule, strong-taken initialization, and interaction with\\nthe static backward-taken / JAL predictor remain exactly the same. No new\\npipeline bundles or control signals are introduced, making this a very low-\\nrisk resize of a component that is already known to work.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Widen bht_update_idx from 5 to 7 bits to match the 128-entry table index.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Enlarge the bht array to [0:127], update the init loop bound to 128, and change the read index from pc[6:2] to pc[8:2].\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change bht_update_idx from in.pc[6:2] to in.pc[8:2] so resolved branches write back to the correct 128-entry slot.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Widen bht_update_idx from 5 to 7 bits to match the 128-entry table index.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Enlarge the bht array to [0:127], update the init loop bound to 128, and change the read index from pc[6:2] to pc[8:2].\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change bht_update_idx from in.pc[6:2] to in.pc[8:2] so resolved branches write back to the correct 128-entry slot.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 337.3, \"delta_pct\": -3.01, \"vs_baseline\": 19.26, \"fmax_mhz\": 141.74, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4202246, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 11315, \"ff\": 2133, \"seeds\": [134.34, 143.8, 141.74], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:17:50.929383Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 5, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r5s2 (regression, -3.01%): A 128-entry BHT regressed CoreMark fitness because the 32-entry table already saturates the benchmark's forward-branch locality, and the larger IF-stage read mux degraded Fmax more than reduced aliasing improved IPC.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Fold WB mux into MEM stage and remove dead EX/MEM fields\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move the write-back data selection into the MEM stage so that the MEM/WB\\nregister stores only the final rd_wdata (already muxed between load_data and\\nalu_result).  The WB stage then becomes a pure passthrough.  This removes one\\n32-bit mux from the MEM/WB->EX forwarding critical path.  At the same time,\\ndelete the unused branch_taken and branch_target fields from ex_mem_t to\\nreduce area and routing congestion.  No pipeline behaviour changes; IPC stays\\nidentical and Fmax should improve slightly.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove branch_taken and branch_target from ex_mem_t (dead fields).\\nReplace alu_result and read_data in mem_wb_t with a single rd_wdata\\nfield that holds the final register write data.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Stop writing branch_taken and branch_target into the EX/MEM register.\\nAll other fields remain unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute rd_wdata = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? load_data : in.alu_result\\ncombinationally and store it in the MEM/WB register as reg_q.rd_wdata.\\nRemove the now-redundant alu_result and read_data assignments.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/wb_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the mem_to_reg mux with a passthrough: w_data = in.rd_wdata.\\nw_en and w_addr logic stays identical.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove branch_taken and branch_target from ex_mem_t (dead fields).\\nReplace alu_result and read_data in mem_wb_t with a single rd_wdata\\nfield that holds the final register write data.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Stop writing branch_taken and branch_target into the EX/MEM register.\\nAll other fields remain unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute rd_wdata = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? load_data : in.alu_result\\ncombinationally and store it in the MEM/WB register as reg_q.rd_wdata.\\nRemove the now-redundant alu_result and read_data assignments.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/wb_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the mem_to_reg mux with a passthrough: w_data = in.rd_wdata.\\nw_en and w_addr logic stays identical.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 229.88, \"delta_pct\": -33.9, \"vs_baseline\": -18.72, \"fmax_mhz\": 96.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10222, \"ff\": 1915, \"seeds\": [99.71, 96.63, 92.38], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:50:14.606389Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 6, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Precompute forwarding selects in ID stage to shorten EX critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The EX-stage critical path currently includes the forward_unit's 5-bit\\naddress comparison, priority encoder, and operand forwarding mux before the\\nALU.  On a LUT-based FPGA these extra logic levels consume precious\\nnanoseconds.  By shifting the forwarding decision into the ID stage\\u2014where\\nthe same comparison is performed against the instructions currently in EX\\nand MEM\\u2014we register the 2-bit select signals into the ID/EX pipeline\\nregister.  This removes the comparison and control generation from the\\nEX-stage datapath without changing pipeline behaviour or IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX-stage critical path currently includes the forward_unit's 5-bit\\naddress comparison, priority encoder, and operand forwarding mux before the\\nALU.  On a LUT-based FPGA these extra logic levels consume precious\\nnanoseconds.  By shifting the forwarding decision into the ID stage\\u2014where\\nthe same comparison is performed against the instructions currently in EX\\nand MEM\\u2014we register the 2-bit select signals into the ID/EX pipeline\\nregister.  This removes the comparison and control generation from the\\nEX-stage datapath without changing pipeline behaviour or IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add fwd_rs1_sel and fwd_rs2_sel (2 bits each) to the id_ex_t bundle.\\nIn id_stage, compute the forwarding selects combinationally by comparing\\nthe current IF/ID instruction's rs1_addr/rs2_addr against the rd and\\nreg_write flags of the instruction currently in EX (the ID/EX register)\\nand the instruction currently in MEM (ex_mem_w), preserving the same\\nEX/MEM-over-MEM/WB priority and x0 guard that forward_unit uses today.\\nRegister these selects into the ID/EX payload.  In ex_stage, remove the\\nforward_unit input ports and use the precomputed in.fwd_rs1_sel /\\nin.fwd_rs2_sel directly in the operand forwarding muxes.  In core.sv,\\nwire ex_mem_w.rd and ex_mem_w.ctrl.reg_write into id_stage for the\\nprecomputation, remove the forward_unit instantiation, and connect the\\nprecomputed selects straight through to ex_stage.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_rs1_sel [1:0] and fwd_rs2_sel [1:0] fields to the id_ex_t struct.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add inputs ex_mem_rd [4:0] and ex_mem_reg_write. Compute next_fwd_rs1/next_fwd_rs2 combinationally by comparing in.instr[19:15] and in.instr[24:20] against reg_q.rd and ex_mem_rd with the same write-enable / x0 guards used by forward_unit. Register the resulting 2-bit values into the ID/EX payload.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the fwd_rs1_sel and fwd_rs2_sel input ports. Use in.fwd_rs1_sel and in.fwd_rs2_sel directly in the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes instead of the former forward_unit-driven selects.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire ex_mem_w.rd and ex_mem_w.ctrl.reg_write into the id_stage instance for precomputation.  Remove the forward_unit instantiation and its wires.  Connect id_ex_w.fwd_rs1_sel and id_ex_w.fwd_rs2_sel directly to ex_stage.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_rs1_sel [1:0] and fwd_rs2_sel [1:0] fields to the id_ex_t struct.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add inputs ex_mem_rd [4:0] and ex_mem_reg_write. Compute next_fwd_rs1/next_fwd_rs2 combinationally by comparing in.instr[19:15] and in.instr[24:20] against reg_q.rd and ex_mem_rd with the same write-enable / x0 guards used by forward_unit. Register the resulting 2-bit values into the ID/EX payload.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"