e_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r9s0\", \"title\": \"Word-load bypass from MEM to EX stage\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Prior MEM-to-EX load bypass failed because the critical path through\\nvariable-shift + sign-extend degraded Fmax enough to cancel IPC gains.\\nWord loads (LW) are the dominant load type in CoreMark pointer chasing\\nand need no byte-alignment or sign-extension. A bypass that forwards\\nraw dmem_rdata straight from MEM to EX for LW-only dependencies keeps\\nthe bypass wire path very short, potentially recovering the IPC gain\\nwithout the Fmax loss that killed the full-width bypass.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior MEM-to-EX load bypass failed because the critical path through\\nvariable-shift + sign-extend degraded Fmax enough to cancel IPC gains.\\nWord loads (LW) are the dominant load type in CoreMark pointer chasing\\nand need no byte-alignment or sign-extension. A bypass that forwards\\nraw dmem_rdata straight from MEM to EX for LW-only dependencies keeps\\nthe bypass wire path very short, potentially recovering the IPC gain\\nwithout the Fmax loss that killed the full-width bypass.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a fast MEM-to-EX forwarding path for word loads only: when a LW is\\nin MEM and the instruction in EX reads its rd, forward io_dmemRData\\ndirectly into the EX operand muxes (encoding 2'd3). Suppress the\\nload-use stall in hazard_unit when the load in EX is a word load\\n(mem_width == 2'd2), so the dependent instruction reaches EX in the\\ncycle the LW is in MEM. Keep the existing 1-cycle stall for byte and\\nhalfword loads. Extend forward_unit to prioritise the new dmem bypass\\nover EX/MEM forwarding when active.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Route io_dmemRData into ex_stage as fwd_dmem_rdata. Compute fwd_dmem_en from ex_mem_w (mem_read && mem_width==word && rd!=0) and feed it to both forward_unit and ex_stage.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add id_ex_mem_width input. Suppress load_use_hazard when id_ex_mem_width == 2'd2 (word load) so the stall is only inserted for byte/halfword loads.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_dmem_en input. Prioritise dmem bypass (2'd3) over normal EX/MEM forwarding when a word load sits in MEM and its rd matches the EX-stage rs1/rs2.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_dmem_rdata and fwd_dmem_en inputs. Extend the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes to select fwd_dmem_rdata for select code 2'd3.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Route io_dmemRData into ex_stage as fwd_dmem_rdata. Compute fwd_dmem_en from ex_mem_w (mem_read && mem_width==word && rd!=0) and feed it to both forward_unit and ex_stage.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add id_ex_mem_width input. Suppress load_use_hazard when id_ex_mem_width == 2'd2 (word load) so the stall is only inserted for byte/halfword loads.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_dmem_en input. Prioritise dmem bypass (2'd3) over normal EX/MEM forwarding when a word load sits in MEM and its rd matches the EX-stage rs1/rs2.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_dmem_rdata and fwd_dmem_en inputs. Extend the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes to select fwd_dmem_rdata for select code 2'd3.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T07:06:41.666406Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 9, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r9s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/forward_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 9, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The fitness contract injects ~22% random backpressure on the instruction\\nbus.  Today every !imem_ready cycle asserts a global stall_if / flush_if\\nthat freezes the PC and forces a NOP bubble into ID/EX.  A tiny 2-entry\\nskid buffer decouples fetch from issue: when the downstream pipeline is\\nstalled (load-use, dmem) but the bus is ready, the buffer prefetches\\nahead; when the bus subsequently stalls but the buffer is non-empty, the\\ncore continues issuing without bubbles.  This is a pure structural\\ndecoupling that should raise effective fetch throughput with only\\n~130 flops and no new long combinational paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure if_stage to hold a 2-entry ring buffer (valid, pc,\\ninstr, pred_taken per entry, plus a head pointer and 2-bit count).\\nThe fetch side advances the PC and enqueues the fetched instruction\\nwhenever imem_ready is high, count<2, and there is no redirect.  The\\nissue side selects the buffered head when count>0, otherwise the live\\nimem_data.  A true NOP is emitted only when the buffer is empty and\\nimem_ready is low.  In hazard_unit, remove imem_ready from stall_if\\nand flush_if so the pipeline no longer stalls globally for bus\\nbackpressure; stall_if is asserted only for load-use and dmem stalls,\\nand flush_if only for redirect.  In core.sv, wire io_imemReady into the\\nnew if_stage port and keep all top-level IO unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 2-entry ring buffer inside if_stage (buf_valid[1:0],\\nbuf_pc[1:0], buf_instr[1:0], buf_pred_taken[1:0], head pointer,\\ncount 0..2).  Add new input `imem_ready`.  Fetch PC advances and\\nenqueues into tail when imem_ready && count<2 && !redirect.\\nIssue selects buffered head if count>0, else live imem_data if\\nimem_ready, else NOP.  Count increments on fetch, decrements on\\nissue.  On redirect clear count/head and reset PC to redirect_target.\\nKeep existing BHT and static predictor logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove imem_ready from stall_if and flush_if.  Keep the imem_ready\\nport connected but unused (or remove it entirely).  Assert stall_if\\nonly for load-use hazards and dmem stalls; assert flush_if only for\\nredirect.  All other stall/flush logic (stall_id, flush_id,\\nstall_ex_mem, hold_mem_wb) remains exactly the same.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire io_imemReady to the new `imem_ready` port of if_stage.  No\\nother top-level IO changes; all RVFI and imem/dmem port names and\\nwidths stay identical.\\n\"}]}}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"Add 8-entry loop predictor for backward branch exits\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit BHT already captures forward branch directions and\\nbackward-taken bias, but it cannot avoid mispredicting the final iteration\\nof every loop (predicted taken, actually not-taken). CoreMark contains\\nmany small inner loops (list traversal, matrix rows, CRC updates) where\\nthis exit misprediction wastes cycles. A dedicated loop predictor learns\\nthe trip count of individual backward branches and predicts not-taken on\\nthe last iteration, removing the only remaining systematic direction\\nmispredictions with only ~100 flops and no wider BHT mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit BHT already captures forward branch directions and\\nbackward-taken bias, but it cannot avoid mispredicting the final iteration\\nof every loop (predicted taken, actually not-taken). CoreMark contains\\nmany small inner loops (list traversal, matrix rows, CRC updates) where\\nthis exit misprediction wastes cycles. A dedicated loop predictor learns\\nthe trip count of individual backward branches and predicts not-taken on\\nthe last iteration, removing the only remaining systematic direction\\nmispredictions with only ~100 flops and no wider BHT mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an 8-entry direct-mapped loop predictor table to the IF stage.\\nEach entry stores a tag, a trained iteration length, a speculative\\ndown-counter, and a 1-bit confidence flag.\\nWhen a backward branch is fetched, if the entry is valid, tag matches,\\nand confidence is high, the predictor overrides the BHT:\\n  - down-counter > 0  \\u2192 predict taken and decrement the counter.\\n  - down-counter == 0 \\u2192 predict not-taken.\\nIn EX, resolved backward branches update the table:\\n  - During training (confidence low) the table counts taken outcomes;\\n    the first not-taken exit stores the count as the trained length\\n    and sets confidence high.\\n  - On a correct exit (predicted not-taken) the counter is reloaded\\n    from the trained length for the next loop invocation.\\n  - On a length mismatch (mispredict) confidence is cleared so the\\n    entry re-trains on the next invocation.\\nThis attacks the last predictable bubble source without touching the\\nexisting BHT or pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 8-entry loop-predictor array (tag, length, count, conf), combinational read/decrement, and integrate with predict_taken so a matching confident entry overrides the BHT for backward branches.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop-predictor update logic: on resolved backward branches allocate/train entries, reload counters on correct exits, and clear confidence on mispredicts. Drive update signals back to IF.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop_predictor_entry_t struct and confidence constants to the package.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new loop-predictor update signals between ex_stage and if_stage.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 8-entry loop-predictor array (tag, length, count, conf), combinational read/decrement, and integrate with predict_taken so a matching confident entry overrides the BHT for backward branches.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop-predictor update logic: on resolved backward branches allocate/train entries, reload counters on correct exits, and clear confidence on mispredicts. Drive update signals back to IF.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop_predictor_entry_t struct and confidence constants to the package.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new loop-predictor update signals between ex_stage and if_stage.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 302.03, \"delta_pct\": -13.15, \"vs_baseline\": 6.79, \"fmax_mhz\": 126.68, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4194286, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10454, \"ff\": 1951, \"seeds\": [114.19, 126.68, 139.82], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T08:24:35.661190Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 11, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe rewrote /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/LESSONS.md instead of appending; reverted to prior content\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r13s2\", \"title\": \"Hash-mix higher PC bits into 32-entry BHT index to reduce aliasing\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter BHT is the proven sweet spot for\\nthis core, delivering a +7.3% fitness gain. A follow-up attempt to grow\\nthe table to 128 entries regressed -3% because the wider read mux hurt\\nFmax, while gshare global-history variants regressed due to history\\nstaleness. The remaining occasional forward-branch mispredictions may\\nstem from destructive aliasing among branches that share the low five\\nPC bits. A zero-cost hash that XORs higher PC bits into the index\\nscatters colliding branches without enlarging the array or adding any\\nnew state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter BHT is the proven sweet spot for\\nthis core, delivering a +7.3% fitness gain. A follow-up attempt to grow\\nthe table to 128 entries regressed -3% because the wider read mux hurt\\nFmax, while gshare global-history variants regressed due to history\\nstaleness. The remaining occasional forward-branch mispredictions may\\nstem from destructive aliasing among branches that share the low five\\nPC bits. A zero-cost hash that XORs higher PC bits into the index\\nscatters colliding branches without enlarging the array or adding any\\nnew state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the proven 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter table unchanged, but\\nchange both the read index and the write-back index from pc[6:2] to\\npc[6:2] ^ pc[11:7]. In the IF stage this mixes bits 7-11 of the PC\\ninto the existing 5-bit index, reducing the chance that two branches\\nwhose lower five bits collide map to the same counter. In the EX stage\\nthe update index uses in.pc[6:2] ^ in.pc[11:7] so the counter write\\nhits exactly the entry that was read during fetch. The combinational\\ncost is a single 5-bit XOR, which Yosys will absorb into the existing\\nLUT fabric with negligible Fmax impact. No new flops, pipeline bundles,\\nor control signals are introduced.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change BHT read index from pc[6:2] to pc[6:2] ^ pc[11:7].\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change BHT update index from in.pc[6:2] to in.pc[6:2] ^ in.pc[11:7].\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change BHT read index from pc[6:2] to pc[6:2] ^ pc[11:7].\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change BHT update index from in.pc[6:2] to in.pc[6:2] ^ in.pc[11:7].\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 235.82, \"delta_pct\": -32.19, \"vs_baseline\": -16.62, \"fmax_mhz\": 99.0, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4198050, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10363, \"ff\": 1934, \"seeds\": [99.0, 105.12, 96.15], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T09:19:06.627254Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 13, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n","exit":0,"description":"Search log for forward-related hypotheses","truncated":true,"outputPath":"/Users/bonetto/.local/share/opencode/tool-output/tool_e25d73160002gQ8dxOaETvV7CA"},"title":"Search log for forward-related hypotheses","time":{"start":1778751320404,"end":1778751320417}},"id":"prt_e25d72e81003EfW66tH6QUcduY","sessionID":"ses_1da325275ffethxWFZGYDI5HFe","messageID":"msg_e25d7048a001oJQdQLIweWePgo"}}
