national MEM-to-EX load bypass eliminated load-use stalls functionally but yielded zero net fitness gain because the longer critical path (dmem read → sign-extend → EX operand mux) degraded Fmax enough to cancel the IPC improvement.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r4s2 (improvement, +7.31%): After a static backward-taken baseline captures the easy loop gains, a minimal 32-entry 2-bit BHT (64 flops) still recovers +7.3% fitness by predicting forward conditional branches; forward-branch direction is the largest remaining dynamic bubble source in CoreMark.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r5s0 (regression, +0.00%): Opcode-aware elimination of false load-use stalls on I/U/J-type instructions after loads yielded zero CoreMark improvement; the benchmark's pointer-chasing critical path is dominated by genuine R-type and STORE dependencies, making false stalls on non-R-type instructions too rare to impact IPC.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r5s2 (regression, -3.01%): A 128-entry BHT regressed CoreMark fitness because the 32-entry table already saturates the benchmark's forward-branch locality, and the larger IF-stage read mux degraded Fmax more than reduced aliasing improved IPC.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r6s1 (broken, n/a): A multi-cycle divider in EX requires a per-instruction state machine, not raw combinational busy/done logic: without a 'started' bit, `div_busy` deadlocks after a pulsed `done` because the instruction never leaves EX, while a level `done` prevents subsequent divides from re-starting.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r6s2 (regression, -6.77%): Non-speculative GHR update at EX-stage resolution leaves history stale for tightly packed branches, causing the 5-bit XOR to increase destructive aliasing in the 32-entry BHT and regress CoreMark IPC.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r7s1 (regression, +0.00%): Even with a correct 3-state divider FSM (fixing the prior 'started'-bit deadlock), a 33-cycle iterative unit yielded zero fitness gain because CoreMark never exercises division; the combinational divider's area was not the critical-path bottleneck, and the added stall logic offset any potential Fmax gain.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r9s2 (regression, +0.00%): Speculative IF-stage GHR update with mispredict restore fixes the history-staleness bug but still yields zero net gain over the bimodal 32-entry BHT; CoreMark's branch working set is small enough that 2-bit saturating counters capture all exploitable locality, leaving global history with no accuracy upside.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r11s0 (regression, -7.98%): Yosys infers efficient byte-select logic from variable shift-by-8 patterns; explicit nested-case byte-lane muxes are larger and slower than the inferred barrel-shifter equivalent.\n\n(End of file - total 10 lines)","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/LESSONS.md","time":{"start":1778753444454,"end":1778753444458}},"id":"prt_e25f797a1002gtrIQ4HGordpo4","sessionID":"ses_1da08a9b3ffeiE0K02BupWfSfi","messageID":"msg_e25f756a6001PI06xNoieMJkDC"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778753445212,"sessionID":"ses_1da08a9b3ffeiE0K02BupWfSfi","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"grep:1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"\"category\":\\s*\"structural\"","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 14 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Add static branch predictor (backward-taken, JAL-always-taken)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core incurs a 1-cycle bubble on every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause IF always speculatively fetches PC+4. CoreMark is loop-heavy, so backward\\nbranches and function calls are frequent. A static predictor that fetches the\\ntarget for backward branches and JAL eliminates the bubble on the common case,\\nimproving IPC with negligible LUT cost (~50 LUTs) and no impact on the critical\\npath.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core incurs a 1-cycle bubble on every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause IF always speculatively fetches PC+4. CoreMark is loop-heavy, so backward\\nbranches and function calls are frequent. A static predictor that fetches the\\ntarget for backward branches and JAL eliminates the bubble on the common case,\\nimproving IPC with negligible LUT cost (~50 LUTs) and no impact on the critical\\npath.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert decode-and-predict logic in the IF stage. When the fetched instruction is\\na BRANCH with a negative immediate (backward loop) or an unconditional JAL, the\\nPC is updated to the computed target instead of PC+4. A 1-bit pred_taken flag is\\nthreaded through the IF/ID and ID/EX bundles. The EX stage suppresses redirect\\nwhen the prediction was correct; it only asserts redirect (triggering IF/ID flush)\\non mispredict. JALR remains unpredicted. This saves one cycle per correctly\\npredicted taken branch or JAL.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add pred_taken bit to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Decode BRANCH/JAL opcodes from imem_data, compute B/J immediates, set predict_taken for backward branches and JAL, and select next_pc from the predicted target when predict_taken is asserted.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"desc...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/forward_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/mem_stage.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 2}\n\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260513-002-r3s1 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260513-001-r3s0', 'hyp-20260513-002-r3s1', 'hyp-20260513-003-r3s2'])\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 3}\n\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Move JALR target resolution to ID stage to cut penalty from 2 to 1 cycle\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"JALR is currently unpredicted in IF and resolved in EX, incurring a 2-cycle\\nmisprediction bubble on every function return and indirect call. CoreMark's\\nlist benchmark makes frequent function calls through pointers, so JALR\\nbubbles are a real IPC limiter.  Because the return address register (x1)\\nis almost always in the regfile when the JALR reaches ID (no forwarding\\nneeded), we can compute the target address in ID stage and redirect IF one\\ncycle earlier, shrinking the penalty to a single flushed fetch slot.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"JALR is currently unpredicted in IF and resolved in EX, incurring a 2-cycle\\nmisprediction bubble on every function return and indirect call. CoreMark's\\nlist benchmark makes frequent function calls through pointers, so JALR\\nbubbles are a real IPC limiter.  Because the return address register (x1)\\nis almost always in the regfile when the JALR reaches ID (no forwarding\\nneeded), we can compute the target address in ID stage and redirect IF one\\ncycle earlier, shrinking the penalty to a single flushed fetch slot.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a JALR target adder in the ID stage: when the decoded instruction is\\nJALR and its rs1 is not the subject of an in-flight load-use hazard, compute\\njalr_target = (rs1_data + imm) & ~1 and assert a new id_redirect signal.\\nThread a jalr_redirected flag through the id_ex_t bundle so the EX stage\\nsuppresses its own redirect for JALRs that were already handled in ID.\\nAt the top level, OR the new id_redirect with the existing ex_redirect to\\ndrive the PC, and adjust flush_if/flush_id so that a JALR in ID is allowed\\nto advance into EX while the speculative fetch in IF is killed.\\nThis structural change shortens the JALR resolution loop by one full stage\\nwithout touching any other instruction type.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct...\n  Line 15: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 5, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The IF stage currently stalls the entire pipeline on every imem_ready=0 cycle,\\ninjecting a NOP bubble into ID/EX. At the same time, during load-use or dmem\\nstalls the PC holds even though imem may be ready, wasting a fetch slot.\\nDecoupling fetch from issue with a 1-entry buffer lets us prefetch one\\ninstruction ahead during downstream stalls and then issue it when imem\\nsubsequently stalls, hiding single-cycle bus bubbles without lengthening\\nany critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure if_stage to hold a 1-entry prefetch buffer (buf_pc, buf_instr,\\nbuf_pred_taken, buf_valid).  The fetch PC advances whenever imem_ready is\\nhigh and there is a free buffer slot.  An instruction is issued to ID from\\nthe buffer if available, otherwise directly from imem_data, and only a\\ntrue NOP is emitted when both sources are empty.  In hazard_unit, stop\\ntreating imem_ready=0 as a global stall_if / flush_if event; instead let\\nif_stage backpressure itself locally.  This structural decoupling turns\\notherwise-wasted fetch slots during load-use/dmem stalls into prefetches,\\nimproving average IPC at the cost of ~66 flops and a few LUTs.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 1-entry prefetch buffer registers and rewrite the issue / fill\\nFSM so that fetch_pc advances on every imem_ready while a slot exists.\\nOutput mux selects buffer, direct imem_data, or NOP based on buffer\\noccupancy and imem_ready.  Accept stall_core (load-use + dmem only)\\nand imem_ready directly instead of the old stall/flush pair.\\n\"...\n  Line 18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX stage alone consumes over\\n6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is dominated by arithmetic primitives.\\nDivision is essentially unused in CoreMark, yet the divider consumes a massive\\namount of area and routing resources that congest the fabric around the critical\\nALU adder path. Removing the combinational divider should relieve routing\\ncongestion and raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX stage alone consumes over\\n6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is dominated by arithmetic primitives.\\nDivision is essentially unused in CoreMark, yet the divider consumes a massive\\namount of area and routing resources that congest the fabric around the critical\\nALU adder path. Removing the combinational divider should relieve routing\\ncongestion and raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extract DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of the combinational ALU into a new\\n`divider.sv` module that performs non-restoring division in 33 cycles.\\nIn `ex_stage`, detect divide ops and assert a `div_busy` signal that\\nstalls the pipeline via the hazard unit until the divider finishes.\\nThe main ALU keeps all I-type ops and the multiplier path (which maps\\nto the on-chip DSP block). Update `hazard_unit` to extend `stall_ex_mem`\\nand `stall_id` when `div_busy` is high. This structural change shrinks\\nthe EX stage significantly, frees routing capacity on the critical path,\\nand should improve median Fmax without hurting CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": ...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the\\nSystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX\\nstage alone consumes over 6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is\\ndominated by arithmetic primitives. Division is essentially unused in\\nCoreMark, yet the combinational divider consumes massive area and\\nrouting resources that congest the fabric around the critical ALU adder\\npath, limiting Fmax. A prior attempt at this change failed because the\\ndivider state machine lacked a proper IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM with a\\n'started' bit, causing deadlock. With a correct FSM implementation,\\nremoving the combinational divider should relieve routing congestion\\nand raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the\\nSystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX\\nstage alone consumes over 6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is\\ndominated by arithmetic primitives. Division is essentially unused in\\nCoreMark, yet the combinational divider consumes massive area and\\nrouting resources that congest the fabric around the critical ALU adder\\npath, limiting Fmax. A prior attempt at this change failed because the\\ndivider state machine lacked a proper IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM with a\\n'started' bit, causing deadlock. With a correct FSM implementation,\\nremoving the combinational divider should relieve routing congestion\\nand raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extract DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of the combinational ALU into a new\\n`divider.sv` module that performs restoring division in 33 cycles.\\nThe divider MUST use a proper 3-state FSM (IDLE, RUNNING, DONE) with\\na registered 'started' bit:\\n  - IDLE:  waiting for start pulse. busy=0, done=0.\\n  - RUNNING: counting dow...\n  Line 24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/alu.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 8}\n\n  Line 27: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r9s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/forward_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 9, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The fitness contract injects ~22% random backpressure on the instruction\\nbus.  Today every !imem_ready cycle asserts a global stall_if / flush_if\\nthat freezes the PC and forces a NOP bubble into ID/EX.  A tiny 2-entry\\nskid buffer decouples fetch from issue: when the downstream pipeline is\\nstalled (load-use, dmem) but the bus is ready, the buffer prefetches\\nahead; when the bus subsequently stalls but the buffer is non-empty, the\\ncore continues issuing without bubbles.  This is a pure structural\\ndecoupling that should raise effective fetch throughput with only\\n~130 flops and no new long combinational paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure if_stage to hold a 2-entry ring buffer (valid, pc,\\ninstr, pred_taken per entry, plus a head pointer and 2-bit count).\\nThe fetch side advances the PC and enqueues the fetched instruction\\nwhenever imem_ready is high, count<2, and there is no redirect.  The\\nissue side selects the buffered head when count>0, otherwise the live\\nimem_data.  A true NOP is emitted only when the buffer is empty and\\nimem_ready is low.  In hazard_unit, remove imem_ready from stall_if\\nand flush_if so the pipeline no longer stalls globally for bus\\nbackpressure; stall_if is asserted only for load-use and dmem stalls,\\nand flush_if only for redirect.  In core.sv, wire io_imemReady into the\\nnew if_stage port and keep all top-level IO unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 2-entry ring buffer inside if...\n  Line 30: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r10s1\", \"title\": \"Add 1-entry instruction skid buffer in IF to hide imem stalls and prefetch during downstream stalls\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The cosim fitness model injects ~22% random imem stalls, and every !imem_ready\\ncycle currently asserts a global stall_if/flush_if that freezes the PC and\\nforces a NOP into ID/EX, wasting the fetch slot.  Worse, during load-use or\\ndmem stalls the PC also holds even when imem_ready is high, so a valid\\ninstruction arriving on the bus is discarded.  A tiny 1-entry skid buffer\\ndecouples fetch from issue: it captures prefetches while the downstream\\npipeline is stalled, and replays them when the bus subsequently stalls.\\nThis hides single-cycle (and occasionally multi-cycle) imem bubbles with\\nonly ~66 flops and a few LUTs of mux logic, improving effective fetch\\nthroughput without lengthening any critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The cosim fitness model injects ~22% random imem stalls, and every !imem_ready\\ncycle currently asserts a global stall_if/flush_if that freezes the PC and\\nforces a NOP into ID/EX, wasting the fetch slot.  Worse, during load-use or\\ndmem stalls the PC also holds even when imem_ready is high, so a valid\\ninstruction arriving on the bus is discarded.  A tiny 1-entry skid buffer\\ndecouples fetch from issue: it captures prefetches while the downstream\\npipeline is stalled, and replays them when the bus subsequently stalls.\\nThis hides single-cycle (and occasionally multi-cycle) imem bubbles with\\nonly ~66 flops and a few LUTs of mux logic, improving effective fetch\\nthroughput without lengthening any critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure if_stage to hold a 1-entry buffer (buf_pc, buf_instr,\\nbuf_pred_taken, buf_valid).  The PC advances whenever imem_ready is high\\nAND there is a place to put the fetched instruction (either issued directly\\nor buffered).  The output to ID is: buffer hit when buf_valid and the bus\\nis stalled or we choose to...\n  Line 33: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Add 1-entry non-blocking store buffer to hide dmem backpressure on stores\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit currently stalls the entire pipeline on every !dmem_ready cycle\\nwhenever any memory operation is in MEM. Stores are roughly 20-25% of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream and the cosim model injects ~22% random dmem stalls, so about\\n5% of total cycles are wasted waiting for the store bus. Because stores do not\\nproduce register results, the instructions behind them are almost always\\nindependent and could continue executing if the store were decoupled. A 1-entry\\nstore buffer captures a stalled store and lets the pipeline advance while the\\nbuffer drains asynchronously, converting store-bus stalls into useful execution\\ncycles with minimal area and no new long combinational paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit currently stalls the entire pipeline on every !dmem_ready cycle\\nwhenever any memory operation is in MEM. Stores are roughly 20-25% of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream and the cosim model injects ~22% random dmem stalls, so about\\n5% of total cycles are wasted waiting for the store bus. Because stores do not\\nproduce register results, the instructions behind them are almost always\\nindependent and could continue executing if the store were decoupled. A 1-entry\\nstore buffer captures a stalled store and lets the pipeline advance while the\\nbuffer drains asynchronously, converting store-bus stalls into useful execution\\ncycles with minimal area and no new long combinational paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a 1-entry store buffer between the MEM stage and the external dmem interface.\\nWhen a store reaches MEM and dmem_ready is low, the buffer captures the address,\\ndata, and byte mask instead of asserting a global stall. The buffer continuously\\nretries the write whenever dmem_ready is high. The top-level dmem outputs are\\nmuxed between the buffer (when valid) and the live M...\n  Line 36: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r12s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-002-r12s1 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r12s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r12s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r12s2'])\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 12}\n\n  Line 39: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r13s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-002-r13s1 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r13s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r13s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r13s2'])\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 13}\n\n  Line 42: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r14s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-002-r14s1 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r14s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r14s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r14s2'])\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 14}\n","metadata":{"matches":14,"truncated":false},"title":"\"category\":\\s*\"structural\"","time":{"start":1778753445206,"end":1778753445211}},"id":"prt_e25f79a66002St2YzgtfswoG1K","sessionID":"ses_1da08a9b3ffeiE0K02BupWfSfi","messageID":"msg_e25f756a6001PI06xNoieMJkDC"}}
