{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778754615410,"sessionID":"ses_1da08a9b3ffeiE0K02BupWfSfi","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"bash:14","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -r '\"category\": \"structural\"' /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/*/experiments/log.jsonl 2>/dev/null | grep '\"outcome\": \"improvement\"' | head -n 10","description":"Search structural improvements across all cores"},"output":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Add static branch predictor (backward-taken, JAL-always-taken)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core incurs a 1-cycle bubble on every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause IF always speculatively fetches PC+4. CoreMark is loop-heavy, so backward\\nbranches and function calls are frequent. A static predictor that fetches the\\ntarget for backward branches and JAL eliminates the bubble on the common case,\\nimproving IPC with negligible LUT cost (~50 LUTs) and no impact on the critical\\npath.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core incurs a 1-cycle bubble on every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause IF always speculatively fetches PC+4. CoreMark is loop-heavy, so backward\\nbranches and function calls are frequent. A static predictor that fetches the\\ntarget for backward branches and JAL eliminates the bubble on the common case,\\nimproving IPC with negligible LUT cost (~50 LUTs) and no impact on the critical\\npath.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert decode-and-predict logic in the IF stage. When the fetched instruction is\\na BRANCH with a negative immediate (backward loop) or an unconditional JAL, the\\nPC is updated to the computed target instead of PC+4. A 1-bit pred_taken flag is\\nthreaded through the IF/ID and ID/EX bundles. The EX stage suppresses redirect\\nwhen the prediction was correct; it only asserts redirect (triggering IF/ID flush)\\non mispredict. JALR remains unpredicted. This saves one cycle per correctly\\npredicted taken branch or JAL.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add pred_taken bit to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Decode BRANCH/JAL opcodes from imem_data, compute B/J immediates, set predict_taken for backward branches and JAL, and select next_pc from the predicted target when predict_taken is asserted.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Thread pred_taken from the IF/ID combinational bundle into the ID/EX pipeline register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the unconditional redirect logic with mispredict detection. redirect is asserted only when a conditional branch outcome differs from pred_taken, or for unpredicte JALR. Correctly predicted branches and JAL no longer flush the pipeline.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add pred_taken bit to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Decode BRANCH/JAL opcodes from imem_data, compute B/J immediates, set predict_taken for backward branches and JAL, and select next_pc from the predicted target when predict_taken is asserted.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Thread pred_taken from the IF/ID combinational bundle into the ID/EX pipeline register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the unconditional redirect logic with mispredict detection. redirect is asserted only when a conditional branch outcome differs from pred_taken, or for unpredicte JALR. Correctly predicted branches and JAL no longer flush the pipeline.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 324.08, \"delta_pct\": 14.59, \"vs_baseline\": 14.59, \"fmax_mhz\": 138.05, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4259699, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10189, \"ff\": 1874, \"seeds\": [133.46, 138.05, 148.35], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T02:11:08.300480Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r1s1 (improvement, +14.59%): Even a trivial static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken) eliminates the taken-branch bubble and yields double-digit IPC gains on loop-heavy benchmarks like CoreMark, with negligible LUT cost.\"}\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/v1/experiments/log.jsonl:{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-017-r8s1\", \"title\": \"One-Deep Store Retirement Slot With Direct Fast Path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core is dominated by the post-DIV/REM timing shape, with\\nmedian Fmax now high enough that broad datapath changes have mostly hurt\\nplacement. The remaining structural opportunity with measured evidence is\\nstore backpressure: the previous one-entry store buffer reduced CoreMark\\ncycles from 4,259,618 to 4,226,169, but its dmem arbitration and MEM-stage\\nmuxing cost slightly more Fmax than the cycle gain recovered.\\n\\nThe promising angle is therefore not a larger buffer, but a smaller and more\\ntiming-local retiring store slot. Keep the zero-wait store path identical to\\nthe current best design, and add state only for the uncommon case where a\\nnormal RAM store reaches MEM while io_dmemReady is low. That targets the same\\nrandom-dStall cycles as the prior structural attempt while avoiding a\\npermanent dmem-port mux on every load/store cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core is dominated by the post-DIV/REM timing shape, with\\nmedian Fmax now high enough that broad datapath changes have mostly hurt\\nplacement. The remaining structural opportunity with measured evidence is\\nstore backpressure: the previous one-entry store buffer reduced CoreMark\\ncycles from 4,259,618 to 4,226,169, but its dmem arbitration and MEM-stage\\nmuxing cost slightly more Fmax than the cycle gain recovered.\\n\\nThe promising angle is therefore not a larger buffer, but a smaller and more\\ntiming-local retiring store slot. Keep the zero-wait store path identical to\\nthe current best design, and add state only for the uncommon case where a\\nnormal RAM store reaches MEM while io_dmemReady is low. That targets the same\\nrandom-dStall cycles as the prior structural attempt while avoiding a\\npermanent dmem-port mux on every load/store cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-deep pending-store retirement slot that is used only on a legal,\\naligned normal-RAM store when io_dmemReady is low. When io_dmemReady is high\\nand the slot is empty, stores drive the existing dmem outputs directly and\\nretire exactly as they do today. When io_dmemReady is low, the MEM stage\\ncaptures the store address, replicated write data, byte mask, and RVFI memory\\nmetadata into the slot, retires that store once through MEM/WB, and lets\\nyounger non-memory instructions continue while the slot drains.\\n\\nThe slot has priority only while valid. Younger loads, younger stores, and all\\nMMIO/marker/UART stores stall until the pending store drains, preserving\\nin-order memory visibility and exact timing-marker behavior. Misaligned or\\ntrapping stores never enter the slot. This should keep most of the cycle-count\\nbenefit seen in the previous store-buffer experiment, but recover Fmax by\\nleaving the direct ready-store/load path structurally close to the current\\nbest RTL and confining the extra muxing to the stall-only drain path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/store_slot.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a one-entry pending-store slot with valid, enqueue, drain-valid, and\\ndrain-ready controls. The entry holds byte address, replicated write data,\\nand byte mask for legal aligned normal-RAM stores only. It is allocated\\nonly when the live store cannot handshake immediately.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Split store completion into a direct fast path and a low-ready enqueue\\npath. Keep the current dmem outputs and MEM/WB behavior unchanged when\\nio_dmemReady is high and no pending store exists. On a bufferable store\\nwith io_dmemReady low, enqueue the precomputed store fields, retire the\\nstore once with correct RVFI mem_addr, mem_wmask, and mem_wdata, and\\nreport explicit MEM backpressure for loads, nonbufferable stores, stores\\nbehind a valid slot, and full-slot cases.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the generic dmem-stall predicate with MEM-stage wait inputs that\\ndistinguish live loads/nonbufferable stores from a draining pending store.\\nStall IF/ID/EX only when the instruction in MEM truly cannot retire or\\nwhen a younger memory operation must wait behind the slot; allow younger\\nnon-memory instructions to proceed while the slot drains.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the pending-store slot and arbitrate the top-level dmem port\\nso the live MEM-stage request uses the direct path whenever the slot is\\nempty, while the slot drives the port only when valid. Preserve the top\\nmodule IO, RVFI NRET=2 fields, strict channel-0 retirement ordering, and\\ntied-off channel 1.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/store_slot.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a one-entry pending-store slot with valid, enqueue, drain-valid, and\\ndrain-ready controls. The entry holds byte address, replicated write data,\\nand byte mask for legal aligned normal-RAM stores only. It is allocated\\nonly when the live store cannot handshake immediately.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Split store completion into a direct fast path and a low-ready enqueue\\npath. Keep the current dmem outputs and MEM/WB behavior unchanged when\\nio_dmemReady is high and no pending store exists. On a bufferable store\\nwith io_dmemReady low, enqueue the precomputed store fields, retire the\\nstore once with correct RVFI mem_addr, mem_wmask, and mem_wdata, and\\nreport explicit MEM backpressure for loads, nonbufferable stores, stores\\nbehind a valid slot, and full-slot cases.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the generic dmem-stall predicate with MEM-stage wait inputs that\\ndistinguish live loads/nonbufferable stores from a draining pending store.\\nStall IF/ID/EX only when the instruction in MEM truly cannot retire or\\nwhen a younger memory operation must wait behind the slot; allow younger\\nnon-memory instructions to proceed while the slot drains.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the pending-store slot and arbitrate the top-level dmem port\\nso the live MEM-stage request uses the direct path whenever the slot is\\nempty, while the slot drives the port only when valid. Preserve the top\\nmodule IO, RVFI NRET=2 fields, strict channel-0 retirement ordering, and\\ntied-off channel 1.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 397.55, \"delta_pct\": 5.89, \"vs_baseline\": 32.06, \"fmax_mhz\": 168.01, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4226169, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5854, \"ff\": 2226, \"seeds\": [168.01, 173.97, 133.92], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"# Implementation Notes\\n\\n## What changed\\n\\n- Added `rtl/store_slot.sv`, a one-entry pending-store slot that holds byte address, replicated write data, and byte mask until `io_dmemReady` accepts the write.\\n- Split the MEM-stage dmem path into a live direct request and an enqueue path. Legal, aligned normal-RAM stores enqueue only when `io_dmemReady` is low and the slot is empty; ready stores keep the existing direct path.\\n- Added precise `mem_wait` classification in `rtl/mem_stage.sv` for live loads, nonbufferable stores, and younger memory operations blocked behind a valid slot.\\n- Updated `rtl/hazard_unit.sv` to consume `mem_wait` instead of rebuilding `!dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_op`, allowing younger non-memory instructions to continue while the slot drains.\\n- Updated `rtl/core.sv` to instantiate the slot and arbitrate the top-level dmem port with slot priority while valid.\\n- Updated the cocotb pipeline source list to include `store_slot.sv`.\\n\\n## Deviations\\n\\n- The slot stores the physical drain fields only. RVFI memory metadata for an enqueued store is still generated and retired through the normal MEM/WB register on the enqueue cycle, so there is no second RVFI event when the slot drains.\\n- `bash formal/run_all.sh` could not run in-place in this sandbox because `formal/riscv-formal` is a symlink to a read-only path outside the writable worktree, and the script failed while removing stale staged files. I copied the same formal tree, wrapper, checks config, and current `rtl/*.sv` into `/tmp/codex-formal-r8s1.FkHGdP` and ran the unchanged `formal/run_all.sh` there.\\n\\n## Concerns\\n\\n- The riscv-formal wrapper ties `io_dmemReady` high, so formal proves the unchanged direct path but does not exercise pending-slot drain behavior. The slot path is covered by lint and structural review here; downstream random-dStall cosim remains the main gate for that behavior.\\n\\n## Local verification\\n\\n- `verilator --lint-only -Wall -Wno-MULTITOP -sv rtl/*.sv`: pass.\\n- `bash formal/run_all.sh` from writable `/tmp` mirror: pass, `Formal: 105 passed, 0 failed`.\\n- `pytest -q test/test_pipeline.py`: pass, `1 passed`.\\n\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-04-28T05:00:14.609332\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 8}\n","metadata":{"output":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Add static branch predictor (backward-taken, JAL-always-taken)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core incurs a 1-cycle bubble on every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause IF always speculatively fetches PC+4. CoreMark is loop-heavy, so backward\\nbranches and function calls are frequent. A static predictor that fetches the\\ntarget for backward branches and JAL eliminates the bubble on the common case,\\nimproving IPC with negligible LUT cost (~50 LUTs) and no impact on the critical\\npath.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core incurs a 1-cycle bubble on every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause IF always speculatively fetches PC+4. CoreMark is loop-heavy, so backward\\nbranches and function calls are frequent. A static predictor that fetches the\\ntarget for backward branches and JAL eliminates the bubble on the common case,\\nimproving IPC with negligible LUT cost (~50 LUTs) and no impact on the critical\\npath.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert decode-and-predict logic in the IF stage. When the fetched instruction is\\na BRANCH with a negative immediate (backward loop) or an unconditional JAL, the\\nPC is updated to the computed target instead of PC+4. A 1-bit pred_taken flag is\\nthreaded through the IF/ID and ID/EX bundles. The EX stage suppresses redirect\\nwhen the prediction was correct; it only asserts redirect (triggering IF/ID flush)\\non mispredict. JALR remains unpredicted. This saves one cycle per correctly\\npredicted taken branch or JAL.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add pred_taken bit to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Decode BRANCH/JAL opcodes from imem_data, compute B/J immediates, set predict_taken for backward branches and JAL, and select next_pc from the predicted target when predict_taken is asserted.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Thread pred_taken from the IF/ID combinational bundle into the ID/EX pipeline register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the unconditional redirect logic with mispredict detection. redirect is asserted only when a conditional branch outcome differs from pred_taken, or for unpredicte JALR. Correctly predicted branches and JAL no longer flush the pipeline.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add pred_taken bit to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Decode BRANCH/JAL opcodes from imem_data, compute B/J immediates, set predict_taken for backward branches and JAL, and select next_pc from the predicted target when predict_taken is asserted.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Thread pred_taken from the IF/ID combinational bundle into the ID/EX pipeline register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the unconditional redirect logic with mispredict detection. redirect is asserted only when a conditional branch outcome differs from pred_taken, or for unpredicte JALR. Correctly predicted branches and JAL no longer flush the pipeline.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 324.08, \"delta_pct\": 14.59, \"vs_baseline\": 14.59, \"fmax_mhz\": 138.05, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4259699, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10189, \"ff\": 1874, \"seeds\": [133.46, 138.05, 148.35], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T02:11:08.300480Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r1s1 (improvement, +14.59%): Even a trivial static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken) eliminates the taken-branch bubble and yields double-digit IPC gains on loop-heavy benchmarks like CoreMark, with negligible LUT cost.\"}\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/v1/experiments/log.jsonl:{\"id\": \"hyp-20260428-017-r8s1\", \"title\": \"One-Deep Store Retirement Slot With Direct Fast Path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core is dominated by the post-DIV/REM timing shape, with\\nmedian Fmax now high enough that broad datapath changes have mostly hurt\\nplacement. The remaining structural opportunity with measured evidence is\\nstore backpressure: the previous one-entry store buffer reduced CoreMark\\ncycles from 4,259,618 to 4,226,169, but its dmem arbitration and MEM-stage\\nmuxing cost slightly more Fmax than the cycle gain recovered.\\n\\nThe promising angle is therefore not a larger buffer, but a smaller and more\\ntiming-local retiring store slot. Keep the zero-wait store path identical to\\nthe current best design, and add state only for the uncommon case where a\\nnormal RAM store reaches MEM while io_dmemReady is low. That targets the same\\nrandom-dStall cycles as the prior structural attempt while avoiding a\\npermanent dmem-port mux on every load/store cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core is dominated by the post-DIV/REM timing shape, with\\nmedian Fmax now high enough that broad datapath changes have mostly hurt\\nplacement. The remaining structural opportunity with measured evidence is\\nstore backpressure: the previous one-entry store buffer reduced CoreMark\\ncycles from 4,259,618 to 4,226,169, but its dmem arbitration and MEM-stage\\nmuxing cost slightly more Fmax than the cycle gain recovered.\\n\\nThe promising angle is therefore not a larger buffer, but a smaller and more\\ntiming-local retiring store slot. Keep the zero-wait store path identical to\\nthe current best design, and add state only for the uncommon case where a\\nnormal RAM store reaches MEM while io_dmemReady is low. That targets the same\\nrandom-dStall cycles as the prior structural attempt while avoiding a\\npermanent dmem-port mux on every load/store cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-deep pending-store retirement slot that is used only on a legal,\\naligned normal-RAM store when io_dmemReady is low. When io_dmemReady is high\\nand the slot is empty, stores drive the existing dmem outputs directly and\\nretire exactly as they do today. When io_dmemReady is low, the MEM stage\\ncaptures the store address, replicated write data, byte mask, and RVFI memory\\nmetadata into the slot, retires that store once through MEM/WB, and lets\\nyounger non-memory instructions continue while the slot drains.\\n\\nThe slot has priority only while valid. Younger loads, younger stores, and all\\nMMIO/marker/UART stores stall until the pending store drains, preserving\\nin-order memory visibility and exact timing-marker behavior. Misaligned or\\ntrapping stores never enter the slot. This should keep most of the cycle-count\\nbenefit seen in the previous store-buffer experiment, but recover Fmax by\\nleaving the direct ready-store/load path structurally close to the current\\nbest RTL and confining the extra muxing to the stall-only drain path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/store_slot.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a one-entry pending-store slot with valid, enqueue, drain-valid, and\\ndrain-ready controls. The entry holds byte address, replicated write data,\\nand byte mask for legal aligned normal-RAM stores only. It is allocated\\nonly when the live store cannot handshake immediately.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Split store completion into a direct fast path and a low-ready enqueue\\npath. Keep the current dmem outputs and MEM/WB behavior unchanged when\\nio_dmemReady is high and no pending store exists. On a bufferable store\\nwith io_dmemReady low, enqueue the precomputed store fields, retire the\\nstore once with correct RVFI mem_addr, mem_wmask, and mem_wdata, and\\nreport explicit MEM backpressure for loads, nonbufferable stores, stores\\nbehind a valid slot, and full-slot cases.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the generic dmem-stall predicate with MEM-stage wait inputs that\\ndistinguish live loads/nonbufferable stores from a draining pending store.\\nStall IF/ID/EX only when the instruction in MEM truly cannot retire or\\nwhen a younger memory operation must wait behind the slot; allow younger\\nnon-memory instructions to proceed while the slot drains.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the pending-store slot and arbitrate the top-level dmem port\\nso the live MEM-stage request uses the direct path whenever the slot is\\nempty, while the slot drives the port only when valid. Preserve the top\\nmodule IO, RVFI NRET=2 fields, strict channel-0 retirement ordering, and\\ntied-off channel 1.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/store_slot.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a one-entry pending-store slot with valid, enqueue, drain-valid, and\\ndrain-ready controls. The entry holds byte address, replicated write data,\\nand byte mask for legal aligned normal-RAM stores only. It is allocated\\nonly when the live store cannot handshake immediately.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Split store completion into a direct fast path and a low-ready enqueue\\npath. Keep the current dmem outputs and MEM/WB behavior unchanged when\\nio_dmemReady is high and no pending store exists. On a bufferable store\\nwith io_dmemReady low, enqueue the precomputed store fields, retire the\\nstore once with correct RVFI mem_addr, mem_wmask, and mem_wdata, and\\nreport explicit MEM backpressure for loads, nonbufferable stores, stores\\nbehind a valid slot, and full-slot cases.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the generic dmem-stall predicate with MEM-stage wait inputs that\\ndistinguish live loads/nonbufferable stores from a draining pending store.\\nStall IF/ID/EX only when the instruction in MEM truly cannot retire or\\nwhen a younger memory operation must wait behind the slot; allow younger\\nnon-memory instructions to proceed while the slot drains.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the pending-store slot and arbitrate the top-level dmem port\\nso the live MEM-stage request uses the direct path whenever the slot is\\nempty, while the slot drives the port only when valid. Preserve the top\\nmodule IO, RVFI NRET=2 fields, strict channel-0 retirement ordering, and\\ntied-off channel 1.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 397.55, \"delta_pct\": 5.89, \"vs_baseline\": 32.06, \"fmax_mhz\": 168.01, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4226169, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5854, \"ff\": 2226, \"seeds\": [168.01, 173.97, 133.92], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"# Implementation Notes\\n\\n## What changed\\n\\n- Added `rtl/store_slot.sv`, a one-entry pending-store slot that holds byte address, replicated write data, and byte mask until `io_dmemReady` accepts the write.\\n- Split the MEM-stage dmem path into a live direct request and an enqueue path. Legal, aligned normal-RAM stores enqueue only when `io_dmemReady` is low and the slot is empty; ready stores keep the existing direct path.\\n- Added precise `mem_wait` classification in `rtl/mem_stage.sv` for live loads, nonbufferable stores, and younger memory operations blocked behind a valid slot.\\n- Updated `rtl/hazard_unit.sv` to consume `mem_wait` instead of rebuilding `!dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_op`, allowing younger non-memory instructions to continue while the slot drains.\\n- Updated `rtl/core.sv` to instantiate the slot and arbitrate the top-level dmem port with slot priority while valid.\\n- Updated the cocotb pipeline source list to include `store_slot.sv`.\\n\\n## Deviations\\n\\n- The slot stores the physical drain fields only. RVFI memory metadata for an enqueued store is still generated and retired through the normal MEM/WB register on the enqueue cycle, so there is no second RVFI event when the slot drains.\\n- `bash formal/run_all.sh` could not run in-place in this sandbox because `formal/riscv-formal` is a symlink to a read-only path outside the writable worktree, and the script failed while removing stale staged files. I copied the same formal tree, wrapper, checks config, and current `rtl/*.sv` into `/tmp/codex-formal-r8s1.FkHGdP` and ran the unchanged `formal/run_all.sh` there.\\n\\n## Concerns\\n\\n- The riscv-formal wrapper ties `io_dmemReady` high, so formal proves the unchanged direct path but does not exercise pending-slot drain behavior. The slot path is covered by lint and structural review here; downstream random-dStall cosim remains the main gate for that behavior.\\n\\n## Local verification\\n\\n- `verilator --lint-only -Wall -Wno-MULTITOP -sv rtl/*.sv`: pass.\\n- `bash formal/run_all.sh` from writable `/tmp` mirror: pass, `Formal: 105 passed, 0 failed`.\\n- `pytest -q test/test_pipeline.py`: pass, `1 passed`.\\n\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-04-28T05:00:14.609332\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 8}\n","exit":0,"description":"Search structural improvements across all cores","truncated":false},"title":"Search structural improvements across all cores","time":{"start":1778754615406,"end":1778754615409}},"id":"prt_e260973a7001SxknqFOTGGm375","sessionID":"ses_1da08a9b3ffeiE0K02BupWfSfi","messageID":"msg_e2605a1f1001H4nxk020YOTWUX"}}
