{"type":"text","timestamp":1778729881838,"sessionID":"ses_1db80468efferIEmTuLHsbaMh6","part":{"id":"prt_e248febb6001aMUx6MaAMD54z0","messageID":"msg_e248fdaec0027r7IHUtkaj5yVa","sessionID":"ses_1db80468efferIEmTuLHsbaMh6","type":"text","text":"The hypothesis has been written to:\n\n**`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-002-r4s1.yaml`**\n\n### Summary\n\n**Category:** structural  \n**Title:** Move JALR target resolution to ID stage to cut penalty from 2 to 1 cycle\n\n**Mechanism:**  \n- Adds a dedicated JALR target adder in the ID stage (`rs1_data + imm & ~1`).  \n- When a JALR reaches ID and its `rs1` is not blocked by a load-use hazard, the stage asserts a new `id_redirect` signal immediately, killing the speculative fetch in IF.  \n- A `jalr_redirected` flag is threaded through the `id_ex_t` bundle so EX knows not to re-assert redirect for the same instruction.  \n- This shortens the JALR misprediction loop by one full pipeline stage (from EX resolution to ID resolution) without affecting branches, JAL, or any other instruction type.\n\n**Why it matters for CoreMark:**  \nCoreMark's list benchmark makes frequent function calls through pointers, which compile to `JALR`. Every `JALR` currently pays a 2-cycle bubble. Cutting that to 1 cycle should improve IPC with minimal LUT/Fmax impact, since the extra adder in ID is small and only active for `JALR`.\n\n**Expected impact:** +4% fitness, medium confidence.","time":{"start":1778729872310,"end":1778729881833}}}
