{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778732993352,"sessionID":"ses_1db4197e9ffexCweu7nh1xESav","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"bash:3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"cat /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | python3 -c \"\nimport sys, json\nlines = [json.loads(l) for l in sys.stdin]\nfor l in lines:\n    if 'r2s2' in l['id'] or 'r3s2' in l['id']:\n        print(f\\\"=== {l['id']} | {l.get('outcome','?')} | fitness={l.get('fitness','?')} ===\\\")\n        print(l.get('title',''))\n        print(l.get('motivation',''))\n        print(l.get('hypothesis',''))\n        print()\n\"","description":"Show predictor experiments"},"output":"=== hyp-20260513-003-r2s2 | regression | fitness=297.42 ===\nAdd 4-entry Return Address Stack for JALR return prediction\nThe existing static predictor eliminates bubbles for backward branches and\nunconditional JAL, but every JALR (function return) still incurs a 1-cycle\nflush because the target is unknown until EX. CoreMark contains frequent\nnested function calls, so returns are a noticeable fraction of the dynamic\ninstruction stream. A tiny Return Address Stack (RAS) pushes the link\naddress on JAL-to-x1/x5 and pops it on JALR-from-x1/x5, predicting the\nreturn target in IF with high accuracy at negligible area cost.\n\n{'motivation': 'The existing static predictor eliminates bubbles for backward branches and\\nunconditional JAL, but every JALR (function return) still incurs a 1-cycle\\nflush because the target is unknown until EX. CoreMark contains frequent\\nnested function calls, so returns are a noticeable fraction of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream. A tiny Return Address Stack (RAS) pushes the link\\naddress on JAL-to-x1/x5 and pops it on JALR-from-x1/x5, predicting the\\nreturn target in IF with high accuracy at negligible area cost.\\n', 'hypothesis': 'Extend the IF-stage predictor with a 4-entry RAS. When the fetched\\ninstruction is a JAL with rd=x1 or x5, push PC+4 onto the stack. When the\\nfetched instruction is a JALR with rs1=x1 or x5 and the stack is non-empty,\\npop the top entry and treat it as the predicted target (pred_taken=1,\\npred_target=ras_top). Thread the predicted target through the IF/ID and\\nID/EX bundles so that EX can verify it. In EX, a JALR only causes a\\nredirect when it was unpredicted (!pred_taken) or when the actual target\\ndiffers from pred_target. The RAS pointer is updated only on non-stalled,\\nnon-flushed cycles. This removes the bubble on the vast majority of\\nreturns.\\n', 'expected_impact': {'fitness_delta_pct': 3, 'confidence': 'medium'}, 'changes': [{'file': 'rtl/core_pkg.sv', 'description': 'Add a 32-bit pred_target field to if_id_t and id_ex_t so the predicted address can flow to EX for mispredict checking.'}, {'file': 'rtl/if_stage.sv', 'description': 'Instantiate a 4-entry RAS. Detect call (JAL rd=x1/x5) and return (JALR rs1=x1/x5) patterns from imem_data, push/pop accordingly, and drive predict_taken/predict_target for returns.'}, {'file': 'rtl/id_stage.sv', 'description': 'Thread the new pred_target bit from the IF/ID bundle into the ID/EX register.'}, {'file': 'rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'description': 'For JALR, assert redirect only on mispredict (unpredicted or predicted target != actual jump_target). Keep existing branch/JAL/misalign logic unchanged.'}]}\n\n=== hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 | broken | fitness=? ===\nAdd 32-entry tagged BTB with 2-bit saturating counters for branch target caching and forward-branch learning\nThe existing static predictor correctly predicts backward branches and JAL,\nbut forward branches that are frequently taken are always mispredicted.\nAdditionally, the combinational branch-target computation in the IF stage\n(opcode decode → immediate extraction → sign-extension → PC adder) may\ncontribute to the critical path. A small Branch Target Buffer can learn\ntaken forward branches, cache targets to shorten the IF-stage path, and\ncoexist safely with the existing static BTFN predictor.\n\n{'motivation': 'The existing static predictor correctly predicts backward branches and JAL,\\nbut forward branches that are frequently taken are always mispredicted.\\nAdditionally, the combinational branch-target computation in the IF stage\\n(opcode decode → immediate extraction → sign-extension → PC adder) may\\ncontribute to the critical path. A small Branch Target Buffer can learn\\ntaken forward branches, cache targets to shorten the IF-stage path, and\\ncoexist safely with the existing static BTFN predictor.\\n', 'hypothesis': 'Add a 32-entry direct-mapped Branch Target Buffer in the IF stage.\\nEach entry stores a valid bit, a 5-bit tag (PC[11:7]), a 30-bit\\nword-aligned target, and a 2-bit saturating counter.  In IF, a BTB\\nhit on a branch or JAL supplies the target directly from a register\\nread, bypassing the combinational immediate+adder path.  Direction\\nprediction remains static-taken for backward branches and JAL, but\\nthe BTB can additionally predict taken for forward branches once\\ntheir counter reaches 2.  In EX, every resolved branch/JAL writes\\nits outcome and target back into the BTB.  JALR is excluded from\\nBTB usage to avoid aliasing noise.  This should improve IPC on\\ntaken forward branches and may raise Fmax by reducing IF-stage\\ncombinational delay.\\n', 'expected_impact': {'fitness_delta_pct': 5, 'confidence': 'medium'}, 'changes': [{'file': 'rtl/core_pkg.sv', 'description': 'Add a packed `btb_entry_t` struct (valid, tag[4:0], target[29:0],\\ncounter[1:0]) for the 32-entry Branch Target Buffer.\\n'}, {'file': 'rtl/if_stage.sv', 'description': 'Add the 32-entry BTB array and combinational read logic.  Use the\\nBTB target on hit for branches/JAL, falling back to the existing\\ncombinational immediate+adder path on miss.  Add `btb_update_en`,\\n`btb_update_idx`, and `btb_update_entry` input ports so EX can\\nwrite resolved outcomes back.  Keep the static backward-taken/JAL\\nprediction as a base; allow BTB to override only to predict taken\\nfor forward branches when the counter is saturated.\\n'}, {'file': 'rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'description': 'Add combinational BTB update logic that drives `btb_update_en`,\\n`btb_update_idx` (from `in.pc[6:2]`), and `btb_update_entry`\\n(valid=1, tag=PC[11:7], target=resolved target, counter updated\\nby the 2-bit saturating counter rule) on every resolved branch\\nor jump.  Gate the update on `!stall && in.valid`.\\n'}, {'file': 'rtl/core.sv', 'description': 'Instantiate new wires `btb_update_en`, `btb_update_idx[4:0]`, and\\n`btb_update_entry` and route them from `ex_stage` outputs to\\n`if_stage` inputs so the BTB can be updated from EX.\\n'}]}\n\n","metadata":{"output":"=== hyp-20260513-003-r2s2 | regression | fitness=297.42 ===\nAdd 4-entry Return Address Stack for JALR return prediction\nThe existing static predictor eliminates bubbles for backward branches and\nunconditional JAL, but every JALR (function return) still incurs a 1-cycle\nflush because the target is unknown until EX. CoreMark contains frequent\nnested function calls, so returns are a noticeable fraction of the dynamic\ninstruction stream. A tiny Return Address Stack (RAS) pushes the link\naddress on JAL-to-x1/x5 and pops it on JALR-from-x1/x5, predicting the\nreturn target in IF with high accuracy at negligible area cost.\n\n{'motivation': 'The existing static predictor eliminates bubbles for backward branches and\\nunconditional JAL, but every JALR (function return) still incurs a 1-cycle\\nflush because the target is unknown until EX. CoreMark contains frequent\\nnested function calls, so returns are a noticeable fraction of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream. A tiny Return Address Stack (RAS) pushes the link\\naddress on JAL-to-x1/x5 and pops it on JALR-from-x1/x5, predicting the\\nreturn target in IF with high accuracy at negligible area cost.\\n', 'hypothesis': 'Extend the IF-stage predictor with a 4-entry RAS. When the fetched\\ninstruction is a JAL with rd=x1 or x5, push PC+4 onto the stack. When the\\nfetched instruction is a JALR with rs1=x1 or x5 and the stack is non-empty,\\npop the top entry and treat it as the predicted target (pred_taken=1,\\npred_target=ras_top). Thread the predicted target through the IF/ID and\\nID/EX bundles so that EX can verify it. In EX, a JALR only causes a\\nredirect when it was unpredicted (!pred_taken) or when the actual target\\ndiffers from pred_target. The RAS pointer is updated only on non-stalled,\\nnon-flushed cycles. This removes the bubble on the vast majority of\\nreturns.\\n', 'expected_impact': {'fitness_delta_pct': 3, 'confidence': 'medium'}, 'changes': [{'file': 'rtl/core_pkg.sv', 'description': 'Add a 32-bit pred_target field to if_id_t and id_ex_t so the predicted address can flow to EX for mispredict checking.'}, {'file': 'rtl/if_stage.sv', 'description': 'Instantiate a 4-entry RAS. Detect call (JAL rd=x1/x5) and return (JALR rs1=x1/x5) patterns from imem_data, push/pop accordingly, and drive predict_taken/predict_target for returns.'}, {'file': 'rtl/id_stage.sv', 'description': 'Thread the new pred_target bit from the IF/ID bundle into the ID/EX register.'}, {'file': 'rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'description': 'For JALR, assert redirect only on mispredict (unpredicted or predicted target != actual jump_target). Keep existing branch/JAL/misalign logic unchanged.'}]}\n\n=== hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 | broken | fitness=? ===\nAdd 32-entry tagged BTB with 2-bit saturating counters for branch target caching and forward-branch learning\nThe existing static predictor correctly predicts backward branches and JAL,\nbut forward branches that are frequently taken are always mispredicted.\nAdditionally, the combinational branch-target computation in the IF stage\n(opcode decode → immediate extraction → sign-extension → PC adder) may\ncontribute to the critical path. A small Branch Target Buffer can learn\ntaken forward branches, cache targets to shorten the IF-stage path, and\ncoexist safely with the existing static BTFN predictor.\n\n{'motivation': 'The existing static predictor correctly predicts backward branches and JAL,\\nbut forward branches that are frequently taken are always mispredicted.\\nAdditionally, the combinational branch-target computation in the IF stage\\n(opcode decode → immediate extraction → sign-extension → PC adder) may\\ncontribute to the critical path. A small Branch Target Buffer can learn\\ntaken forward branches, cache targets to shorten the IF-stage path, and\\ncoexist safely with the existing static BTFN predictor.\\n', 'hypothesis': 'Add a 32-entry direct-mapped Branch Target Buffer in the IF stage.\\nEach entry stores a valid bit, a 5-bit tag (PC[11:7]), a 30-bit\\nword-aligned target, and a 2-bit saturating counter.  In IF, a BTB\\nhit on a branch or JAL supplies the target directly from a register\\nread, bypassing the combinational immediate+adder path.  Direction\\nprediction remains static-taken for backward branches and JAL, but\\nthe BTB can additionally predict taken for forward branches once\\ntheir counter reaches 2.  In EX, every resolved branch/JAL writes\\nits outcome and target back into the BTB.  JALR is excluded from\\nBTB usage to avoid aliasing noise.  This should improve IPC on\\ntaken forward branches and may raise Fmax by reducing IF-stage\\ncombinational delay.\\n', 'expected_impact': {'fitness_delta_pct': 5, 'confidence': 'medium'}, 'changes': [{'file': 'rtl/core_pkg.sv', 'description': 'Add a packed `btb_entry_t` struct (valid, tag[4:0], target[29:0],\\ncounter[1:0]) for the 32-entry Branch Target Buffer.\\n'}, {'file': 'rtl/if_stage.sv', 'description': 'Add the 32-entry BTB array and combinational read logic.  Use the\\nBTB target on hit for branches/JAL, falling back to the existing\\ncombinational immediate+adder path on miss.  Add `btb_update_en`,\\n`btb_update_idx`, and `btb_update_entry` input ports so EX can\\nwrite resolved outcomes back.  Keep the static backward-taken/JAL\\nprediction as a base; allow BTB to override only to predict taken\\nfor forward branches when the counter is saturated.\\n'}, {'file': 'rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'description': 'Add combinational BTB update logic that drives `btb_update_en`,\\n`btb_update_idx` (from `in.pc[6:2]`), and `btb_update_entry`\\n(valid=1, tag=PC[11:7], target=resolved target, counter updated\\nby the 2-bit saturating counter rule) on every resolved branch\\nor jump.  Gate the update on `!stall && in.valid`.\\n'}, {'file': 'rtl/core.sv', 'description': 'Instantiate new wires `btb_update_en`, `btb_update_idx[4:0]`, and\\n`btb_update_entry` and route them from `ex_stage` outputs to\\n`if_stage` inputs so the BTB can be updated from EX.\\n'}]}\n\n","exit":0,"description":"Show predictor experiments","truncated":false},"title":"Show predictor experiments","time":{"start":1778732993348,"end":1778732993351}},"id":"prt_e24bf7f8100137XjBC8nu5NpE4","sessionID":"ses_1db4197e9ffexCweu7nh1xESav","messageID":"msg_e24bec1f7002uiVByp26tCk2lF"}}
