{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1778736177424,"sessionID":"ses_1db13f5b1ffeB0Ml9LQdwP7u82","part":{"id":"prt_e24f02110001ZWSd6M0v2qFR2S","messageID":"msg_e24f013b90011I9V57GjKcj8DZ","sessionID":"ses_1db13f5b1ffeB0Ml9LQdwP7u82","snapshot":"89686d71751ec0dd44b75cd6243e56cc77a97ffe","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778736384590,"sessionID":"ses_1db13f5b1ffeB0Ml9LQdwP7u82","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"bash:7","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -A 20 'hyp-20260514-002-r6s1' /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | head -30","description":"Read multi-cycle divider hypothesis details"},"output":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX stage alone consumes over\\n6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is dominated by arithmetic primitives.\\nDivision is essentially unused in CoreMark, yet the divider consumes a massive\\namount of area and routing resources that congest the fabric around the critical\\nALU adder path. Removing the combinational divider should relieve routing\\ncongestion and raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX stage alone consumes over\\n6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is dominated by arithmetic primitives.\\nDivision is essentially unused in CoreMark, yet the divider consumes a massive\\namount of area and routing resources that congest the fabric around the critical\\nALU adder path. Removing the combinational divider should relieve routing\\ncongestion and raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extract DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of the combinational ALU into a new\\n`divider.sv` module that performs non-restoring division in 33 cycles.\\nIn `ex_stage`, detect divide ops and assert a `div_busy` signal that\\nstalls the pipeline via the hazard unit until the divider finishes.\\nThe main ALU keeps all I-type ops and the multiplier path (which maps\\nto the on-chip DSP block). Update `hazard_unit` to extend `stall_ex_mem`\\nand `stall_id` when `div_busy` is high. This structural change shrinks\\nthe EX stage significantly, frees routing capacity on the critical path,\\nand should improve median Fmax without hurting CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and all combinational divide/rem\\nlogic. Keep the multiplier paths (mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) and the\\nRISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative non-restoring divider. Inputs: clock, reset, start,\\ndividend[31:0], divisor[31:0], signed_div. Outputs: quotient[31:0],\\nremainder[31:0], busy, done. Latency = 33 cycles. busy stays high\\nfrom start until done rises for one cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide ops from `in.ctrl.alu_op`. Route operands to the\\ndivider and assert `div_busy` while the divider is running. Drive\\n`alu_result` from the divider output when a divide op retires.\\nSuppress normal EX/MEM updates during `div_busy`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `div_busy` input. Assert `stall_ex_mem` and `stall_id` when\\n`div_busy` is high so the entire pipeline freezes until division\\ncompletes. Keep existing load-use and bus-stall logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the divider between EX and hazard unit. Wire\\n`div_busy` into the hazard unit. Connect divider inputs from\\n`id_ex_w` operands and `ex_mem_w` controls. No top-level IO\\nchanges.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and all combinational divide/rem\\nlogic. Keep the multiplier paths (mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) and the\\nRISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative non-restoring divider. Inputs: clock, reset, start,\\ndividend[31:0], divisor[31:0], signed_div. Outputs: quotient[31:0],\\nremainder[31:0], busy, done. Latency = 33 cycles. busy stays high\\nfrom start until done rises for one cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide ops from `in.ctrl.alu_op`. Route operands to the\\ndivider and assert `div_busy` while the divider is running. Drive\\n`alu_result` from the divider output when a divide op retires.\\nSuppress normal EX/MEM updates during `div_busy`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `div_busy` input. Assert `stall_ex_mem` and `stall_id` when\\n`div_busy` is high so the entire pipeline freezes until division\\ncompletes. Keep existing load-use and bus-stall logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the divider between EX and hazard unit. Wire\\n`div_busy` into the hazard unit. Connect divider inputs from\\n`id_ex_w` operands and `ex_mem_w` controls. No top-level IO\\nchanges.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"cosim_failed: selftest.elf\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 6, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r6s1 (broken, n/a): A multi-cycle divider in EX requires a per-instruction state machine, not raw combinational busy/done logic: without a 'started' bit, `div_busy` deadlocks after a pulsed `done` because the instruction never leaves EX, while a level `done` prevents subsequent divides from re-starting.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Add 5-bit GHR gshare indexing to existing 32-entry BHT\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the proven 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter table, but index it\\nwith pc[6:2] ^ ghr[4:0] instead of pc[6:2] alone. A 5-bit GHR register\\nshifts in actual branch outcomes from EX-stage resolution, so the BHT\\nentry used for prediction is a function of both the branch address and\\nthe recent global control-flow path. To ensure the EX-stage counter\\nupdate writes the same entry that IF read, the GHR value present at\\nfetch time is snapshotted and threaded through the IF/ID and ID/EX\\npipeline bundles. The update rule (strongly-taken init, saturating\\nincrement/decrement) and the static backward-taken / JAL-always-taken\\nbase policy remain unchanged. This costs only 5 flops for the GHR plus\\n5 bits of pipeline state, with negligible combinational delay (a 5-bit\\nXOR on an already-existing mux path).\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0.\\nUpdate it on every EX-stage branch resolution by shifting in\\nbht_update_taken (ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_update_taken}).\\nReplace the BHT read index pc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr.\\nDrive the current ghr value into the combinational if_id_t output.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr into the ID/EX register so the snapshot reaches EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr so the counter update\\nwrites the exact entry that was read during fetch.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0.\\nUpdate it on every EX-stage branch resolution by shifting in\\nbht_update_taken (ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_update_taken}).\\nReplace the BHT read index pc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr.\\nDrive the current ghr value into the combinational if_id_t output.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr into the ID/EX register so the snapshot reaches EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr so the counter update\\nwrites the exact entry that was read during fetch.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 324.21, \"delta_pct\": -6.77, \"vs_baseline\": 14.63, \"fmax_mhz\": 136.99, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4225388, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10358, \"ff\": 1938, \"seeds\": [137.48, 135.85, 136.99], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:39:37.400024Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 6, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r6s2 (regression, -6.77%): Non-speculative GHR update at EX-stage resolution leaves history stale for tightly packed branches, causing the 5-bit XOR to increase destructive aliasing in the 32-entry BHT and regress CoreMark IPC.\"}\n","metadata":{"output":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX stage alone consumes over\\n6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is dominated by arithmetic primitives.\\nDivision is essentially unused in CoreMark, yet the divider consumes a massive\\namount of area and routing resources that congest the fabric around the critical\\nALU adder path. Removing the combinational divider should relieve routing\\ncongestion and raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX stage alone consumes over\\n6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is dominated by arithmetic primitives.\\nDivision is essentially unused in CoreMark, yet the divider consumes a massive\\namount of area and routing resources that congest the fabric around the critical\\nALU adder path. Removing the combinational divider should relieve routing\\ncongestion and raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extract DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of the combinational ALU into a new\\n`divider.sv` module that performs non-restoring division in 33 cycles.\\nIn `ex_stage`, detect divide ops and assert a `div_busy` signal that\\nstalls the pipeline via the hazard unit until the divider finishes.\\nThe main ALU keeps all I-type ops and the multiplier path (which maps\\nto the on-chip DSP block). Update `hazard_unit` to extend `stall_ex_mem`\\nand `stall_id` when `div_busy` is high. This structural change shrinks\\nthe EX stage significantly, frees routing capacity on the critical path,\\nand should improve median Fmax without hurting CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and all combinational divide/rem\\nlogic. Keep the multiplier paths (mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) and the\\nRISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative non-restoring divider. Inputs: clock, reset, start,\\ndividend[31:0], divisor[31:0], signed_div. Outputs: quotient[31:0],\\nremainder[31:0], busy, done. Latency = 33 cycles. busy stays high\\nfrom start until done rises for one cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide ops from `in.ctrl.alu_op`. Route operands to the\\ndivider and assert `div_busy` while the divider is running. Drive\\n`alu_result` from the divider output when a divide op retires.\\nSuppress normal EX/MEM updates during `div_busy`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `div_busy` input. Assert `stall_ex_mem` and `stall_id` when\\n`div_busy` is high so the entire pipeline freezes until division\\ncompletes. Keep existing load-use and bus-stall logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the divider between EX and hazard unit. Wire\\n`div_busy` into the hazard unit. Connect divider inputs from\\n`id_ex_w` operands and `ex_mem_w` controls. No top-level IO\\nchanges.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and all combinational divide/rem\\nlogic. Keep the multiplier paths (mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) and the\\nRISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative non-restoring divider. Inputs: clock, reset, start,\\ndividend[31:0], divisor[31:0], signed_div. Outputs: quotient[31:0],\\nremainder[31:0], busy, done. Latency = 33 cycles. busy stays high\\nfrom start until done rises for one cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide ops from `in.ctrl.alu_op`. Route operands to the\\ndivider and assert `div_busy` while the divider is running. Drive\\n`alu_result` from the divider output when a divide op retires.\\nSuppress normal EX/MEM updates during `div_busy`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `div_busy` input. Assert `stall_ex_mem` and `stall_id` when\\n`div_busy` is high so the entire pipeline freezes until division\\ncompletes. Keep existing load-use and bus-stall logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the divider between EX and hazard unit. Wire\\n`div_busy` into the hazard unit. Connect divider inputs from\\n`id_ex_w` operands and `ex_mem_w` controls. No top-level IO\\nchanges.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"cosim_failed: selftest.elf\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 6, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r6s1 (broken, n/a): A multi-cycle divider in EX requires a per-instruction state machine, not raw combinational busy/done logic: without a 'started' bit, `div_busy` deadlocks after a pulsed `done` because the instruction never leaves EX, while a level `done` prevents subsequent divides from re-starting.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Add 5-bit GHR gshare indexing to existing 32-entry BHT\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the proven 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter table, but index it\\nwith pc[6:2] ^ ghr[4:0] instead of pc[6:2] alone. A 5-bit GHR register\\nshifts in actual branch outcomes from EX-stage resolution, so the BHT\\nentry used for prediction is a function of both the branch address and\\nthe recent global control-flow path. To ensure the EX-stage counter\\nupdate writes the same entry that IF read, the GHR value present at\\nfetch time is snapshotted and threaded through the IF/ID and ID/EX\\npipeline bundles. The update rule (strongly-taken init, saturating\\nincrement/decrement) and the static backward-taken / JAL-always-taken\\nbase policy remain unchanged. This costs only 5 flops for the GHR plus\\n5 bits of pipeline state, with negligible combinational delay (a 5-bit\\nXOR on an already-existing mux path).\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0.\\nUpdate it on every EX-stage branch resolution by shifting in\\nbht_update_taken (ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_update_taken}).\\nReplace the BHT read index pc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr.\\nDrive the current ghr value into the combinational if_id_t output.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr into the ID/EX register so the snapshot reaches EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr so the counter update\\nwrites the exact entry that was read during fetch.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0.\\nUpdate it on every EX-stage branch resolution by shifting in\\nbht_update_taken (ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_update_taken}).\\nReplace the BHT read index pc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr.\\nDrive the current ghr value into the combinational if_id_t output.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr into the ID/EX register so the snapshot reaches EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr so the counter update\\nwrites the exact entry that was read during fetch.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 324.21, \"delta_pct\": -6.77, \"vs_baseline\": 14.63, \"fmax_mhz\": 136.99, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4225388, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10358, \"ff\": 1938, \"seeds\": [137.48, 135.85, 136.99], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:39:37.400024Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 6, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r6s2 (regression, -6.77%): Non-speculative GHR update at EX-stage resolution leaves history stale for tightly packed branches, causing the 5-bit XOR to increase destructive aliasing in the 32-entry BHT and regress CoreMark IPC.\"}\n","exit":0,"description":"Read multi-cycle divider hypothesis details","truncated":false},"title":"Read multi-cycle divider hypothesis details","time":{"start":1778736384586,"end":1778736384589}},"id":"prt_e24f346d5001P2kuZhnno6bZjQ","sessionID":"ses_1db13f5b1ffeB0Ml9LQdwP7u82","messageID":"msg_e24f013b90011I9V57GjKcj8DZ"}}
