\\"}], \\\"outcome\\\": \\\"broken\\\", \\\"formal_passed\\\": false, \\\"cosim_passed\\\": false, \\\"error\\\": \\\"cosim_failed: selftest.elf\\\", \\\"slot\\\": 1, \\\"round_id\\\": 6, \\\"lesson\\\": \\\"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r6s1 (broken, n/a): A multi-cycle divider in EX requires a per-instruction state machine, not raw combinational busy/done logic: without a 'started' bit, `div_busy` deadlocks after a pulsed `done` because the instruction never leaves EX, while a level `done` prevents subsequent divides from re-starting.\\\"}\\n{\\\"id\\\": \\\"hyp-20260514-003-r6s2\\\", \\\"title\\\": \\\"Add 5-bit GHR gshare indexing to existing 32-entry BHT\\\", \\\"category\\\": \\\"predictor\\\", \\\"motivation\\\": \\\"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\\\nlearn.\\\\n\\\", \\\"hypothesis\\\": {\\\"motivation\\\": \\\"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\\\nlearn.\\\\n\\\", \\\"hypothesis\\\": \\\"Keep the proven 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter table, but index it\\\\nwith pc[6:2] ^ ghr[4:0] instead of pc[6:2] alone. A 5-bit GHR register\\\\nshifts in actual branch outcomes from EX-stage resolution, so the BHT\\\\nentry used for prediction is a function of both the branch address and\\\\nthe recent global control-flow path. To ensure the EX-stage counter\\\\nupdate writes the same entry that IF read, the GHR value present at\\\\nfetch time is snapshotted and threaded through the IF/ID and ID/EX\\\\npipeline bundles. The update rule (strongly-taken init, saturating\\\\nincrement/decrement) and the static backward-taken / JAL-always-taken\\\\nbase policy remain unchanged. This costs only 5 flops for the GHR plus\\\\n5 bits of pipeline state, with negligible combinational delay (a 5-bit\\\\nXOR on an already-existing mux path).\\\\n\\\", \\\"expected_impact\\\": {\\\"fitness_delta_pct\\\": 2, \\\"confidence\\\": \\\"medium\\\"}, \\\"changes\\\": [{\\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/core_pkg.sv\\\", \\\"description\\\": \\\"Add a 5-bit ghr field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\\\"}, {\\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/if_stage.sv\\\", \\\"description\\\": \\\"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0.\\\\nUpdate it on every EX-stage branch resolution by shifting in\\\\nbht_update_taken (ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_update_taken}).\\\\nReplace the BHT read index pc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr.\\\\nDrive the current ghr value into the combinational if_id_t output.\\\\n\\\"}, {\\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/id_stage.sv\\\", \\\"description\\\": \\\"Capture in.ghr into the ID/EX register so the snapshot reaches EX.\\\"}, {\\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/ex_stage.sv\\\", \\\"description\\\": \\\"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr so the counter update\\\\nwrites the exact entry that was read during fetch.\\\\n\\\"}]}, \\\"expected_impact\\\": {\\\"fitness_delta_pct\\\": 2, \\\"confidence\\\": \\\"medium\\\"}, \\\"changes\\\": [{\\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/core_pkg.sv\\\", \\\"description\\\": \\\"Add a 5-bit ghr field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\\\"}, {\\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/if_stage.sv\\\", \\\"description\\\": \\\"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0.\\\\nUpdate it on every EX-stage branch resolution by shifting in\\\\nbht_update_taken (ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_update_taken}).\\\\nReplace the BHT read index pc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr.\\\\nDrive the current ghr value into the combinational if_id_t output.\\\\n\\\"}, {\\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/id_stage.sv\\\", \\\"description\\\": \\\"Capture in.ghr into the ID/EX register so the snapshot reaches EX.\\\"}, {\\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/ex_stage.sv\\\", \\\"description\\\": \\\"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr so the counter update\\\\nwrites the exact entry that was read during fetch.\\\\n\\\"}], \\\"outcome\\\": \\\"regression\\\", \\\"fitness\\\": 324.21, \\\"delta_pct\\\": -6.77, \\\"vs_baseline\\\": 14.63, \\\"fmax_mhz\\\": 136.99, \\\"ipc_coremark\\\": 2e-06, \\\"cycles\\\": 4225388, \\\"iterations\\\": 10, \\\"lut4\\\": 10358, \\\"ff\\\": 1938, \\\"seeds\\\": [137.48, 135.85, 136.99], \\\"formal_passed\\\": true, \\\"cosim_passed\\\": true, \\\"error\\\": null, \\\"implementation_notes\\\": \\\"\\\", \\\"timestamp\\\": \\\"2026-05-14T04:39:37.400024Z\\\", \\\"slot\\\": 2, \\\"round_id\\\": 6, \\\"lesson\\\": \\\"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r6s2 (regression, -6.77%): Non-speculative GHR update at EX-stage resolution leaves history stale for tightly packed branches, causing the 5-bit XOR to increase destructive aliasing in the 32-entry BHT and regress CoreMark IPC.\\\"}\\n\",\"exit\":0,\"description\":\"Read multi-cycle divider hypothesis details\",\"truncated\":false},\"title\":\"Read multi-cycle divider hypothesis details\",\"time\":{\"start\":1778736384586,\"end\":1778736384589}},\"id\":\"prt_e24f346d5001P2kuZhnno6bZjQ\",\"sessionID\":\"ses_1db13f5b1ffeB0Ml9LQdwP7u82\",\"messageID\":\"msg_e24f013b90011I9V57GjKcj8DZ\"}}\n{\"type\":\"step_finish\",\"timestamp\":1778736385065,\"sessionID\":\"ses_1db13f5b1ffeB0Ml9LQdwP7u82\",\"part\":{\"id\":\"prt_e24f34c28001xeyeP9SjIErk5v\",\"reason\":\"tool-calls\",\"snapshot\":\"89686d71751ec0dd44b75cd6243e56cc77a97ffe\",\"messageID\":\"msg_e24f013b90011I9V57GjKcj8DZ\",\"sessionID\":\"ses_1db13f5b1ffeB0Ml9LQdwP7u82\",\"type\":\"step-finish\",\"tokens\":{\"total\":74283,\"input\":342,\"output\":0,\"reasoning\":15284,\"cache\":{\"write\":0,\"read\":59648}},\"cost\":0.07100458}}\n{\"type\":\"step_start\",\"timestamp\":1778736390654,\"sessionID\":\"ses_1db13f5b1ffeB0Ml9LQdwP7u82\",\"part\":{\"id\":\"prt_e24f361fc001kb41QqTci5NFJp\",\"messageID\":\"msg_e24f34c4b0010Z6fofmQjXYt0s\",\"sessionID\":\"ses_1db13f5b1ffeB0Ml9LQdwP7u82\",\"snapshot\":\"89686d71751ec0dd44b75cd6243e56cc77a97ffe\",\"type\":\"step-start\"}}\n{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"timestamp\":1778736443478,\"sessionID\":\"ses_1db13f5b1ffeB0Ml9LQdwP7u82\",\"part\":{\"type\":\"tool\",\"tool\":\"read\",\"callID\":\"read:8\",\"state\":{\"status\":\"completed\",\"input\":{\"filePath\":\"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/formal/checks_si.cfg\"},\"output\":\"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/formal/checks_si.cfg</path>\\n<type>file</type>\\n<content>\\n1: [options]\\n2: isa rv32im\\n3: nret 1\\n4: solver bitwuzla\\n5: \\n6: [depth]\\n7: # BMC depth per check. 2nd column (where present) is the k-induction prove\\n8: # depth. Keep depths matched to the current pipeline so bugs within ~20\\n9: # cycles of any symbolic instruction stream are exposed.\\n10: insn          20\\n11: reg       10  20\\n12: pc_fwd    10  20\\n13: pc_bwd    10  20\\n14: causal    10  20\\n15: # unique   — no two retirements share rvfi_order (catches double-retire)\\n16: # cover    — sanity that the CPU retires (prevents vacuous-pass suites)\\n17: # ill      — illegal instructions must trap; rvfi_trap from decoder.is_illegal\\n18: # liveness — CPU makes forward progress under any symbolic stream\\n19: unique     1 10 20\\n20: cover      1    20\\n21: ill             20\\n22: liveness   1 10 20\\n23: \\n24: [defines]\\n25: `define RISCV_FORMAL_ALIGNED_MEM\\n26: # RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS — fast mode. Same as checks.cfg. See checks.cfg for\\n27: # the full rationale on what ALTOPS does and does not prove. M-extension\\n28: # arithmetic correctness is covered by test/test_alu.py and `make formal-deep`.\\n29: `define RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS\\n30: \\n31: [cover]\\n32: # Sanity cover: the CPU must retire at least one non-trapping instruction.\\n33: always @* if (!reset) cover (rvfi_valid && !rvfi_trap);\\n34: \\n35: [verilog-files]\\n36: # run_all.sh rebuilds this section from the actual rtl/ glob; the list\\n37: # below is overwritten before genchecks runs. Kept as a placeholder so\\n38: # the section is syntactically present for any reader inspecting the cfg.\\n39: @basedir@/cores/@core@/core.sv\\n40: @basedir@/cores/@core@/wrapper.sv\\n\\n(End of file - total 40 lines)\\n</content>\",\"metadata\":{\"preview\":\"[options]\\nisa rv32im\\nnret 1\\nsolver bitwuzla\\n\\n[depth]\\n# BMC depth per check. 2nd column (where present) is the k-induction prove\\n# depth. Keep depths matched to the current pipeline so bugs within ~20\\n# cycles of any symbolic instruction stream are exposed.\\ninsn          20\\nreg       10  20\\npc_fwd    10  20\\npc_bwd    10  20\\ncausal    10  20\\n# unique   — no two retirements share rvfi_order (catches double-retire)\\n# cover    — sanity that the CPU retires (prevents vacuous-pass suites)\\n# ill      — illegal instructions must trap; rvfi_trap from decoder.is_illegal\\n# liveness — CPU makes forward progress under any symbolic stream\\nunique     1 10 20\\ncover      1    20\",\"truncated\":false,\"loaded\":[]},\"title\":\"formal/checks_si.cfg\",\"time\":{\"start\":1778736443467,\"end\":1778736443476}},\"id\":\"prt_e24f42eff001BGtQtUGULgAFac\",\"sessionID\":\"ses_1db13f5b1ffeB0Ml9LQdwP7u82\",\"messageID\":\"msg_e24f34c4b0010Z6fofmQjXYt0s\"}}\n{\"type\":\"step_finish\",\"timestamp\":1778736443983,\"sessionID\":\"ses_1db13f5b1ffeB0Ml9LQdwP7u82\",\"part\":{\"id\":\"prt_e24f4324e0016FIgGbF2YQ7RyT\",\"reason\":\"tool-calls\",\"snapshot\":\"89686d71751ec0dd44b75cd6243e56cc77a97ffe\",\"messageID\":\"msg_e24f34c4b0010Z6fofmQjXYt0s\",\"sessionID\":\"ses_1db13f5b1ffeB0Ml9LQdwP7u82\",\"type\":\"step-finish\",\"tokens\":{\"total\":80395,\"input\":6822,\"output\":0,\"reasoning\":3946,\"cache\":{\"write\":0,\"read\":70144}},\"cost\":0.03348794}}\n{\"type\":\"step_start\",\"timestamp\":1778736448710,\"sessionID\":\"ses_1db13f5b1ffeB0Ml9LQdwP7u82\",\"part\":{\"id\":\"prt_e24f444c5001RDZIR1JUdEAqrU\",\"messageID\":\"msg_e24f43274001YY6wwRFC9Jm3JI\",\"sessionID\":\"ses_1db13f5b1ffeB0Ml9LQdwP7u82\",\"snapshot\":\"89686d71751ec0dd44b75cd6243e56cc77a97ffe\",\"type\":\"step-start\"}}\n{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"timestamp\":1778736470158,\"sessionID\":\"ses_1db13f5b1ffeB0Ml9LQdwP7u82\",\"part\":{\"type\":\"tool\",\"tool\":\"bash\",\"callID\":\"bash:9\",\"state\":{\"status\":\"completed\",\"input\":{\"command\":\"python3 -c \\\"\\nimport json\\nwith open('/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl') as f:\\n    for line in f:\\n        d = json.loads(line)\\n        if d.get('id') == 'hyp-20260514-002-r4s1':\\n            print(json.dumps(d, indent=2))\\n            break\\n\\\"\",\"description\":\"Get full JALR hypothesis record\"},\"output\":\"{\\n  \\\"id\\\": \\\"hyp-20260514-002-r4s1\\\",\\n  \\\"title\\\": \\\"Move JALR target resolution to ID stage to cut penalty from 2 to 1 cycle\\\",\\n  \\\"category\\\": \\\"structural\\\",\\n  \\\"motivation\\\": \\\"JALR is currently unpredicted in IF and resolved in EX, incurring a 2-cycle\\\\nmisprediction bubble on every function return and indirect call. CoreMark's\\\\nlist benchmark makes frequent function calls through pointers, so JALR\\\\nbubbles are a real IPC limiter.  Because the return address register (x1)\\\\nis almost always in the regfile when the JALR reaches ID (no forwarding\\\\nneeded), we can compute the target address in ID stage and redirect IF one\\\\ncycle earlier, shrinking the penalty to a single flushed fetch slot.\\\\n\\\",\\n  \\\"hypothesis\\\": {\\n    \\\"motivation\\\": \\\"JALR is currently unpredicted in IF and resolved in EX, incurring a 2-cycle\\\\nmisprediction bubble on every function return and indirect call. CoreMark's\\\\nlist benchmark makes frequent function calls through pointers, so JALR\\\\nbubbles are a real IPC limiter.  Because the return address register (x1)\\\\nis almost always in the regfile when the JALR reaches ID (no forwarding\\\\nneeded), we can compute the target address in ID stage and redirect IF one\\\\ncycle earlier, shrinking the penalty to a single flushed fetch slot.\\\\n\\\",\\n    \\\"hypothesis\\\": \\\"Add a JALR target adder in the ID stage: when the decoded instruction is\\\\nJALR and its rs1 is not the subject of an in-flight load-use hazard, compute\\\\njalr_target = (rs1_data + imm) & ~1 and assert a new id_redirect signal.\\\\nThread a jalr_redirected flag through the id_ex_t bundle so the EX stage\\\\nsuppresses its own redirect for JALRs that were already handled in ID.\\\\nAt the top level, OR the new id_redirect with the existing ex_redirect to\\\\ndrive the PC, and adjust flush_if/flush_id so that a JALR in ID is allowed\\\\nto advance into EX while the speculative fetch in IF is killed.\\\\nThis structural change shortens the JALR resolution loop by one full stage\\\\nwithout touching any other instruction type.\\\\n\\\",\\n    \\\"expected_impact\\\": {\\n      \\\"fitness_delta_pct\\\": 4,\\n      \\\"confidence\\\": \\\"medium\\\"\\n    },\\n    \\\"changes\\\": [\\n      {\\n        \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/core_pkg.sv\\\",\\n        \\\"description\\\": \\\"Add jalr_redirected bit to id_ex_t bundle.\\\"\\n      },\\n      {\\n        \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/id_stage.sv\\\",\\n        \\\"description\\\": \\\"Compute JALR target from regfile rs1 + imm. Assert id_redirect when JALR has no load-use hazard on rs1. Set jalr_redirected flag in the ID/EX register.\\\"\\n      },\\n      {\\n        \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/ex_stage.sv\\\",\\n        \\\"description\\\": \\\"Suppress redirect for JALR instructions when jalr_redirected is set; otherwise keep existing redirect logic unchanged.\\\"\\n      },\\n      {\\n        \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\\\",\\n        \\\"description\\\": \\\"Add id_redirect input to flush_if logic. Ensure load-use hazard on JALR rs1 stalls ID (do not assert id_redirect until hazard clears).\\\"\\n      },\\n      {\\n        \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/core.sv\\\",\\n        \\\"description\\\": \\\"Wire new id_redirect from id_stage to hazard_unit and PC logic. Combine id_redirect with ex_redirect for top-level redirect and flush control.\\\"\\n      }\\n    ]\\n  },\\n  \\\"expected_impact\\\": {\\n    \\\"fitness_delta_pct\\\": 4,\\n    \\\"confidence\\\": \\\"medium\\\"\\n  },\\n  \\\"changes\\\": [\\n    {\\n      \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/core_pkg.sv\\\",\\n      \\\"description\\\": \\\"Add jalr_redirected bit to id_ex_t bundle.\\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/id_stage.sv\\\",\\n      \\\"description\\\": \\\"Compute JALR target from regfile rs1 + imm. Assert id_redirect when JALR has no load-use hazard on rs1. Set jalr_redirected flag in the ID/EX register.\\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/ex_stage.sv\\\",\\n      \\\"description\\\": \\\"Suppress redirect for JALR instructions when jalr_redirected is set; otherwise keep existing redirect logic unchanged.\\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\\\",\\n      \\\"description\\\": \\\"Add id_redirect input to flush_if logic. Ensure load-use hazard on JALR rs1 stalls ID (do not assert id_redirect until hazard clears).\\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/core.sv\\\",\\n      \\\"description\\\": \\\"Wire new id_redirect from id_stage to hazard_unit and PC logic. Combine id_redirect with ex_redirect for top-level redirect and flush control.\\\"\\n    }\\n  ],\\n  \\\"outcome\\\": \\\"regression\\\",\\n  \\\"fitness\\\": 324.08,\\n  \\\"delta_pct\\\": 0.0,\\n  \\\"vs_baseline\\\": 14.59,\\n  \\\"fmax_mhz\\\": 138.05,\\n  \\\"ipc_coremark\\\": 2e-06,\\n  \\\"cycles\\\": 4259699,\\n  \\\"iterations\\\": 10,\\n  \\\"lut4\\\": 10189,\\n  \\\"ff\\\": 1874,\\n  \\\"seeds\\\": [\\n    133.46,\\n    138.05,\\n    148.35\\n  ],\\n  \\\"formal_passed\\\": true,\\n  \\\"cosim_passed\\\": true,\\n  \\\"error\\\": null,\\n  \\\"implementation_notes\\\": \\\"\\\",\\n  \\\"timestamp\\\": \\\"2026-05-14T04:05:58.810116Z\\\",\\n  \\\"slot\\\": 1,\\n  \\\"round_id\\\": 4\\n}\\n\",\"metadata\":{\"output\":\"{\\n  \\\"id\\\": \\\"hyp-20260514-002-r4s1\\\",\\n  \\\"title\\\": \\\"Move JALR target resolution to ID stage to cut penalty from 2 to 1 cycle\\\",\\n  \\\"category\\\": \\\"structural\\\",\\n  \\\"motivation\\\": \\\"JALR is currently unpredicted in IF and resolved in EX, incurring a 2-cycle\\\\nmisprediction bubble on every function return and indirect call. CoreMark's\\\\nlist benchmark makes frequent function calls through pointers, so JALR\\\\nbubbles are a real IPC limiter.  Because the return address register (x1)\\\\nis almost always in the regfile when the JALR reaches ID (no forwarding\\\\nneeded), we can compute the target address in ID stage and redirect IF one\\\\ncycle earlier, shrinking the penalty to a single flushed fetch slot.\\\\n\\\",\\n  \\\"hypothesis\\\": {\\n    \\\"motivation\\\": \\\"JALR is currently unpredicted in IF and resolved in EX, incurring a 2-cycle\\\\nmisprediction bubble on every function return and indirect call. CoreMark's\\\\nlist benchmark makes frequent function calls through pointers, so JALR\\\\nbubbles are a real IPC limiter.  Because the return address register (x1)\\\\nis almost always in the regfile when the JALR reaches ID (no forwarding\\\\nneeded), we can compute the target address in ID stage and redirect IF one\\\\ncycle earlier, shrinking the penalty to a single flushed fetch slot.\\\\n\\\",\\n    \\\"hypothesis\\\": \\\"Add a JALR target adder in the ID stage: when the decoded instruction is\\\\nJALR and its rs1 is not the subject of an in-flight load-use hazard, compute\\\\njalr_target = (rs1_data + imm) & ~1 and assert a new id_redirect signal.\\\\nThread a jalr_redirected flag through the id_ex_t bundle so the EX stage\\\\nsuppresses its own redirect for JALRs that were already handled in ID.\\\\nAt the top level, OR the new id_redirect with the existing ex_redirect to\\\\ndrive the PC, and adjust flush_if/flush_id so that a JALR in ID is allowed\\\\nto advance into EX while the speculative fetch in IF is killed.\\\\nThis structural change shortens the JALR resolution loop by one full stage\\\\nwithout touching any other instruction type.\\\\n\\\",\\n    \\\"expected_impact\\\": {\\n      \\\"fitness_delta_pct\\\": 4,\\n      \\\"confidence\\\": \\\"medium\\\"\\n    },\\n    \\\"changes\\\": [\\n      {\\n        \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/core_pkg.sv\\\",\\n        \\\"description\\\": \\\"Add jalr_redirected bit to id_ex_t bundle.\\\"\\n      },\\n      {\\n        \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/id_stage.sv\\\",\\n        \\\"description\\\": \\\"Compute JALR target from regfile rs1 + imm. Assert id_redirect when JALR has no load-use hazard on rs1. Set jalr_redirected flag in the ID/EX register.\\\"\\n      },\\n      {\\n        \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/ex_stage.sv\\\",\\n        \\\"description\\\": \\\"Suppress redirect for JALR instructions when jalr_redirected is set; otherwise keep existing redirect logic unchanged.\\\"\\n      },\\n      {\\n        \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\\\",\\n        \\\"description\\\": \\\"Add id_redirect input to flush_if logic. Ensure load-use hazard on JALR rs1 stalls ID (do not assert id_redirect until hazard clears).\\\"\\n      },\\n      {\\n        \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/core.sv\\\",\\n        \\\"description\\\": \\\"Wire new id_redirect from id_stage to hazard_unit and PC logic. Combine id_redirect with ex_redirect for top-level redirect and flush control.\\\"\\n      }\\n    ]\\n  },\\n  \\\"expected_impact\\\": {\\n    \\\"fitness_delta_pct\\\": 4,\\n    \\\"confidence\\\": \\\"medium\\\"\\n  },\\n  \\\"changes\\\": [\\n    {\\n      \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/core_pkg.sv\\\",\\n      \\\"description\\\": \\\"Add jalr_redirected bit to id_ex_t bundle.\\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/id_stage.sv\\\",\\n      \\\"description\\\": \\\"Compute JALR target from regfile rs1 + imm. Assert id_redirect when JALR has no load-use hazard on rs1. Set jalr_redirected flag in the ID/EX register.\\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/ex_stage.sv\\\",\\n      \\\"description\\\": \\\"Suppress redirect for JALR instructions when jalr_redirected is set; otherwise keep existing redirect logic unchanged.\\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\\\",\\n      \\\"description\\\": \\\"Add id_redirect input to flush_if logic. Ensure load-use hazard on JALR rs1 stalls ID (do not assert id_redirect until hazard clears).\\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\\"file\\\": \\\"rtl/core.sv\\\",\\n      \\\"description\\\": \\\"Wire new id_redirect from id_stage to hazard_unit and PC logic. Combine id_redirect with ex_redirect for top-level redirect and flush control.\\\"\\n    }\\n  ],\\n  \\\"outcome\\\": \\\"regression\\\",\\n  \\\"fitness\\\": 324.08,\\n  \\\"delta_pct\\\": 0.0,\\n  \\\"vs_baseline\\\": 14.59,\\n  \\\"fmax_mhz\\\": 138.05,\\n  \\\"ipc_coremark\\\": 2e-06,\\n  \\\"cycles\\\": 4259699,\\n  \\\"iterations\\\": 10,\\n  \\\"lut4\\\": 10189,\\n  \\\"ff\\\": 1874,\\n  \\\"seeds\\\": [\\n    