{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778741472698,"sessionID":"ses_1dac84d93ffeovARKJoi7VUZtl","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"functions.bash:2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -E '\"category\": \"structural\"' cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | head -20","description":"List prior structural experiments"},"output":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Add static branch predictor (backward-taken, JAL-always-taken)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core incurs a 1-cycle bubble on every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause IF always speculatively fetches PC+4. CoreMark is loop-heavy, so backward\\nbranches and function calls are frequent. A static predictor that fetches the\\ntarget for backward branches and JAL eliminates the bubble on the common case,\\nimproving IPC with negligible LUT cost (~50 LUTs) and no impact on the critical\\npath.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core incurs a 1-cycle bubble on every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause IF always speculatively fetches PC+4. CoreMark is loop-heavy, so backward\\nbranches and function calls are frequent. A static predictor that fetches the\\ntarget for backward branches and JAL eliminates the bubble on the common case,\\nimproving IPC with negligible LUT cost (~50 LUTs) and no impact on the critical\\npath.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert decode-and-predict logic in the IF stage. When the fetched instruction is\\na BRANCH with a negative immediate (backward loop) or an unconditional JAL, the\\nPC is updated to the computed target instead of PC+4. A 1-bit pred_taken flag is\\nthreaded through the IF/ID and ID/EX bundles. The EX stage suppresses redirect\\nwhen the prediction was correct; it only asserts redirect (triggering IF/ID flush)\\non mispredict. JALR remains unpredicted. This saves one cycle per correctly\\npredicted taken branch or JAL.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add pred_taken bit to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Decode BRANCH/JAL opcodes from imem_data, compute B/J immediates, set predict_taken for backward branches and JAL, and select next_pc from the predicted target when predict_taken is asserted.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Thread pred_taken from the IF/ID combinational bundle into the ID/EX pipeline register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the unconditional redirect logic with mispredict detection. redirect is asserted only when a conditional branch outcome differs from pred_taken, or for unpredicte JALR. Correctly predicted branches and JAL no longer flush the pipeline.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add pred_taken bit to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Decode BRANCH/JAL opcodes from imem_data, compute B/J immediates, set predict_taken for backward branches and JAL, and select next_pc from the predicted target when predict_taken is asserted.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Thread pred_taken from the IF/ID combinational bundle into the ID/EX pipeline register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the unconditional redirect logic with mispredict detection. redirect is asserted only when a conditional branch outcome differs from pred_taken, or for unpredicte JALR. Correctly predicted branches and JAL no longer flush the pipeline.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 324.08, \"delta_pct\": 14.59, \"vs_baseline\": 14.59, \"fmax_mhz\": 138.05, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4259699, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10189, \"ff\": 1874, \"seeds\": [133.46, 138.05, 148.35], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T02:11:08.300480Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r1s1 (improvement, +14.59%): Even a trivial static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken) eliminates the taken-branch bubble and yields double-digit IPC gains on loop-heavy benchmarks like CoreMark, with negligible LUT cost.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/forward_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/mem_stage.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 2}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260513-002-r3s1 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260513-001-r3s0', 'hyp-20260513-002-r3s1', 'hyp-20260513-003-r3s2'])\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 3}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Move JALR target resolution to ID stage to cut penalty from 2 to 1 cycle\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"JALR is currently unpredicted in IF and resolved in EX, incurring a 2-cycle\\nmisprediction bubble on every function return and indirect call. CoreMark's\\nlist benchmark makes frequent function calls through pointers, so JALR\\nbubbles are a real IPC limiter.  Because the return address register (x1)\\nis almost always in the regfile when the JALR reaches ID (no forwarding\\nneeded), we can compute the target address in ID stage and redirect IF one\\ncycle earlier, shrinking the penalty to a single flushed fetch slot.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"JALR is currently unpredicted in IF and resolved in EX, incurring a 2-cycle\\nmisprediction bubble on every function return and indirect call. CoreMark's\\nlist benchmark makes frequent function calls through pointers, so JALR\\nbubbles are a real IPC limiter.  Because the return address register (x1)\\nis almost always in the regfile when the JALR reaches ID (no forwarding\\nneeded), we can compute the target address in ID stage and redirect IF one\\ncycle earlier, shrinking the penalty to a single flushed fetch slot.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a JALR target adder in the ID stage: when the decoded instruction is\\nJALR and its rs1 is not the subject of an in-flight load-use hazard, compute\\njalr_target = (rs1_data + imm) & ~1 and assert a new id_redirect signal.\\nThread a jalr_redirected flag through the id_ex_t bundle so the EX stage\\nsuppresses its own redirect for JALRs that were already handled in ID.\\nAt the top level, OR the new id_redirect with the existing ex_redirect to\\ndrive the PC, and adjust flush_if/flush_id so that a JALR in ID is allowed\\nto advance into EX while the speculative fetch in IF is killed.\\nThis structural change shortens the JALR resolution loop by one full stage\\nwithout touching any other instruction type.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add jalr_redirected bit to id_ex_t bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute JALR target from regfile rs1 + imm. Assert id_redirect when JALR has no load-use hazard on rs1. Set jalr_redirected flag in the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Suppress redirect for JALR instructions when jalr_redirected is set; otherwise keep existing redirect logic unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add id_redirect input to flush_if logic. Ensure load-use hazard on JALR rs1 stalls ID (do not assert id_redirect until hazard clears).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new id_redirect from id_stage to hazard_unit and PC logic. Combine id_redirect with ex_redirect for top-level redirect and flush control.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add jalr_redirected bit to id_ex_t bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute JALR target from regfile rs1 + imm. Assert id_redirect when JALR has no load-use hazard on rs1. Set jalr_redirected flag in the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Suppress redirect for JALR instructions when jalr_redirected is set; otherwise keep existing redirect logic unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add id_redirect input to flush_if logic. Ensure load-use hazard on JALR rs1 stalls ID (do not assert id_redirect until hazard clears).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new id_redirect from id_stage to hazard_unit and PC logic. Combine id_redirect with ex_redirect for top-level redirect and flush control.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 324.08, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 14.59, \"fmax_mhz\": 138.05, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4259699, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10189, \"ff\": 1874, \"seeds\": [133.46, 138.05, 148.35], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:05:58.810116Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 4}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 5, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The IF stage currently stalls the entire pipeline on every imem_ready=0 cycle,\\ninjecting a NOP bubble into ID/EX. At the same time, during load-use or dmem\\nstalls the PC holds even though imem may be ready, wasting a fetch slot.\\nDecoupling fetch from issue with a 1-entry buffer lets us prefetch one\\ninstruction ahead during downstream stalls and then issue it when imem\\nsubsequently stalls, hiding single-cycle bus bubbles without lengthening\\nany critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure if_stage to hold a 1-entry prefetch buffer (buf_pc, buf_instr,\\nbuf_pred_taken, buf_valid).  The fetch PC advances whenever imem_ready is\\nhigh and there is a free buffer slot.  An instruction is issued to ID from\\nthe buffer if available, otherwise directly from imem_data, and only a\\ntrue NOP is emitted when both sources are empty.  In hazard_unit, stop\\ntreating imem_ready=0 as a global stall_if / flush_if event; instead let\\nif_stage backpressure itself locally.  This structural decoupling turns\\notherwise-wasted fetch slots during load-use/dmem stalls into prefetches,\\nimproving average IPC at the cost of ~66 flops and a few LUTs.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 1-entry prefetch buffer registers and rewrite the issue / fill\\nFSM so that fetch_pc advances on every imem_ready while a slot exists.\\nOutput mux selects buffer, direct imem_data, or NOP based on buffer\\noccupancy and imem_ready.  Accept stall_core (load-use + dmem only)\\nand imem_ready directly instead of the old stall/flush pair.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove imem_stall from stall_if so that the pipeline only stalls for\\nload-use hazards and dmem stalls.  Reduce flush_if to redirect only;\\nimem backpressure is now handled locally inside if_stage.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire io_imemReady directly to if_stage and connect the new stall_core\\nsignal from hazard_unit to if_stage.  Remove the old stall_if / flush_if\\nplumbing that coupled imem backpressure to the whole pipeline.\\n\"}]}}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX stage alone consumes over\\n6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is dominated by arithmetic primitives.\\nDivision is essentially unused in CoreMark, yet the divider consumes a massive\\namount of area and routing resources that congest the fabric around the critical\\nALU adder path. Removing the combinational divider should relieve routing\\ncongestion and raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX stage alone consumes over\\n6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is dominated by arithmetic primitives.\\nDivision is essentially unused in CoreMark, yet the divider consumes a massive\\namount of area and routing resources that congest the fabric around the critical\\nALU adder path. Removing the combinational divider should relieve routing\\ncongestion and raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extract DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of the combinational ALU into a new\\n`divider.sv` module that performs non-restoring division in 33 cycles.\\nIn `ex_stage`, detect divide ops and assert a `div_busy` signal that\\nstalls the pipeline via the hazard unit until the divider finishes.\\nThe main ALU keeps all I-type ops and the multiplier path (which maps\\nto the on-chip DSP block). Update `hazard_unit` to extend `stall_ex_mem`\\nand `stall_id` when `div_busy` is high. This structural change shrinks\\nthe EX stage significantly, frees routing capacity on the critical path,\\nand should improve median Fmax without hurting CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and all combinational divide/rem\\nlogic. Keep the multiplier paths (mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) and the\\nRISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative non-restoring divider. Inputs: clock, reset, start,\\ndividend[31:0], divisor[31:0], signed_div. Outputs: quotient[31:0],\\nremainder[31:0], busy, done. Latency = 33 cycles. busy stays high\\nfrom start until done rises for one cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide ops from `in.ctrl.alu_op`. Route operands to the\\ndivider and assert `div_busy` while the divider is running. Drive\\n`alu_result` from the divider output when a divide op retires.\\nSuppress normal EX/MEM updates during `div_busy`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `div_busy` input. Assert `stall_ex_mem` and `stall_id` when\\n`div_busy` is high so the entire pipeline freezes until division\\ncompletes. Keep existing load-use and bus-stall logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the divider between EX and hazard unit. Wire\\n`div_busy` into the hazard unit. Connect divider inputs from\\n`id_ex_w` operands and `ex_mem_w` controls. No top-level IO\\nchanges.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and all combinational divide/rem\\nlogic. Keep the multiplier paths (mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) and the\\nRISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative non-restoring divider. Inputs: clock, reset, start,\\ndividend[31:0], divisor[31:0], signed_div. Outputs: quotient[31:0],\\nremainder[31:0], busy, done. Latency = 33 cycles. busy stays high\\nfrom start until done rises for one cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide ops from `in.ctrl.alu_op`. Route operands to the\\ndivider and assert `div_busy` while the divider is running. Drive\\n`alu_result` from the divider output when a divide op retires.\\nSuppress normal EX/MEM updates during `div_busy`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `div_busy` input. Assert `stall_ex_mem` and `stall_id` when\\n`div_busy` is high so the entire pipeline freezes until division\\ncompletes. Keep existing load-use and bus-stall logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the divider between EX and hazard unit. Wire\\n`div_busy` into the hazard unit. Connect divider inputs from\\n`id_ex_w` operands and `ex_mem_w` controls. No top-level IO\\nchanges.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"cosim_failed: selftest.elf\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 6, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r6s1 (broken, n/a): A multi-cycle divider in EX requires a per-instruction state machine, not raw combinational busy/done logic: without a 'started' bit, `div_busy` deadlocks after a pulsed `done` because the instruction never leaves EX, while a level `done` prevents subsequent divides from re-starting.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the\\nSystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX\\nstage alone consumes over 6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is\\ndominated by arithmetic primitives. Division is essentially unused in\\nCoreMark, yet the combinational divider consumes massive area and\\nrouting resources that congest the fabric around the critical ALU adder\\npath, limiting Fmax. A prior attempt at this change failed because the\\ndivider state machine lacked a proper IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM with a\\n'started' bit, causing deadlock. With a correct FSM implementation,\\nremoving the combinational divider should relieve routing congestion\\nand raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the\\nSystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX\\nstage alone consumes over 6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is\\ndominated by arithmetic primitives. Division is essentially unused in\\nCoreMark, yet the combinational divider consumes massive area and\\nrouting resources that congest the fabric around the critical ALU adder\\npath, limiting Fmax. A prior attempt at this change failed because the\\ndivider state machine lacked a proper IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM with a\\n'started' bit, causing deadlock. With a correct FSM implementation,\\nremoving the combinational divider should relieve routing congestion\\nand raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extract DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of the combinational ALU into a new\\n`divider.sv` module that performs restoring division in 33 cycles.\\nThe divider MUST use a proper 3-state FSM (IDLE, RUNNING, DONE) with\\na registered 'started' bit:\\n  - IDLE:  waiting for start pulse. busy=0, done=0.\\n  - RUNNING: counting down 32 bits. busy=1, done=0.\\n  - DONE: result valid for one cycle. busy=0, done=1. Next clock\\n    returns to IDLE automatically.\\nIn `ex_stage`, detect divide ops and assert `div_start` for exactly\\none cycle when the divider is in IDLE. The hazard unit stalls IF,\\nID, and EX/MEM while `div_busy` (= RUNNING) is high. Because `busy`\\nis LOW in the DONE state, the EX/MEM register naturally captures the\\ndivider result on the done cycle and the next instruction can enter\\nEX on the following cycle. The main ALU keeps all I-type ops and the\\nmultiplier path. This structural change shrinks the EX stage\\nsignificantly, frees routing capacity on the critical path, and\\nshould improve median Fmax without hurting CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and all combinational divide/rem\\nlogic. Keep the multiplier paths and the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS\\nbranch unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative restoring divider with IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM.\\nInputs: clock, reset, start, dividend[31:0], divisor[31:0],\\nop[3:0] selecting DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU. Outputs: result[31:0],\\nbusy, done. 33-cycle latency. busy is high only in RUNNING.\\ndone is high for one cycle in DONE. Returns to IDLE on next\\nclock edge. Handles all RV32M corner cases (divide by zero,\\nINT_MIN/-1).\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide ops from in.ctrl.alu_op. Route operands to the\\ndivider and assert div_start when the divider is idle.\\nCapture divider result into ex_mem_w.alu_result when div_done\\nis high. Stall EX/MEM via hazard_unit during div_busy.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add div_busy input. Extend stall_if, stall_id, and stall_ex_mem\\nto freeze the entire pipeline while div_busy is high. Do not\\nassert flush_id during div_busy; hold the pipeline state.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate divider module. Wire div_busy into hazard_unit.\\nConnect divider inputs from id_ex_w operands. No top-level IO\\nchanges.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and all combinational divide/rem\\nlogic. Keep the multiplier paths and the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS\\nbranch unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative restoring divider with IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM.\\nInputs: clock, reset, start, dividend[31:0], divisor[31:0],\\nop[3:0] selecting DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU. Outputs: result[31:0],\\nbusy, done. 33-cycle latency. busy is high only in RUNNING.\\ndone is high for one cycle in DONE. Returns to IDLE on next\\nclock edge. Handles all RV32M corner cases (divide by zero,\\nINT_MIN/-1).\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide ops from in.ctrl.alu_op. Route operands to the\\ndivider and assert div_start when the divider is idle.\\nCapture divider result into ex_mem_w.alu_result when div_done\\nis high. Stall EX/MEM via hazard_unit during div_busy.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add div_busy input. Extend stall_if, stall_id, and stall_ex_mem\\nto freeze the entire pipeline while div_busy is high. Do not\\nassert flush_id during div_busy; hold the pipeline state.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate divider module. Wire div_busy into hazard_unit.\\nConnect divider inputs from id_ex_w operands. No top-level IO\\nchanges.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T06:07:59.336648Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 7, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/alu.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/test/test_alu.py', 'cores/bench/test/test_pipeline.py', 'cores/bench/rtl/divider.sv', 'cores/bench/test/test_divider.py']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/alu.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 8}\n","metadata":{"output":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Add static branch predictor (backward-taken, JAL-always-taken)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core incurs a 1-cycle bubble on every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause IF always speculatively fetches PC+4. CoreMark is loop-heavy, so backward\\nbranches and function calls are frequent. A static predictor that fetches the\\ntarget for backward branches and JAL eliminates the bubble on the common case,\\nimproving IPC with negligible LUT cost (~50 LUTs) and no impact on the critical\\npath.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core incurs a 1-cycle bubble on every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause IF always speculatively fetches PC+4. CoreMark is loop-heavy, so backward\\nbranches and function calls are frequent. A static predictor that fetches the\\ntarget for backward branches and JAL eliminates the bubble on the common case,\\nimproving IPC with negligible LUT cost (~50 LUTs) and no impact on the critical\\npath.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert decode-and-predict logic in the IF stage. When the fetched instruction is\\na BRANCH with a negative immediate (backward loop) or an unconditional JAL, the\\nPC is updated to the computed target instead of PC+4. A 1-bit pred_taken flag is\\nthreaded through the IF/ID and ID/EX bundles. The EX stage suppresses redirect\\nwhen the prediction was correct; it only asserts redirect (triggering IF/ID flush)\\non mispredict. JALR remains unpredicted. This saves one cycle per correctly\\npredicted taken branch or JAL.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add pred_taken bit to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Decode BRANCH/JAL opcodes from imem_data, compute B/J immediates, set predict_taken for backward branches and JAL, and select next_pc from the predicted target when predict_taken is asserted.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Thread pred_taken from the IF/ID combinational bundle into the ID/EX pipeline register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the unconditional redirect logic with mispredict detection. redirect is asserted only when a conditional branch outcome differs from pred_taken, or for unpredicte JALR. Correctly predicted branches and JAL no longer flush the pipeline.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add pred_taken bit to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Decode BRANCH/JAL opcodes from imem_data, compute B/J immediates, set predict_taken for backward branches and JAL, and select next_pc from the predicted target when predict_taken is asserted.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Thread pred_taken from the IF/ID combinational bundle into the ID/EX pipeline register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the unconditional redirect logic with mispredict detection. redirect is asserted only when a conditional branch outcome differs from pred_taken, or for unpredicte JALR. Correctly predicted branches and JAL no longer flush the pipeline.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 324.08, \"delta_pct\": 14.59, \"vs_baseline\": 14.59, \"fmax_mhz\": 138.05, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4259699, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10189, \"ff\": 1874, \"seeds\": [133.46, 138.05, 148.35], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T02:11:08.300480Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r1s1 (improvement, +14.59%): Even a trivial static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken) eliminates the taken-branch bubble and yields double-digit IPC gains on loop-heavy benchmarks like CoreMark, with negligible LUT cost.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/forward_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/mem_stage.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 2}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260513-002-r3s1 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260513-001-r3s0', 'hyp-20260513-002-r3s1', 'hyp-20260513-003-r3s2'])\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 3}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Move JALR target resolution to ID stage to cut penalty from 2 to 1 cycle\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"JALR is currently unpredicted in IF and resolved in EX, incurring a 2-cycle\\nmisprediction bubble on every function return and indirect call. CoreMark's\\nlist benchmark makes frequent function calls through pointers, so JALR\\nbubbles are a real IPC limiter.  Because the return address register (x1)\\nis almost always in the regfile when the JALR reaches ID (no forwarding\\nneeded), we can compute the target address in ID stage and redirect IF one\\ncycle earlier, shrinking the penalty to a single flushed fetch slot.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"JALR is currently unpredicted in IF and resolved in EX, incurring a 2-cycle\\nmisprediction bubble on every function return and indirect call. CoreMark's\\nlist benchmark makes frequent function calls through pointers, so JALR\\nbubbles are a real IPC limiter.  Because the return address register (x1)\\nis almost always in the regfile when the JALR reaches ID (no forwarding\\nneeded), we can compute the target address in ID stage and redirect IF one\\ncycle earlier, shrinking the penalty to a single flushed fetch slot.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a JALR target adder in the ID stage: when the decoded instruction is\\nJALR and its rs1 is not the subject of an in-flight load-use hazard, compute\\njalr_target = (rs1_data + imm) & ~1 and assert a new id_redirect signal.\\nThread a jalr_redirected flag through the id_ex_t bundle so the EX stage\\nsuppresses its own redirect for JALRs that were already handled in ID.\\nAt the top level, OR the new id_redirect with the existing ex_redirect to\\ndrive the PC, and adjust flush_if/flush_id so that a JALR in ID is allowed\\nto advance into EX while the speculative fetch in IF is killed.\\nThis structural change shortens the JALR resolution loop by one full stage\\nwithout touching any other instruction type.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add jalr_redirected bit to id_ex_t bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute JALR target from regfile rs1 + imm. Assert id_redirect when JALR has no load-use hazard on rs1. Set jalr_redirected flag in the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Suppress redirect for JALR instructions when jalr_redirected is set; otherwise keep existing redirect logic unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add id_redirect input to flush_if logic. Ensure load-use hazard on JALR rs1 stalls ID (do not assert id_redirect until hazard clears).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new id_redirect from id_stage to hazard_unit and PC logic. Combine id_redirect with ex_redirect for top-level redirect and flush control.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add jalr_redirected bit to id_ex_t bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute JALR target from regfile rs1 + imm. Assert id_redirect when JALR has no load-use hazard on rs1. Set jalr_redirected flag in the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Suppress redirect for JALR instructions when jalr_redirected is set; otherwise keep existing redirect logic unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add id_redirect input to flush_if logic. Ensure load-use hazard on JALR rs1 stalls ID (do not assert id_redirect until hazard clears).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new id_redirect from id_stage to hazard_unit and PC logic. Combine id_redirect with ex_redirect for top-level redirect and flush control.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 324.08, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 14.59, \"fmax_mhz\": 138.05, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4259699, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10189, \"ff\": 1874, \"seeds\": [133.46, 138.05, 148.35], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:05:58.810116Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 4}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 5, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The IF stage currently stalls the entire pipeline on every imem_ready=0 cycle,\\ninjecting a NOP bubble into ID/EX. At the same time, during load-use or dmem\\nstalls the PC holds even though imem may be ready, wasting a fetch slot.\\nDecoupling fetch from issue with a 1-entry buffer lets us prefetch one\\ninstruction ahead during downstream stalls and then issue it when imem\\nsubsequently stalls, hiding single-cycle bus bubbles without lengthening\\nany critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure if_stage to hold a 1-entry prefetch buffer (buf_pc, buf_instr,\\nbuf_pred_taken, buf_valid).  The fetch PC advances whenever imem_ready is\\nhigh and there is a free buffer slot.  An instruction is issued to ID from\\nthe buffer if available, otherwise directly from imem_data, and only a\\ntrue NOP is emitted when both sources are empty.  In hazard_unit, stop\\ntreating imem_ready=0 as a global stall_if / flush_if event; instead let\\nif_stage backpressure itself locally.  This structural decoupling turns\\notherwise-wasted fetch slots during load-use/dmem stalls into prefetches,\\nimproving average IPC at the cost of ~66 flops and a few LUTs.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 1-entry prefetch buffer registers and rewrite the issue / fill\\nFSM so that fetch_pc advances on every imem_ready while a slot exists.\\nOutput mux selects buffer, direct imem_data, or NOP based on buffer\\noccupancy and imem_ready.  Accept stall_core (load-use + dmem only)\\nand imem_ready directly instead of the old stall/flush pair.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove imem_stall from stall_if so that the pipeline only stalls for\\nload-use hazards and dmem stalls.  Reduce flush_if to redirect only;\\nimem backpressure is now handled locally inside if_stage.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire io_imemReady directly to if_stage and connect the new stall_core\\nsignal from hazard_unit to if_stage.  Remove the old stall_if / flush_if\\nplumbing that coupled imem backpressure to the whole pipeline.\\n\"}]}}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX stage alone consumes over\\n6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is dominated by arithmetic primitives.\\nDivision is essentially unused in CoreMark, yet the divider consumes a massive\\namount of area and routing resources that congest the fabric around the critical\\nALU adder path. Removing the combinational divider should relieve routing\\ncongestion and raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX stage alone consumes over\\n6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is dominated by arithmetic primitives.\\nDivision is essentially unused in CoreMark, yet the divider consumes a massive\\namount of area and routing resources that congest the fabric around the critical\\nALU adder path. Removing the combinational divider should relieve routing\\ncongestion and raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extract DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of the combinational ALU into a new\\n`divider.sv` module that performs non-restoring division in 33 cycles.\\nIn `ex_stage`, detect divide ops and assert a `div_busy` signal that\\nstalls the pipeline via the hazard unit until the divider finishes.\\nThe main ALU keeps all I-type ops and the multiplier path (which maps\\nto the on-chip DSP block). Update `hazard_unit` to extend `stall_ex_mem`\\nand `stall_id` when `div_busy` is high. This structural change shrinks\\nthe EX stage significantly, frees routing capacity on the critical path,\\nand should improve median Fmax without hurting CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and all combinational divide/rem\\nlogic. Keep the multiplier paths (mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) and the\\nRISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative non-restoring divider. Inputs: clock, reset, start,\\ndividend[31:0], divisor[31:0], signed_div. Outputs: quotient[31:0],\\nremainder[31:0], busy, done. Latency = 33 cycles. busy stays high\\nfrom start until done rises for one cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide ops from `in.ctrl.alu_op`. Route operands to the\\ndivider and assert `div_busy` while the divider is running. Drive\\n`alu_result` from the divider output when a divide op retires.\\nSuppress normal EX/MEM updates during `div_busy`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `div_busy` input. Assert `stall_ex_mem` and `stall_id` when\\n`div_busy` is high so the entire pipeline freezes until division\\ncompletes. Keep existing load-use and bus-stall logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the divider between EX and hazard unit. Wire\\n`div_busy` into the hazard unit. Connect divider inputs from\\n`id_ex_w` operands and `ex_mem_w` controls. No top-level IO\\nchanges.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and all combinational divide/rem\\nlogic. Keep the multiplier paths (mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) and the\\nRISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative non-restoring divider. Inputs: clock, reset, start,\\ndividend[31:0], divisor[31:0], signed_div. Outputs: quotient[31:0],\\nremainder[31:0], busy, done. Latency = 33 cycles. busy stays high\\nfrom start until done rises for one cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide ops from `in.ctrl.alu_op`. Route operands to the\\ndivider and assert `div_busy` while the divider is running. Drive\\n`alu_result` from the divider output when a divide op retires.\\nSuppress normal EX/MEM updates during `div_busy`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `div_busy` input. Assert `stall_ex_mem` and `stall_id` when\\n`div_busy` is high so the entire pipeline freezes until division\\ncompletes. Keep existing load-use and bus-stall logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the divider between EX and hazard unit. Wire\\n`div_busy` into the hazard unit. Connect divider inputs from\\n`id_ex_w` operands and `ex_mem_w` controls. No top-level IO\\nchanges.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"cosim_failed: selftest.elf\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 6, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r6s1 (broken, n/a): A multi-cycle divider in EX requires a per-instruction state machine, not raw combinational busy/done logic: without a 'started' bit, `div_busy` deadlocks after a pulsed `done` because the instruction never leaves EX, while a level `done` prevents subsequent divides from re-starting.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the\\nSystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX\\nstage alone consumes over 6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is\\ndominated by arithmetic primitives. Division is essentially unused in\\nCoreMark, yet the combinational divider consumes massive area and\\nrouting resources that congest the fabric around the critical ALU adder\\npath, limiting Fmax. A prior attempt at this change failed because the\\ndivider state machine lacked a proper IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM with a\\n'started' bit, causing deadlock. With a correct FSM implementation,\\nremoving the combinational divider should relieve routing congestion\\nand raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the\\nSystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX\\nstage alone consumes over 6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is\\ndominated by arithmetic primitives. Division is essentially unused in\\nCoreMark, yet the combinational divider consumes massive area and\\nrouting resources that congest the fabric around the critical ALU adder\\npath, limiting Fmax. A prior attempt at this change failed because the\\ndivider state machine lacked a proper IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM with a\\n'started' bit, causing deadlock. With a correct FSM implementation,\\nremoving the combinational divider should relieve routing congestion\\nand raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extract DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of the combinational ALU into a new\\n`divider.sv` module that performs restoring division in 33 cycles.\\nThe divider MUST use a proper 3-state FSM (IDLE, RUNNING, DONE) with\\na registered 'started' bit:\\n  - IDLE:  waiting for start pulse. busy=0, done=0.\\n  - RUNNING: counting down 32 bits. busy=1, done=0.\\n  - DONE: result valid for one cycle. busy=0, done=1. Next clock\\n    returns to IDLE automatically.\\nIn `ex_stage`, detect divide ops and assert `div_start` for exactly\\none cycle when the divider is in IDLE. The hazard unit stalls IF,\\nID, and EX/MEM while `div_busy` (= RUNNING) is high. Because `busy`\\nis LOW in the DONE state, the EX/MEM register naturally captures the\\ndivider result on the done cycle and the next instruction can enter\\nEX on the following cycle. The main ALU keeps all I-type ops and the\\nmultiplier path. This structural change shrinks the EX stage\\nsignificantly, frees routing capacity on the critical path, and\\nshould improve median Fmax without hurting CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and all combinational divide/rem\\nlogic. Keep the multiplier paths and the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS\\nbranch unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative restoring divider with IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM.\\nInputs: clock, reset, start, dividend[31:0], divisor[31:0],\\nop[3:0] selecting DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU. Outputs: result[31:0],\\nbusy, done. 33-cycle latency. busy is high only in RUNNING.\\ndone is high for one cycle in DONE. Returns to IDLE on next\\nclock edge. Handles all RV32M corner cases (divide by zero,\\nINT_MIN/-1).\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide ops from in.ctrl.alu_op. Route operands to the\\ndivider and assert div_start when the divider is idle.\\nCapture divider result into ex_mem_w.alu_result when div_done\\nis high. Stall EX/MEM via hazard_unit during div_busy.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add div_busy input. Extend stall_if, stall_id, and stall_ex_mem\\nto freeze the entire pipeline while div_busy is high. Do not\\nassert flush_id during div_busy; hold the pipeline state.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate divider module. Wire div_busy into hazard_unit.\\nConnect divider inputs from id_ex_w operands. No top-level IO\\nchanges.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and all combinational divide/rem\\nlogic. Keep the multiplier paths and the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS\\nbranch unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative restoring divider with IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM.\\nInputs: clock, reset, start, dividend[31:0], divisor[31:0],\\nop[3:0] selecting DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU. Outputs: result[31:0],\\nbusy, done. 33-cycle latency. busy is high only in RUNNING.\\ndone is high for one cycle in DONE. Returns to IDLE on next\\nclock edge. Handles all RV32M corner cases (divide by zero,\\nINT_MIN/-1).\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide ops from in.ctrl.alu_op. Route operands to the\\ndivider and assert div_start when the divider is idle.\\nCapture divider result into ex_mem_w.alu_result when div_done\\nis high. Stall EX/MEM via hazard_unit during div_busy.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add div_busy input. Extend stall_if, stall_id, and stall_ex_mem\\nto freeze the entire pipeline while div_busy is high. Do not\\nassert flush_id during div_busy; hold the pipeline state.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate divider module. Wire div_busy into hazard_unit.\\nConnect divider inputs from id_ex_w operands. No top-level IO\\nchanges.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T06:07:59.336648Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 7, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/alu.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/test/test_alu.py', 'cores/bench/test/test_pipeline.py', 'cores/bench/rtl/divider.sv', 'cores/bench/test/test_divider.py']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/alu.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 8}\n","exit":0,"description":"List prior structural experiments","truncated":false},"title":"List prior structural experiments","time":{"start":1778741472694,"end":1778741472696}},"id":"prt_e2540eb3f001yWIB1wdQmJwPQC","sessionID":"ses_1dac84d93ffeovARKJoi7VUZtl","messageID":"msg_e253e4938001JDqqQM1o9AdQkK"}}
