{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778742017227,"sessionID":"ses_1dac84d93ffeovARKJoi7VUZtl","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"functions.read:5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-002-r9s1.yaml"},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-002-r9s1.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260514-002-r9s1\n2: title: Add 2-entry instruction skid buffer to hide imem stalls\n3: category: structural\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The fitness contract injects ~22% random backpressure on the instruction\n6:   bus.  Today every !imem_ready cycle asserts a global stall_if / flush_if\n7:   that freezes the PC and forces a NOP bubble into ID/EX.  A tiny 2-entry\n8:   skid buffer decouples fetch from issue: when the downstream pipeline is\n9:   stalled (load-use, dmem) but the bus is ready, the buffer prefetches\n10:   ahead; when the bus subsequently stalls but the buffer is non-empty, the\n11:   core continues issuing without bubbles.  This is a pure structural\n12:   decoupling that should raise effective fetch throughput with only\n13:   ~130 flops and no new long combinational paths.\n14: hypothesis: |\n15:   Restructure if_stage to hold a 2-entry ring buffer (valid, pc,\n16:   instr, pred_taken per entry, plus a head pointer and 2-bit count).\n17:   The fetch side advances the PC and enqueues the fetched instruction\n18:   whenever imem_ready is high, count<2, and there is no redirect.  The\n19:   issue side selects the buffered head when count>0, otherwise the live\n20:   imem_data.  A true NOP is emitted only when the buffer is empty and\n21:   imem_ready is low.  In hazard_unit, remove imem_ready from stall_if\n22:   and flush_if so the pipeline no longer stalls globally for bus\n23:   backpressure; stall_if is asserted only for load-use and dmem stalls,\n24:   and flush_if only for redirect.  In core.sv, wire io_imemReady into the\n25:   new if_stage port and keep all top-level IO unchanged.\n26: expected_impact:\n27:   fitness_delta_pct: 10\n28:   confidence: medium\n29: changes:\n30:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n31:     description: |\n32:       Add a 2-entry ring buffer inside if_stage (buf_valid[1:0],\n33:       buf_pc[1:0], buf_instr[1:0], buf_pred_taken[1:0], head pointer,\n34:       count 0..2).  Add new input `imem_ready`.  Fetch PC advances and\n35:       enqueues into tail when imem_ready && count<2 && !redirect.\n36:       Issue selects buffered head if count>0, else live imem_data if\n37:       imem_ready, else NOP.  Count increments on fetch, decrements on\n38:       issue.  On redirect clear count/head and reset PC to redirect_target.\n39:       Keep existing BHT and static predictor logic unchanged.\n40:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n41:     description: |\n42:       Remove imem_ready from stall_if and flush_if.  Keep the imem_ready\n43:       port connected but unused (or remove it entirely).  Assert stall_if\n44:       only for load-use hazards and dmem stalls; assert flush_if only for\n45:       redirect.  All other stall/flush logic (stall_id, flush_id,\n46:       stall_ex_mem, hold_mem_wb) remains exactly the same.\n47:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n48:     description: |\n49:       Wire io_imemReady to the new `imem_ready` port of if_stage.  No\n50:       other top-level IO changes; all RVFI and imem/dmem port names and\n51:       widths stay identical.\n\n(End of file - total 51 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260514-002-r9s1\ntitle: Add 2-entry instruction skid buffer to hide imem stalls\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The fitness contract injects ~22% random backpressure on the instruction\n  bus.  Today every !imem_ready cycle asserts a global stall_if / flush_if\n  that freezes the PC and forces a NOP bubble into ID/EX.  A tiny 2-entry\n  skid buffer decouples fetch from issue: when the downstream pipeline is\n  stalled (load-use, dmem) but the bus is ready, the buffer prefetches\n  ahead; when the bus subsequently stalls but the buffer is non-empty, the\n  core continues issuing without bubbles.  This is a pure structural\n  decoupling that should raise effective fetch throughput with only\n  ~130 flops and no new long combinational paths.\nhypothesis: |\n  Restructure if_stage to hold a 2-entry ring buffer (valid, pc,\n  instr, pred_taken per entry, plus a head pointer and 2-bit count).\n  The fetch side advances the PC and enqueues the fetched instruction\n  whenever imem_ready is high, count<2, and there is no redirect.  The\n  issue side selects the buffered head when count>0, otherwise the live\n  imem_data.  A true NOP is emitted only when the buffer is empty and","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-002-r9s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778742017217,"end":1778742017226}},"id":"prt_e254938f1001wTHZcSEXbsZhzL","sessionID":"ses_1dac84d93ffeovARKJoi7VUZtl","messageID":"msg_e25492cb6001vH4lMN5JbFaiMR"}}
