{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778742690676,"sessionID":"ses_1daaccb0fffezVBWA81N4wfQIn","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"bash:0","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -i \"ras\\|return.*stack\\|call\\|jalr\\|return\\|address.*stack\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | head -20","description":"Search for RAS attempts in log"},"output":"...output truncated...\n\nFull output saved to: /Users/bonetto/.local/share/opencode/tool-output/tool_e255383720024oNwiy7fFfcZW7\n\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Move JALR target resolution to ID stage to cut penalty from 2 to 1 cycle\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"JALR is currently unpredicted in IF and resolved in EX, incurring a 2-cycle\\nmisprediction bubble on every function return and indirect call. CoreMark's\\nlist benchmark makes frequent function calls through pointers, so JALR\\nbubbles are a real IPC limiter.  Because the return address register (x1)\\nis almost always in the regfile when the JALR reaches ID (no forwarding\\nneeded), we can compute the target address in ID stage and redirect IF one\\ncycle earlier, shrinking the penalty to a single flushed fetch slot.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"JALR is currently unpredicted in IF and resolved in EX, incurring a 2-cycle\\nmisprediction bubble on every function return and indirect call. CoreMark's\\nlist benchmark makes frequent function calls through pointers, so JALR\\nbubbles are a real IPC limiter.  Because the return address register (x1)\\nis almost always in the regfile when the JALR reaches ID (no forwarding\\nneeded), we can compute the target address in ID stage and redirect IF one\\ncycle earlier, shrinking the penalty to a single flushed fetch slot.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a JALR target adder in the ID stage: when the decoded instruction is\\nJALR and its rs1 is not the subject of an in-flight load-use hazard, compute\\njalr_target = (rs1_data + imm) & ~1 and assert a new id_redirect signal.\\nThread a jalr_redirected flag through the id_ex_t bundle so the EX stage\\nsuppresses its own redirect for JALRs that were already handled in ID.\\nAt the top level, OR the new id_redirect with the existing ex_redirect to\\ndrive the PC, and adjust flush_if/flush_id so that a JALR in ID is allowed\\nto advance into EX while the speculative fetch in IF is killed.\\nThis structural change shortens the JALR resolution loop by one full stage\\nwithout touching any other instruction type.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add jalr_redirected bit to id_ex_t bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute JALR target from regfile rs1 + imm. Assert id_redirect when JALR has no load-use hazard on rs1. Set jalr_redirected flag in the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Suppress redirect for JALR instructions when jalr_redirected is set; otherwise keep existing redirect logic unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add id_redirect input to flush_if logic. Ensure load-use hazard on JALR rs1 stalls ID (do not assert id_redirect until hazard clears).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new id_redirect from id_stage to hazard_unit and PC logic. Combine id_redirect with ex_redirect for top-level redirect and flush control.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add jalr_redirected bit to id_ex_t bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute JALR target from regfile rs1 + imm. Assert id_redirect when JALR has no load-use hazard on rs1. Set jalr_redirected flag in the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Suppress redirect for JALR instructions when jalr_redirected is set; otherwise keep existing redirect logic unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add id_redirect input to flush_if logic. Ensure load-use hazard on JALR rs1 stalls ID (do not assert id_redirect until hazard clears).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new id_redirect from id_stage to hazard_unit and PC logic. Combine id_redirect with ex_redirect for top-level redirect and flush control.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 324.08, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 14.59, \"fmax_mhz\": 138.05, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4259699, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10189, \"ff\": 1874, \"seeds\": [133.46, 138.05, 148.35], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:05:58.810116Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 4}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"Add 32-entry 2-bit BHT for forward branch direction prediction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped Branch History Table with 2-bit saturating\\ncounters to the IF stage. The table is indexed by PC[6:2] and initialized to\\nstrongly-taken (2'b11) so backward loops are correct immediately without any\\ntraining cost. For every conditional branch, the BHT entry MSB drives\\npredict_taken; unconditional JAL continues to be always predicted taken. In\\nEX stage, each resolved branch writes its actual outcome back to the entry\\nindexed by the branch PC using a standard saturating update rule. This adds\\nonly 64 flops and a few LUTs of combinational logic, does not widen any\\npipeline register, and the BHT read is off the critical instruction-fetch path\\nbecause the PC is known at the start of the cycle while the opcode decode\\n(which selects the BHT result) happens later in parallel.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 32-entry x 2-bit BHT array inside the IF stage.  Combinational read uses pc[6:2] to select the counter; the MSB becomes the direction prediction for conditional branches.  Add three new input ports (bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], bht_update_taken) and a saturating update rule that increments on taken and decrements on not-taken.  Modify predict_taken so that conditional branches use the BHT MSB while JAL remains unconditionally taken.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add output ports bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken.  Drive bht_update_en high on every cycle a conditional branch is resolved (!stall && in.valid && in.ctrl.is_branch). bht_update_idx is in.pc[6:2] and bht_update_taken is the combinational branch_taken signal.  No other EX-stage logic is changed.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken and route them from ex_stage outputs to if_stage inputs. No top-level IO or RVFI changes.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 32-entry x 2-bit BHT array inside the IF stage.  Combinational read uses pc[6:2] to select the counter; the MSB becomes the direction prediction for conditional branches.  Add three new input ports (bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], bht_update_taken) and a saturating update rule that increments on taken and decrements on not-taken.  Modify predict_taken so that conditional branches use the BHT MSB while JAL remains unconditionally taken.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add output ports bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken.  Drive bht_update_en high on every cycle a conditional branch is resolved (!stall && in.valid && in.ctrl.is_branch). bht_update_idx is in.pc[6:2] and bht_update_taken is the combinational branch_taken signal.  No other EX-stage logic is changed.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken and route them from ex_stage outputs to if_stage inputs. No top-level IO or RVFI changes.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 7.31, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T03:44:01.694682Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 4, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r4s2 (improvement, +7.31%): After a static backward-taken baseline captures the easy loop gains, a minimal 32-entry 2-bit BHT (64 flops) still recovers +7.3% fitness by predicting forward conditional branches; forward-branch direction is the largest remaining dynamic bubble source in CoreMark.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Eliminate false load-use stalls via opcode-aware hazard detection\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit conservatively stalls on any LOAD-to-use sequence where the\\nLOAD's rd matches either rs1 or rs2 of the next instruction, regardless of\\nwhether those fields are actually register reads. For I-type instructions\\n(OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR) the rs2 field encodes an immediate or shamt; for U-type\\n(LUI, AUIPC), J-type (JAL), and SYSTEM/FENCE instructions neither field is a\\nregister read. These false stalls waste cycles\\u2014especially on CoreMark's heavy\\nuse of ADDI, LUI, and JAL immediately after pointer loads\\u2014with negligible\\nLUT cost and no impact on Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit conservatively stalls on any LOAD-to-use sequence where the\\nLOAD's rd matches either rs1 or rs2 of the next instruction, regardless of\\nwhether those fields are actually register reads. For I-type instructions\\n(OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR) the rs2 field encodes an immediate or shamt; for U-type\\n(LUI, AUIPC), J-type (JAL), and SYSTEM/FENCE instructions neither field is a\\nregister read. These false stalls waste cycles\\u2014especially on CoreMark's heavy\\nuse of ADDI, LUI, and JAL immediately after pointer loads\\u2014with negligible\\nLUT cost and no impact on Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add opcode decoding to hazard_unit so the load_use_hazard term only fires\\nwhen the instruction in ID genuinely reads rs1 or rs2. R-type, BRANCH, and\\nSTORE read both; I-type reads only rs1; U/J/FENCE/SYSTEM read neither. The\\nstall_if / stall_id / flush_id logic otherwise stays identical, so no other\\npipeline behavior changes. This removes spurious one-cycle bubbles without\\nlengthening any critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a new 7-bit `if_id_opcode` input. Inside the module compute\\n`uses_rs1` and `uses_rs2` flags from the opcode (R/BRANCH/STORE = both;\\nI-type = rs1 only; U/J/FENCE/SYSTEM = neither). Qualify the\\n`load_use_hazard` expression with these flags so that matches on\\nimmediate fields no longer stall the pipeline.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire `if_id_w.instr[6:0]` into the new `if_id_opcode` port of the\\n`hazard_unit` instance. No other top-level signals are modified.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a new 7-bit `if_id_opcode` input. Inside the module compute\\n`uses_rs1` and `uses_rs2` flags from the opcode (R/BRANCH/STORE = both;\\nI-type = rs1 only; U/J/FENCE/SYSTEM = neither). Qualify the\\n`load_use_hazard` expression with these flags so that matches on\\nimmediate fields no longer stall the pipeline.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire `if_id_w.instr[6:0]` into the new `if_id_opcode` port of the\\n`hazard_unit` instance. No other top-level signals are modified.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:24:18.728881Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 5, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/test/test_pipeline.py']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 5, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The IF stage currently stalls the entire pipeline on every imem_ready=0 cycle,\\ninjecting a NOP bubble into ID/EX. At the same time, during load-use or dmem\\nstalls the PC holds even though imem may be ready, wasting a fetch slot.\\nDecoupling fetch from issue with a 1-entry buffer lets us prefetch one\\ninstruction ahead during downstream stalls and then issue it when imem\\nsubsequently stalls, hiding single-cycle bus bubbles without lengthening\\nany critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure if_stage to hold a 1-entry prefetch buffer (buf_pc, buf_instr,\\nbuf_pred_taken, buf_valid).  The fetch PC advances whenever imem_ready is\\nhigh and there is a free buffer slot.  An instruction is issued to ID from\\nthe buffer if available, otherwise directly from imem_data, and only a\\ntrue NOP is emitted when both sources are empty.  In hazard_unit, stop\\ntreating imem_ready=0 as a global stall_if / flush_if event; instead let\\nif_stage backpressure itself locally.  This structural decoupling turns\\notherwise-wasted fetch slots during load-use/dmem stalls into prefetches,\\nimproving average IPC at the cost of ~66 flops and a few LUTs.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 1-entry prefetch buffer registers and rewrite the issue / fill\\nFSM so that fetch_pc advances on every imem_ready while a slot exists.\\nOutput mux selects buffer, direct imem_data, or NOP based on buffer\\noccupancy and imem_ready.  Accept stall_core (load-use + dmem only)\\nand imem_ready directly instead of the old stall/flush pair.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove imem_stall from stall_if so that the pipeline only stalls for\\nload-use hazards and dmem stalls.  Reduce flush_if to redirect only;\\nimem backpressure is now handled locally inside if_stage.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire io_imemReady directly to if_stage and connect the new stall_core\\nsignal from hazard_unit to if_stage.  Remove the old stall_if / flush_if\\nplumbing that coupled imem backpressure to the whole pipeline.\\n\"}]}}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Precompute forwarding selects in ID stage to shorten EX critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The EX-stage critical path currently includes the forward_unit's 5-bit\\naddress comparison, priority encoder, and operand forwarding mux before the\\nALU.  On a LUT-based FPGA these extra logic levels consume precious\\nnanoseconds.  By shifting the forwarding decision into the ID stage\\u2014where\\nthe same comparison is performed against the instructions currently in EX\\nand MEM\\u2014we register the 2-bit select signals into the ID/EX pipeline\\nregister.  This removes the comparison and control generation from the\\nEX-stage datapath without changing pipeline behaviour or IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX-stage critical path currently includes the forward_unit's 5-bit\\naddress comparison, priority encoder, and operand forwarding mux before the\\nALU.  On a LUT-based FPGA these extra logic levels consume precious\\nnanoseconds.  By shifting the forwarding decision into the ID stage\\u2014where\\nthe same comparison is performed against the instructions currently in EX\\nand MEM\\u2014we register the 2-bit select signals into the ID/EX pipeline\\nregister.  This removes the comparison and control generation from the\\nEX-stage datapath without changing pipeline behaviour or IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add fwd_rs1_sel and fwd_rs2_sel (2 bits each) to the id_ex_t bundle.\\nIn id_stage, compute the forwarding selects combinationally by comparing\\nthe current IF/ID instruction's rs1_addr/rs2_addr against the rd and\\nreg_write flags of the instruction currently in EX (the ID/EX register)\\nand the instruction currently in MEM (ex_mem_w), preserving the same\\nEX/MEM-over-MEM/WB priority and x0 guard that forward_unit uses today.\\nRegister these selects into the ID/EX payload.  In ex_stage, remove the\\nforward_unit input ports and use the precomputed in.fwd_rs1_sel /\\nin.fwd_rs2_sel directly in the operand forwarding muxes.  In core.sv,\\nwire ex_mem_w.rd and ex_mem_w.ctrl.reg_write into id_stage for the\\nprecomputation, remove the forward_unit instantiation, and connect the\\nprecomputed selects straight through to ex_stage.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_rs1_sel [1:0] and fwd_rs2_sel [1:0] fields to the id_ex_t struct.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add inputs ex_mem_rd [4:0] and ex_mem_reg_write. Compute next_fwd_rs1/next_fwd_rs2 combinationally by comparing in.instr[19:15] and in.instr[24:20] against reg_q.rd and ex_mem_rd with the same write-enable / x0 guards used by forward_unit. Register the resulting 2-bit values into the ID/EX payload.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the fwd_rs1_sel and fwd_rs2_sel input ports. Use in.fwd_rs1_sel and in.fwd_rs2_sel directly in the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes instead of the former forward_unit-driven selects.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire ex_mem_w.rd and ex_mem_w.ctrl.reg_write into the id_stage instance for precomputation.  Remove the forward_unit instantiation and its wires.  Connect id_ex_w.fwd_rs1_sel and id_ex_w.fwd_rs2_sel directly to ex_stage.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_rs1_sel [1:0] and fwd_rs2_sel [1:0] fields to the id_ex_t struct.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add inputs ex_mem_rd [4:0] and ex_mem_reg_write. Compute next_fwd_rs1/next_fwd_rs2 combinationally by comparing in.instr[19:15] and in.instr[24:20] against reg_q.rd and ex_mem_rd with the same write-enable / x0 guards used by forward_unit. Register the resulting 2-bit values into the ID/EX payload.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the fwd_rs1_sel and fwd_rs2_sel input ports. Use in.fwd_rs1_sel and in.fwd_rs2_sel directly in the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes instead of the former forward_unit-driven selects.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire ex_mem_w.rd and ex_mem_w.ctrl.reg_write into the id_stage instance for precomputation.  Remove the forward_unit instantiation and its wires.  Connect id_ex_w.fwd_rs1_sel and id_ex_w.fwd_rs2_sel directly to ex_stage.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"formal_failed: reg_ch0\\n: pass\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_sw_ch0] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_sw_ch0] summary: Elapsed process time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_sw_ch0] summary: engine_0 (smtbmc bitwuzla) returned pass\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_sw_ch0] summary: engine_0 did not produce any traces\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_sw_ch0] DONE (PASS, rc=0)\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_xori_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Checking assertions in step 20..\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_xori_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Status: passed\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_xori_ch0] engine_0: finished (returncode=0)\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_xori_ch0] engine_0: Status returned by engine: pass\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_xori_ch0] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:00 (0)\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_xori_ch