       'description': 'Capture in.ghr_snapshot into the ID/EX '\\n                                 'register so it reaches EX.'},\\n                 {'file': 'rtl/ex_stage.sv',\\n                  'description': 'Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ '\\n                                 'in.ghr_snapshot so the counter update '\\n                                 'writes the exact entry that was read '\\n                                 'during fetch. Add output ports '\\n                                 'ghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en. '\\n                                 'Drive ghr_restore = '\\n                                 '{in.ghr_snapshot[3:0], branch_taken} and '\\n                                 'assert ghr_restore_en whenever redirect '\\n                                 'is asserted for a conditional branch '\\n                                 '(in.ctrl.is_branch). JAL/JALR redirects '\\n                                 'must not assert restore_en.\\\\n'},\\n                 {'file': 'rtl/core.sv',\\n                  'description': 'Wire the new ghr_restore/ghr_restore_en '\\n                                 'signals from ex_stage back to '\\n                                 'if_stage.'}]}\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 7, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The prior 32-entry BHT added +7.3% fitness, but a follow-up gshare variant\\nregressed -6.7% because its GHR was updated non-speculatively in EX. By the\\ntime a branch resolved, the next branch had already been fetched with stale\\nhistory, increasing destructive aliasing. CoreMark contains short basic blocks\\nwith back-to-back branches where history staleness is fatal.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the non-speculative EX-stage GHR update with a speculative IF-stage\\nupdate plus EX-stage restore on mispredict. A 5-bit GHR register in IF is\\nshifted left with predict_taken whenever a conditional branch is fetched.\\nThe pre-update GHR value is snapshotted into a new 5-bit field in the IF/ID\\nand ID/EX bundles. In EX, when a conditional branch mispredicts (redirect),\\nthe GHR is restored to {snapshot[3:0], actual_taken}; on correct prediction\\nthe speculative update is already exact and needs no action. The BHT read\\nindex remains pc[6:2] ^ ghr and the update index remains pc[6:2] ^ snapshot.\\nThis gives the 32-entry BHT history-aware indexing without any Fmax penalty\\nfrom a larger array, and fixes the staleness that broke the first gshare.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr_snapshot field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0. Compute BHT read index as pc[6:2] ^ ghr. Drive the current ghr value into out.ghr_snapshot. On non-stalled, non-flushed cycles where the fetched instruction is a conditional branch, speculatively update ghr <= {ghr[3:0], predict_taken}. Add a new input port ghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en; when restore_en is asserted on redirect from EX, reload ghr with ghr_restore.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr_snapshot into the ID/EX register so it reaches EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr_snapshot so the counter update writes the exact entry that was read during fetch. Add output ports ghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en. Drive ghr_restore = {in.ghr_snapshot[3:0], branch_taken} and assert ghr_restore_en whenever redirect is asserted for a conditional branch (in.ctrl.is_branch). JAL/JALR redirects must not assert restore_en.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new ghr_restore/ghr_restore_en signals from ex_stage back to if_stage.\"}]}}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Consolidate ALU multipliers to reduce routing congestion and improve Fmax\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU unconditionally computes three separate 64-bit products\\n(mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) on every cycle even though only one multiply\\nop is ever active.  On FPGA this causes the synthesis tool to infer\\nmultiple wide multipliers and large cross-products that consume DSP\\nblocks and routing resources around the EX stage.  CoreMark is\\nmultiply-heavy (matrix operations), so the ALU multiplier path is\\nlikely on or near the critical path.  By sharing a single 64-bit\\nmultiplier and selecting the signedness mode per-op, we cut the\\nmultiplier area by roughly two thirds and relieve routing\\ncongestion, which should raise median Fmax with zero IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU unconditionally computes three separate 64-bit products\\n(mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) on every cycle even though only one multiply\\nop is ever active.  On FPGA this causes the synthesis tool to infer\\nmultiple wide multipliers and large cross-products that consume DSP\\nblocks and routing resources around the EX stage.  CoreMark is\\nmultiply-heavy (matrix operations), so the ALU multiplier path is\\nlikely on or near the critical path.  By sharing a single 64-bit\\nmultiplier and selecting the signedness mode per-op, we cut the\\nmultiplier area by roughly two thirds and relieve routing\\ncongestion, which should raise median Fmax with zero IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the three always-computed 64-bit products in alu.sv with one\\nshared 64-bit multiplier whose operands are muxed per the active ALU\\nop: unsigned*unsigned for MUL/MULHU, signed*signed for MULH, and\\nsigned*unsigned for MULHSU.  Add a small case block before the\\nmultiplication that selects the correctly-extended a and b inputs.\\nThe DIV/REM family remains combinational (unchanged); only the MUL\\nfamily is touched.  This reduces inferred multiplier count from three\\nto one, shrinking EX-stage area and easing nextpnr placement.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the three always-on 64-bit product wires (mul_ss, mul_uu,\\nmul_su).  Add a shared 64-bit `mul_result` wire.  Precede the\\nmultiply with a combinational mux that selects the sign-extended\\noperands based on the current ALU op, then assign mul_result once.\\nUpdate the MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU case arms to pick the correct\\nhigh or low half of mul_result.  Keep the ALTOPS branch intact.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the three always-on 64-bit product wires (mul_ss, mul_uu,\\nmul_su).  Add a shared 64-bit `mul_result` wire.  Precede the\\nmultiply with a combinational mux that selects the sign-extended\\noperands based on the current ALU op, then assign mul_result once.\\nUpdate the MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU case arms to pick the correct\\nhigh or low half of mul_result.  Keep the ALTOPS branch intact.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T06:38:10.504767Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 8}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r8s2\", \"title\": \"(slot 2 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-003-r8s2 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r8s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r8s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r8s2'])\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 8}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r9s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/forward_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 9, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The fitness contract injects ~22% random backpressure on the instruction\\nbus.  Today every !imem_ready cycle asserts a global stall_if / flush_if\\nthat freezes the PC and forces a NOP bubble into ID/EX.  A tiny 2-entry\\nskid buffer decouples fetch from issue: when the downstream pipeline is\\nstalled (load-use, dmem) but the bus is ready, the buffer prefetches\\nahead; when the bus subsequently stalls but the buffer is non-empty, the\\ncore continues issuing without bubbles.  This is a pure structural\\ndecoupling that should raise effective fetch throughput with only\\n~130 flops and no new long combinational paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure if_stage to hold a 2-entry ring buffer (valid, pc,\\ninstr, pred_taken per entry, plus a head pointer and 2-bit count).\\nThe fetch side advances the PC and enqueues the fetched instruction\\nwhenever imem_ready is high, count<2, and there is no redirect.  The\\nissue side selects the buffered head when count>0, otherwise the live\\nimem_data.  A true NOP is emitted only when the buffer is empty and\\nimem_ready is low.  In hazard_unit, remove imem_ready from stall_if\\nand flush_if so the pipeline no longer stalls globally for bus\\nbackpressure; stall_if is asserted only for load-use and dmem stalls,\\nand flush_if only for redirect.  In core.sv, wire io_imemReady into the\\nnew if_stage port and keep all top-level IO unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 2-entry ring buffer inside if_stage (buf_valid[1:0],\\nbuf_pc[1:0], buf_instr[1:0], buf_pred_taken[1:0], head pointer,\\ncount 0..2).  Add new input `imem_ready`.  Fetch PC advances and\\nenqueues into tail when imem_ready && count<2 && !redirect.\\nIssue selects buffered head if count>0, else live imem_data if\\nimem_ready, else NOP.  Count increments on fetch, decrements on\\nissue.  On redirect clear count/head and reset PC to redirect_target.\\nKeep existing BHT and static predictor logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove imem_ready from stall_if and flush_if.  Keep the imem_ready\\nport connected but unused (or remove it entirely).  Assert stall_if\\nonly for load-use hazards and dmem stalls; assert flush_if only for\\nredirect.  All other stall/flush logic (stall_id, flush_id,\\nstall_ex_mem, hold_mem_wb) remains exactly the same.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire io_imemReady to the new `imem_ready` port of if_stage.  No\\nother top-level IO changes; all RVFI and imem/dmem port names and\\nwidths stay identical.\\n\"}]}}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r9s2\", \"title\": \"Fix gshare by speculatively updating GHR in IF with mispredict restore\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already yielded +7.3% fitness, but a follow-up\\ngshare variant regressed -6.7% because its GHR was updated non-speculatively\\nin EX. By the time a branch resolved, the next branch had already been\\nfetched with stale history, increasing destructive aliasing. CoreMark\\ncontains short basic blocks with back-to-back branches where history\\nstaleness is fatal. A speculative IF-stage update with EX-stage restore\\nfixes the staleness while keeping the table small and the read path fast.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already yielded +7.3% fitness, but a follow-up\\ngshare variant regressed -6.7% because its GHR was updated non-speculatively\\nin EX. By the time a branch resolved, the next branch had already been\\nfetched with stale history, increasing destructive aliasing. CoreMark\\ncontains short basic blocks with back-to-back branches where history\\nstaleness is fatal. A speculative IF-stage update with EX-stage restore\\nfixes the staleness while keeping the table small and the read path fast.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 5-bit Global History Register (GHR) to the IF stage and XOR it into\\nthe existing 32-entry BHT index (gshare). The GHR is updated speculatively\\nwhenever a conditional branch is fetched: ghr <= {ghr[3:0], predict_taken}.\\nThe pre-update GHR value is snapshotted into a new 5-bit field in the\\nIF/ID and ID/EX bundles. In EX, when a conditional branch mispredicts\\n(redirect is asserted), the GHR is restored to {snapshot[3:0], actual_taken}\\nvia a new feedback port to IF. On correct prediction no restore is needed.\\nThe BHT write index uses pc[6:2] ^ snapshot so the counter update hits the\\nsame entry that was read during fetch. This gives history-aware prediction\\nwithout enlarging the array and with negligible combinational delay (a\\n5-bit XOR on an existing mux path).\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr_snapshot field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles\\nso the GHR value present at fetch time reaches EX for update-index\\ncalculation and mispredict restore.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0. Replace the BHT read index\\npc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr. Drive the current ghr value into\\nout.ghr_snapshot. On non-stalled, non-flushed, non-redirected cycles\\nwhere the fetched instruction is a conditional branch, speculatively\\nupdate ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_pred}. Add new input ports\\nghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en; when restore_en is asserted\\n(from EX on a conditional-branch mispredict), reload ghr with\\nghr_restore, taking precedence over the speculative update.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr_snapshot into the ID/EX register so the snapshot\\nreaches the EX stage for BHT update-index computation and GHR restore.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr_snapshot so the\\nsaturating-counter update writes the exact entry that was read during\\nfetch. Add output ports ghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en. Drive\\nghr_restore = {in.ghr_snapshot[3:0], branch_taken} and assert\\nghr_restore_en whenever redirect is asserted for a conditional branch\\n(in.ctrl.is_branch). JAL/JALR redirects must not assert ghr_restore_en.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires ghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en and route\\nthem from ex_stage outputs back to if_stage inputs. No top-level IO\\nor RVFI changes are required.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr_snapshot field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles\\nso the GHR value present at fetch time reaches EX for update-index\\ncalculation and mispredict restore.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0. Replace the BHT read index\\npc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr. Drive the current ghr value into\\nout.ghr_snapshot. On non-stalled, non-flushed, non-redirected cycles\\nwhere the fetched instruction is a conditional branch, speculatively\\nupdate ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_pred}. Add new input ports\\nghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en; when restore_en is asserted\\n(from EX on a conditional-branch mispredict), reload ghr with\\nghr_restore, taking precedence over the speculative update.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr_snapshot into the ID/EX register so the snapshot\\nreaches the EX stage for BHT update-index computation and GHR restore.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr_snapshot so the\\nsaturating-counter update writes the exact entry that was read during\\nfetch. Add output ports ghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en. Drive\\nghr_restore = {in.ghr_snapshot[3:0], branch_taken} and assert\\nghr_restore_en whenever redirect is asserted for a conditional branch\\n(in.ctrl.is_branch). JAL/JALR redirects must not assert ghr_restore_en.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires ghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en and route\\nthem from ex_stage outputs back to if_stage inputs. No top-level IO\\nor RVFI changes are required.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T06:55:45.098358Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 9, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r9s2 (regression, +0.00%): Speculative IF-stage GHR update with mispredict restore fixes the history-staleness bug but still yields zero net gain over the bimodal 32-entry BHT; CoreMark's branch working set is small enough that 2-bit saturating counters capture all exploitable locality, leaving global history with no accuracy upside.\"}\n","exit":0,"description":"Search predictor hypotheses in log","truncated":true,"outputPath":"/Users/bonetto/.local/share/opencode/tool-output/tool_e255387a0001PLQUubXMCpfGtu"},"title":"Search predictor hypotheses in log","time":{"start":1778742691745,"end":1778742691746}},"id":"prt_e25538360001x0ceYZjVmyRSE2","sessionID":"ses_1daaccb0fffezVBWA81N4wfQIn","messageID":"msg_e2553355c001pgiixpJhMp0p1T"}}
