{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778743012417,"sessionID":"ses_1daaccb0fffezVBWA81N4wfQIn","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"bash:4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -i \"early\\|id.*branch\\|branch.*id\\|comparator.*id\\|resolve.*id\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | grep -v \"truncate\\|saved to\" | head -20","description":"Search for early branch resolution in logs"},"output":"...output truncated...\n\nFull output saved to: /Users/bonetto/.local/share/opencode/tool-output/tool_e25586c3a001yF1jQBwaYfFl6Y\n\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Eliminate false load-use stalls via opcode-aware hazard detection\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit conservatively stalls on any LOAD-to-use sequence where the\\nLOAD's rd matches either rs1 or rs2 of the next instruction, regardless of\\nwhether those fields are actually register reads. For I-type instructions\\n(OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR) the rs2 field encodes an immediate or shamt; for U-type\\n(LUI, AUIPC), J-type (JAL), and SYSTEM/FENCE instructions neither field is a\\nregister read. These false stalls waste cycles\\u2014especially on CoreMark's heavy\\nuse of ADDI, LUI, and JAL immediately after pointer loads\\u2014with negligible\\nLUT cost and no impact on Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit conservatively stalls on any LOAD-to-use sequence where the\\nLOAD's rd matches either rs1 or rs2 of the next instruction, regardless of\\nwhether those fields are actually register reads. For I-type instructions\\n(OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR) the rs2 field encodes an immediate or shamt; for U-type\\n(LUI, AUIPC), J-type (JAL), and SYSTEM/FENCE instructions neither field is a\\nregister read. These false stalls waste cycles\\u2014especially on CoreMark's heavy\\nuse of ADDI, LUI, and JAL immediately after pointer loads\\u2014with negligible\\nLUT cost and no impact on Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add opcode decoding to hazard_unit so the load_use_hazard term only fires\\nwhen the instruction in ID genuinely reads rs1 or rs2. R-type, BRANCH, and\\nSTORE read both; I-type reads only rs1; U/J/FENCE/SYSTEM read neither. The\\nstall_if / stall_id / flush_id logic otherwise stays identical, so no other\\npipeline behavior changes. This removes spurious one-cycle bubbles without\\nlengthening any critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a new 7-bit `if_id_opcode` input. Inside the module compute\\n`uses_rs1` and `uses_rs2` flags from the opcode (R/BRANCH/STORE = both;\\nI-type = rs1 only; U/J/FENCE/SYSTEM = neither). Qualify the\\n`load_use_hazard` expression with these flags so that matches on\\nimmediate fields no longer stall the pipeline.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire `if_id_w.instr[6:0]` into the new `if_id_opcode` port of the\\n`hazard_unit` instance. No other top-level signals are modified.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a new 7-bit `if_id_opcode` input. Inside the module compute\\n`uses_rs1` and `uses_rs2` flags from the opcode (R/BRANCH/STORE = both;\\nI-type = rs1 only; U/J/FENCE/SYSTEM = neither). Qualify the\\n`load_use_hazard` expression with these flags so that matches on\\nimmediate fields no longer stall the pipeline.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire `if_id_w.instr[6:0]` into the new `if_id_opcode` port of the\\n`hazard_unit` instance. No other top-level signals are modified.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:24:18.728881Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 5, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/test/test_pipeline.py']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"Expand BHT to 128 entries to reduce aliasing among forward branches\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the 32-entry BHT in if_stage with a 128-entry direct-mapped BHT.\\nChange the index from pc[6:2] to pc[8:2] (7 bits) and widen the\\nbht_update_idx port from 5 to 7 bits so EX can write back using in.pc[8:2].\\nThe counter update rule, strong-taken initialization, and interaction with\\nthe static backward-taken / JAL predictor remain exactly the same. No new\\npipeline bundles or control signals are introduced, making this a very low-\\nrisk resize of a component that is already known to work.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Widen bht_update_idx from 5 to 7 bits to match the 128-entry table index.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Enlarge the bht array to [0:127], update the init loop bound to 128, and change the read index from pc[6:2] to pc[8:2].\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change bht_update_idx from in.pc[6:2] to in.pc[8:2] so resolved branches write back to the correct 128-entry slot.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Widen bht_update_idx from 5 to 7 bits to match the 128-entry table index.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Enlarge the bht array to [0:127], update the init loop bound to 128, and change the read index from pc[6:2] to pc[8:2].\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change bht_update_idx from in.pc[6:2] to in.pc[8:2] so resolved branches write back to the correct 128-entry slot.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 337.3, \"delta_pct\": -3.01, \"vs_baseline\": 19.26, \"fmax_mhz\": 141.74, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4202246, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 11315, \"ff\": 2133, \"seeds\": [134.34, 143.8, 141.74], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:17:50.929383Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 5, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r5s2 (regression, -3.01%): A 128-entry BHT regressed CoreMark fitness because the 32-entry table already saturates the benchmark's forward-branch locality, and the larger IF-stage read mux degraded Fmax more than reduced aliasing improved IPC.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Fold WB mux into MEM stage and remove dead EX/MEM fields\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move the write-back data selection into the MEM stage so that the MEM/WB\\nregister stores only the final rd_wdata (already muxed between load_data and\\nalu_result).  The WB stage then becomes a pure passthrough.  This removes one\\n32-bit mux from the MEM/WB->EX forwarding critical path.  At the same time,\\ndelete the unused branch_taken and branch_target fields from ex_mem_t to\\nreduce area and routing congestion.  No pipeline behaviour changes; IPC stays\\nidentical and Fmax should improve slightly.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove branch_taken and branch_target from ex_mem_t (dead fields).\\nReplace alu_result and read_data in mem_wb_t with a single rd_wdata\\nfield that holds the final register write data.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Stop writing branch_taken and branch_target into the EX/MEM register.\\nAll other fields remain unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute rd_wdata = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? load_data : in.alu_result\\ncombinationally and store it in the MEM/WB register as reg_q.rd_wdata.\\nRemove the now-redundant alu_result and read_data assignments.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/wb_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the mem_to_reg mux with a passthrough: w_data = in.rd_wdata.\\nw_en and w_addr logic stays identical.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove branch_taken and branch_target from ex_mem_t (dead fields).\\nReplace alu_result and read_data in mem_wb_t with a single rd_wdata\\nfield that holds the final register write data.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Stop writing branch_taken and branch_target into the EX/MEM register.\\nAll other fields remain unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute rd_wdata = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? load_data : in.alu_result\\ncombinationally and store it in the MEM/WB register as reg_q.rd_wdata.\\nRemove the now-redundant alu_result and read_data assignments.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/wb_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the mem_to_reg mux with a passthrough: w_data = in.rd_wdata.\\nw_en and w_addr logic stays identical.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 229.88, \"delta_pct\": -33.9, \"vs_baseline\": -18.72, \"fmax_mhz\": 96.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10222, \"ff\": 1915, \"seeds\": [99.71, 96.63, 92.38], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:50:14.606389Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 6, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX stage alone consumes over\\n6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is dominated by arithmetic primitives.\\nDivision is essentially unused in CoreMark, yet the divider consumes a massive\\namount of area and routing resources that congest the fabric around the critical\\nALU adder path. Removing the combinational divider should relieve routing\\ncongestion and raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX stage alone consumes over\\n6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is dominated by arithmetic primitives.\\nDivision is essentially unused in CoreMark, yet the divider consumes a massive\\namount of area and routing resources that congest the fabric around the critical\\nALU adder path. Removing the combinational divider should relieve routing\\ncongestion and raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extract DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of the combinational ALU into a new\\n`divider.sv` module that performs non-restoring division in 33 cycles.\\nIn `ex_stage`, detect divide ops and assert a `div_busy` signal that\\nstalls the pipeline via the hazard unit until the divider finishes.\\nThe main ALU keeps all I-type ops and the multiplier path (which maps\\nto the on-chip DSP block). Update `hazard_unit` to extend `stall_ex_mem`\\nand `stall_id` when `div_busy` is high. This structural change shrinks\\nthe EX stage significantly, frees routing capacity on the critical path,\\nand should improve median Fmax without hurting CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and all combinational divide/rem\\nlogic. Keep the multiplier paths (mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) and the\\nRISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative non-restoring divider. Inputs: clock, reset, start,\\ndividend[31:0], divisor[31:0], signed_div. Outputs: quotient[31:0],\\nremainder[31:0], busy, done. Latency = 33 cycles. busy stays high\\nfrom start until done rises for one cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide ops from `in.ctrl.alu_op`. Route operands to the\\ndivider and assert `div_busy` while the divider is running. Drive\\n`alu_result` from the divider output when a divide op retires.\\nSuppress normal EX/MEM updates during `div_busy`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `div_busy` input. Assert `stall_ex_mem` and `stall_id` when\\n`div_busy` is high so the entire pipeline freezes until division\\ncompletes. Keep existing load-use and bus-stall logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the divider between EX and hazard unit. Wire\\n`div_busy` into the hazard unit. Connect divider inputs from\\n`id_ex_w` operands and `ex_mem_w` controls. No top-level IO\\nchanges.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and all combinational divide/rem\\nlogic. Keep the multiplier paths (mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) and the\\nRISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative non-restoring divider. Inputs: clock, reset, start,\\ndividend[31:0], divisor[31:0], signed_div. Outputs: quotient[31:0],\\nremainder[31:0], busy, done. Latency = 33 cycles. busy stays high\\nfrom start until done rises for one cycle.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide ops from `in.ctrl.alu_op`. Route operands to the\\ndivider and assert `div_busy` while the divider is running. Drive\\n`alu_result` from the divider output when a divide op retires.\\nSuppress normal EX/MEM updates during `div_busy`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `div_busy` input. Assert `stall_ex_mem` and `stall_id` when\\n`div_busy` is high so the entire pipeline freezes until division\\ncompletes. Keep existing load-use and bus-stall logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the divider between EX and hazard unit. Wire\\n`div_busy` into the hazard unit. Connect divider inputs from\\n`id_ex_w` operands and `ex_mem_w` controls. No top-level IO\\nchanges.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"cosim_failed: selftest.elf\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 6, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r6s1 (broken, n/a): A multi-cycle divider in EX requires a per-instruction state machine, not raw combinational busy/done logic: without a 'started' bit, `div_busy` deadlocks after a pulsed `done` because the instruction never leaves EX, while a level `done` prevents subsequent divides from re-starting.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Add 5-bit GHR gshare indexing to existing 32-entry BHT\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the proven 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter table, but index it\\nwith pc[6:2] ^ ghr[4:0] instead of pc[6:2] alone. A 5-bit GHR register\\nshifts in actual branch outcomes from EX-stage resolution, so the BHT\\nentry used for prediction is a function of both the branch address and\\nthe recent global control-flow path. To ensure the EX-stage counter\\nupdate writes the same entry that IF read, the GHR value present at\\nfetch time is snapshotted and threaded through the IF/ID and ID/EX\\npipeline bundles. The update rule (strongly-taken init, saturating\\nincrement/decrement) and the static backward-taken / JAL-always-taken\\nbase policy remain unchanged. This costs only 5 flops for the GHR plus\\n5 bits of pipeline state, with negligible combinational delay (a 5-bit\\nXOR on an already-existing mux path).\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0.\\nUpdate it on every EX-stage branch resolution by shifting in\\nbht_update_taken (ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_update_taken}).\\nReplace the BHT read index pc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr.\\nDrive the current ghr value into the combinational if_id_t output.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr into the ID/EX register so the snapshot reaches EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr so the counter update\\nwrites the exact entry that was read during fetch.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0.\\nUpdate it on every EX-stage branch resolution by shifting in\\nbht_update_taken (ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_update_taken}).\\nReplace the BHT read index pc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr.\\nDrive the current ghr value into the combinational if_id_t output.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr into the ID/EX register so the snapshot reaches EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr so the counter update\\nwrites the exact entry that was read during fetch.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 324.21, \"delta_pct\": -6.77, \"vs_baseline\": 14.63, \"fmax_mhz\": 136.99, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4225388, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10358, \"ff\": 1938, \"seeds\": [137.48, 135.85, 136.99], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:39:37.400024Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 6, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r6s2 (regression, -6.77%): Non-speculative GHR update at EX-stage resolution leaves history stale for tightly packed branches, causing the 5-bit XOR to increase destructive aliasing in the 32-entry BHT and regress CoreMark IPC.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the\\nSystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX\\nstage alone consumes over 6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is\\ndominated by arithmetic primitives. Division is essentially unused in\\nCoreMark, yet the combinational divider consumes massive area and\\nrouting resources that congest the fabric around the critical ALU adder\\npath, limiting Fmax. A prior attempt at this change failed because the\\ndivider state machine lacked a proper IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM with a\\n'started' bit, causing deadlock. With a correct FSM implementation,\\nremoving the combinational divider should relieve routing congestion\\nand raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the\\nSystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX\\nstage alone consumes over 6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is\\ndominated by arithmetic primitives. Division is essentially unused in\\nCoreMark, yet the combinational divider consumes massive area and\\nrouting resources that congest the fabric around the critical ALU adder\\npath, limiting Fmax. A prior attempt at this change failed because the\\ndivider state machine lacked a proper IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM with a\\n'started' bit, causing deadlock. With a correct FSM implementation,\\nremoving the combinational divider should relieve routing congestion\\nand raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extract DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of the combinational ALU into a new\\n`divider.sv` module that performs restoring division in 33 cycles.\\nThe divider MUST use a proper 3-state FSM (IDLE, RUNNING, DONE) with\\na registered 'started' bit:\\n  - IDLE:  waiting for start pulse. busy=0, done=0.\\n  - RUNNING: counting down 32 bits. busy=1, done=0.\\n  - DONE: result valid for one cycle. busy=0, done=1. Next clock\\n    returns to IDLE automatically.\\nIn `ex_stage`, detect divide ops and assert `div_start` for exactly\\none cycle when the divider is in IDLE. The hazard unit stalls IF,\\nID, and EX/MEM while `div_busy` (= RUNNING) is high. Because `busy`\\nis LOW in the DONE state, the EX/MEM register naturally captures the\\ndivider result on the done cycle and the next instruction can enter\\nEX on the following cycle. The main ALU keeps all I-type ops and the\\nmultiplier path. This structural change shrinks the EX stage\\nsignificantly, frees routing capacity on the critical path, and\\nshould improve median Fmax without hurting CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and all combinational divide/rem\\nlogic. Keep the multiplier paths and the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS\\nbranch unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative restoring divider with IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM.\\nInputs: clock, reset, start, dividend[31:0], divisor[31:0],\\nop[3:0] selecting DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU. Outputs: result[31:0],\\nbusy, done. 33-cycle latency. busy is high only in RUNNING.\\ndone is high for one cycle in DONE. Returns to IDLE on next\\nclock edge. Handles all RV32M corner cases (divide by zero,\\nINT_MIN/-1).\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide ops from in.ctrl.alu_op. Route operands to the\\ndivider and assert div_start when the divider is idle.\\nCapture divider result into ex_mem_w.alu_result when div_done\\nis high. Stall EX/MEM via hazard_unit during div_busy.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add div_busy input. Extend stall_if, stall_id, and stall_ex_mem\\nto freeze the entire pipeline while div_busy is high. Do not\\nassert flush_id during div_busy; hold the pipeline state.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate divider module. Wire div_busy into hazard_unit.\\nConnect divider inputs from id_ex_w operands. No top-level IO\\nchanges.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases and all combinational divide/rem\\nlogic. Keep the multiplier paths and the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS\\nbranch unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New iterative restoring divider with IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM.\\nInputs: clock, reset, start, dividend[31:0], divisor[31:0],\\nop[3:0] selecting DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU. Outputs: result[31:0],\\nbusy, done. 33-cycle latency. busy is high only in RUNNING.\\ndone is high for one cycle in DONE. Returns to IDLE on next\\nclock edge. Handles all RV32M corner cases (divide by zero,\\nINT_MIN/-1).\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect divide ops from in.ctrl.alu_op. Route operands to the\\ndivider and assert div_start when the divider is idle.\\nCapture divider result into ex_mem_w.alu_result when div_done\\nis high. Stall EX/MEM via hazard_unit during div_busy.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add div_busy input. Extend stall_if, stall_id, and stall_ex_mem\\nto freeze the entire pipeline while div_busy is high. Do not\\nassert flush_id during div_busy; hold the pipeline state.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate divider module. Wire div_busy into hazard_unit.\\nConnect divider inputs from id_ex_w operands. No top-level IO\\nchanges.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T06:07:59.336648Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 7, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/alu.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/test/test_alu.py', 'cores/bench/test/test_pipeline.py', 'cores/bench/rtl/divider.sv', 'cores/bench/test/test_divider.py']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r7s2.yaml\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"schema_error: 'category' is a required property\\n\\nFailed validating 'required' in schema:\\n    {'$schema': 'http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#',\\n     'type': 'object',\\n     'required': ['id',\\n                  'title',\\n                  'category',\\n                  'motivation',\\n                  'hypothesis',\\n                  'expected_impact',\\n                  'changes'],\\n     'properties': {'id': {'type': 'string',\\n                           'pattern': '^hyp-[0-9]{8}-[0-9]{3}(-r[0-9]+s[0-9]+)?$'},\\n                    'title': {'type': 'string', 'minLength': 5},\\n                    'category': {'type': 'string',\\n                                 'enum': ['micro_opt',\\n                                          'structural',\\n                                          'extension',\\n                                          'predictor',\\n              