": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped Branch History Table with 2-bit saturating\\ncounters to the IF stage. The table is indexed by PC[6:2] and initialized to\\nstrongly-taken (2'b11) so backward loops are correct immediately without any\\ntraining cost. For every conditional branch, the BHT entry MSB drives\\npredict_taken; unconditional JAL continues to be always predicted taken. In\\nEX stage, each resolved branch writes its actual outcome back to the entry\\nindexed by the branch PC using a standard saturating update rule. This adds\\nonly 64 flops and a few LUTs of combinational logi... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n14: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Eliminate false load-use stalls via opcode-aware hazard detection\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit conservatively stalls on any LOAD-to-use sequence where the\\nLOAD's rd matches either rs1 or rs2 of the next instruction, regardless of\\nwhether those fields are actually register reads. For I-type instructions\\n(OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR) the rs2 field encodes an immediate or shamt; for U-type\\n(LUI, AUIPC), J-type (JAL), and SYSTEM/FENCE instructions neither field is a\\nregister read. These false stalls waste cycles\\u2014especially on CoreMark's heavy\\nuse of ADDI, LUI, and JAL immediately after pointer loads\\u2014with negligible\\nLUT cost and no impact on Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit conservatively stalls on any LOAD-to-use sequence where the\\nLOAD's rd matches either rs1 or rs2 of the next instruction, regardless of\\nwhether those fields are actually register reads. For I-type instructions\\n(OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR) the rs2 field encodes an immediate or shamt; for U-type\\n(LUI, AUIPC), J-type (JAL), and SYSTEM/FENCE instructions neither field is a\\nregister read. These false stalls waste cycles\\u2014especially on CoreMark's heavy\\nuse of ADDI, LUI, and JAL immediately after pointer loads\\u2014with negligible\\nLUT cost and no impact on Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add opcode decoding to hazard_unit so the load_use_hazard term only fires\\nwhen the instruction in ID genuinely reads rs1 or rs2. R-type, BRANCH, and\\nSTORE read both; I-type reads only rs1; U/J/FENCE/SYSTEM read neither. The\\nstall_if / stall_id / flush_id logic otherwise stays identical, so no other\\npipeline behavior changes. This removes spurious one-cycle bubbles without\\nlengthening any critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a new 7-bit `if_id_opcode` input. Inside the module compute\\n`uses_rs1` and `uses_rs2` fla... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n15: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 5, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The IF stage currently stalls the entire pipeline on every imem_ready=0 cycle,\\ninjecting a NOP bubble into ID/EX. At the same time, during load-use or dmem\\nstalls the PC holds even though imem may be ready, wasting a fetch slot.\\nDecoupling fetch from issue with a 1-entry buffer lets us prefetch one\\ninstruction ahead during downstream stalls and then issue it when imem\\nsubsequently stalls, hiding single-cycle bus bubbles without lengthening\\nany critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure if_stage to hold a 1-entry prefetch buffer (buf_pc, buf_instr,\\nbuf_pred_taken, buf_valid).  The fetch PC advances whenever imem_ready is\\nhigh and there is a free buffer slot.  An instruction is issued to ID from\\nthe buffer if available, otherwise directly from imem_data, and only a\\ntrue NOP is emitted when both sources are empty.  In hazard_unit, stop\\ntreating imem_ready=0 as a global stall_if / flush_if event; instead let\\nif_stage backpressure itself locally.  This structural decoupling turns\\notherwise-wasted fetch slots during load-use/dmem stalls into prefetches,\\nimproving average IPC at the cost of ~66 flops and a few LUTs.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 1-entry prefetch buffer registers and rewrite the issue / fill\\nFSM so that fetch_pc advances on every imem_ready while a slot exists.\\nOutput mux selects buffer, direct imem_data, or NOP based on buffer\\noccupancy and imem_ready.  Accept stall_core (load-use + dmem only)\\nand imem_ready directly instead of the old stall/flush pair.\\n\"... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n16: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"Expand BHT to 128 entries to reduce aliasing among forward branches\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the 32-entry BHT in if_stage with a 128-entry direct-mapped BHT.\\nChange the index from pc[6:2] to pc[8:2] (7 bits) and widen the\\nbht_update_idx port from 5 to 7 bits so EX can write back using in.pc[8:2].\\nThe counter update rule, strong-taken initialization, and interaction with\\nthe static backward-taken / JAL predictor remain exactly the same. No new\\npipeline bundles or control signals are introduced, making this a very low-\\nrisk resize of a component that is already known to work.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Widen bht_update_idx from 5 to 7 bits to match the 128-entry table index.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Enlarge the bht array to [0:127], update the init... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n17: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Fold WB mux into MEM stage and remove dead EX/MEM fields\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move the write-back data selection into the MEM stage so that the MEM/WB\\nregister stores only the final rd_wdata (already muxed between load_data and\\nalu_result).  The WB stage then becomes a pure passthrough.  This removes one\\n32-bit mux from the MEM/WB->EX forwarding critical path.  At the same time,\\ndelete the unused branch_taken and branch_target fields from ex_mem_t to\\nreduce area and routing congestion.  No pipeline behaviour changes; IPC stays\\nidentical and Fmax should improve slightly.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove branch_taken ... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX stage alone consumes over\\n6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is dominated by arithmetic primitives.\\nDivision is essentially unused in CoreMark, yet the divider consumes a massive\\namount of area and routing resources that congest the fabric around the critical\\nALU adder path. Removing the combinational divider should relieve routing\\ncongestion and raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX stage alone consumes over\\n6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is dominated by arithmetic primitives.\\nDivision is essentially unused in CoreMark, yet the divider consumes a massive\\namount of area and routing resources that congest the fabric around the critical\\nALU adder path. Removing the combinational divider should relieve routing\\ncongestion and raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extract DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of the combinational ALU into a new\\n`divider.sv` module that performs non-restoring division in 33 cycles.\\nIn `ex_stage`, detect divide ops and assert a `div_busy` signal that\\nstalls the pipeline via the hazard unit until the divider finishes.\\nThe main ALU keeps all I-type ops and the multiplier path (which maps\\nto the on-chip DSP block). Update `hazard_unit` to extend `stall_ex_mem`\\nand `stall_id` when `div_busy` is high. This structural change shrinks\\nthe EX stage significantly, frees routing capacity on the critical path,\\nand should improve median Fmax without hurting CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": ... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n19: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Add 5-bit GHR gshare indexing to existing 32-entry BHT\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the proven 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter table, but index it\\nwith pc[6:2] ^ ghr[4:0] instead of pc[6:2] alone. A 5-bit GHR register\\nshifts in actual branch outcomes from EX-stage resolution, so the BHT\\nentry used for prediction is a function of both the branch address and\\nthe recent global control-flow path. To ensure the EX-stage counter\\nupdate writes the same entry that IF read, the GHR value present at\\nfetch time is snapshotted and threaded through the IF/ID and... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n20: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Precompute forwarding selects in ID stage to shorten EX critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The EX-stage critical path currently includes the forward_unit's 5-bit\\naddress comparison, priority encoder, and operand forwarding mux before the\\nALU.  On a LUT-based FPGA these extra logic levels consume precious\\nnanoseconds.  By shifting the forwarding decision into the ID stage\\u2014where\\nthe same comparison is performed against the instructions currently in EX\\nand MEM\\u2014we register the 2-bit select signals into the ID/EX pipeline\\nregister.  This removes the comparison and control generation from the\\nEX-stage datapath without changing pipeline behaviour or IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX-stage critical path currently includes the forward_unit's 5-bit\\naddress comparison, priority encoder, and operand forwarding mux before the\\nALU.  On a LUT-based FPGA these extra logic levels consume precious\\nnanoseconds.  By shifting the forwarding decision into the ID stage\\u2014where\\nthe same comparison is performed against the instructions currently in EX\\nand MEM\\u2014we register the 2-bit select signals into the ID/EX pipeline\\nregister.  This removes the comparison and control generation from the\\nEX-stage datapath without changing pipeline behaviour or IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add fwd_rs1_sel and fwd_rs2_sel (2 bits each) to the id_ex_t bundle.\\nIn id_stage, compute the forwarding selects combinationally by comparing\\nthe current IF/ID instruction's rs1_addr/rs2_addr against the rd and\\nreg_write flags of the instruction currently in EX (the ID/EX register)\\nand the instruction currently in MEM (ex_mem_w), preserving the same\\nEX/MEM-over-MEM/WB priority and x0 guard that forward_unit uses today.\\nRegister these selects into the ID/EX payload.  In ex_stage, remove the\\nforward_unit input ports and use the precomputed in.fwd_rs1_sel /\\nin.fwd_rs2_sel directly in the operand forwarding muxes.  In... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(Showing lines 1-20 of 31. Use offset=21 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"baseline-bench-4217612\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 282.82, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9563, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [128.72, 127.03, 123.02], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T01:36:12.712654Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r1s0.yaml\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"schema_error: while scanning a simple key\\n  in \\\"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r1s0.yaml\\\", line 6, column 1\\ncould not find expected ':'\\n  in \\\"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r1s0.yaml\\\", line 7, column 1\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 1}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Add static branch predictor (backward-taken, JAL-always-taken)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core incurs a 1-cycle bubble on every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause IF always speculatively fetches PC+4. CoreMark is loop-heavy, so backward\\nbranches and function calls are frequent. A static predictor that fetches the\\ntarget for backward branches and JAL eliminates the bubble on the common case,\\nimproving IPC with negligible LUT cost (~50 LUTs) and no impact on the critical\\npath.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core incurs a 1-cycle bubble on every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause IF always speculatively fetches PC+4. CoreMark is loop-heavy, so backward\\nbranches and function calls are frequent. A static predictor that fetches the\\ntarget for backward branches and JAL eliminates the bubble on the common case,\\nimproving IPC with negligible LUT cost (~50 LUTs) and no impact on the critical\\npath.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert decode-and-predict logic in the IF stage. When the fetched instruction is\\na BRANCH with a negative immediate (backward loop) or an unconditional JAL, the\\nPC is updated to the computed target instead of PC+4. A 1-bit pred_taken flag is\\nthreaded through the IF/ID and ID/EX bundles. The EX stage suppresses redirect\\nwhen the prediction was correct; it only asserts redirect (triggering IF/ID flush)\\non mispredict. JALR remains unpredicted. This saves one cycle per correctly\\npredicted taken branch or JAL.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add pred_taken bit to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Decode BRANCH/JAL opcodes from imem_data, compute B/J immediates, set predict_taken for backward branches and JAL, and select next_pc from the predicted target when predict_taken is asserted.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"desc... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Static BTFN branch predictor + JAL prediction in ID stage\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline resolves all control-flow instructions in EX and pays a\\nfixed 2-cycle bubble (flush IF/ID) for every taken branch and every jump. CoreMark is\\nloop-heavy; backward branches are taken the vast majority of the time. A static\\nBackward-Taken / Forward-Not-Taken (BTFN) predictor combined with unconditional JAL\\nprediction, both computed in the ID stage, eliminates the 2-cycle penalty for the\\nmost common control-flow cases at virtually zero area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline resolves all control-flow instructions in EX and pays a\\nfixed 2-cycle bubble (flush IF/ID) for every taken branch and every jump. CoreMark is\\nloop-heavy; backward branches are taken the vast majority of the time. A static\\nBackward-Taken / Forward-Not-Taken (BTFN) predictor combined with unconditional JAL\\nprediction, both computed in the ID stage, eliminates the 2-cycle penalty for the\\nmost common control-flow cases at virtually zero area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a simple static predictor in the ID stage that:\\n1) Predicts JAL (unconditional jump) always taken.\\n2) Predicts conditional branches as taken iff the immediate is negative (backward).\\n3) Redirects the IF PC and flushes the combinational IF/ID output in the same cycle\\n   the branch/jump is in ID.  A `predict_taken` bit is carried through ID/EX so that\\n   EX only asserts `redirect` on a mispredict (predicted-not-taken but taken, or\\n   predicted-taken but not-taken).  JALR is intentionally *not* predicted because its\\n   target depends on `rs1`, which may still be pending from an in-flight ALU result\\n (forwarding only exists in EX, not ID).\\n\\nThis turns the common-case loop-back branch from a 2-cycle penalty into 0 cycles,\\nand unconditional JAL from 2 cycles to 0 cycles, while keeping forward branches and\\nJALR at their ... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"MEM-to-EX load bypass to eliminate load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline stalls for one cycle on every load-use hazard\\nbecause it can only forward loaded data from MEM/WB, not from the MEM stage\\nitself.  CoreMark pointer-chasing and array-index patterns frequently emit a\\nLOAD followed immediately by a dependent ALU or STORE.  Eliminating the\\nload-use bubble improves IPC with no extra pipeline stages or tables.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline stalls for one cycle on every load-use hazard\\nbecause it can only forward loaded data from MEM/WB, not from the MEM stage\\nitself.  CoreMark pointer-chasing and array-index patterns frequently emit a\\nLOAD followed immediately by a dependent ALU or STORE.  Eliminating the\\nload-use bubble improves IPC with no extra pipeline stages or tables.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a combinational bypass from mem_stage's load_data output back to the\\nEX-stage operand muxes.  Extend the forwarding_unit so that when EX/MEM\\ncontains a LOAD whose rd matches an EX-stage rs, it selects the new bypass\\npath (encoding 2'b11).  Remove the load_use_hazard stall from hazard_unit;\\nthe bypass makes it unnecessary.  All other stalls (imem/dmem backpressure,\\nredirect flush) remain unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 7, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the load_use_hazard term from stall_if, stall_id, and flush_id. The MEM\\u2192EX bypass eliminates the need to stall the pipeline for load-use.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_mem_mem_read input.  When EX/MEM has a matching rd and ex_mem_mem_read is high, drive fwd_rs1/fwd_rs2 = 2'b11 to select the MEM-stage load bypass instead of the ALU-result path.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_mem_load [31:0] input.  Extend the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes to select fwd_mem_load ... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/forward_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/mem_stage.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 2}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Add 4-entry Return Address Stack for JALR return prediction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor eliminates bubbles for backward branches and\\nunconditional JAL, but every JALR (function return) still incurs a 1-cycle\\nflush because the target is unknown until EX. CoreMark contains frequent\\nnested function calls, so returns are a noticeable fraction of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream. A tiny Return Address Stack (RAS) pushes the link\\naddress on JAL-to-x1/x5 and pops it on JALR-from-x1/x5, predicting the\\nreturn target in IF with high accuracy at negligible area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor eliminates bubbles for backward branches and\\nunconditional JAL, but every JALR (function return) still incurs a 1-cycle\\nflush because the target is unknown until EX. CoreMark contains frequent\\nnested function calls, so returns are a noticeable fraction of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream. A tiny Return Address Stack (RAS) pushes the link\\naddress on JAL-to-x1/x5 and pops it on JALR-from-x1/x5, predicting the\\nreturn target in IF with high accuracy at negligible area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extend the IF-stage predictor with a 4-entry RAS. When the fetched\\ninstruction is a JAL with rd=x1 or x5, push PC+4 onto the stack. When the\\nfetched instruction is a JALR with rs1=x1 or x5 and the stack is non-empty,\\npop the top entry and treat it as the predicted target (pred_taken=1,\\npred_target=ras_top). Thread the predicted target through the IF/ID and\\nID/EX bundles so that EX can verify it. In EX, a JALR only causes a\\nredirect when it was unpredicted (!pred_taken) or when the actual target\\ndiffers from pred_target. The RAS pointer is updated only on non-stalled,\\nnon-flushed cycles. This removes the bubble on the vast majority of\\nreturns.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Eliminate false load-use stalls via opcode-aware hazard detection\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current hazard_unit conservatively checks both rs1 (instr[19:15]) and rs2\\n(instr[24:20]) of the instruction in ID against the LOAD's rd in EX,\\nregardless of whether the instruction actually reads those fields as registers.\\nFor I-type (OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR), U-type, and J-type instructions, the rs2\\nfield is an immediate/shamt, not a register address. A LOAD followed by an\\nADDI where imm[4:0] happens to match the LOAD's rd currently triggers a\\nspurious one-cycle stall. CoreMark uses small immediate values extensively,\\nso false stalls on common x1-x5 register numbers are likely frequent.\\nEliminating these false stalls improves IPC with negligible LUT/Fmax cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current hazard_unit conservatively checks both rs1 (instr[19:15]) and rs2\\n(instr[24:20]) of the instruction in ID against the LOAD's rd in EX,\\nregardless of whether the instruction actually reads those fields as registers.\\nFor I-type (OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR), U-type, and J-type instructions, the rs2\\nfield is an immediate/shamt, not a register address. A LOAD followed by an\\nADDI where imm[4:0] happens to match the LOAD's rd currently triggers a\\nspurious one-cycle stall. CoreMark uses small immediate values extensively,\\nso false stalls on common x1-x5 register numbers are likely frequent.\\nEliminating these false stalls improves IPC with negligible LUT/Fmax cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add opcode decoding to hazard_unit so load-use detection only fires when\\nthe instruction in ID actually reads rs1/rs2 as registers. R-type, I-type\\n(OP-IMM/LOAD/JALR), S-type, and B-type use rs1; R-type, S-type, and B-type\\nuse rs2. U-type and J-type use neither. This removes false stalls without\\naltering pipeline structure or lengthening critical paths.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": ... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260513-002-r3s1 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260513-001-r3s0', 'hyp-20260513-002-r3s1', 'hyp-20260513-003-r3s2'])\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 3}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"Add 32-entry tagged BTB with 2-bit saturating counters for branch target caching and forward-branch learning\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor correctly predicts backward branches and JAL,\\nbut forward branches that are frequently taken are always mispredicted.\\nAdditionally, the combinational branch-target computation in the IF stage\\n(opcode decode \\u2192 immediate extraction \\u2192 sign-extension \\u2192 PC adder) may\\ncontribute to the critical path. A small Branch Target Buffer can learn\\ntaken forward branches, cache targets to shorten the IF-stage path, and\\ncoexist safely with the existing static BTFN predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor correctly predicts backward branches and JAL,\\nbut forward branches that are frequently taken are always mispredicted.\\nAdditionally, the combinational branch-target computation in the IF stage\\n(opcode decode \\u2192 immediate extraction \\u2192 sign-extension \\u2192 PC adder) may\\ncontribute to the critical path. A small Branch Target Buffer can learn\\ntaken forward branches, cache targets to shorten the IF-stage path, and\\ncoexist safely with the existing static BTFN predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped Branch Target Buffer in the IF stage.\\nEach entry stores a valid bit, a 5-bit tag (PC[11:7]), a 30-bit\\nword-aligned target, and a 2-bit saturating counter.  In IF, a BTB\\nhit on a branch or JAL supplies the target directly from a register\\nread, bypassing the combinational immediate+adder path.  Direction\\nprediction remains static-taken for backward branches and JAL, but\\nthe BTB can additionally predict taken for forward branches once\\ntheir counter reaches 2.  In EX, every resolved branch/JAL writes\\nits outcome and target back into the BTB.  JALR is excluded from\\nBTB usage to avoid aliasing noise.  This should improve IPC on\\ntaken forward branches and may raise Fmax by reducing IF-... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r4s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r4s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r4s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r4s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r4s2'])\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 4}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Move JALR target resolution to ID stage to cut penalty from 2 to 1 cycle\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"JALR is currently unpredicted in IF and resolved in EX, incurring a 2-cycle\\nmisprediction bubble on every function return and indirect call. CoreMark's\\nlist benchmark makes frequent function calls through pointers, so JALR\\nbubbles are a real IPC limiter.  Because the return address register (x1)\\nis almost always in the regfile when the JALR reaches ID (no forwarding\\nneeded), we can compute the target address in ID stage and redirect IF one\\ncycle earlier, shrinking the penalty to a single flushed fetch slot.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"JALR is currently unpredicted in IF and resolved in EX, incurring a 2-cycle\\nmisprediction bubble on every function return and indirect call. CoreMark's\\nlist benchmark makes frequent function calls through pointers, so JALR\\nbubbles are a real IPC limiter.  Because the return address register (x1)\\nis almost always in the regfile when the JALR reaches ID (no forwarding\\nneeded), we can compute the target address in ID stage and redirect IF one\\ncycle earlier, shrinking the penalty to a single flushed fetch slot.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a JALR target adder in the ID stage: when the decoded instruction is\\nJALR and its rs1 is not the subject of an in-flight load-use hazard, compute\\njalr_target = (rs1_data + imm) & ~1 and assert a new id_redirect signal.\\nThread a jalr_redirected flag through the id_ex_t bundle so the EX stage\\nsuppresses its own redirect for JALRs that were already handled in ID.\\nAt the top level, OR the new id_redirect with the existing ex_redirect to\\ndrive the PC, and adjust flush_if/flush_id so that a JALR in ID is allowed\\nto advance into EX while the speculative fetch in IF is killed.\\nThis structural change shortens the JALR resolution loop by one full stage\\nwithout touching any other instruction type.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"Add 32-entry 2-bit BHT for forward branch direction prediction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped Branch History Table with 2-bit saturating\\ncounters to the IF stage. The table is indexed by PC[6:2] and initialized to\\nstrongly-taken (2'b11) so backward loops are correct immediately without any\\ntraining cost. For every conditional branch, the BHT entry MSB drives\\npredict_taken; unconditional JAL continues to be always predicted taken. In\\nEX stage, each resolved branch writes its actual outcome back to the entry\\nindexed by the branch PC using a standard saturating update rule. This adds\\nonly 64 flops and a few LUTs of combinational logi... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Eliminate false load-use stalls via opcode-aware hazard detection\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit conservatively stalls on any LOAD-to-use sequence where the\\nLOAD's rd matches either rs1 or rs2 of the next instruction, regardless of\\nwhether those fields are actually register reads. For I-type instructions\\n(OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR) the rs2 field encodes an immediate or shamt; for U-type\\n(LUI, AUIPC), J-type (JAL), and SYSTEM/FENCE instructions neither field is a\\nregister read. These false stalls waste cycles\\u2014especially on CoreMark's heavy\\nuse of ADDI, LUI, and JAL immediately after pointer loads\\u2014with negligible\\nLUT cost and no impact on Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit conservatively stalls on any LOAD-to-use sequence where the\\nLOAD's rd matches either rs1 or rs2 of the next instruction, regardless of\\nwhether those fields are actually register reads. For I-type instructions\\n(OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR) the rs2 field encodes an immediate or shamt; for U-type\\n(LUI, AUIPC), J-type (JAL), and SYSTEM/FENCE instructions neither field is a\\nregister read. These false stalls waste cycles\\u2014especially on CoreMark's heavy\\nuse of ADDI, LUI, and JAL immediately after pointer loads\\u2014with negligible\\nLUT cost and no impact on Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add opcode decoding to hazard_unit so the load_use_hazard term only fires\\nwhen the instruction in ID genuinely reads rs1 or rs2. R-type, BRANCH, and\\nSTORE read both; I-type reads only rs1; U/J/FENCE/SYSTEM read neither. The\\nstall_if / stall_id / flush_id logic otherwise stays identical, so no other\\npipeline behavior changes. This removes spurious one-cycle bubbles without\\nlengthening any critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a new 7-bit `if_id_opcode` input. Inside the module compute\\n`uses_rs1` and `uses_rs2` fla... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 5, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The IF stage currently stalls the entire pipeline on every imem_ready=0 cycle,\\ninjecting a NOP bubble into ID/EX. At the same time, during load-use or dmem\\nstalls the PC holds even though imem may be ready, wasting a fetch slot.\\nDecoupling fetch from issue with a 1-entry buffer lets us prefetch one\\ninstruction ahead during downstream stalls and then issue it when imem\\nsubsequently stalls, hiding single-cycle bus bubbles without lengthening\\nany critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure if_stage to hold a 1-entry prefetch buffer (buf_pc, buf_instr,\\nbuf_pred_taken, buf_valid).  The fetch PC advances whenever imem_ready is\\nhigh and there is a free buffer slot.  An instruction is issued to ID from\\nthe buffer if available, otherwise directly from imem_data, and only a\\ntrue NOP is emitted when both sources are empty.  In hazard_unit, stop\\ntreating imem_ready=0 as a global stall_if / flush_if event; instead let\\nif_stage backpressure itself locally.  This structural decoupling turns\\notherwise-wasted fetch slots during load-use/dmem stalls into prefetches,\\nimproving average IPC at the cost of ~66 flops and a few LUTs.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 1-entry prefetch buffer registers and rewrite the issue / fill\\nFSM so that fetch_pc advances on every imem_ready while a slot exists.\\nOutput mux selects buffer, direct imem_data, or NOP based on buffer\\noccupancy and imem_ready.  Accept stall_core (load-use + dmem only)\\nand imem_ready directly instead of the old stall/flush pair.\\n\"... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"Expand BHT to 128 entries to reduce aliasing among forward branches\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the 32-entry BHT in if_stage with a 128-entry direct-mapped BHT.\\nChange the index from pc[6:2] to pc[8:2] (7 bits) and widen the\\nbht_update_idx port from 5 to 7 bits so EX can write back using in.pc[8:2].\\nThe counter update rule, strong-taken initialization, and interaction with\\nthe static backward-taken / JAL predictor remain exactly the same. No new\\npipeline bundles or control signals are introduced, making this a very low-\\nrisk resize of a component that is already known to work.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Widen bht_update_idx from 5 to 7 bits to match the 128-entry table index.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Enlarge the bht array to [0:127], update the init... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Fold WB mux into MEM stage and remove dead EX/MEM fields\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move the write-back data selection into the MEM stage so that the MEM/WB\\nregister stores only the final rd_wdata (already muxed between load_data and\\nalu_result).  The WB stage then becomes a pure passthrough.  This removes one\\n32-bit mux from the MEM/WB->EX forwarding critical path.  At the same time,\\ndelete the unused branch_taken and branch_target fields from ex_mem_t to\\nreduce area and routing congestion.  No pipeline behaviour changes; IPC stays\\nidentical and Fmax should improve slightly.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove branch_taken ... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX stage alone consumes over\\n6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is dominated by arithmetic primitives.\\nDivision is essentially unused in CoreMark, yet the divider consumes a massive\\namount of area and routing resources that congest the fabric around the critical\\nALU adder path. Removing the combinational divider should relieve routing\\ncongestion and raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the SystemVerilog\\n`/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX stage alone consumes over\\n6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is dominated by arithmetic primitives.\\nDivision is essentially unused in CoreMark, yet the divider consumes a massive\\namount of area and routing resources that congest the fabric around the critical\\nALU adder path. Removing the combinational divider should relieve routing\\ncongestion and raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extract DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of the combinational ALU into a new\\n`divider.sv` module that performs non-restoring division in 33 cycles.\\nIn `ex_stage`, detect divide ops and assert a `div_busy` signal that\\nstalls the pipeline via the hazard unit until the divider finishes.\\nThe main ALU keeps all I-type ops and the multiplier path (which maps\\nto the on-chip DSP block). Update `hazard_unit` to extend `stall_ex_mem`\\nand `stall_id` when `div_busy` is high. This structural change shrinks\\nthe EX stage significantly, frees routing capacity on the critical path,\\nand should improve median Fmax without hurting CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": ... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Add 5-bit GHR gshare indexing to existing 32-entry BHT\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and