{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778745335856,"sessionID":"ses_1da8c0d24ffeyR5lnSLdShWPv7","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"grep:13","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"iteration|trip count|exit predict","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 16 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 1: {\"id\": \"baseline-bench-4217612\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 282.82, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9563, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [128.72, 127.03, 123.02], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T01:36:12.712654Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Add static branch predictor (backward-taken, JAL-always-taken)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core incurs a 1-cycle bubble on every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause IF always speculatively fetches PC+4. CoreMark is loop-heavy, so backward\\nbranches and function calls are frequent. A static predictor that fetches the\\ntarget for backward branches and JAL eliminates the bubble on the common case,\\nimproving IPC with negligible LUT cost (~50 LUTs) and no impact on the critical\\npath.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core incurs a 1-cycle bubble on every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause IF always speculatively fetches PC+4. CoreMark is loop-heavy, so backward\\nbranches and function calls are frequent. A static predictor that fetches the\\ntarget for backward branches and JAL eliminates the bubble on the common case,\\nimproving IPC with negligible LUT cost (~50 LUTs) and no impact on the critical\\npath.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert decode-and-predict logic in the IF stage. When the fetched instruction is\\na BRANCH with a negative immediate (backward loop) or an unconditional JAL, the\\nPC is updated to the computed target instead of PC+4. A 1-bit pred_taken flag is\\nthreaded through the IF/ID and ID/EX bundles. The EX stage suppresses redirect\\nwhen the prediction was correct; it only asserts redirect (triggering IF/ID flush)\\non mispredict. JALR remains unpredicted. This saves one cycle per correctly\\npredicted taken branch or JAL.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add pred_taken bit to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Decode BRANCH/JAL opcodes from imem_data, compute B/J immediates, set predict_taken for backward branches and JAL, and select next_pc from the predicted target when predict_taken is asserted.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"desc...\n  Line 4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Static BTFN branch predictor + JAL prediction in ID stage\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline resolves all control-flow instructions in EX and pays a\\nfixed 2-cycle bubble (flush IF/ID) for every taken branch and every jump. CoreMark is\\nloop-heavy; backward branches are taken the vast majority of the time. A static\\nBackward-Taken / Forward-Not-Taken (BTFN) predictor combined with unconditional JAL\\nprediction, both computed in the ID stage, eliminates the 2-cycle penalty for the\\nmost common control-flow cases at virtually zero area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline resolves all control-flow instructions in EX and pays a\\nfixed 2-cycle bubble (flush IF/ID) for every taken branch and every jump. CoreMark is\\nloop-heavy; backward branches are taken the vast majority of the time. A static\\nBackward-Taken / Forward-Not-Taken (BTFN) predictor combined with unconditional JAL\\nprediction, both computed in the ID stage, eliminates the 2-cycle penalty for the\\nmost common control-flow cases at virtually zero area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a simple static predictor in the ID stage that:\\n1) Predicts JAL (unconditional jump) always taken.\\n2) Predicts conditional branches as taken iff the immediate is negative (backward).\\n3) Redirects the IF PC and flushes the combinational IF/ID output in the same cycle\\n   the branch/jump is in ID.  A `predict_taken` bit is carried through ID/EX so that\\n   EX only asserts `redirect` on a mispredict (predicted-not-taken but taken, or\\n   predicted-taken but not-taken).  JALR is intentionally *not* predicted because its\\n   target depends on `rs1`, which may still be pending from an in-flight ALU result\\n (forwarding only exists in EX, not ID).\\n\\nThis turns the common-case loop-back branch from a 2-cycle penalty into 0 cycles,\\nand unconditional JAL from 2 cycles to 0 cycles, while keeping forward branches and\\nJALR at their ...\n  Line 5: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"MEM-to-EX load bypass to eliminate load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline stalls for one cycle on every load-use hazard\\nbecause it can only forward loaded data from MEM/WB, not from the MEM stage\\nitself.  CoreMark pointer-chasing and array-index patterns frequently emit a\\nLOAD followed immediately by a dependent ALU or STORE.  Eliminating the\\nload-use bubble improves IPC with no extra pipeline stages or tables.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline stalls for one cycle on every load-use hazard\\nbecause it can only forward loaded data from MEM/WB, not from the MEM stage\\nitself.  CoreMark pointer-chasing and array-index patterns frequently emit a\\nLOAD followed immediately by a dependent ALU or STORE.  Eliminating the\\nload-use bubble improves IPC with no extra pipeline stages or tables.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a combinational bypass from mem_stage's load_data output back to the\\nEX-stage operand muxes.  Extend the forwarding_unit so that when EX/MEM\\ncontains a LOAD whose rd matches an EX-stage rs, it selects the new bypass\\npath (encoding 2'b11).  Remove the load_use_hazard stall from hazard_unit;\\nthe bypass makes it unnecessary.  All other stalls (imem/dmem backpressure,\\nredirect flush) remain unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 7, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the load_use_hazard term from stall_if, stall_id, and flush_id. The MEM\\u2192EX bypass eliminates the need to stall the pipeline for load-use.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ex_mem_mem_read input.  When EX/MEM has a matching rd and ex_mem_mem_read is high, drive fwd_rs1/fwd_rs2 = 2'b11 to select the MEM-stage load bypass instead of the ALU-result path.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_mem_load [31:0] input.  Extend the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes to select fwd_mem_load ...\n  Line 7: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Add 4-entry Return Address Stack for JALR return prediction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor eliminates bubbles for backward branches and\\nunconditional JAL, but every JALR (function return) still incurs a 1-cycle\\nflush because the target is unknown until EX. CoreMark contains frequent\\nnested function calls, so returns are a noticeable fraction of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream. A tiny Return Address Stack (RAS) pushes the link\\naddress on JAL-to-x1/x5 and pops it on JALR-from-x1/x5, predicting the\\nreturn target in IF with high accuracy at negligible area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor eliminates bubbles for backward branches and\\nunconditional JAL, but every JALR (function return) still incurs a 1-cycle\\nflush because the target is unknown until EX. CoreMark contains frequent\\nnested function calls, so returns are a noticeable fraction of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream. A tiny Return Address Stack (RAS) pushes the link\\naddress on JAL-to-x1/x5 and pops it on JALR-from-x1/x5, predicting the\\nreturn target in IF with high accuracy at negligible area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extend the IF-stage predictor with a 4-entry RAS. When the fetched\\ninstruction is a JAL with rd=x1 or x5, push PC+4 onto the stack. When the\\nfetched instruction is a JALR with rs1=x1 or x5 and the stack is non-empty,\\npop the top entry and treat it as the predicted target (pred_taken=1,\\npred_target=ras_top). Thread the predicted target through the IF/ID and\\nID/EX bundles so that EX can verify it. In EX, a JALR only causes a\\nredirect when it was unpredicted (!pred_taken) or when the actual target\\ndiffers from pred_target. The RAS pointer is updated only on non-stalled,\\nnon-flushed cycles. This removes the bubble on the vast majority of\\nreturns.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description...\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Move JALR target resolution to ID stage to cut penalty from 2 to 1 cycle\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"JALR is currently unpredicted in IF and resolved in EX, incurring a 2-cycle\\nmisprediction bubble on every function return and indirect call. CoreMark's\\nlist benchmark makes frequent function calls through pointers, so JALR\\nbubbles are a real IPC limiter.  Because the return address register (x1)\\nis almost always in the regfile when the JALR reaches ID (no forwarding\\nneeded), we can compute the target address in ID stage and redirect IF one\\ncycle earlier, shrinking the penalty to a single flushed fetch slot.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"JALR is currently unpredicted in IF and resolved in EX, incurring a 2-cycle\\nmisprediction bubble on every function return and indirect call. CoreMark's\\nlist benchmark makes frequent function calls through pointers, so JALR\\nbubbles are a real IPC limiter.  Because the return address register (x1)\\nis almost always in the regfile when the JALR reaches ID (no forwarding\\nneeded), we can compute the target address in ID stage and redirect IF one\\ncycle earlier, shrinking the penalty to a single flushed fetch slot.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a JALR target adder in the ID stage: when the decoded instruction is\\nJALR and its rs1 is not the subject of an in-flight load-use hazard, compute\\njalr_target = (rs1_data + imm) & ~1 and assert a new id_redirect signal.\\nThread a jalr_redirected flag through the id_ex_t bundle so the EX stage\\nsuppresses its own redirect for JALRs that were already handled in ID.\\nAt the top level, OR the new id_redirect with the existing ex_redirect to\\ndrive the PC, and adjust flush_if/flush_id so that a JALR in ID is allowed\\nto advance into EX while the speculative fetch in IF is killed.\\nThis structural change shortens the JALR resolution loop by one full stage\\nwithout touching any other instruction type.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct...\n  Line 13: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"Add 32-entry 2-bit BHT for forward branch direction prediction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped Branch History Table with 2-bit saturating\\ncounters to the IF stage. The table is indexed by PC[6:2] and initialized to\\nstrongly-taken (2'b11) so backward loops are correct immediately without any\\ntraining cost. For every conditional branch, the BHT entry MSB drives\\npredict_taken; unconditional JAL continues to be always predicted taken. In\\nEX stage, each resolved branch writes its actual outcome back to the entry\\nindexed by the branch PC using a standard saturating update rule. This adds\\nonly 64 flops and a few LUTs of combinational logi...\n  Line 14: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Eliminate false load-use stalls via opcode-aware hazard detection\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit conservatively stalls on any LOAD-to-use sequence where the\\nLOAD's rd matches either rs1 or rs2 of the next instruction, regardless of\\nwhether those fields are actually register reads. For I-type instructions\\n(OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR) the rs2 field encodes an immediate or shamt; for U-type\\n(LUI, AUIPC), J-type (JAL), and SYSTEM/FENCE instructions neither field is a\\nregister read. These false stalls waste cycles\\u2014especially on CoreMark's heavy\\nuse of ADDI, LUI, and JAL immediately after pointer loads\\u2014with negligible\\nLUT cost and no impact on Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit conservatively stalls on any LOAD-to-use sequence where the\\nLOAD's rd matches either rs1 or rs2 of the next instruction, regardless of\\nwhether those fields are actually register reads. For I-type instructions\\n(OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR) the rs2 field encodes an immediate or shamt; for U-type\\n(LUI, AUIPC), J-type (JAL), and SYSTEM/FENCE instructions neither field is a\\nregister read. These false stalls waste cycles\\u2014especially on CoreMark's heavy\\nuse of ADDI, LUI, and JAL immediately after pointer loads\\u2014with negligible\\nLUT cost and no impact on Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add opcode decoding to hazard_unit so the load_use_hazard term only fires\\nwhen the instruction in ID genuinely reads rs1 or rs2. R-type, BRANCH, and\\nSTORE read both; I-type reads only rs1; U/J/FENCE/SYSTEM read neither. The\\nstall_if / stall_id / flush_id logic otherwise stays identical, so no other\\npipeline behavior changes. This removes spurious one-cycle bubbles without\\nlengthening any critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a new 7-bit `if_id_opcode` input. Inside the module compute\\n`uses_rs1` and `uses_rs2` fla...\n  Line 16: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"Expand BHT to 128 entries to reduce aliasing among forward branches\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the 32-entry BHT in if_stage with a 128-entry direct-mapped BHT.\\nChange the index from pc[6:2] to pc[8:2] (7 bits) and widen the\\nbht_update_idx port from 5 to 7 bits so EX can write back using in.pc[8:2].\\nThe counter update rule, strong-taken initialization, and interaction with\\nthe static backward-taken / JAL predictor remain exactly the same. No new\\npipeline bundles or control signals are introduced, making this a very low-\\nrisk resize of a component that is already known to work.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Widen bht_update_idx from 5 to 7 bits to match the 128-entry table index.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Enlarge the bht array to [0:127], update the init...\n  Line 17: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Fold WB mux into MEM stage and remove dead EX/MEM fields\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move the write-back data selection into the MEM stage so that the MEM/WB\\nregister stores only the final rd_wdata (already muxed between load_data and\\nalu_result).  The WB stage then becomes a pure passthrough.  This removes one\\n32-bit mux from the MEM/WB->EX forwarding critical path.  At the same time,\\ndelete the unused branch_taken and branch_target fields from ex_mem_t to\\nreduce area and routing congestion.  No pipeline behaviour changes; IPC stays\\nidentical and Fmax should improve slightly.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove branch_taken ...\n  Line 19: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Add 5-bit GHR gshare indexing to existing 32-entry BHT\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the proven 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter table, but index it\\nwith pc[6:2] ^ ghr[4:0] instead of pc[6:2] alone. A 5-bit GHR register\\nshifts in actual branch outcomes from EX-stage resolution, so the BHT\\nentry used for prediction is a function of both the branch address and\\nthe recent global control-flow path. To ensure the EX-stage counter\\nupdate writes the same entry that IF read, the GHR value present at\\nfetch time is snapshotted and threaded through the IF/ID and...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Replace combinational divider with iterative multi-cycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the\\nSystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX\\nstage alone consumes over 6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is\\ndominated by arithmetic primitives. Division is essentially unused in\\nCoreMark, yet the combinational divider consumes massive area and\\nrouting resources that congest the fabric around the critical ALU adder\\npath, limiting Fmax. A prior attempt at this change failed because the\\ndivider state machine lacked a proper IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM with a\\n'started' bit, causing deadlock. With a correct FSM implementation,\\nremoving the combinational divider should relieve routing congestion\\nand raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU infers a full 32-bit combinational divider from the\\nSystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators. Flattened synthesis shows the EX\\nstage alone consumes over 6000 cells (52 % of the entire core) and is\\ndominated by arithmetic primitives. Division is essentially unused in\\nCoreMark, yet the combinational divider consumes massive area and\\nrouting resources that congest the fabric around the critical ALU adder\\npath, limiting Fmax. A prior attempt at this change failed because the\\ndivider state machine lacked a proper IDLE/RUNNING/DONE FSM with a\\n'started' bit, causing deadlock. With a correct FSM implementation,\\nremoving the combinational divider should relieve routing congestion\\nand raise Fmax with negligible IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extract DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of the combinational ALU into a new\\n`divider.sv` module that performs restoring division in 33 cycles.\\nThe divider MUST use a proper 3-state FSM (IDLE, RUNNING, DONE) with\\na registered 'started' bit:\\n  - IDLE:  waiting for start pulse. busy=0, done=0.\\n  - RUNNING: counting dow...\n  Line 23: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Consolidate ALU multipliers to reduce routing congestion and improve Fmax\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU unconditionally computes three separate 64-bit products\\n(mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) on every cycle even though only one multiply\\nop is ever active.  On FPGA this causes the synthesis tool to infer\\nmultiple wide multipliers and large cross-products that consume DSP\\nblocks and routing resources around the EX stage.  CoreMark is\\nmultiply-heavy (matrix operations), so the ALU multiplier path is\\nlikely on or near the critical path.  By sharing a single 64-bit\\nmultiplier and selecting the signedness mode per-op, we cut the\\nmultiplier area by roughly two thirds and relieve routing\\ncongestion, which should raise median Fmax with zero IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU unconditionally computes three separate 64-bit products\\n(mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su) on every cycle even though only one multiply\\nop is ever active.  On FPGA this causes the synthesis tool to infer\\nmultiple wide multipliers and large cross-products that consume DSP\\nblocks and routing resources around the EX stage.  CoreMark is\\nmultiply-heavy (matrix operations), so the ALU multiplier path is\\nlikely on or near the critical path.  By sharing a single 64-bit\\nmultiplier and selecting the signedness mode per-op, we cut the\\nmultiplier area by roughly two thirds and relieve routing\\ncongestion, which should raise median Fmax with zero IPC impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the three always-computed 64-bit products in alu.sv with one\\nshared 64-bit multiplier whose operands are muxed per the active ALU\\nop: unsigned*unsigned for MUL/MULHU, signed*signed for MULH, and\\nsigned*unsigned for MULHSU.  Add a small case block before the\\nmultiplication that selects the correctly-extended a and b inputs.\\nThe DIV/REM family remains combinational (unchanged); only the MUL\\nfamily is touched.  This reduces inferred multi...\n  Line 26: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r9s0\", \"title\": \"Word-load bypass from MEM to EX stage\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Prior MEM-to-EX load bypass failed because the critical path through\\nvariable-shift + sign-extend degraded Fmax enough to cancel IPC gains.\\nWord loads (LW) are the dominant load type in CoreMark pointer chasing\\nand need no byte-alignment or sign-extension. A bypass that forwards\\nraw dmem_rdata straight from MEM to EX for LW-only dependencies keeps\\nthe bypass wire path very short, potentially recovering the IPC gain\\nwithout the Fmax loss that killed the full-width bypass.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior MEM-to-EX load bypass failed because the critical path through\\nvariable-shift + sign-extend degraded Fmax enough to cancel IPC gains.\\nWord loads (LW) are the dominant load type in CoreMark pointer chasing\\nand need no byte-alignment or sign-extension. A bypass that forwards\\nraw dmem_rdata straight from MEM to EX for LW-only dependencies keeps\\nthe bypass wire path very short, potentially recovering the IPC gain\\nwithout the Fmax loss that killed the full-width bypass.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a fast MEM-to-EX forwarding path for word loads only: when a LW is\\nin MEM and the instruction in EX reads its rd, forward io_dmemRData\\ndirectly into the EX operand muxes (encoding 2'd3). Suppress the\\nload-use stall in hazard_unit when the load in EX is a word load\\n(mem_width == 2'd2), so the dependent instruction reaches EX in the\\ncycle the LW is in MEM. Keep the existing 1-cycle stall for byte and\\nhalfword loads. Extend forward_unit to prioritise the new dmem bypass\\nover EX/MEM forwarding when active.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Route io_dmemRData into ex_stage as fwd_dmem_rdata. Compute fwd_dmem_en from ex_mem_w (mem_read && mem_width==word && rd!=0) and feed it to both forward_unit and ex_stage.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"descript...\n  Line 28: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r9s2\", \"title\": \"Fix gshare by speculatively updating GHR in IF with mispredict restore\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already yielded +7.3% fitness, but a follow-up\\ngshare variant regressed -6.7% because its GHR was updated non-speculatively\\nin EX. By the time a branch resolved, the next branch had already been\\nfetched with stale history, increasing destructive aliasing. CoreMark\\ncontains short basic blocks with back-to-back branches where history\\nstaleness is fatal. A speculative IF-stage update with EX-stage restore\\nfixes the staleness while keeping the table small and the read path fast.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already yielded +7.3% fitness, but a follow-up\\ngshare variant regressed -6.7% because its GHR was updated non-speculatively\\nin EX. By the time a branch resolved, the next branch had already been\\nfetched with stale history, increasing destructive aliasing. CoreMark\\ncontains short basic blocks with back-to-back branches where history\\nstaleness is fatal. A speculative IF-stage update with EX-stage restore\\nfixes the staleness while keeping the table small and the read path fast.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 5-bit Global History Register (GHR) to the IF stage and XOR it into\\nthe existing 32-entry BHT index (gshare). The GHR is updated speculatively\\nwhenever a conditional branch is fetched: ghr <= {ghr[3:0], predict_taken}.\\nThe pre-update GHR value is snapshotted into a new 5-bit field in the\\nIF/ID and ID/EX bundles. In EX, when a conditional branch mispredicts\\n(redirect is asserted), the GHR is restored to {snapshot[3:0], actual_taken}\\nvia a new feedback port to IF. On correct prediction no restore is needed.\\nThe BHT write index uses pc[6:2] ^ snapshot so the counter update hits the\\nsame entry that was read during fetch. This gives history-aware prediction\\nwithout enlarging the array and with negligible combinational delay (a\\n5-bit XOR on an existi...\n  Line 30: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r10s1\", \"title\": \"Add 1-entry instruction skid buffer in IF to hide imem stalls and prefetch during downstream stalls\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The cosim fitness model injects ~22% random imem stalls, and every !imem_ready\\ncycle currently asserts a global stall_if/flush_if that freezes the PC and\\nforces a NOP into ID/EX, wasting the fetch slot.  Worse, during load-use or\\ndmem stalls the PC also holds even when imem_ready is high, so a valid\\ninstruction arriving on the bus is discarded.  A tiny 1-entry skid buffer\\ndecouples fetch from issue: it captures prefetches while the downstream\\npipeline is stalled, and replays them when the bus subsequently stalls.\\nThis hides single-cycle (and occasionally multi-cycle) imem bubbles with\\nonly ~66 flops and a few LUTs of mux logic, improving effective fetch\\nthroughput without lengthening any critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The cosim fitness model injects ~22% random imem stalls, and every !imem_ready\\ncycle currently asserts a global stall_if/flush_if that freezes the PC and\\nforces a NOP into ID/EX, wasting the fetch slot.  Worse, during load-use or\\ndmem stalls the PC also holds even when imem_ready is high, so a valid\\ninstruction arriving on the bus is discarded.  A tiny 1-entry skid buffer\\ndecouples fetch from issue: it captures prefetches while the downstream\\npipeline is stalled, and replays them when the bus subsequently stalls.\\nThis hides single-cycle (and occasionally multi-cycle) imem bubbles with\\nonly ~66 flops and a few LUTs of mux logic, improving effective fetch\\nthroughput without lengthening any critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure if_stage to hold a 1-entry buffer (buf_pc, buf_instr,\\nbuf_pred_taken, buf_valid).  The PC advances whenever imem_ready is high\\nAND there is a place to put the fetched instruction (either issued directly\\nor buffered).  The output to ID is: buffer hit when buf_valid and the bus\\nis stalled or we choose to...","metadata":{"matches":16,"truncated":false},"title":"iteration|trip count|exit predict","time":{"start":1778745335836,"end":1778745335854}},"id":"prt_e257bdb47001Ub3hKqbVtHNmwU","sessionID":"ses_1da8c0d24ffeyR5lnSLdShWPv7","messageID":"msg_e257a85fb0019M06JwLFBe6CMc"}}
