{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778750719175,"sessionID":"ses_1da325336fferLJv5DX6QjzZyq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"read:0","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/LESSONS.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/LESSONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r1s1 (improvement, +14.59%): Even a trivial static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken) eliminates the taken-branch bubble and yields double-digit IPC gains on loop-heavy benchmarks like CoreMark, with negligible LUT cost.\n2: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r2s0 (regression, +0.00%): Combinational MEM-to-EX load bypass eliminated load-use stalls functionally but yielded zero net fitness gain because the longer critical path (dmem read → sign-extend → EX operand mux) degraded Fmax enough to cancel the IPC improvement.\n3: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r4s2 (improvement, +7.31%): After a static backward-taken baseline captures the easy loop gains, a minimal 32-entry 2-bit BHT (64 flops) still recovers +7.3% fitness by predicting forward conditional branches; forward-branch direction is the largest remaining dynamic bubble source in CoreMark.\n4: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r5s0 (regression, +0.00%): Opcode-aware elimination of false load-use stalls on I/U/J-type instructions after loads yielded zero CoreMark improvement; the benchmark's pointer-chasing critical path is dominated by genuine R-type and STORE dependencies, making false stalls on non-R-type instructions too rare to impact IPC.\n5: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r5s2 (regression, -3.01%): A 128-entry BHT regressed CoreMark fitness because the 32-entry table already saturates the benchmark's forward-branch locality, and the larger IF-stage read mux degraded Fmax more than reduced aliasing improved IPC.\n6: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r6s1 (broken, n/a): A multi-cycle divider in EX requires a per-instruction state machine, not raw combinational busy/done logic: without a 'started' bit, `div_busy` deadlocks after a pulsed `done` because the instruction never leaves EX, while a level `done` prevents subsequent divides from re-starting.\n7: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r6s2 (regression, -6.77%): Non-speculative GHR update at EX-stage resolution leaves history stale for tightly packed branches, causing the 5-bit XOR to increase destructive aliasing in the 32-entry BHT and regress CoreMark IPC.\n8: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r7s1 (regression, +0.00%): Even with a correct 3-state divider FSM (fixing the prior 'started'-bit deadlock), a 33-cycle iterative unit yielded zero fitness gain because CoreMark never exercises division; the combinational divider's area was not the critical-path bottleneck, and the added stall logic offset any potential Fmax gain.\n9: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r9s2 (regression, +0.00%): Speculative IF-stage GHR update with mispredict restore fixes the history-staleness bug but still yields zero net gain over the bimodal 32-entry BHT; CoreMark's branch working set is small enough that 2-bit saturating counters capture all exploitable locality, leaving global history with no accuracy upside.\n10: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r11s0 (regression, -7.98%): Yosys infers efficient byte-select logic from variable shift-by-8 patterns; explicit nested-case byte-lane muxes are larger and slower than the inferred barrel-shifter equivalent.\n11: \n12: (End of file - total 10 lines)\n\n(End of file - total 12 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r1s1 (improvement, +14.59%): Even a trivial static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken) eliminates the taken-branch bubble and yields double-digit IPC gains on loop-heavy benchmarks like CoreMark, with negligible LUT cost.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r2s0 (regression, +0.00%): Combinational MEM-to-EX load bypass eliminated load-use stalls functionally but yielded zero net fitness gain because the longer critical path (dmem read → sign-extend → EX operand mux) degraded Fmax enough to cancel the IPC improvement.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r4s2 (improvement, +7.31%): After a static backward-taken baseline captures the easy loop gains, a minimal 32-entry 2-bit BHT (64 flops) still recovers +7.3% fitness by predicting forward conditional branches; forward-branch direction is the largest remaining dynamic bubble source in CoreMark.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r5s0 (regression, +0.00%): Opcode-aware elimination of false load-use stalls on I/U/J-type instructions after loads yielded zero CoreMark improvement; the benchmark's pointer-chasing critical path is dominated by genuine R-type and STORE dependencies, making false stalls on non-R-type instructions too rare to impact IPC.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r5s2 (regression, -3.01%): A 128-entry BHT regressed CoreMark fitness because the 32-entry table already saturates the benchmark's forward-branch locality, and the larger IF-stage read mux degraded Fmax more than reduced aliasing improved IPC.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r6s1 (broken, n/a): A multi-cycle divider in EX requires a per-instruction state machine, not raw combinational busy/done logic: without a 'started' bit, `div_busy` deadlocks after a pulsed `done` because the instruction never leaves EX, while a level `done` prevents subsequent divides from re-starting.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r6s2 (regression, -6.77%): Non-speculative GHR update at EX-stage resolution leaves history stale for tightly packed branches, causing the 5-bit XOR to increase destructive aliasing in the 32-entry BHT and regress CoreMark IPC.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r7s1 (regression, +0.00%): Even with a correct 3-state divider FSM (fixing the prior 'started'-bit deadlock), a 33-cycle iterative unit yielded zero fitness gain because CoreMark never exercises division; the combinational divider's area was not the critical-path bottleneck, and the added stall logic offset any potential Fmax gain.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r9s2 (regression, +0.00%): Speculative IF-stage GHR update with mispredict restore fixes the history-staleness bug but still yields zero net gain over the bimodal 32-entry BHT; CoreMark's branch working set is small enough that 2-bit saturating counters capture all exploitable locality, leaving global history with no accuracy upside.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r11s0 (regression, -7.98%): Yosys infers efficient byte-select logic from variable shift-by-8 patterns; explicit nested-case byte-lane muxes are larger and slower than the inferred barrel-shifter equivalent.\n\n(End of file - total 10 lines)","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/LESSONS.md","time":{"start":1778750719160,"end":1778750719174}},"id":"prt_e25ce0076001USblOpunS19rHK","sessionID":"ses_1da325336fferLJv5DX6QjzZyq","messageID":"msg_e25cdad010010nNu0IGxuSxRNc"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778750720081,"sessionID":"ses_1da325336fferLJv5DX6QjzZyq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"grep:1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"\"category\": \"predictor\"","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 13 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Static BTFN branch predictor + JAL prediction in ID stage\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline resolves all control-flow instructions in EX and pays a\\nfixed 2-cycle bubble (flush IF/ID) for every taken branch and every jump. CoreMark is\\nloop-heavy; backward branches are taken the vast majority of the time. A static\\nBackward-Taken / Forward-Not-Taken (BTFN) predictor combined with unconditional JAL\\nprediction, both computed in the ID stage, eliminates the 2-cycle penalty for the\\nmost common control-flow cases at virtually zero area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline resolves all control-flow instructions in EX and pays a\\nfixed 2-cycle bubble (flush IF/ID) for every taken branch and every jump. CoreMark is\\nloop-heavy; backward branches are taken the vast majority of the time. A static\\nBackward-Taken / Forward-Not-Taken (BTFN) predictor combined with unconditional JAL\\nprediction, both computed in the ID stage, eliminates the 2-cycle penalty for the\\nmost common control-flow cases at virtually zero area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a simple static predictor in the ID stage that:\\n1) Predicts JAL (unconditional jump) always taken.\\n2) Predicts conditional branches as taken iff the immediate is negative (backward).\\n3) Redirects the IF PC and flushes the combinational IF/ID output in the same cycle\\n   the branch/jump is in ID.  A `predict_taken` bit is carried through ID/EX so that\\n   EX only asserts `redirect` on a mispredict (predicted-not-taken but taken, or\\n   predicted-taken but not-taken).  JALR is intentionally *not* predicted because its\\n   target depends on `rs1`, which may still be pending from an in-flight ALU result\\n (forwarding only exists in EX, not ID).\\n\\nThis turns the common-case loop-back branch from a 2-cycle penalty into 0 cycles,\\nand unconditional JAL from 2 cycles to 0 cycles, while keeping forward branches and\\nJALR at their ...\n  Line 7: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Add 4-entry Return Address Stack for JALR return prediction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor eliminates bubbles for backward branches and\\nunconditional JAL, but every JALR (function return) still incurs a 1-cycle\\nflush because the target is unknown until EX. CoreMark contains frequent\\nnested function calls, so returns are a noticeable fraction of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream. A tiny Return Address Stack (RAS) pushes the link\\naddress on JAL-to-x1/x5 and pops it on JALR-from-x1/x5, predicting the\\nreturn target in IF with high accuracy at negligible area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor eliminates bubbles for backward branches and\\nunconditional JAL, but every JALR (function return) still incurs a 1-cycle\\nflush because the target is unknown until EX. CoreMark contains frequent\\nnested function calls, so returns are a noticeable fraction of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream. A tiny Return Address Stack (RAS) pushes the link\\naddress on JAL-to-x1/x5 and pops it on JALR-from-x1/x5, predicting the\\nreturn target in IF with high accuracy at negligible area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extend the IF-stage predictor with a 4-entry RAS. When the fetched\\ninstruction is a JAL with rd=x1 or x5, push PC+4 onto the stack. When the\\nfetched instruction is a JALR with rs1=x1 or x5 and the stack is non-empty,\\npop the top entry and treat it as the predicted target (pred_taken=1,\\npred_target=ras_top). Thread the predicted target through the IF/ID and\\nID/EX bundles so that EX can verify it. In EX, a JALR only causes a\\nredirect when it was unpredicted (!pred_taken) or when the actual target\\ndiffers from pred_target. The RAS pointer is updated only on non-stalled,\\nnon-flushed cycles. This removes the bubble on the vast majority of\\nreturns.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description...\n  Line 10: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"Add 32-entry tagged BTB with 2-bit saturating counters for branch target caching and forward-branch learning\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor correctly predicts backward branches and JAL,\\nbut forward branches that are frequently taken are always mispredicted.\\nAdditionally, the combinational branch-target computation in the IF stage\\n(opcode decode \\u2192 immediate extraction \\u2192 sign-extension \\u2192 PC adder) may\\ncontribute to the critical path. A small Branch Target Buffer can learn\\ntaken forward branches, cache targets to shorten the IF-stage path, and\\ncoexist safely with the existing static BTFN predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor correctly predicts backward branches and JAL,\\nbut forward branches that are frequently taken are always mispredicted.\\nAdditionally, the combinational branch-target computation in the IF stage\\n(opcode decode \\u2192 immediate extraction \\u2192 sign-extension \\u2192 PC adder) may\\ncontribute to the critical path. A small Branch Target Buffer can learn\\ntaken forward branches, cache targets to shorten the IF-stage path, and\\ncoexist safely with the existing static BTFN predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped Branch Target Buffer in the IF stage.\\nEach entry stores a valid bit, a 5-bit tag (PC[11:7]), a 30-bit\\nword-aligned target, and a 2-bit saturating counter.  In IF, a BTB\\nhit on a branch or JAL supplies the target directly from a register\\nread, bypassing the combinational immediate+adder path.  Direction\\nprediction remains static-taken for backward branches and JAL, but\\nthe BTB can additionally predict taken for forward branches once\\ntheir counter reaches 2.  In EX, every resolved branch/JAL writes\\nits outcome and target back into the BTB.  JALR is excluded from\\nBTB usage to avoid aliasing noise.  This should improve IPC on\\ntaken forward branches and may raise Fmax by reducing IF-...\n  Line 13: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"Add 32-entry 2-bit BHT for forward branch direction prediction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped Branch History Table with 2-bit saturating\\ncounters to the IF stage. The table is indexed by PC[6:2] and initialized to\\nstrongly-taken (2'b11) so backward loops are correct immediately without any\\ntraining cost. For every conditional branch, the BHT entry MSB drives\\npredict_taken; unconditional JAL continues to be always predicted taken. In\\nEX stage, each resolved branch writes its actual outcome back to the entry\\nindexed by the branch PC using a standard saturating update rule. This adds\\nonly 64 flops and a few LUTs of combinational logi...\n  Line 16: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"Expand BHT to 128 entries to reduce aliasing among forward branches\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the 32-entry BHT in if_stage with a 128-entry direct-mapped BHT.\\nChange the index from pc[6:2] to pc[8:2] (7 bits) and widen the\\nbht_update_idx port from 5 to 7 bits so EX can write back using in.pc[8:2].\\nThe counter update rule, strong-taken initialization, and interaction with\\nthe static backward-taken / JAL predictor remain exactly the same. No new\\npipeline bundles or control signals are introduced, making this a very low-\\nrisk resize of a component that is already known to work.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Widen bht_update_idx from 5 to 7 bits to match the 128-entry table index.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Enlarge the bht array to [0:127], update the init...\n  Line 19: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Add 5-bit GHR gshare indexing to existing 32-entry BHT\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the proven 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter table, but index it\\nwith pc[6:2] ^ ghr[4:0] instead of pc[6:2] alone. A 5-bit GHR register\\nshifts in actual branch outcomes from EX-stage resolution, so the BHT\\nentry used for prediction is a function of both the branch address and\\nthe recent global control-flow path. To ensure the EX-stage counter\\nupdate writes the same entry that IF read, the GHR value present at\\nfetch time is snapshotted and threaded through the IF/ID and...\n  Line 22: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r7s2.yaml\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"schema_error: 'category' is a required property\\n\\nFailed validating 'required' in schema:\\n    {'$schema': 'http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#',\\n     'type': 'object',\\n     'required': ['id',\\n                  'title',\\n                  'category',\\n                  'motivation',\\n                  'hypothesis',\\n                  'expected_impact',\\n                  'changes'],\\n     'properties': {'id': {'type': 'string',\\n                           'pattern': '^hyp-[0-9]{8}-[0-9]{3}(-r[0-9]+s[0-9]+)?$'},\\n                    'title': {'type': 'string', 'minLength': 5},\\n                    'category': {'type': 'string',\\n                                 'enum': ['micro_opt',\\n                                         