eps\\nthe bypass wire path very short, potentially recovering the IPC gain\\nwithout the Fmax loss that killed the full-width bypass.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a fast MEM-to-EX forwarding path for word loads only: when a LW is\\nin MEM and the instruction in EX reads its rd, forward io_dmemRData\\ndirectly into the EX operand muxes (encoding 2'd3). Suppress the\\nload-use stall in hazard_unit when the load in EX is a word load\\n(mem_width == 2'd2), so the dependent instruction reaches EX in the\\ncycle the LW is in MEM. Keep the existing 1-cycle stall for byte and\\nhalfword loads. Extend forward_unit to prioritise the new dmem bypass\\nover EX/MEM forwarding when active.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Route io_dmemRData into ex_stage as fwd_dmem_rdata. Compute fwd_dmem_en from ex_mem_w (mem_read && mem_width==word && rd!=0) and feed it to both forward_unit and ex_stage.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add id_ex_mem_width input. Suppress load_use_hazard when id_ex_mem_width == 2'd2 (word load) so the stall is only inserted for byte/halfword loads.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_dmem_en input. Prioritise dmem bypass (2'd3) over normal EX/MEM forwarding when a word load sits in MEM and its rd matches the EX-stage rs1/rs2.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_dmem_rdata and fwd_dmem_en inputs. Extend the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes to select fwd_dmem_rdata for select code 2'd3.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Route io_dmemRData into ex_stage as fwd_dmem_rdata. Compute fwd_dmem_en from ex_mem_w (mem_read && mem_width==word && rd!=0) and feed it to both forward_unit and ex_stage.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add id_ex_mem_width input. Suppress load_use_hazard when id_ex_mem_width == 2'd2 (word load) so the stall is only inserted for byte/halfword loads.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_dmem_en input. Prioritise dmem bypass (2'd3) over normal EX/MEM forwarding when a word load sits in MEM and its rd matches the EX-stage rs1/rs2.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_dmem_rdata and fwd_dmem_en inputs. Extend the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes to select fwd_dmem_rdata for select code 2'd3.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T07:06:41.666406Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 9, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe touched off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv']\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r9s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/forward_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 9, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The fitness contract injects ~22% random backpressure on the instruction\\nbus.  Today every !imem_ready cycle asserts a global stall_if / flush_if\\nthat freezes the PC and forces a NOP bubble into ID/EX.  A tiny 2-entry\\nskid buffer decouples fetch from issue: when the downstream pipeline is\\nstalled (load-use, dmem) but the bus is ready, the buffer prefetches\\nahead; when the bus subsequently stalls but the buffer is non-empty, the\\ncore continues issuing without bubbles.  This is a pure structural\\ndecoupling that should raise effective fetch throughput with only\\n~130 flops and no new long combinational paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure if_stage to hold a 2-entry ring buffer (valid, pc,\\ninstr, pred_taken per entry, plus a head pointer and 2-bit count).\\nThe fetch side advances the PC and enqueues the fetched instruction\\nwhenever imem_ready is high, count<2, and there is no redirect.  The\\nissue side selects the buffered head when count>0, otherwise the live\\nimem_data.  A true NOP is emitted only when the buffer is empty and\\nimem_ready is low.  In hazard_unit, remove imem_ready from stall_if\\nand flush_if so the pipeline no longer stalls globally for bus\\nbackpressure; stall_if is asserted only for load-use and dmem stalls,\\nand flush_if only for redirect.  In core.sv, wire io_imemReady into the\\nnew if_stage port and keep all top-level IO unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 2-entry ring buffer inside if_stage (buf_valid[1:0],\\nbuf_pc[1:0], buf_instr[1:0], buf_pred_taken[1:0], head pointer,\\ncount 0..2).  Add new input `imem_ready`.  Fetch PC advances and\\nenqueues into tail when imem_ready && count<2 && !redirect.\\nIssue selects buffered head if count>0, else live imem_data if\\nimem_ready, else NOP.  Count increments on fetch, decrements on\\nissue.  On redirect clear count/head and reset PC to redirect_target.\\nKeep existing BHT and static predictor logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove imem_ready from stall_if and flush_if.  Keep the imem_ready\\nport connected but unused (or remove it entirely).  Assert stall_if\\nonly for load-use hazards and dmem stalls; assert flush_if only for\\nredirect.  All other stall/flush logic (stall_id, flush_id,\\nstall_ex_mem, hold_mem_wb) remains exactly the same.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire io_imemReady to the new `imem_ready` port of if_stage.  No\\nother top-level IO changes; all RVFI and imem/dmem port names and\\nwidths stay identical.\\n\"}]}}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r9s2\", \"title\": \"Fix gshare by speculatively updating GHR in IF with mispredict restore\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already yielded +7.3% fitness, but a follow-up\\ngshare variant regressed -6.7% because its GHR was updated non-speculatively\\nin EX. By the time a branch resolved, the next branch had already been\\nfetched with stale history, increasing destructive aliasing. CoreMark\\ncontains short basic blocks with back-to-back branches where history\\nstaleness is fatal. A speculative IF-stage update with EX-stage restore\\nfixes the staleness while keeping the table small and the read path fast.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already yielded +7.3% fitness, but a follow-up\\ngshare variant regressed -6.7% because its GHR was updated non-speculatively\\nin EX. By the time a branch resolved, the next branch had already been\\nfetched with stale history, increasing destructive aliasing. CoreMark\\ncontains short basic blocks with back-to-back branches where history\\nstaleness is fatal. A speculative IF-stage update with EX-stage restore\\nfixes the staleness while keeping the table small and the read path fast.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 5-bit Global History Register (GHR) to the IF stage and XOR it into\\nthe existing 32-entry BHT index (gshare). The GHR is updated speculatively\\nwhenever a conditional branch is fetched: ghr <= {ghr[3:0], predict_taken}.\\nThe pre-update GHR value is snapshotted into a new 5-bit field in the\\nIF/ID and ID/EX bundles. In EX, when a conditional branch mispredicts\\n(redirect is asserted), the GHR is restored to {snapshot[3:0], actual_taken}\\nvia a new feedback port to IF. On correct prediction no restore is needed.\\nThe BHT write index uses pc[6:2] ^ snapshot so the counter update hits the\\nsame entry that was read during fetch. This gives history-aware prediction\\nwithout enlarging the array and with negligible combinational delay (a\\n5-bit XOR on an existing mux path).\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr_snapshot field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles\\nso the GHR value present at fetch time reaches EX for update-index\\ncalculation and mispredict restore.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0. Replace the BHT read index\\npc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr. Drive the current ghr value into\\nout.ghr_snapshot. On non-stalled, non-flushed, non-redirected cycles\\nwhere the fetched instruction is a conditional branch, speculatively\\nupdate ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_pred}. Add new input ports\\nghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en; when restore_en is asserted\\n(from EX on a conditional-branch mispredict), reload ghr with\\nghr_restore, taking precedence over the speculative update.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr_snapshot into the ID/EX register so the snapshot\\nreaches the EX stage for BHT update-index computation and GHR restore.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr_snapshot so the\\nsaturating-counter update writes the exact entry that was read during\\nfetch. Add output ports ghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en. Drive\\nghr_restore = {in.ghr_snapshot[3:0], branch_taken} and assert\\nghr_restore_en whenever redirect is asserted for a conditional branch\\n(in.ctrl.is_branch). JAL/JALR redirects must not assert ghr_restore_en.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires ghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en and route\\nthem from ex_stage outputs back to if_stage inputs. No top-level IO\\nor RVFI changes are required.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr_snapshot field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles\\nso the GHR value present at fetch time reaches EX for update-index\\ncalculation and mispredict restore.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0. Replace the BHT read index\\npc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr. Drive the current ghr value into\\nout.ghr_snapshot. On non-stalled, non-flushed, non-redirected cycles\\nwhere the fetched instruction is a conditional branch, speculatively\\nupdate ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_pred}. Add new input ports\\nghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en; when restore_en is asserted\\n(from EX on a conditional-branch mispredict), reload ghr with\\nghr_restore, taking precedence over the speculative update.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr_snapshot into the ID/EX register so the snapshot\\nreaches the EX stage for BHT update-index computation and GHR restore.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr_snapshot so the\\nsaturating-counter update writes the exact entry that was read during\\nfetch. Add output ports ghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en. Drive\\nghr_restore = {in.ghr_snapshot[3:0], branch_taken} and assert\\nghr_restore_en whenever redirect is asserted for a conditional branch\\n(in.ctrl.is_branch). JAL/JALR redirects must not assert ghr_restore_en.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires ghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en and route\\nthem from ex_stage outputs back to if_stage inputs. No top-level IO\\nor RVFI changes are required.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T06:55:45.098358Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 9, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r9s2 (regression, +0.00%): Speculative IF-stage GHR update with mispredict restore fixes the history-staleness bug but still yields zero net gain over the bimodal 32-entry BHT; CoreMark's branch working set is small enough that 2-bit saturating counters capture all exploitable locality, leaving global history with no accuracy upside.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r10s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r10s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r10s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r10s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r10s2'])\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 10}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r10s1\", \"title\": \"Add 1-entry instruction skid buffer in IF to hide imem stalls and prefetch during downstream stalls\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The cosim fitness model injects ~22% random imem stalls, and every !imem_ready\\ncycle currently asserts a global stall_if/flush_if that freezes the PC and\\nforces a NOP into ID/EX, wasting the fetch slot.  Worse, during load-use or\\ndmem stalls the PC also holds even when imem_ready is high, so a valid\\ninstruction arriving on the bus is discarded.  A tiny 1-entry skid buffer\\ndecouples fetch from issue: it captures prefetches while the downstream\\npipeline is stalled, and replays them when the bus subsequently stalls.\\nThis hides single-cycle (and occasionally multi-cycle) imem bubbles with\\nonly ~66 flops and a few LUTs of mux logic, improving effective fetch\\nthroughput without lengthening any critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The cosim fitness model injects ~22% random imem stalls, and every !imem_ready\\ncycle currently asserts a global stall_if/flush_if that freezes the PC and\\nforces a NOP into ID/EX, wasting the fetch slot.  Worse, during load-use or\\ndmem stalls the PC also holds even when imem_ready is high, so a valid\\ninstruction arriving on the bus is discarded.  A tiny 1-entry skid buffer\\ndecouples fetch from issue: it captures prefetches while the downstream\\npipeline is stalled, and replays them when the bus subsequently stalls.\\nThis hides single-cycle (and occasionally multi-cycle) imem bubbles with\\nonly ~66 flops and a few LUTs of mux logic, improving effective fetch\\nthroughput without lengthening any critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure if_stage to hold a 1-entry buffer (buf_pc, buf_instr,\\nbuf_pred_taken, buf_valid).  The PC advances whenever imem_ready is high\\nAND there is a place to put the fetched instruction (either issued directly\\nor buffered).  The output to ID is: buffer hit when buf_valid and the bus\\nis stalled or we choose to consume; otherwise live imem_data; otherwise NOP.\\nIn hazard_unit, remove imem_ready from stall_if and flush_if so that\\nload-use and dmem stalls no longer freeze the fetch side.  In core.sv,\\nwire io_imemReady into the new if_stage port and keep all other top-level\\nIO unchanged.  The buffer adds no new combinational long paths; the extra\\nmux sits in the already-combinational IF/ID boundary and should not degrade\\nthe EX/MEM\\u2192dmem\\u2192MEM/WB critical path that currently limits Fmax.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 1-entry skid-buffer registers (buf_pc[31:0], buf_instr[31:0],\\nbuf_pred_taken, buf_valid) and rewrite the issue / prefetch FSM.\\nPC advances when imem_ready && (!stall || !buf_valid).  Output mux\\nselects buffered instruction, live imem_data, or NOP.  Buffer fills\\non downstream stall with imem_ready and buf_valid==0, or refills\\natomically when consuming the buffer on a non-stall cycle with\\nimem_ready.  Clear buf_valid on reset or redirect.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove imem_ready input and stop using imem_stall.  stall_if is now\\nasserted only for load_use_hazard || dmem_stall.  flush_if is now\\nasserted only for redirect (no longer on imem stall).  This lets the\\nIF stage continue prefetching into its skid buffer while the rest of\\nthe pipeline is stalled for data hazards or memory backpressure.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire io_imemReady into the new if_stage.imem_ready port.  Wire\\nflush_if into if_stage.flush (it now equals redirect).  Keep all other\\nport connections and RVFI logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"No bundle changes required; the skid buffer is entirely internal to\\nif_stage.  Verify the ifndef guard is intact.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 1-entry skid-buffer registers (buf_pc[31:0], buf_instr[31:0],\\nbuf_pred_taken, buf_valid) and rewrite the issue / prefetch FSM.\\nPC advances when imem_ready && (!stall || !buf_valid).  Output mux\\nselects buffered instruction, live imem_data, or NOP.  Buffer fills\\non downstream stall with imem_ready and buf_valid==0, or refills\\natomically when consuming the buffer on a non-stall cycle with\\nimem_ready.  Clear buf_valid on reset or redirect.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove imem_ready input and stop using imem_stall.  stall_if is now\\nasserted only for load_use_hazard || dmem_stall.  flush_if is now\\nasserted only for redirect (no longer on imem stall).  This lets the\\nIF stage continue prefetching into its skid buffer while the rest of\\nthe pipeline is stalled for data hazards or memory backpressure.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire io_imemReady into the new if_stage.imem_ready port.  Wire\\nflush_if into if_stage.flush (it now equals redirect).  Keep all other\\nport connections and RVFI logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"No bundle changes required; the skid buffer is entirely internal to\\nif_stage.  Verify the ifndef guard is intact.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 283.99, \"delta_pct\": -18.34, \"vs_baseline\": 0.41, \"fmax_mhz\": 114.39, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4028010, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10347, \"ff\": 2011, \"seeds\": [118.39, 114.39, 108.83], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T07:41:58.772598Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 10, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r10s2\", \"title\": \"(slot 2 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-003-r10s2 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r10s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r10s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r10s2'])\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 10}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r11s0\", \"title\": \"Replace mem_stage barrel shifter with explicit byte-lane selects\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The failed MEM-to-EX load bypass hypothesis identified the variable\\nbarrel shifter (dmem_rdata >> (addr*8)) as part of the critical path\\nthat degraded Fmax enough to cancel IPC gains.  The current mem_stage\\ncomputes this 32-bit shift for every memory operation, even though\\nCoreMark is dominated by word loads (LW) which need no shifting.\\nYosys often infers a full barrel-shifter network for the variable\\nshift pattern, adding unnecessary LUT depth on the dmem read path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The failed MEM-to-EX load bypass hypothesis identified the variable\\nbarrel shifter (dmem_rdata >> (addr*8)) as part of the critical path\\nthat degraded Fmax enough to cancel IPC gains.  The current mem_stage\\ncomputes this 32-bit shift for every memory operation, even though\\nCoreMark is dominated by word loads (LW) which need no shifting.\\nYosys often infers a full barrel-shifter network for the variable\\nshift pattern, adding unnecessary LUT depth on the dmem read path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure mem_stage load-data extraction to eliminate the variable\\nbarrel shifter.  Word loads bypass all formatting (load_data = dmem_rdata).\\nByte loads use an explicit 4:1 byte-select mux on dmem_rdata driven by\\naddr[1:0].  Halfword loads use an explicit 2:1 halfword select.\\nGuard the shift/sign-extend logic behind in.ctrl.mem_read so it is\\ncompletely elided for stores.  This shortens the dmem_rdata-to-MEM/WB\\npath for the dominant LW case and reduces overall LUT depth for\\nbyte/halfword accesses, improving median Fmax with zero IPC impact.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the unconditional 'shifted = dmem_rdata >> (alu_result[1:0]*8)'\\npattern with explicit case-based byte and halfword lane extraction.\\nWord loads bypass all formatting.  Gate the load formatting logic\\nbehind in.ctrl.mem_read so it is dead-code eliminated for stores.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the unconditional 'shifted = dmem_rdata >> (alu_result[1:0]*8)'\\npattern with explicit case-based byte and halfword lane extraction.\\nWord loads bypass all formatting.  Gate the load formatting logic\\nbehind in.ctrl.mem_read so it is dead-code eliminated for stores.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 320.02, \"delta_pct\": -7.98, \"vs_baseline\": 13.15, \"fmax_mhz\": 134.52, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10250, \"ff\": 1942, \"seeds\": [127.1, 134.52, 135.76], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T08:19:05.454681Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 11, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r11s0 (regression, -7.98%): Yosys infers efficient byte-select logic from variable shift-by-8 patterns; explicit nested-case byte-lane muxes are larger and slower than the inferred barrel-shifter equivalent.\\n\\n(End of file - total 10 lines)\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Add 1-entry non-blocking store buffer to hide dmem backpressure on stores\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit currently stalls the entire pipeline on every !dmem_ready cycle\\nwhenever any memory operation is in MEM. Stores are roughly 20-25% of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream and the cosim model injects ~22% random dmem stalls, so about\\n5% of total cycles are wasted waiting for the store bus. Because stores do not\\nproduce register results, the instructions behind them are almost always\\nindependent and could continue executing if the store were decoupled. A 1-entry\\nstore buffer captures a stalled store and lets the pipeline advance while the\\nbuffer drains asynchronously, converting store-bus stalls into useful execution\\ncycles with minimal area and no new long combinational paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit currently stalls the entire pipeline on every !dmem_ready cycle\\nwhenever any memory operation is in MEM. Stores are roughly 20-25% of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream and the cosim model injects ~22% random dmem stalls, so about\\n5% of total cycles are wasted waiting for the store bus. Because stores do not\\nproduce register results, the instructions behind them are almost always\\nindependent and could continue executing if the store were decoupled. A 1-entry\\nstore buffer captures a stalled store and lets the pipeline advance while the\\nbuffer drains asynchronously, converting store-bus stalls into useful execution\\ncycles with minimal area and no new long combinational paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a 1-entry store buffer between the MEM stage and the external dmem interface.\\nWhen a store reaches MEM and dmem_ready is low, the buffer captures the address,\\ndata, and byte mask instead of asserting a global stall. The buffer continuously\\nretries the write whenever dmem_ready is high. The top-level dmem outputs are\\nmuxed between the buffer (when valid) and the live MEM stage. The hazard_unit\\nis extended so that:\\n  - Loads still stall on !dmem_ready; stores use the buffer instead of stalling.\\n  - Any memory operation (load or store) stalls while the buffer is valid, because\\n    the single port is busy with the buffered write.\\n  - Non-memory instructions pass through MEM unimpeded even while the buffer drains.\\nThis structural decoupling should recover the cycles currently lost to store stalls.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/store_buffer.sv\", \"description\": \"New 1-entry buffer module holding addr, wdata, wmask, and valid. Captures on\\nen when a store is in MEM and dmem_ready is low. Drains on dmem_ready when\\nvalid. Clears valid when drained.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate store_buffer between mem_stage and the dmem pins. Route\\nex_mem_w write fields to the buffer inputs. Mux io_dmemAddr, io_dmemWData,\\nio_dmemWEn, and io_dmemREn between buffer outputs and mem_stage outputs.\\nWire store_buffer_valid into hazard_unit. Pass ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read as\\na new ex_mem_mem_read port to hazard_unit.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add store_buffer_valid and ex_mem_mem_read inputs. Replace the monolithic\\ndmem_stall = !dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_op with two terms:\\n  (!dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_read)  // loads still wait for the bus\\n  || (store_buffer_valid && ex_mem_mem_op) // any mem op waits while buffer busy.\\nKeep all other stall/flush logic unchanged.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/store_buffer.sv\", \"description\": \"New 1-entry buffer module holding addr, wdata, wmask, and valid. Captures on\\nen when a store is in MEM and dmem_ready is low. Drains on dmem_ready when\\nvalid. Clears valid when drained.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate store_buffer between mem_stage and the dmem pins. Route\\nex_mem_w write fields to the buffer inputs. Mux io_dmemAddr, io_dmemWData,\\nio_dmemWEn, and io_dmemREn between buffer outputs and mem_stage outputs.\\nWire store_buffer_valid into hazard_unit. Pass ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read as\\na new ex_mem_mem_read port to hazard_unit.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add store_buffer_valid and ex_mem_mem_read inputs. Replace the monolithic\\ndmem_stall = !dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_op with two terms:\\n  (!dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_read)  // loads still wait for the bus\\n  || (store_buffer_valid && ex_mem_mem_op) // any mem op waits while buffer busy.\\nKeep all other stall/flush logic unchanged.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 328.83, \"delta_pct\": -5.44, \"vs_baseline\": 16.27, \"fmax_mhz\": 137.16, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4171199, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10826, \"ff\": 1951, \"seeds\": [131.73, 138.1, 137.16], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T08:15:37.115966Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 11, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"Add 8-entry loop predictor for backward branch exits\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit BHT already captures forward branch directions and\\nbackward-taken bias, but it cannot avoid mispredicting the final iteration\\nof every loop (predicted taken, actually not-taken). CoreMark contains\\nmany small inner loops (list traversal, matrix rows, CRC updates) where\\nthis exit misprediction wastes cycles. A dedicated loop predictor learns\\nthe trip count of individual backward branches and predicts not-taken on\\nthe last iteration, removing the only remaining systematic direction\\nmispredictions with only ~100 flops and no wider BHT mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit BHT already captures forward branch directions and\\nbackward-taken bias, but it cannot avoid mispredicting the final iteration\\nof every loop (predicted taken, actually not-taken). CoreMark contains\\nmany small inner loops (list traversal, matrix rows, CRC updates) where\\nthis exit misprediction wastes cycles. A dedicated loop predictor learns\\nthe trip count of individual backward branches and predicts not-taken on\\nthe last iteration, removing the only remaining systematic direction\\nmispredictions with only ~100 flops and no wider BHT mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an 8-entry direct-mapped loop predictor table to the IF stage.\\nEach entry stores a tag, a trained iteration length, a speculative\\ndown-counter, and a 1-bit confidence flag.\\nWhen a backward branch is fetched, if the entry is valid, tag matches,\\nand confidence is high, the predictor overrides the BHT:\\n  - down-counter > 0  \\u2192 predict taken and decrement the counter.\\n  - down-counter == 0 \\u2192 predict not-taken.\\nIn EX, resolved backward branches update the table:\\n  - During training (confidence low) the table counts taken outcomes;\\n    the first not-taken exit stores the count as the trained length\\n    and sets confidence high.\\n  - On a correct exit (predicted not-taken) the counter is reloaded\\n    from the trained length for the next loop invocation.\\n  - On a length mismatch (mispredict) confidence is cleared so the\\n    entry re-trains on the next invocation.\\nThis attacks the last predictable bubble source without touching the\\nexisting BHT or pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 8-entry loop-predictor array (tag, length, count, conf), combinational read/decrement, and integrate with predict_taken so a matching confident entry overrides the BHT for backward branches.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop-predictor update logic: on resolved backward branches allocate/train entries, reload counters on correct exits, and clear confidence on mispredicts. Drive update signals back to IF.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop_predictor_entry_t struct and confidence constants to the package.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new loop-predictor update signals between ex_stage and if_stage.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 8-entry loop-predictor array (tag, length, count, conf), combinational read/decrement, and integrate with predict_taken so a matching confident entry overrides the BHT for backward branches.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop-predictor update logic: on resolved backward branches allocate/train entries, reload counters on correct exits, and clear confidence on mispredicts. Drive update signals back to IF.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop_predictor_entry_t struct and confidence constants to the package.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new loop-predictor update signals between ex_stage and if_stage.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 302.03, \"delta_pct\": -13.15, \"vs_baseline\": 6.79, \"fmax_mhz\": 126.68, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4194286, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10454, \"ff\": 1951, \"seeds\": [114.19, 126.68, 139.82], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T08:24:35.661190Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 11, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe rewrote /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/LESSONS.md instead of appending; reverted to prior content\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r12s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core_pkg.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/id_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/if_stage.sv']\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 12}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r12s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-002-r12s1 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r12s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r12s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r12s2'])\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 12}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r12s2\", \"title\": \"Add 4-entry return-address stack for JALR prediction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current predictor correctly handles conditional branches (32-entry BHT)\\nand JAL (always-taken), but JALR is never predicted. Every function return\\ncauses a 2-cycle redirect bubble in EX. CoreMark contains many small function\\ncalls; a return-address stack predicts return targets with near-perfect\\naccuracy for a tiny area cost (~130 flops), improving IPC without degrading\\nFmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current predictor correctly handles conditional branches (32-entry BHT)\\nand JAL (always-taken), but JALR is never predicted. Every function return\\ncauses a 2-cycle redirect bubble in EX. CoreMark contains many small function\\ncalls; a return-address stack predicts return targets with near-perfect\\naccuracy for a tiny area cost (~130 flops), improving IPC without degrading\\nFmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 4-entry return-address stack (RAS) to the IF stage. Push PC+4 on\\nany JAL or JALR call (rd = x1/x5). Pop the RAS and predict taken on any\\nJALR return (rd = x0, rs1 = x1/x5). Thread the predicted target through a\\nnew `pred_target` field in the IF/ID and ID/EX bundles. In EX stage,\\ncompare the actual JALR target with `pred_target`; only redirect on\\nmispredict or when JALR was not predicted. This eliminates the redirect\\nbubble on correct function returns.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `pred_target` field to `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t` structs.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 4-entry RAS with push/pop control; use RAS top as predicted target for JALR returns; drive `out.pred_target`.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Thread `in.pred_target` into the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace unconditional JALR redirect with mispredict detection using `in.pred_target`; only redirect when JALR was not predicted or target mismatches.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `pred_target` field to `if_id_t` and `id_ex_t` structs.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 4-entry RAS with push/pop control; use RAS top as predicted target for JALR returns; drive `out.pred_target`.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Thread `in.pred_target` into the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace unconditional JALR redirect with mispredict detection using `in.pred_target`; only redirect when JALR was not predicted or target mismatches.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T08:56:28.477087Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 12}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r13s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r13s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r13s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r13s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r13s2'])\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 13}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r13s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-002-r13s1 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r13s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r13s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r13s2'])\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 13}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r13s2\", \"title\": \"Hash-mix higher PC bits into 32-entry BHT index to reduce aliasing\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter BHT is the proven sweet spot for\\nthis core, delivering a +7.3% fitness gain. A follow-up attempt to grow\\nthe table to 128 entries regressed -3% because the wider read mux hurt\\nFmax, while gshare global-history variants regressed due to history\\nstaleness. The remaining occasional forward-branch mispredictions may\\nstem from destructive aliasing among branches that share the low five\\nPC bits. A zero-cost hash that XORs higher PC bits into the index\\nscatters colliding branches without enlarging the array or adding any\\nnew state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter BHT is the proven sweet spot for\\nthis core, delivering a +7.3% fitness gain. A follow-up attempt to grow\\nthe table to 128 entries regressed -3% because the wider read mux hurt\\nFmax, while gshare global-history variants regressed due to history\\nstaleness. The remaining occasional forward-branch mispredictions may\\nstem from destructive aliasing among branches that share the low five\\nPC bits. A zero-cost hash that XORs higher PC bits into the index\\nscatters colliding branches without enlarging the array or adding any\\nnew state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the proven 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter table unchanged, but\\nchange both the read index and the write-back index from pc[6:2] to\\npc[6:2] ^ pc[11:7]. In the IF stage this mixes bits 7-11 of the PC\\ninto the existing 5-bit index, reducing the chance that two branches\\nwhose lower five bits collide map to the same counter. In the EX stage\\nthe update index uses in.pc[6:2] ^ in.pc[11:7] so the counter write\\nhits exactly the entry that was read during fetch. The combinational\\ncost is a single 5-bit XOR, which Yosys will absorb into the existing\\nLUT fabric with negligible Fmax impact. No new flops, pipeline bundles,\\nor control signals are introduced.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change BHT read index from pc[6:2] to pc[6:2] ^ pc[11:7].\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change BHT update index from in.pc[6:2] to in.pc[6:2] ^ in.pc[11:7].\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change BHT read index from pc[6:2] to pc[6:2] ^ pc[11:7].\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change BHT update index from in.pc[6:2] to in.pc[6:2] ^ in.pc[11:7].\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 235.82, \"delta_pct\": -32.19, \"vs_baseline\": -16.62, \"fmax_mhz\": 99.0, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4198050, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10363, \"ff\": 1934, \"seeds\": [99.0, 105.12, 96.15], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T09:19:06.627254Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 13, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n","metadata":{"output":"...\n\nestore = {in.ghr_snapshot[3:0], branch_taken} and assert\\nghr_restore_en whenever redirect is asserted for a conditional branch\\n(in.ctrl.is_branch). JAL/JALR redirects must not assert ghr_restore_en.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires ghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en and route\\nthem from ex_stage outputs back to if_stage inputs. No top-level IO\\nor RVFI changes are required.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr_snapshot field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles\\nso the GHR value present at fetch time reaches EX for update-index\\ncalculation and mispredict restore.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0. Replace the BHT read index\\npc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr. Drive the current ghr value into\\nout.ghr_snapshot. On non-stalled, non-flushed, non-redirected cycles\\nwhere the fetched instruction is a conditional branch, speculatively\\nupdate ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_pred}. Add new input ports\\nghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en; when restore_en is asserted\\n(from EX on a conditional-branch mispredict), reload ghr with\\nghr_restore, taking precedence over the speculative update.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr_snapshot into the ID/EX register so the snapshot\\nreaches the EX stage for BHT update-index computation and GHR restore.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr_snapshot so the\\nsaturating-counter update writes the exact entry that was read during\\nfetch. Add output ports ghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en. Drive\\nghr_restore = {in.ghr_snapshot[3:0], branch_taken} and assert\\nghr_restore_en whenever redirect is asserted for a conditional branch\\n(in.ctrl.is_branch). JAL/JALR redirects must not assert ghr_restore_en.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires ghr_restore[4:0] and ghr_restore_en and route\\nthem from ex_stage outputs back to if_stage inputs. No top-level IO\\nor RVFI changes are required.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T06:55:45.098358Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 9, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r9s2 (regression, +0.00%): Speculative IF-stage GHR update with mispredict restore fixes the history-staleness bug but still yields zero net gain over the bimodal 32-entry BHT; CoreMark's branch working set is small enough that 2-bit saturating counters capture all exploitable locality, leaving global history with no accuracy upside.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r10s0\", \"title\": \"(slot 0 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-001-r10s0 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r10s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r10s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r10s2'])\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 10}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r10s1\", \"title\": \"Add 1-entry instruction skid buffer in IF to hide imem stalls and prefetch during downstream stalls\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The cosim fitness model injects ~22% random imem stalls, and every !imem_ready\\ncycle currently asserts a global stall_if/flush_if that freezes the PC and\\nforces a NOP into ID/EX, wasting the fetch slot.  Worse, during load-use or\\ndmem stalls the PC also holds even when imem_ready is high, so a valid\\ninstruction arriving on the bus is discarded.  A tiny 1-entry skid buffer\\ndecouples fetch from issue: it captures prefetches while the downstream\\npipeline is stalled, and replays them when the bus subsequently stalls.\\nThis hides single-cycle (and occasionally multi-cycle) imem bubbles with\\nonly ~66 flops and a few LUTs of mux logic, improving effective fetch\\nthroughput without lengthening any critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The cosim fitness model injects ~22% random imem stalls, and every !imem_ready\\ncycle currently asserts a global stall_if/flush_if that freezes the PC and\\nforces a NOP into ID/EX, wasting the fetch slot.  Worse, during load-use or\\ndmem stalls the PC also holds even when imem_ready is high, so a valid\\ninstruction arriving on the bus is discarded.  A tiny 1-entry skid buffer\\ndecouples fetch from issue: it captures prefetches while the downstream\\npipeline is stalled, and replays them when the bus subsequently stalls.\\nThis hides single-cycle (and occasionally multi-cycle) imem bubbles with\\nonly ~66 flops and a few LUTs of mux logic, improving effective fetch\\nthroughput without lengthening any critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure if_stage to hold a 1-entry buffer (buf_pc, buf_instr,\\nbuf_pred_taken, buf_valid).  The PC advances whenever imem_ready is high\\nAND there is a place to put the fetched instruction (either issued directly\\nor buffered).  The output to ID is: buffer hit when buf_valid and the bus\\nis stalled or we choose to consume; otherwise live imem_data; otherwise NOP.\\nIn hazard_unit, remove imem_ready from stall_if and flush_if so that\\nload-use and dmem stalls no longer freeze the fetch side.  In core.sv,\\nwire io_imemReady into the new if_stage port and keep all other top-level\\nIO unchanged.  The buffer adds no new combinational long paths; the extra\\nmux sits in the already-combinational IF/ID boundary and should not degrade\\nthe EX/MEM\\u2192dmem\\u2192MEM/WB critical path that currently limits Fmax.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 1-entry skid-buffer registers (buf_pc[31:0], buf_instr[31:0],\\nbuf_pred_taken, buf_valid) and rewrite the issue / prefetch FSM.\\nPC advances when imem_ready && (!stall || !buf_valid).  Output mux\\nselects buffered instruction, live imem_data, or NOP.  Buffer fills\\non downstream stall with imem_ready and buf_valid==0, or refills\\natomically when consuming the buffer on a non-stall cycle with\\nimem_ready.  Clear buf_valid on reset or redirect.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove imem_ready input and stop using imem_stall.  stall_if is now\\nasserted only for load_use_hazard || dmem_stall.  flush_if is now\\nasserted only for redirect (no longer on imem stall).  This lets the\\nIF stage continue prefetching into its skid buffer while the rest of\\nthe pipeline is stalled for data hazards or memory backpressure.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire io_imemReady into the new if_stage.imem_ready port.  Wire\\nflush_if into if_stage.flush (it now equals redirect).  Keep all other\\nport connections and RVFI logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"No bundle changes required; the skid buffer is entirely internal to\\nif_stage.  Verify the ifndef guard is intact.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 1-entry skid-buffer registers (buf_pc[31:0], buf_instr[31:0],\\nbuf_pred_taken, buf_valid) and rewrite the issue / prefetch FSM.\\nPC advances when imem_ready && (!stall || !buf_valid).  Output mux\\nselects buffered instruction, live imem_data, or NOP.  Buffer fills\\non downstream stall with imem_ready and buf_valid==0, or refills\\natomically when consuming the buffer on a non-stall cycle with\\nimem_ready.  Clear buf_valid on reset or redirect.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove imem_ready input and stop using imem_stall.  stall_if is now\\nasserted only for load_use_hazard || dmem_stall.  flush_if is now\\nasserted only for redirect (no longer on imem stall).  This lets the\\nIF stage continue prefetching into its skid buffer while the rest of\\nthe pipeline is stalled for data hazards or memory backpressure.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire io_imemReady into the new if_stage.imem_ready port.  Wire\\nflush_if into if_stage.flush (it now equals redirect).  Keep all other\\nport connections and RVFI logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"No bundle changes required; the skid buffer is entirely internal to\\nif_stage.  Verify the ifndef guard is intact.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 283.99, \"delta_pct\": -18.34, \"vs_baseline\": 0.41, \"fmax_mhz\": 114.39, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4028010, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10347, \"ff\": 2011, \"seeds\": [118.39, 114.39, 108.83], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T07:41:58.772598Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 10, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r10s2\", \"title\": \"(slot 2 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent did not write a file for slot hyp-20260514-003-r10s2 (allowed_yaml_ids=['hyp-20260514-001-r10s0', 'hyp-20260514-002-r10s1', 'hyp-20260514-003-r10s2'])\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 10}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r11s0\", \"title\": \"Replace mem_stage barrel shifter with explicit byte-lane selects\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The failed MEM-to-EX load bypass hypothesis identified the variable\\nbarrel shifter (dmem_rdata >> (addr*8)) as part of the critical path\\nthat degraded Fmax enough to cancel IPC gains.  The current mem_stage\\ncomputes this 32-bit shift for every memory operation, even though\\nCoreMark is dominated by word loads (LW) which need no shifting.\\nYosys often infers a full barrel-shifter network for the variable\\nshift pattern, adding unnecessary LUT depth on the dmem read path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The failed MEM-to-EX load bypass hypothesis identified the variable\\nbarrel shifter (dmem_rdata >> (addr*8)) as part of the critical path\\nthat degraded Fmax enough to cancel IPC gains.  The current mem_stage\\ncomputes this 32-bit shift for every memory operation, even though\\nCoreMark is dominated by word loads (LW) which need no shifting.\\nYosys often infers a full barrel-shifter network for the variable\\nshift pattern, adding unnecessary LUT depth on the dmem read path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure mem_stage load-data extraction to eliminate the variable\\nbarrel shifter.  Word loads bypass all formatting (load_data = dmem_rdata).\\nByte loads use an explicit 4:1 byte-select mux on dmem_rdata driven by\\naddr[1:0].  Halfword loads use an explicit 2:1 halfword select.\\nGuard the shift/sign-extend logic behind in.ctrl.mem_read so it is\\ncompletely elided for stores.  This shortens the dmem_rdata-to-MEM/WB\\npath for the dominant LW case and reduces overall LUT depth for\\nbyte/halfword accesses, improving median Fmax with zero IPC impact.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the unconditional 'shifted = dmem_rdata >> (alu_result[1:0]*8)'\\npattern with explicit case-based byte and halfword lane extraction.\\nWord loads bypass all formatting.  Gate the load formatting logic\\nbehind in.ctrl.mem_read so it is dead-code eliminated for stores.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the unconditional 'shifted = dmem_rdata >> (alu_result[1:0]*8)'\\npattern with explicit case-based byte and halfword lane extraction.\\nWord loads bypass all formatting.  Gate the load formatting logic\\nbehind in.ctrl.mem_read so it is dead-code eliminated for stores.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 320.02, \"delta_pct\": -7.98, \"vs_baseline\": 13.15, \"fmax_mhz\": 134.52, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10250, \"ff\": 1942, \"seeds\": [127.1, 134.52, 135.76], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T08:19:05.454681Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 11, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r11s0 (regression, -7.98%): Yosys infers efficient byte-select logic from variable shift-by-8 patterns; explicit nested-case byte-lane muxes are larger and slower than the inferred barrel-shifter equivalent.\\n\\n(End of file - total 10 lines)\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Add 1-entry non-blocking store buffer to hide dmem backpressure on stores\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit currently stalls the entire pipeline on every !dmem_ready cycle\\nwhenever any memory operation is in MEM. Stores are roughly 20-25% of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream and the cosim model injects ~22% random dmem stalls, so about\\n5% of total cycles are wasted waiting for the store bus. Because stores do not\\nproduce register results, the instructions behind them are almost always\\nindependent and could continue executing if the store were decoupled. A 1-entry\\nstore buffer captures a stalled store and lets the pipeline advance while the\\nbuffer drains asynchronously, converting store-bus stalls into useful execution\\ncycles with minimal area and no new long combinational paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The hazard_unit currently stalls the entire pipeline on every !dmem_ready cycle\\nwhenever any memory operation is in MEM. Stores are roughly 20-25% of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream and the cosim model injects ~22% random dmem stalls, so about\\n5% of total cycles are wasted waiting for the store bus. Because stores do not\\nproduce register results, the instructions behind them are almost always\\nindependent and could continue executing if the store were decoupled. A 1-entry\\nstore buffer captures a stalled store and lets the pipeline advance while the\\nbuffer drains asynchronously, converting store-bus stalls into useful execution\\ncycles with minimal area and no new long combinational paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a 1-entry store buffer between the MEM stage and the external dmem interface.\\nWhen a store reaches MEM and dmem_ready is low, the buffer captures the address,\\ndata, and byte mask instead of asserting a global stall. The buffer continuously\\nretries the write whenever dmem_ready is high. The top-level dmem outputs are\\nmuxed between the buffer (when valid) and the live MEM stage. The hazard_unit\\nis extended so that:\\n  - Loads still stall on !dmem_ready; stores use the buffer instead of stalling.\\n  - Any memory operation (load or store) stalls while the buffer is valid, because\\n    the single port is busy with the buffered write.\\n  - Non-memory instructions pass through MEM unimpeded even while the buffer drains.\\nThis structural decoupling should recover the cycles currently lost to store stalls.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/store_buffer.sv\", \"description\": \"New 1-entry buffer module holding addr, wdata, wmask, and valid. Captures on\\nen when a store is in MEM and dmem_ready is low. Drains on dmem_ready when\\nvalid. Clears valid when drained.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate store_buffer between mem_stage and the dmem pins. Route\\nex_mem_w write fields to the buffer inputs. Mux io_dmemAddr, io_dmemWData,\\nio_dmemWEn, and io_dmemREn between buffer outputs and mem_stage outputs.\\nWire store_buffer_valid into hazard_unit. Pass ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read as\\na new ex_mem_mem_read port to hazard_unit.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add store_buffer_valid and ex_mem_mem_read inputs. Replace the monolithic\\ndmem_stall = !dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_op with two terms:\\n  (!dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_read)  // loads still wait for the bus\\n  || (store_buffer_valid && ex_mem_mem_op) // any mem op waits while buffer busy.\\nKeep all other stall/flush logic unchanged.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/store_buffer.sv\", \"description\": \"New 1-entry buffer module holding addr, wdata, wmask, and valid. Captures on\\nen when a store is in MEM and dmem_ready is low. Drains on dmem_ready when\\nvalid. Clears valid when drained.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate store_buffer between mem_stage and the dmem pins. Route\\nex_mem_w write fields to the buffer inputs. Mux io_dmemAddr, io_dmemWData,\\nio_dmemWEn, and io_dmemREn between buffer outputs and mem_stage outputs.\\nWire store_buffer_valid into hazard_unit. Pass ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read as\\na new ex_mem_mem_read port to hazard_unit.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add store_buffer_valid and ex_mem_mem_read inputs. Replace the monolithic\\ndmem_stall = !dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_op with two terms:\\n  (!dmem_ready && ex_mem_mem_read)  // loads still wait for the bus\\n  || (store_buffer_valid && ex_mem_mem_op) // any mem op waits while buffer busy.\\nKeep all other stall/flush logic unchanged.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 328.83, \"delta_pct\": -5.44, \"vs_baseline\": 16.27, \"fmax_mhz\": 137.16, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4171199, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10826, \"ff\": 1951, \"seeds\": [131.73, 138.1, 137.16], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T08:15:37.115966Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 11, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"Add 8-entry loop predictor for backward branch exits\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit BHT already captures forward branch directions and\\nbackward-taken bias, but it cannot avoid mispredicting the final iteration\\nof every loop (predicted taken, actually not-taken). CoreMark contains\\nmany small inner loops (list traversal, matrix rows, CRC updates) where\\nthis exit misprediction wastes cycles. A dedicated loop predictor learns\\nthe trip count of individual backward branches and predicts not-taken on\\nthe last iteration, removing the only remaining systematic direction\\nmispredictions with only ~100 flops and no wider BHT mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit BHT already captures forward branch directions and\\nbackward-taken bias, but it cannot avoid mispredicting the final iteration\\nof every loop (predicted taken, actually not-taken). CoreMark contains\\nmany small inner loops (list traversal, matrix rows, CRC updates) where\\nthis exit misprediction wastes cycles. A dedicated loop predictor learns\\nthe trip count of individual backward branches and predicts not-taken on\\nthe last iteration, removing the only remaining systematic direction\\nmispredictions with only ~100 flops and no wider BHT mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an 8-entry direct-mapped loop predictor table to the IF stage.\\nEach entry stores a tag, a trained iteration length, a speculative\\ndown-counter, and a 1-bit confidence flag.\\nWhen a backward branch is fetched, if the entry is valid, tag matches,\\nand confidence is high, the predictor overrides the BHT:\\n  - down-counter > 0  \\u2192 predict taken and decrement the counter.\\n  - down-counter == 0 \\u2192 predict not-taken.\\nIn EX, resolved backward branches update the table:\\n  - During training (confidence low) the table counts taken outcomes;\\n    the first not-taken exit stores the count as the trained length\\n    and sets confidence high.\\n  - On a correct exit (predicted not-taken) the counter is reloaded\\n    from the trained length for the next loop invocation.\\n  - On a length mismatch (mispredict) confidence is cleared so the\\n    entry re-trains on the next invocation.\\nThis attacks the last predictable bubble source without touching the\\nexisting BHT or pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 8-entry loop-predictor array (tag, length, count, conf), combinational read/decrement, and integrate with predict_taken so a matching confident entry overrides the BHT for backward branches.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop-predictor update logic: on resolved backward branches allocate/train entries, reload counters on correct exits, and clear confidence on mispredicts. Drive update signals back to IF.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop_predictor_entry_t struct and confidence constants to the package.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new loop-predictor update signals between ex_stage and if_stage.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 8-entry loop-predictor array (tag, length, count, conf), combinational read/decrement, and integrate with predict_taken so a matching confident entry overrides the BHT for backward branches.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop-predictor update logic: on resolved backward branches allocate/train entries, reload counters on correct exits, and clear confidence on mispredicts. Drive update signals back to IF.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop_predictor_entry_t struct and confidence constants to the package.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new loop-predictor update signals between ex_stage and if_stage.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 302.03, \"delta_pct\": -13.15, \"vs_baseline\": 6.79, \"fmax_mhz\": 126.68, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4194286, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10454, \"ff\": 1951, \"seeds\": [114.19, 126.68, 139.82], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T08:24:35.661190Z\", 