{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778751014097,"sessionID":"ses_1da325336fferLJv5DX6QjzZyq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"bash:8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -i 'static.*bht\\|bht.*static\\|forward.*taken\\|backward.*taken' /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | head -n 20","description":"Search for prior static+BHT hybrid attempts"},"output":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Add static branch predictor (backward-taken, JAL-always-taken)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core incurs a 1-cycle bubble on every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause IF always speculatively fetches PC+4. CoreMark is loop-heavy, so backward\\nbranches and function calls are frequent. A static predictor that fetches the\\ntarget for backward branches and JAL eliminates the bubble on the common case,\\nimproving IPC with negligible LUT cost (~50 LUTs) and no impact on the critical\\npath.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage core incurs a 1-cycle bubble on every taken branch and JAL\\nbecause IF always speculatively fetches PC+4. CoreMark is loop-heavy, so backward\\nbranches and function calls are frequent. A static predictor that fetches the\\ntarget for backward branches and JAL eliminates the bubble on the common case,\\nimproving IPC with negligible LUT cost (~50 LUTs) and no impact on the critical\\npath.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert decode-and-predict logic in the IF stage. When the fetched instruction is\\na BRANCH with a negative immediate (backward loop) or an unconditional JAL, the\\nPC is updated to the computed target instead of PC+4. A 1-bit pred_taken flag is\\nthreaded through the IF/ID and ID/EX bundles. The EX stage suppresses redirect\\nwhen the prediction was correct; it only asserts redirect (triggering IF/ID flush)\\non mispredict. JALR remains unpredicted. This saves one cycle per correctly\\npredicted taken branch or JAL.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add pred_taken bit to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Decode BRANCH/JAL opcodes from imem_data, compute B/J immediates, set predict_taken for backward branches and JAL, and select next_pc from the predicted target when predict_taken is asserted.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Thread pred_taken from the IF/ID combinational bundle into the ID/EX pipeline register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the unconditional redirect logic with mispredict detection. redirect is asserted only when a conditional branch outcome differs from pred_taken, or for unpredicte JALR. Correctly predicted branches and JAL no longer flush the pipeline.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add pred_taken bit to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Decode BRANCH/JAL opcodes from imem_data, compute B/J immediates, set predict_taken for backward branches and JAL, and select next_pc from the predicted target when predict_taken is asserted.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Thread pred_taken from the IF/ID combinational bundle into the ID/EX pipeline register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the unconditional redirect logic with mispredict detection. redirect is asserted only when a conditional branch outcome differs from pred_taken, or for unpredicte JALR. Correctly predicted branches and JAL no longer flush the pipeline.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 324.08, \"delta_pct\": 14.59, \"vs_baseline\": 14.59, \"fmax_mhz\": 138.05, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4259699, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10189, \"ff\": 1874, \"seeds\": [133.46, 138.05, 148.35], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T02:11:08.300480Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r1s1 (improvement, +14.59%): Even a trivial static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken) eliminates the taken-branch bubble and yields double-digit IPC gains on loop-heavy benchmarks like CoreMark, with negligible LUT cost.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Static BTFN branch predictor + JAL prediction in ID stage\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline resolves all control-flow instructions in EX and pays a\\nfixed 2-cycle bubble (flush IF/ID) for every taken branch and every jump. CoreMark is\\nloop-heavy; backward branches are taken the vast majority of the time. A static\\nBackward-Taken / Forward-Not-Taken (BTFN) predictor combined with unconditional JAL\\nprediction, both computed in the ID stage, eliminates the 2-cycle penalty for the\\nmost common control-flow cases at virtually zero area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage pipeline resolves all control-flow instructions in EX and pays a\\nfixed 2-cycle bubble (flush IF/ID) for every taken branch and every jump. CoreMark is\\nloop-heavy; backward branches are taken the vast majority of the time. A static\\nBackward-Taken / Forward-Not-Taken (BTFN) predictor combined with unconditional JAL\\nprediction, both computed in the ID stage, eliminates the 2-cycle penalty for the\\nmost common control-flow cases at virtually zero area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a simple static predictor in the ID stage that:\\n1) Predicts JAL (unconditional jump) always taken.\\n2) Predicts conditional branches as taken iff the immediate is negative (backward).\\n3) Redirects the IF PC and flushes the combinational IF/ID output in the same cycle\\n   the branch/jump is in ID.  A `predict_taken` bit is carried through ID/EX so that\\n   EX only asserts `redirect` on a mispredict (predicted-not-taken but taken, or\\n   predicted-taken but not-taken).  JALR is intentionally *not* predicted because its\\n   target depends on `rs1`, which may still be pending from an in-flight ALU result\\n (forwarding only exists in EX, not ID).\\n\\nThis turns the common-case loop-back branch from a 2-cycle penalty into 0 cycles,\\nand unconditional JAL from 2 cycles to 0 cycles, while keeping forward branches and\\nJALR at their existing penalties.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `logic predict_taken` field to the `id_ex_t` struct.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute `predict_taken` in decode (JAL || backward branch).  Add combinational\\noutputs `predict_redirect` and `predict_target` driven from the ID/EX register;\\nassert `predict_redirect` when `reg_q` is a predicted-taken control-flow instruction\\nand capture `predict_taken` into the ID/EX register.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Accept `predict_redirect` / `predict_target` inputs.  Give them priority over `stall`\\nbut below the EX-stage `redirect`.  Flush the combinational IF/ID output (NOP) on\\n`predict_redirect` so the fall-through instruction is discarded.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Use the new `in.predict_taken` bit to distinguish correct predictions from\\nmispredictions.  Assert `redirect` only when a branch mispredicts; for correctly\\npredicted jumps do not assert `redirect`.  Keep the existing misalignment-trap\\nlogic untouched.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new `predict_redirect` / `predict_target` signals from `id_stage` to\\n`if_stage`, and connect the ID-stage `predict_taken` path into the `id_ex_t` bundle.\\nNo top-level IO changes; RVFI and memory interfaces remain identical.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `logic predict_taken` field to the `id_ex_t` struct.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute `predict_taken` in decode (JAL || backward branch).  Add combinational\\noutputs `predict_redirect` and `predict_target` driven from the ID/EX register;\\nassert `predict_redirect` when `reg_q` is a predicted-taken control-flow instruction\\nand capture `predict_taken` into the ID/EX register.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Accept `predict_redirect` / `predict_target` inputs.  Give them priority over `stall`\\nbut below the EX-stage `redirect`.  Flush the combinational IF/ID output (NOP) on\\n`predict_redirect` so the fall-through instruction is discarded.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Use the new `in.predict_taken` bit to distinguish correct predictions from\\nmispredictions.  Assert `redirect` only when a branch mispredicts; for correctly\\npredicted jumps do not assert `redirect`.  Keep the existing misalignment-trap\\nlogic untouched.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new `predict_redirect` / `predict_target` signals from `id_stage` to\\n`if_stage`, and connect the ID-stage `predict_taken` path into the `id_ex_t` bundle.\\nNo top-level IO changes; RVFI and memory interfaces remain identical.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 282.82, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9563, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [128.72, 127.03, 123.02], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T02:01:33.428670Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 1}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Add 4-entry Return Address Stack for JALR return prediction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor eliminates bubbles for backward branches and\\nunconditional JAL, but every JALR (function return) still incurs a 1-cycle\\nflush because the target is unknown until EX. CoreMark contains frequent\\nnested function calls, so returns are a noticeable fraction of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream. A tiny Return Address Stack (RAS) pushes the link\\naddress on JAL-to-x1/x5 and pops it on JALR-from-x1/x5, predicting the\\nreturn target in IF with high accuracy at negligible area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor eliminates bubbles for backward branches and\\nunconditional JAL, but every JALR (function return) still incurs a 1-cycle\\nflush because the target is unknown until EX. CoreMark contains frequent\\nnested function calls, so returns are a noticeable fraction of the dynamic\\ninstruction stream. A tiny Return Address Stack (RAS) pushes the link\\naddress on JAL-to-x1/x5 and pops it on JALR-from-x1/x5, predicting the\\nreturn target in IF with high accuracy at negligible area cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extend the IF-stage predictor with a 4-entry RAS. When the fetched\\ninstruction is a JAL with rd=x1 or x5, push PC+4 onto the stack. When the\\nfetched instruction is a JALR with rs1=x1 or x5 and the stack is non-empty,\\npop the top entry and treat it as the predicted target (pred_taken=1,\\npred_target=ras_top). Thread the predicted target through the IF/ID and\\nID/EX bundles so that EX can verify it. In EX, a JALR only causes a\\nredirect when it was unpredicted (!pred_taken) or when the actual target\\ndiffers from pred_target. The RAS pointer is updated only on non-stalled,\\nnon-flushed cycles. This removes the bubble on the vast majority of\\nreturns.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 32-bit pred_target field to if_id_t and id_ex_t so the predicted address can flow to EX for mispredict checking.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate a 4-entry RAS. Detect call (JAL rd=x1/x5) and return (JALR rs1=x1/x5) patterns from imem_data, push/pop accordingly, and drive predict_taken/predict_target for returns.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Thread the new pred_target bit from the IF/ID bundle into the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"For JALR, assert redirect only on mispredict (unpredicted or predicted target != actual jump_target). Keep existing branch/JAL/misalign logic unchanged.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 32-bit pred_target field to if_id_t and id_ex_t so the predicted address can flow to EX for mispredict checking.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate a 4-entry RAS. Detect call (JAL rd=x1/x5) and return (JALR rs1=x1/x5) patterns from imem_data, push/pop accordingly, and drive predict_taken/predict_target for returns.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Thread the new pred_target bit from the IF/ID bundle into the ID/EX register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"For JALR, assert redirect only on mispredict (unpredicted or predicted target != actual jump_target). Keep existing branch/JAL/misalign logic unchanged.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 297.42, \"delta_pct\": -8.23, \"vs_baseline\": 5.16, \"fmax_mhz\": 126.28, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4245805, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10086, \"ff\": 1950, \"seeds\": [123.23, 135.1, 126.28], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T02:34:32.311729Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 2, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"Add 32-entry tagged BTB with 2-bit saturating counters for branch target caching and forward-branch learning\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor correctly predicts backward branches and JAL,\\nbut forward branches that are frequently taken are always mispredicted.\\nAdditionally, the combinational branch-target computation in the IF stage\\n(opcode decode \\u2192 immediate extraction \\u2192 sign-extension \\u2192 PC adder) may\\ncontribute to the critical path. A small Branch Target Buffer can learn\\ntaken forward branches, cache targets to shorten the IF-stage path, and\\ncoexist safely with the existing static BTFN predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor correctly predicts backward branches and JAL,\\nbut forward branches that are frequently taken are always mispredicted.\\nAdditionally, the combinational branch-target computation in the IF stage\\n(opcode decode \\u2192 immediate extraction \\u2192 sign-extension \\u2192 PC adder) may\\ncontribute to the critical path. A small Branch Target Buffer can learn\\ntaken forward branches, cache targets to shorten the IF-stage path, and\\ncoexist safely with the existing static BTFN predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped Branch Target Buffer in the IF stage.\\nEach entry stores a valid bit, a 5-bit tag (PC[11:7]), a 30-bit\\nword-aligned target, and a 2-bit saturating counter.  In IF, a BTB\\nhit on a branch or JAL supplies the target directly from a register\\nread, bypassing the combinational immediate+adder path.  Direction\\nprediction remains static-taken for backward branches and JAL, but\\nthe BTB can additionally predict taken for forward branches once\\ntheir counter reaches 2.  In EX, every resolved branch/JAL writes\\nits outcome and target back into the BTB.  JALR is excluded from\\nBTB usage to avoid aliasing noise.  This should improve IPC on\\ntaken forward branches and may raise Fmax by reducing IF-stage\\ncombinational delay.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a packed `btb_entry_t` struct (valid, tag[4:0], target[29:0],\\ncounter[1:0]) for the 32-entry Branch Target Buffer.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add the 32-entry BTB array and combinational read logic.  Use the\\nBTB target on hit for branches/JAL, falling back to the existing\\ncombinational immediate+adder path on miss.  Add `btb_update_en`,\\n`btb_update_idx`, and `btb_update_entry` input ports so EX can\\nwrite resolved outcomes back.  Keep the static backward-taken/JAL\\nprediction as a base; allow BTB to override only to predict taken\\nfor forward branches when the counter is saturated.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add combinational BTB update logic that drives `btb_update_en`,\\n`btb_update_idx` (from `in.pc[6:2]`), and `btb_update_entry`\\n(valid=1, tag=PC[11:7], target=resolved target, counter updated\\nby the 2-bit saturating counter rule) on every resolved branch\\nor jump.  Gate the update on `!stall && in.valid`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires `btb_update_en`, `btb_update_idx[4:0]`, and\\n`btb_update_entry` and route them from `ex_stage` outputs to\\n`if_stage` inputs so the BTB can be updated from EX.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a packed `btb_entry_t` struct (valid, tag[4:0], target[29:0],\\ncounter[1:0]) for the 32-entry Branch Target Buffer.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add the 32-entry BTB array and combinational read logic.  Use the\\nBTB target on hit for branches/JAL, falling back to the existing\\ncombinational immediate+adder path on miss.  Add `btb_update_en`,\\n`btb_update_idx`, and `btb_update_entry` input ports so EX can\\nwrite resolved outcomes back.  Keep the static backward-taken/JAL\\nprediction as a base; allow BTB to override only to predict taken\\nfor forward branches when the counter is saturated.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add combinational BTB update logic that drives `btb_update_en`,\\n`btb_update_idx` (from `in.pc[6:2]`), and `btb_update_entry`\\n(valid=1, tag=PC[11:7], target=resolved target, counter updated\\nby the 2-bit saturating counter rule) on every resolved branch\\nor jump.  Gate the update on `!stall && in.valid`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires `btb_update_en`, `btb_update_idx[4:0]`, and\\n`btb_update_entry` and route them from `ex_stage` outputs to\\n`if_stage` inputs so the BTB can be updated from EX.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"cosim_failed: coremark.elf\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 3, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"Add 32-entry 2-bit BHT for forward branch direction prediction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped Branch History Table with 2-bit saturating\\ncounters to the IF stage. The table is indexed by PC[6:2] and initialized to\\nstrongly-taken (2'b11) so backward loops are correct immediately without any\\ntraining cost. For every conditional branch, the BHT entry MSB drives\\npredict_taken; unconditional JAL continues to be always predicted taken. In\\nEX stage, each resolved branch writes its actual outcome back to the entry\\nindexed by the branch PC using a standard saturating update rule. This adds\\nonly 64 flops and a few LUTs of combinational logic, does not widen any\\npipeline register, and the BHT read is off the critical instruction-fetch path\\nbecause the PC is known at the start of the cycle while the opcode decode\\n(which selects the BHT result) happens later in parallel.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 32-entry x 2-bit BHT array inside the IF stage.  Combinational read uses pc[6:2] to select the counter; the MSB becomes the direction prediction for conditional branches.  Add three new input ports (bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], bht_update_taken) and a saturating update rule that increments on taken and decrements on not-taken.  Modify predict_taken so that conditional branches use the BHT MSB while JAL remains unconditionally taken.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add output ports bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken.  Drive bht_update_en high on every cycle a conditional branch is resolved (!stall && in.valid && in.ctrl.is_branch). bht_update_idx is in.pc[6:2] and bht_update_taken is the combinational branch_taken signal.  No other EX-stage logic is changed.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken and route them from ex_stage outputs to if_stage inputs. No top-level IO or RVFI changes.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 32-entry x 2-bit BHT array inside the IF stage.  Combinational read uses pc[6:2] to select the counter; the MSB becomes the direction prediction for conditional branches.  Add three new input ports (bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], bht_update_taken) and a saturating update rule that increments on taken and decrements on not-taken.  Modify predict_taken so that conditional branches use the BHT MSB while JAL remains unconditionally taken.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add output ports bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken.  Drive bht_update_en high on every cycle a conditional branch is resolved (!stall && in.valid && in.ctrl.is_branch). bht_update_idx is in.pc[6:2] and bht_update_taken is the combinational branch_taken signal.  No other EX-stage logic is changed.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken and route them from ex_stage outputs to if_stage inputs. No top-level IO or RVFI changes.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 7.31, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T03:44:01.694682Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 4, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r4s2 (improvement, +7.31%): After a static backward-taken baseline captures the easy loop gains, a minimal 32-entry 2-bit BHT (64 flops) still recovers +7.3% fitness by predicting forward conditional branches; forward-branch direction is the largest remaining dynamic bubble source in CoreMark.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"Expand BHT to 128 entries to reduce aliasing among forward branches\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the 32-entry BHT in if_stage with a 128-entry direct-mapped BHT.\\nChange the index from pc[6:2] to pc[8:2] (7 bits) and widen the\\nbht_update_idx port from 5 to 7 bits so EX can write back using in.pc[8:2].\\nThe counter update rule, strong-taken initialization, and interaction with\\nthe static backward-taken / JAL predictor remain exactly the same. No new\\npipeline bundles or control signals are introduced, making this a very low-\\nrisk resize of a component that is already known to work.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Widen bht_update_idx from 5 to 7 bits to match the 128-entry table index.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Enlarge the bht array to [0:127], update the init loop bound to 128, and change the read index from pc[6:2] to pc[8:2].\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change bht_update_idx from in.pc[6:2] to in.pc[8:2] so resolved branches write back to the correct 128-entry slot.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Widen bht_update_idx from 5 to 7 bits to match the 128-entry table index.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Enlarge the bht array to [0:127], update the init loop bound to 128, and change the read index from pc[6:2] to pc[8:2].\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change bht_update_idx from in.pc[6:2] to in.pc[8:2] so resolved branches write back to the correct 128-entry slot.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 337.3, \"delta_pct\": -3.01, \"vs_baseline\": 19.26, \"fmax_mhz\": 141.74, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4202246, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 11315, \"ff\": 2133, \"seeds\": [134.34, 143.8, 141.74], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:17:50.929383Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 5, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r5s2 (regression, -3.01%): A 128-entry BHT regressed CoreMark fitness because the 32-entry table already saturates the benchmark's forward-branch locality, and the larger IF-stage read mux degraded Fmax more than reduced aliasing improved IPC.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Fold WB mux into MEM stage and remove dead EX/MEM fields\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move the write-back data selection into the MEM stage so that the MEM/WB\\nregister stores only the final rd_wdata (already muxed between load_data and\\nalu_result).  The WB stage then becomes a pure passthrough.  This removes one\\n32-bit mux from the MEM/WB->EX forwarding critical path.  At the same time,\\ndelete the unused branch_taken and branch_target fields from ex_mem_t to\\nreduce area and routing congestion.  No pipeline behaviour changes; IPC stays\\nidentical and Fmax should improve slightly.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove branch_taken and branch_target from ex_mem_t (dead fields).\\nReplace alu_result and read_data in mem_wb_t with a single rd_wdata\\nfield that holds the final register write data.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Stop writing branch_taken and branch_target into the EX/MEM register.\\nAll other fields remain unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute rd_wdata = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? load_data : in.alu_result\\ncombinationally and store it in the MEM/WB register as reg_q.rd_wdata.\\nRemove the now-redundant alu_result and read_data assignments.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/wb_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the mem_to_reg mux with a passthrough: w_data = in.rd_wdata.\\nw_en and w_addr logic stays identical.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove branch_taken and branch_target from ex_mem_t (dead fields).\\nReplace alu_result and read_data in mem_wb_t with a single rd_wdata\\nfield that holds the final register write data.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Stop writing branch_taken and branch_target into the EX/MEM register.\\nAll other fields remain unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute rd_wdata = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? load_data : in.alu_result\\ncombinationally and store it in the MEM/WB register as reg_q.rd_wdata.\\nRemove the now-redundant alu_result and read_data assignments.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/wb_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the mem_to_reg mux with a passthrough: w_data = in.rd_wdata.\\nw_en and w_addr logic stays identical.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 229.88, \"delta_pct\": -33.9, \"vs_baseline\": -18.72, \"fmax_mhz\": 96.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10222, \"ff\": 1915, \"seeds\": [99.71, 96.63, 92.38], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:50:14.606389Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 6, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Add 5-bit GHR gshare indexing to existing 32-entry BHT\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the proven 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter table, but index it\\nwith pc[6:2] ^ ghr[4:0] instead of pc[6:2] alone. A 5-bit GHR register\\nshifts in actual branch outcomes from EX-stage resolution, so the BHT\\nentry used for prediction is a function of both the branch address and\\nthe recent global control-flow path. To ensure the EX-stage counter\\nupdate writes the same entry that IF read, the GHR value present at\\nfetch time is snapshotted and threaded through the IF/ID and ID/EX\\npipeline bundles. The update rule (strongly-taken init, saturating\\nincrement/decrement) and the static backward-taken / JAL-always-taken\\nbase policy remain unchanged. This costs only 5 flops for the GHR plus\\n5 bits of pipeline state, with negligible combinational delay (a 5-bit\\nXOR on an already-existing mux path).\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0.\\nUpdate it on every EX-stage branch resolution by shifting in\\nbht_update_taken (ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_update_taken}).\\nReplace the BHT read index pc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr.\\nDrive the current ghr value into the combinational if_id_t output.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr into the ID/EX register so the snapshot reaches EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr so the counter update\\nwrites the exact entry that was read during fetch.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0.\\nUpdate it on every EX-stage branch resolution by shifting in\\nbht_update_taken (ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_update_taken}).\\nReplace the BHT read index pc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr.\\nDrive the current ghr value into the combinational if_id_t output.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr into the ID/EX register so the snapshot reaches EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr so the counter update\\nwrites the exact entry that was read during fetch.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 324.21, \"delta_pct\": -6.77, \"vs_baseline\": 14.63, \"fmax_mhz\": 136.99, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4225388, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10358, \"ff\": 1938, \"seeds\": [137.48, 135.85, 136.99], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:39:37.400024Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 6, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r6s2 (regression, -6.77%): Non-speculative GHR update at EX-stage resolution leaves history stale for tightly packed branches, causing the 5-bit XOR to increase destructive aliasing in the 32-entry BHT and regress CoreMark IPC.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r9s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/forward_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 9, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The fitness contract injects ~22% random backpressure on the instruction\\nbus.  Today every !imem_ready cycle asserts a global stall_if / flush_if\\nthat freezes the PC and forces a NOP bubble into ID/EX.  A tiny 2-entry\\nskid buffer decouples fetch from issue: when the downstream pipeline is\\nstalled (load-use, dmem) but the bus is ready, the buffer prefetches\\nahead; when the bus subsequently stalls but the buffer is non-empty, the\\ncore continues issuing without bubbles.  This is a pure structural\\ndecoupling that should raise effective fetch throughput with only\\n~130 flops and no new long combinational paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure if_stage to hold a 2-entry ring buffer (valid, pc,\\ninstr, pred_taken per entry, plus a head pointer and 2-bit count).\\nThe fetch side advances the PC and enqueues the fetched instruction\\nwhenever imem_ready is high, count<2, and there is no redirect.  The\\nissue side selects the buffered head when count>0, otherwise the live\\nimem_data.  A true NOP is emitted only when the buffer is empty and\\nimem_ready is low.  In hazard_unit, remove imem_ready from stall_if\\nand flush_if so the pipeline no longer stalls globally for bus\\nbackpressure; stall_if is asserted only for load-use and dmem stalls,\\nand flush_if only for redirect.  In core.sv, wire io_imemReady into the\\nnew if_stage port and keep all top-level IO unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 2-entry ring buffer inside if_stage (buf_valid[1:0],\\nbuf_pc[1:0], buf_instr[1:0], buf_pred_taken[1:0], head pointer,\\ncount 0..2).  Add new input `imem_ready`.  Fetch PC advances and\\nenqueues into tail when imem_ready && count<2 && !redirect.\\nIssue selects buffered head if count>0, else live imem_data if\\nimem_ready, else NOP.  Count increments on fetch, decrements on\\nissue.  On redirect clear count/head and reset PC to redirect_target.\\nKeep existing BHT and static predictor logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove imem_ready from stall_if and flush_if.  Keep the imem_ready\\nport connected but unused (or remove it entirely).  Assert stall_if\\nonly for load-use hazards and dmem stalls; assert flush_if only for\\nredirect.  All other stall/flush logic (stall_id, flush_id,\\nstall_ex_mem, hold_mem_wb) remains exactly the same.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire io_imemReady to the new `imem_ready` port of if_stage.  No\\nother top-level IO changes; all RVFI and imem/dmem port names and\\nwidths stay identical.\\n\"}]}}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"Add 8-entry loop predictor for backward branch exits\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit BHT already captures forward branch directions and\\nbackward-taken bias, but it cannot avoid mispredicting the final iteration\\nof every loop (predicted taken, actually not-taken). CoreMark contains\\nmany small inner loops (list traversal, matrix rows, CRC updates) where\\nthis exit misprediction wastes cycles. A dedicated loop predictor learns\\nthe trip count of individual backward branches and predicts not-taken on\\nthe last iteration, removing the only remaining systematic direction\\nmispredictions with only ~100 flops and no wider BHT mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit BHT already captures forward branch directions and\\nbackward-taken bias, but it cannot avoid mispredicting the final iteration\\nof every loop (predicted taken, actually not-taken). CoreMark contains\\nmany small inner loops (list traversal, matrix rows, CRC updates) where\\nthis exit misprediction wastes cycles. A dedicated loop predictor learns\\nthe trip count of individual backward branches and predicts not-taken on\\nthe last iteration, removing the only remaining systematic direction\\nmispredictions with only ~100 flops and no wider BHT mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an 8-entry direct-mapped loop predictor table to the IF stage.\\nEach entry stores a tag, a trained iteration length, a speculative\\ndown-counter, and a 1-bit confidence flag.\\nWhen a backward branch is fetched, if the entry is valid, tag matches,\\nand confidence is high, the predictor overrides the BHT:\\n  - down-counter > 0  \\u2192 predict taken and decrement the counter.\\n  - down-counter == 0 \\u2192 predict not-taken.\\nIn EX, resolved backward branches update the table:\\n  - During training (confidence low) the table counts taken outcomes;\\n    the first not-taken exit stores the count as the trained length\\n    and sets confidence high.\\n  - On a correct exit (predicted not-taken) the counter is reloaded\\n    from the trained length for the next loop invocation.\\n  - On a length mismatch (mispredict) confidence is cleared so the\\n    entry re-trains on the next invocation.\\nThis attacks the last predictable bubble source without touching the\\nexisting BHT or pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 8-entry loop-predictor array (tag, length, count, conf), combinational read/decrement, and integrate with predict_taken so a matching confident entry overrides the BHT for backward branches.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop-predictor update logic: on resolved backward branches allocate/train entries, reload counters on correct exits, and clear confidence on mispredicts. Drive update signals back to IF.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop_predictor_entry_t struct and confidence constants to the package.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new loop-predictor update signals between ex_stage and if_stage.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 8-entry loop-predictor array (tag, length, count, conf), combinational read/decrement, and integrate with predict_taken so a matching confident entry overrides the BHT for backward branches.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop-predictor update logic: on resolved backward branches allocate/train entries, reload counters on correct exits, and clear confidence on mispredicts. Drive update signals back to IF.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop_predictor_entry_t struct and confidence constants to the package.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new loop-predictor update signals between ex_stage and if_stage.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 302.03, \"delta_pct\": -13.15, \"vs_baseline\": 6.79, \"fmax_mhz\": 126.68, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4194286, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10454, \"ff\": 1951, \"seeds\": [114.19, 126.68, 139.82], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T08:24:35.661190Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 11, \"scribe_skipped\": \"PermissionError: scribe rewrote /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/LESSONS.md instead of appending; reverted to prior content\"}\n","metadata":{"output":"...\n\n05-14T02:34:32.311729Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 2, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"Add 32-entry tagged BTB with 2-bit saturating counters for branch target caching and forward-branch learning\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor correctly predicts backward branches and JAL,\\nbut forward branches that are frequently taken are always mispredicted.\\nAdditionally, the combinational branch-target computation in the IF stage\\n(opcode decode \\u2192 immediate extraction \\u2192 sign-extension \\u2192 PC adder) may\\ncontribute to the critical path. A small Branch Target Buffer can learn\\ntaken forward branches, cache targets to shorten the IF-stage path, and\\ncoexist safely with the existing static BTFN predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing static predictor correctly predicts backward branches and JAL,\\nbut forward branches that are frequently taken are always mispredicted.\\nAdditionally, the combinational branch-target computation in the IF stage\\n(opcode decode \\u2192 immediate extraction \\u2192 sign-extension \\u2192 PC adder) may\\ncontribute to the critical path. A small Branch Target Buffer can learn\\ntaken forward branches, cache targets to shorten the IF-stage path, and\\ncoexist safely with the existing static BTFN predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped Branch Target Buffer in the IF stage.\\nEach entry stores a valid bit, a 5-bit tag (PC[11:7]), a 30-bit\\nword-aligned target, and a 2-bit saturating counter.  In IF, a BTB\\nhit on a branch or JAL supplies the target directly from a register\\nread, bypassing the combinational immediate+adder path.  Direction\\nprediction remains static-taken for backward branches and JAL, but\\nthe BTB can additionally predict taken for forward branches once\\ntheir counter reaches 2.  In EX, every resolved branch/JAL writes\\nits outcome and target back into the BTB.  JALR is excluded from\\nBTB usage to avoid aliasing noise.  This should improve IPC on\\ntaken forward branches and may raise Fmax by reducing IF-stage\\ncombinational delay.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a packed `btb_entry_t` struct (valid, tag[4:0], target[29:0],\\ncounter[1:0]) for the 32-entry Branch Target Buffer.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add the 32-entry BTB array and combinational read logic.  Use the\\nBTB target on hit for branches/JAL, falling back to the existing\\ncombinational immediate+adder path on miss.  Add `btb_update_en`,\\n`btb_update_idx`, and `btb_update_entry` input ports so EX can\\nwrite resolved outcomes back.  Keep the static backward-taken/JAL\\nprediction as a base; allow BTB to override only to predict taken\\nfor forward branches when the counter is saturated.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add combinational BTB update logic that drives `btb_update_en`,\\n`btb_update_idx` (from `in.pc[6:2]`), and `btb_update_entry`\\n(valid=1, tag=PC[11:7], target=resolved target, counter updated\\nby the 2-bit saturating counter rule) on every resolved branch\\nor jump.  Gate the update on `!stall && in.valid`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires `btb_update_en`, `btb_update_idx[4:0]`, and\\n`btb_update_entry` and route them from `ex_stage` outputs to\\n`if_stage` inputs so the BTB can be updated from EX.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a packed `btb_entry_t` struct (valid, tag[4:0], target[29:0],\\ncounter[1:0]) for the 32-entry Branch Target Buffer.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add the 32-entry BTB array and combinational read logic.  Use the\\nBTB target on hit for branches/JAL, falling back to the existing\\ncombinational immediate+adder path on miss.  Add `btb_update_en`,\\n`btb_update_idx`, and `btb_update_entry` input ports so EX can\\nwrite resolved outcomes back.  Keep the static backward-taken/JAL\\nprediction as a base; allow BTB to override only to predict taken\\nfor forward branches when the counter is saturated.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add combinational BTB update logic that drives `btb_update_en`,\\n`btb_update_idx` (from `in.pc[6:2]`), and `btb_update_entry`\\n(valid=1, tag=PC[11:7], target=resolved target, counter updated\\nby the 2-bit saturating counter rule) on every resolved branch\\nor jump.  Gate the update on `!stall && in.valid`.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires `btb_update_en`, `btb_update_idx[4:0]`, and\\n`btb_update_entry` and route them from `ex_stage` outputs to\\n`if_stage` inputs so the BTB can be updated from EX.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"cosim_failed: coremark.elf\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 3, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"Add 32-entry 2-bit BHT for forward branch direction prediction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped Branch History Table with 2-bit saturating\\ncounters to the IF stage. The table is indexed by PC[6:2] and initialized to\\nstrongly-taken (2'b11) so backward loops are correct immediately without any\\ntraining cost. For every conditional branch, the BHT entry MSB drives\\npredict_taken; unconditional JAL continues to be always predicted taken. In\\nEX stage, each resolved branch writes its actual outcome back to the entry\\nindexed by the branch PC using a standard saturating update rule. This adds\\nonly 64 flops and a few LUTs of combinational logic, does not widen any\\npipeline register, and the BHT read is off the critical instruction-fetch path\\nbecause the PC is known at the start of the cycle while the opcode decode\\n(which selects the BHT result) happens later in parallel.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 32-entry x 2-bit BHT array inside the IF stage.  Combinational read uses pc[6:2] to select the counter; the MSB becomes the direction prediction for conditional branches.  Add three new input ports (bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], bht_update_taken) and a saturating update rule that increments on taken and decrements on not-taken.  Modify predict_taken so that conditional branches use the BHT MSB while JAL remains unconditionally taken.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add output ports bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken.  Drive bht_update_en high on every cycle a conditional branch is resolved (!stall && in.valid && in.ctrl.is_branch). bht_update_idx is in.pc[6:2] and bht_update_taken is the combinational branch_taken signal.  No other EX-stage logic is changed.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken and route them from ex_stage outputs to if_stage inputs. No top-level IO or RVFI changes.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 32-entry x 2-bit BHT array inside the IF stage.  Combinational read uses pc[6:2] to select the counter; the MSB becomes the direction prediction for conditional branches.  Add three new input ports (bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], bht_update_taken) and a saturating update rule that increments on taken and decrements on not-taken.  Modify predict_taken so that conditional branches use the BHT MSB while JAL remains unconditionally taken.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add output ports bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken.  Drive bht_update_en high on every cycle a conditional branch is resolved (!stall && in.valid && in.ctrl.is_branch). bht_update_idx is in.pc[6:2] and bht_update_taken is the combinational branch_taken signal.  No other EX-stage logic is changed.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken and route them from ex_stage outputs to if_stage inputs. No top-level IO or RVFI changes.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 347.76, \"delta_pct\": 7.31, \"vs_baseline\": 22.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10254, \"ff\": 1940, \"seeds\": [146.18, 132.82, 146.26], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T03:44:01.694682Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 4, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r4s2 (improvement, +7.31%): After a static backward-taken baseline captures the easy loop gains, a minimal 32-entry 2-bit BHT (64 flops) still recovers +7.3% fitness by predicting forward conditional branches; forward-branch direction is the largest remaining dynamic bubble source in CoreMark.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"Expand BHT to 128 entries to reduce aliasing among forward branches\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the 32-entry BHT in if_stage with a 128-entry direct-mapped BHT.\\nChange the index from pc[6:2] to pc[8:2] (7 bits) and widen the\\nbht_update_idx port from 5 to 7 bits so EX can write back using in.pc[8:2].\\nThe counter update rule, strong-taken initialization, and interaction with\\nthe static backward-taken / JAL predictor remain exactly the same. No new\\npipeline bundles or control signals are introduced, making this a very low-\\nrisk resize of a component that is already known to work.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Widen bht_update_idx from 5 to 7 bits to match the 128-entry table index.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Enlarge the bht array to [0:127], update the init loop bound to 128, and change the read index from pc[6:2] to pc[8:2].\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change bht_update_idx from in.pc[6:2] to in.pc[8:2] so resolved branches write back to the correct 128-entry slot.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"high\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Widen bht_update_idx from 5 to 7 bits to match the 128-entry table index.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Enlarge the bht array to [0:127], update the init loop bound to 128, and change the read index from pc[6:2] to pc[8:2].\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change bht_update_idx from in.pc[6:2] to in.pc[8:2] so resolved branches write back to the correct 128-entry slot.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 337.3, \"delta_pct\": -3.01, \"vs_baseline\": 19.26, \"fmax_mhz\": 141.74, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4202246, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 11315, \"ff\": 2133, \"seeds\": [134.34, 143.8, 141.74], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:17:50.929383Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 5, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r5s2 (regression, -3.01%): A 128-entry BHT regressed CoreMark fitness because the 32-entry table already saturates the benchmark's forward-branch locality, and the larger IF-stage read mux degraded Fmax more than reduced aliasing improved IPC.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Fold WB mux into MEM stage and remove dead EX/MEM fields\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The MEM/WB->EX forwarding path currently includes the combinational WB-stage\\nmux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result). Because fwd_mem_wb is driven by\\nwb_w_data, every instruction that forwards from MEM/WB pays the delay of this\\n32-bit 2:1 mux on top of the MEM/WB register Q, forwarding comparison, and\\nEX operand mux.  On a low-end FPGA this extra mux depth can be the difference\\nbetween timing closure and a slight Fmax loss.  Additionally, ex_mem_t carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target fields that are written in EX but never read\\ndownstream, wasting ~33 flops.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move the write-back data selection into the MEM stage so that the MEM/WB\\nregister stores only the final rd_wdata (already muxed between load_data and\\nalu_result).  The WB stage then becomes a pure passthrough.  This removes one\\n32-bit mux from the MEM/WB->EX forwarding critical path.  At the same time,\\ndelete the unused branch_taken and branch_target fields from ex_mem_t to\\nreduce area and routing congestion.  No pipeline behaviour changes; IPC stays\\nidentical and Fmax should improve slightly.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove branch_taken and branch_target from ex_mem_t (dead fields).\\nReplace alu_result and read_data in mem_wb_t with a single rd_wdata\\nfield that holds the final register write data.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Stop writing branch_taken and branch_target into the EX/MEM register.\\nAll other fields remain unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute rd_wdata = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? load_data : in.alu_result\\ncombinationally and store it in the MEM/WB register as reg_q.rd_wdata.\\nRemove the now-redundant alu_result and read_data assignments.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/wb_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the mem_to_reg mux with a passthrough: w_data = in.rd_wdata.\\nw_en and w_addr logic stays identical.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove branch_taken and branch_target from ex_mem_t (dead fields).\\nReplace alu_result and read_data in mem_wb_t with a single rd_wdata\\nfield that holds the final register write data.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Stop writing branch_taken and branch_target into the EX/MEM register.\\nAll other fields remain unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute rd_wdata = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? load_data : in.alu_result\\ncombinationally and store it in the MEM/WB register as reg_q.rd_wdata.\\nRemove the now-redundant alu_result and read_data assignments.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/wb_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the mem_to_reg mux with a passthrough: w_data = in.rd_wdata.\\nw_en and w_addr logic stays identical.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 229.88, \"delta_pct\": -33.9, \"vs_baseline\": -18.72, \"fmax_mhz\": 96.63, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4203461, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10222, \"ff\": 1915, \"seeds\": [99.71, 96.63, 92.38], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:50:14.606389Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 6, \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Add 5-bit GHR gshare indexing to existing 32-entry BHT\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the proven 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter table, but index it\\nwith pc[6:2] ^ ghr[4:0] instead of pc[6:2] alone. A 5-bit GHR register\\nshifts in actual branch outcomes from EX-stage resolution, so the BHT\\nentry used for prediction is a function of both the branch address and\\nthe recent global control-flow path. To ensure the EX-stage counter\\nupdate writes the same entry that IF read, the GHR value present at\\nfetch time is snapshotted and threaded through the IF/ID and ID/EX\\npipeline bundles. The update rule (strongly-taken init, saturating\\nincrement/decrement) and the static backward-taken / JAL-always-taken\\nbase policy remain unchanged. This costs only 5 flops for the GHR plus\\n5 bits of pipeline state, with negligible combinational delay (a 5-bit\\nXOR on an already-existing mux path).\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0.\\nUpdate it on every EX-stage branch resolution by shifting in\\nbht_update_taken (ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_update_taken}).\\nReplace the BHT read index pc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr.\\nDrive the current ghr value into the combinational if_id_t output.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr into the ID/EX register so the snapshot reaches EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr so the counter update\\nwrites the exact entry that was read during fetch.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0.\\nUpdate it on every EX-stage branch resolution by shifting in\\nbht_update_taken (ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_update_taken}).\\nReplace the BHT read index pc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr.\\nDrive the current ghr value into the combinational if_id_t output.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr into the ID/EX register so the snapshot reaches EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr so the counter update\\nwrites the exact entry that was read during fetch.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 324.21, \"delta_pct\": -6.77, \"vs_baseline\": 14.63, \"fmax_mhz\": 136.99, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4225388, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10358, \"ff\": 1938, \"seeds\": [137.48, 135.85, 136.99], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:39:37.400024Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 6, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r6s2 (regression, -6.77%): Non-speculative GHR update at EX-stage resolution leaves history stale for tightly packed branches, causing the 5-bit XOR to increase destructive aliasing in the 32-entry BHT and regress CoreMark IPC.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-002-r9s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/rtl/core.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/ex_stage.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/forward_unit.sv', 'cores/bench/rtl/hazard_unit.sv']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 9, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The fitness contract injects ~22% random backpressure on the instruction\\nbus.  Today every !imem_ready cycle asserts a global stall_if / flush_if\\nthat freezes the PC and forces a NOP bubble into ID/EX.  A tiny 2-entry\\nskid buffer decouples fetch from issue: when the downstream pipeline is\\nstalled (load-use, dmem) but the bus is ready, the buffer prefetches\\nahead; when the bus subsequently stalls but the buffer is non-empty, the\\ncore continues issuing without bubbles.  This is a pure structural\\ndecoupling that should raise effective fetch throughput with only\\n~130 flops and no new long combinational paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure if_stage to hold a 2-entry ring buffer (valid, pc,\\ninstr, pred_taken per entry, plus a head pointer and 2-bit count).\\nThe fetch side advances the PC and enqueues the fetched instruction\\nwhenever imem_ready is high, count<2, and there is no redirect.  The\\nissue side selects the buffered head when count>0, otherwise the live\\nimem_data.  A true NOP is emitted only when the buffer is empty and\\nimem_ready is low.  In hazard_unit, remove imem_ready from stall_if\\nand flush_if so the pipeline no longer stalls globally for bus\\nbackpressure; stall_if is asserted only for load-use and dmem stalls,\\nand flush_if only for redirect.  In core.sv, wire io_imemReady into the\\nnew if_stage port and keep all top-level IO unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 10, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 2-entry ring buffer inside if_stage (buf_valid[1:0],\\nbuf_pc[1:0], buf_instr[1:0], buf_pred_taken[1:0], head pointer,\\ncount 0..2).  Add new input `imem_ready`.  Fetch PC advances and\\nenqueues into tail when imem_ready && count<2 && !redirect.\\nIssue selects buffered head if count>0, else live imem_data if\\nimem_ready, else NOP.  Count increments on fetch, decrements on\\nissue.  On redirect clear count/head and reset PC to redirect_target.\\nKeep existing BHT and static predictor logic unchanged.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove imem_ready from stall_if and flush_if.  Keep the imem_ready\\nport connected but unused (or remove it entirely).  Assert stall_if\\nonly for load-use hazards and dmem stalls; assert flush_if only for\\nredirect.  All other stall/flush logic (stall_id, flush_id,\\nstall_ex_mem, hold_mem_wb) remains exactly the same.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire io_imemReady to the new `imem_ready` port of if_stage.  No\\nother top-level IO changes; all RVFI and imem/dmem port names and\\nwidths stay identical.\\n\"}]}}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"Add 8-entry loop predictor for backward branch exits\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit BHT already captures forward branch directions and\\nbackward-taken bias, but it cannot avoid mispredicting the final iteration\\nof every loop (predicted taken, actually not-taken). CoreMark contains\\nmany small inner loops (list traversal, matrix rows, CRC updates) where\\nthis exit misprediction wastes cycles. A dedicated loop predictor learns\\nthe trip count of individual backward branches and predicts not-taken on\\nthe last iteration, removing the only remaining systematic direction\\nmispredictions with only ~100 flops and no wider BHT mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry 2-bit BHT already captures forward branch directions and\\nbackward-taken bias, but it cannot avoid mispredicting the final iteration\\nof every loop (predicted taken, actually not-taken). CoreMark contains\\nmany small inner loops (list traversal, matrix rows, CRC updates) where\\nthis exit misprediction wastes cycles. A dedicated loop predictor learns\\nthe trip count of individual backward branches and predicts not-taken on\\nthe last iteration, removing the only remaining systematic direction\\nmispredictions with only ~100 flops and no wider BHT mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an 8-entry direct-mapped loop predictor table to the IF stage.\\nEach entry stores a tag, a trained iteration length, a speculative\\ndown-counter, and a 1-bit confidence flag.\\nWhen a backward branch is fetched, if the entry is valid, tag matches,\\nand confidence is high, the predictor overrides the BHT:\\n  - down-counter > 0  \\u2192 predict taken and decrement the counter.\\n  - down-counter == 0 \\u2192 predict not-taken.\\nIn EX, resolved backward branches update the table:\\n  - During training (confidence low) the table counts taken outcomes;\\n    the first not-taken exit stores the count as the trained length\\n    and sets confidence high.\\n  - On a correct exit (predicted not-taken) the counter is reloaded\\n    from the trained length for the next loop invocation.\\n  - On a length mismatch (mispredict) confidence is cleared so the\\n    entry re-trains on the next invocation.\\nThis attacks the last predictable bubble source without touching the\\nexisting BHT or pipeline bundles.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 8-entry loop-predictor array (tag, length, count, conf), combinational read/decrement, and integrate with predict_taken so a matching confident entry overrides the BHT for backward branches.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop-predictor update logic: on resolved backward branches allocate/train entries, reload counters on correct exits, and clear confidence on mispredicts. Drive update signals back to IF.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop_predictor_entry_t struct and confidence constants to the package.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new loop-predictor update signals between ex_stage and if_stage.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add 8-entry loop-predictor array (tag, length, count, conf), combinational read/decrement, and integrate with predict_taken so a matching confident entry overrides the BHT for backward branches.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop-predictor update logic: on resolved backward branches allocate/train entries, reload counters on correct exits, and clear confidence on mispredicts. Drive update signals back to IF.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add loop_predictor_entry_t struct and confidence constants to the package.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the new loop-predictor update signals between ex_stage and if_stage.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 302.03, \"delta_pct\": -13.15, \"vs_baseline\": 6.79, \"fmax_mhz\": 126.68, \"ipc_coremark\": 