{"type":"text","timestamp":1778751881812,"sessionID":"ses_1da325336fferLJv5DX6QjzZyq","part":{"id":"prt_e25dfa43d001DQHRb8HJR11IG5","messageID":"msg_e25df4d5f001MGE4hnEPheJKmW","sessionID":"ses_1da325336fferLJv5DX6QjzZyq","type":"text","text":"I've written the hypothesis YAML to:\n\n`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r14s2.yaml`\n\n**Summary of the proposal:**\n\n- **Category:** predictor\n- **Idea:** Add a *single global loop-exit predictor* to the IF stage. It tracks one active innermost loop (PC, learned trip count, speculative down-counter). When the fetched backward branch matches the stored loop PC, the counter overrides the BHT: predict taken while the counter is positive, then predict not-taken on the final iteration.\n- **Why it should help:** The 32-entry BHT cannot avoid mispredicting every loop exit (it stays saturated “taken”). CoreMark is full of small inner loops, so each exit costs a 2-cycle bubble. A prior 8-entry tagged loop predictor regressed because its tag-CAM and per-entry state machines hurt Fmax; a single global counter is far simpler (~45 flops + one 32-bit comparator) and should add negligible combinational delay.\n- **Expected impact:** +3% fitness (medium confidence).","time":{"start":1778751874109,"end":1778751881810}}}
