{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778753443768,"sessionID":"ses_1da08a948ffexAF2vXJ8iXXlVW","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"read:0","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/LESSONS.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/LESSONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r1s1 (improvement, +14.59%): Even a trivial static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken) eliminates the taken-branch bubble and yields double-digit IPC gains on loop-heavy benchmarks like CoreMark, with negligible LUT cost.\n2: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r2s0 (regression, +0.00%): Combinational MEM-to-EX load bypass eliminated load-use stalls functionally but yielded zero net fitness gain because the longer critical path (dmem read → sign-extend → EX operand mux) degraded Fmax enough to cancel the IPC improvement.\n3: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r4s2 (improvement, +7.31%): After a static backward-taken baseline captures the easy loop gains, a minimal 32-entry 2-bit BHT (64 flops) still recovers +7.3% fitness by predicting forward conditional branches; forward-branch direction is the largest remaining dynamic bubble source in CoreMark.\n4: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r5s0 (regression, +0.00%): Opcode-aware elimination of false load-use stalls on I/U/J-type instructions after loads yielded zero CoreMark improvement; the benchmark's pointer-chasing critical path is dominated by genuine R-type and STORE dependencies, making false stalls on non-R-type instructions too rare to impact IPC.\n5: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r5s2 (regression, -3.01%): A 128-entry BHT regressed CoreMark fitness because the 32-entry table already saturates the benchmark's forward-branch locality, and the larger IF-stage read mux degraded Fmax more than reduced aliasing improved IPC.\n6: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r6s1 (broken, n/a): A multi-cycle divider in EX requires a per-instruction state machine, not raw combinational busy/done logic: without a 'started' bit, `div_busy` deadlocks after a pulsed `done` because the instruction never leaves EX, while a level `done` prevents subsequent divides from re-starting.\n7: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r6s2 (regression, -6.77%): Non-speculative GHR update at EX-stage resolution leaves history stale for tightly packed branches, causing the 5-bit XOR to increase destructive aliasing in the 32-entry BHT and regress CoreMark IPC.\n8: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r7s1 (regression, +0.00%): Even with a correct 3-state divider FSM (fixing the prior 'started'-bit deadlock), a 33-cycle iterative unit yielded zero fitness gain because CoreMark never exercises division; the combinational divider's area was not the critical-path bottleneck, and the added stall logic offset any potential Fmax gain.\n9: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r9s2 (regression, +0.00%): Speculative IF-stage GHR update with mispredict restore fixes the history-staleness bug but still yields zero net gain over the bimodal 32-entry BHT; CoreMark's branch working set is small enough that 2-bit saturating counters capture all exploitable locality, leaving global history with no accuracy upside.\n10: - 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r11s0 (regression, -7.98%): Yosys infers efficient byte-select logic from variable shift-by-8 patterns; explicit nested-case byte-lane muxes are larger and slower than the inferred barrel-shifter equivalent.\n11: \n12: (End of file - total 10 lines)\n\n(End of file - total 12 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r1s1 (improvement, +14.59%): Even a trivial static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken) eliminates the taken-branch bubble and yields double-digit IPC gains on loop-heavy benchmarks like CoreMark, with negligible LUT cost.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r2s0 (regression, +0.00%): Combinational MEM-to-EX load bypass eliminated load-use stalls functionally but yielded zero net fitness gain because the longer critical path (dmem read → sign-extend → EX operand mux) degraded Fmax enough to cancel the IPC improvement.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r4s2 (improvement, +7.31%): After a static backward-taken baseline captures the easy loop gains, a minimal 32-entry 2-bit BHT (64 flops) still recovers +7.3% fitness by predicting forward conditional branches; forward-branch direction is the largest remaining dynamic bubble source in CoreMark.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r5s0 (regression, +0.00%): Opcode-aware elimination of false load-use stalls on I/U/J-type instructions after loads yielded zero CoreMark improvement; the benchmark's pointer-chasing critical path is dominated by genuine R-type and STORE dependencies, making false stalls on non-R-type instructions too rare to impact IPC.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r5s2 (regression, -3.01%): A 128-entry BHT regressed CoreMark fitness because the 32-entry table already saturates the benchmark's forward-branch locality, and the larger IF-stage read mux degraded Fmax more than reduced aliasing improved IPC.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r6s1 (broken, n/a): A multi-cycle divider in EX requires a per-instruction state machine, not raw combinational busy/done logic: without a 'started' bit, `div_busy` deadlocks after a pulsed `done` because the instruction never leaves EX, while a level `done` prevents subsequent divides from re-starting.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r6s2 (regression, -6.77%): Non-speculative GHR update at EX-stage resolution leaves history stale for tightly packed branches, causing the 5-bit XOR to increase destructive aliasing in the 32-entry BHT and regress CoreMark IPC.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-002-r7s1 (regression, +0.00%): Even with a correct 3-state divider FSM (fixing the prior 'started'-bit deadlock), a 33-cycle iterative unit yielded zero fitness gain because CoreMark never exercises division; the combinational divider's area was not the critical-path bottleneck, and the added stall logic offset any potential Fmax gain.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r9s2 (regression, +0.00%): Speculative IF-stage GHR update with mispredict restore fixes the history-staleness bug but still yields zero net gain over the bimodal 32-entry BHT; CoreMark's branch working set is small enough that 2-bit saturating counters capture all exploitable locality, leaving global history with no accuracy upside.\n- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-001-r11s0 (regression, -7.98%): Yosys infers efficient byte-select logic from variable shift-by-8 patterns; explicit nested-case byte-lane muxes are larger and slower than the inferred barrel-shifter equivalent.\n\n(End of file - total 10 lines)","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/LESSONS.md","time":{"start":1778753443759,"end":1778753443767}},"id":"prt_e25f793c9001CLghg89CjJr8X8","sessionID":"ses_1da08a948ffexAF2vXJ8iXXlVW","messageID":"msg_e25f75729001CvG2JEZN2wkKNo"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778753445345,"sessionID":"ses_1da08a948ffexAF2vXJ8iXXlVW","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"bash:1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"cat /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | python3 -c \"\nimport sys, json\nfor line in sys.stdin:\n    obj = json.loads(line)\n    if obj.get('category') == 'predictor':\n        print(json.dumps(obj, indent=2))\n\"","description":"Filter log.jsonl for predictor category"},"output":"...output truncated...\n\nFull output saved to: /Users/bonetto/.local/share/opencode/tool-output/tool_e25f79ddd001Z3rdiilpkKHUC4\n\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires `btb_update_en`, `btb_update_idx[4:0]`, and\\n`btb_update_entry` and route them from `ex_stage` outputs to\\n`if_stage` inputs so the BTB can be updated from EX.\\n\"\n      }\n    ]\n  },\n  \"expected_impact\": {\n    \"fitness_delta_pct\": 5,\n    \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n  },\n  \"changes\": [\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add a packed `btb_entry_t` struct (valid, tag[4:0], target[29:0],\\ncounter[1:0]) for the 32-entry Branch Target Buffer.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add the 32-entry BTB array and combinational read logic.  Use the\\nBTB target on hit for branches/JAL, falling back to the existing\\ncombinational immediate+adder path on miss.  Add `btb_update_en`,\\n`btb_update_idx`, and `btb_update_entry` input ports so EX can\\nwrite resolved outcomes back.  Keep the static backward-taken/JAL\\nprediction as a base; allow BTB to override only to predict taken\\nfor forward branches when the counter is saturated.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add combinational BTB update logic that drives `btb_update_en`,\\n`btb_update_idx` (from `in.pc[6:2]`), and `btb_update_entry`\\n(valid=1, tag=PC[11:7], target=resolved target, counter updated\\nby the 2-bit saturating counter rule) on every resolved branch\\nor jump.  Gate the update on `!stall && in.valid`.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires `btb_update_en`, `btb_update_idx[4:0]`, and\\n`btb_update_entry` and route them from `ex_stage` outputs to\\n`if_stage` inputs so the BTB can be updated from EX.\\n\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"outcome\": \"broken\",\n  \"formal_passed\": false,\n  \"cosim_passed\": false,\n  \"error\": \"cosim_failed: coremark.elf\",\n  \"slot\": 2,\n  \"round_id\": 3,\n  \"scribe_skipped\": \"TimeoutError: scribe timed out after 240s\"\n}\n{\n  \"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r4s2\",\n  \"title\": \"Add 32-entry 2-bit BHT for forward branch direction prediction\",\n  \"category\": \"predictor\",\n  \"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\",\n  \"hypothesis\": {\n    \"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\",\n    \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped Branch History Table with 2-bit saturating\\ncounters to the IF stage. The table is indexed by PC[6:2] and initialized to\\nstrongly-taken (2'b11) so backward loops are correct immediately without any\\ntraining cost. For every conditional branch, the BHT entry MSB drives\\npredict_taken; unconditional JAL continues to be always predicted taken. In\\nEX stage, each resolved branch writes its actual outcome back to the entry\\nindexed by the branch PC using a standard saturating update rule. This adds\\nonly 64 flops and a few LUTs of combinational logic, does not widen any\\npipeline register, and the BHT read is off the critical instruction-fetch path\\nbecause the PC is known at the start of the cycle while the opcode decode\\n(which selects the BHT result) happens later in parallel.\\n\",\n    \"expected_impact\": {\n      \"fitness_delta_pct\": 3,\n      \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n    },\n    \"changes\": [\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Add a 32-entry x 2-bit BHT array inside the IF stage.  Combinational read uses pc[6:2] to select the counter; the MSB becomes the direction prediction for conditional branches.  Add three new input ports (bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], bht_update_taken) and a saturating update rule that increments on taken and decrements on not-taken.  Modify predict_taken so that conditional branches use the BHT MSB while JAL remains unconditionally taken.\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Add output ports bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken.  Drive bht_update_en high on every cycle a conditional branch is resolved (!stall && in.valid && in.ctrl.is_branch). bht_update_idx is in.pc[6:2] and bht_update_taken is the combinational branch_taken signal.  No other EX-stage logic is changed.\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken and route them from ex_stage outputs to if_stage inputs. No top-level IO or RVFI changes.\\n\"\n      }\n    ]\n  },\n  \"expected_impact\": {\n    \"fitness_delta_pct\": 3,\n    \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n  },\n  \"changes\": [\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add a 32-entry x 2-bit BHT array inside the IF stage.  Combinational read uses pc[6:2] to select the counter; the MSB becomes the direction prediction for conditional branches.  Add three new input ports (bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], bht_update_taken) and a saturating update rule that increments on taken and decrements on not-taken.  Modify predict_taken so that conditional branches use the BHT MSB while JAL remains unconditionally taken.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add output ports bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken.  Drive bht_update_en high on every cycle a conditional branch is resolved (!stall && in.valid && in.ctrl.is_branch). bht_update_idx is in.pc[6:2] and bht_update_taken is the combinational branch_taken signal.  No other EX-stage logic is changed.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Instantiate new wires bht_update_en, bht_update_idx[4:0], and bht_update_taken and route them from ex_stage outputs to if_stage inputs. No top-level IO or RVFI changes.\\n\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"outcome\": \"improvement\",\n  \"fitness\": 347.76,\n  \"delta_pct\": 7.31,\n  \"vs_baseline\": 22.96,\n  \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18,\n  \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06,\n  \"cycles\": 4203461,\n  \"iterations\": 10,\n  \"lut4\": 10254,\n  \"ff\": 1940,\n  \"seeds\": [\n    146.18,\n    132.82,\n    146.26\n  ],\n  \"formal_passed\": true,\n  \"cosim_passed\": true,\n  \"error\": null,\n  \"implementation_notes\": \"\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T03:44:01.694682Z\",\n  \"slot\": 2,\n  \"round_id\": 4,\n  \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r4s2 (improvement, +7.31%): After a static backward-taken baseline captures the easy loop gains, a minimal 32-entry 2-bit BHT (64 flops) still recovers +7.3% fitness by predicting forward conditional branches; forward-branch direction is the largest remaining dynamic bubble source in CoreMark.\"\n}\n{\n  \"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r5s2\",\n  \"title\": \"Expand BHT to 128 entries to reduce aliasing among forward branches\",\n  \"category\": \"predictor\",\n  \"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\",\n  \"hypothesis\": {\n    \"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\",\n    \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the 32-entry BHT in if_stage with a 128-entry direct-mapped BHT.\\nChange the index from pc[6:2] to pc[8:2] (7 bits) and widen the\\nbht_update_idx port from 5 to 7 bits so EX can write back using in.pc[8:2].\\nThe counter update rule, strong-taken initialization, and interaction with\\nthe static backward-taken / JAL predictor remain exactly the same. No new\\npipeline bundles or control signals are introduced, making this a very low-\\nrisk resize of a component that is already known to work.\\n\",\n    \"expected_impact\": {\n      \"fitness_delta_pct\": 3,\n      \"confidence\": \"high\"\n    },\n    \"changes\": [\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Widen bht_update_idx from 5 to 7 bits to match the 128-entry table index.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Enlarge the bht array to [0:127], update the init loop bound to 128, and change the read index from pc[6:2] to pc[8:2].\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Change bht_update_idx from in.pc[6:2] to in.pc[8:2] so resolved branches write back to the correct 128-entry slot.\\n\"\n      }\n    ]\n  },\n  \"expected_impact\": {\n    \"fitness_delta_pct\": 3,\n    \"confidence\": \"high\"\n  },\n  \"changes\": [\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Widen bht_update_idx from 5 to 7 bits to match the 128-entry table index.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Enlarge the bht array to [0:127], update the init loop bound to 128, and change the read index from pc[6:2] to pc[8:2].\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Change bht_update_idx from in.pc[6:2] to in.pc[8:2] so resolved branches write back to the correct 128-entry slot.\\n\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"outcome\": \"regression\",\n  \"fitness\": 337.3,\n  \"delta_pct\": -3.01,\n  \"vs_baseline\": 19.26,\n  \"fmax_mhz\": 141.74,\n  \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06,\n  \"cycles\": 4202246,\n  \"iterations\": 10,\n  \"lut4\": 11315,\n  \"ff\": 2133,\n  \"seeds\": [\n    134.34,\n    143.8,\n    141.74\n  ],\n  \"formal_passed\": true,\n  \"cosim_passed\": true,\n  \"error\": null,\n  \"implementation_notes\": \"\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:17:50.929383Z\",\n  \"slot\": 2,\n  \"round_id\": 5,\n  \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r5s2 (regression, -3.01%): A 128-entry BHT regressed CoreMark fitness because the 32-entry table already saturates the benchmark's forward-branch locality, and the larger IF-stage read mux degraded Fmax more than reduced aliasing improved IPC.\"\n}\n{\n  \"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r6s2\",\n  \"title\": \"Add 5-bit GHR gshare indexing to existing 32-entry BHT\",\n  \"category\": \"predictor\",\n  \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\",\n  \"hypothesis\": {\n    \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\",\n    \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the proven 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter table, but index it\\nwith pc[6:2] ^ ghr[4:0] instead of pc[6:2] alone. A 5-bit GHR register\\nshifts in actual branch outcomes from EX-stage resolution, so the BHT\\nentry used for prediction is a function of both the branch address and\\nthe recent global control-flow path. To ensure the EX-stage counter\\nupdate writes the same entry that IF read, the GHR value present at\\nfetch time is snapshotted and threaded through the IF/ID and ID/EX\\npipeline bundles. The update rule (strongly-taken init, saturating\\nincrement/decrement) and the static backward-taken / JAL-always-taken\\nbase policy remain unchanged. This costs only 5 flops for the GHR plus\\n5 bits of pipeline state, with negligible combinational delay (a 5-bit\\nXOR on an already-existing mux path).\\n\",\n    \"expected_impact\": {\n      \"fitness_delta_pct\": 2,\n      \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n    },\n    \"changes\": [\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0.\\nUpdate it on every EX-stage branch resolution by shifting in\\nbht_update_taken (ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_update_taken}).\\nReplace the BHT read index pc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr.\\nDrive the current ghr value into the combinational if_id_t output.\\n\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr into the ID/EX register so the snapshot reaches EX.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\",\n        \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr so the counter update\\nwrites the exact entry that was read during fetch.\\n\"\n      }\n    ]\n  },\n  \"expected_impact\": {\n    \"fitness_delta_pct\": 2,\n    \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n  },\n  \"changes\": [\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0.\\nUpdate it on every EX-stage branch resolution by shifting in\\nbht_update_taken (ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_update_taken}).\\nReplace the BHT read index pc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr.\\nDrive the current ghr value into the combinational if_id_t output.\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr into the ID/EX register so the snapshot reaches EX.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\",\n      \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr so the counter update\\nwrites the exact entry that was read during fetch.\\n\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"outcome\": \"regression\",\n  \"fitness\": 324.21,\n  \"delta_pct\": -6.77,\n  \"vs_baseline\": 14.63,\n  \"fmax_mhz\": 136.99,\n  \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06,\n  \"cycles\": 4225388,\n  \"iterations\": 10,\n  \"lut4\": 10358,\n  \"ff\": 1938,\n  \"seeds\": [\n    137.48,\n    135.85,\n    136.99\n  ],\n  \"formal_passed\": true,\n  \"cosim_passed\": true,\n  \"error\": null,\n  \"implementation_notes\": \"\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:39:37.400024Z\",\n  \"slot\": 2,\n  \"round_id\": 6,\n  \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r6s2 (regression, -6.77%): Non-speculative GHR update at EX-stage resolution leaves history stale for tightly packed branches, causing the 5-bit XOR to increase destructive aliasing in the 32-entry BHT and regress CoreMark IPC.\"\n}\n{\n  \"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r7s2\",\n  \"title\": \"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r7s2.yaml\",\n  \"category\": \"predictor\",\n  \"outco