{"type":"text","timestamp":1778731861582,"sessionID":"ses_1db556982ffeOpDgGDUzASRGrB","part":{"id":"prt_e24ae37f4001djBVjXzGbbGHFD","messageID":"msg_e24ae2a5e0013RAwVVSgZYNh4s","sessionID":"ses_1db556982ffeOpDgGDUzASRGrB","type":"text","text":"Done. I wrote the hypothesis YAML to:\n\n`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r5s2.yaml`\n\n**Summary of the proposal:**\n- **Category:** predictor\n- **Idea:** Expand the existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT to **128 entries** (index `PC[8:2]`) to reduce aliasing among forward conditional branches in the 6 KB CoreMark working set.\n- **Why it should help:** The 32-entry BHT already delivered +7.3% fitness; destructive interference between branches with colliding lower PC bits is the main remaining source of mispredictions. A 128-entry table is still tiny (256 flops) but provides 4× the capacity, cutting aliasing without adding new pipeline bundles or control logic.\n- **Risk:** Very low—this is a purely structural resize of a proven component.\n- **Expected impact:** +3% fitness, high confidence.","time":{"start":1778731857908,"end":1778731861580}}}
