{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778739683562,"sessionID":"ses_1dadf93b3ffeMfaoMLwX4gHiIS","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"functions.bash:5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"sed -n '13p' /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | python3 -m json.tool | grep -E 'outcome|fitness|delta_pct|fmax_mhz|lut4|ff|cycles|error'","description":"Extract 32-entry BHT outcome"},"output":"    \"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\",\n        \"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\",\n        \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped Branch History Table with 2-bit saturating\\ncounters to the IF stage. The table is indexed by PC[6:2] and initialized to\\nstrongly-taken (2'b11) so backward loops are correct immediately without any\\ntraining cost. For every conditional branch, the BHT entry MSB drives\\npredict_taken; unconditional JAL continues to be always predicted taken. In\\nEX stage, each resolved branch writes its actual outcome back to the entry\\nindexed by the branch PC using a standard saturating update rule. This adds\\nonly 64 flops and a few LUTs of combinational logic, does not widen any\\npipeline register, and the BHT read is off the critical instruction-fetch path\\nbecause the PC is known at the start of the cycle while the opcode decode\\n(which selects the BHT result) happens later in parallel.\\n\",\n            \"fitness_delta_pct\": 3,\n        \"fitness_delta_pct\": 3,\n    \"outcome\": \"improvement\",\n    \"fitness\": 347.76,\n    \"delta_pct\": 7.31,\n    \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18,\n    \"cycles\": 4203461,\n    \"lut4\": 10254,\n    \"ff\": 1940,\n    \"error\": null,\n    \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r4s2 (improvement, +7.31%): After a static backward-taken baseline captures the easy loop gains, a minimal 32-entry 2-bit BHT (64 flops) still recovers +7.3% fitness by predicting forward conditional branches; forward-branch direction is the largest remaining dynamic bubble source in CoreMark.\"\n","metadata":{"output":"    \"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\",\n        \"motivation\": \"The existing IF-stage static predictor (backward-taken + JAL-always-taken)\\nalready eliminated the largest source of control bubbles, yielding a +14.6%\\nfitness gain. The remaining dynamic mispredictions come mainly from forward\\nconditional branches that are frequently taken (e.g. early exits, loop-internal\\nconditionals) and from JALR returns. A prior 4-entry RAS improved IPC by only\\n0.3% because returns are rare, while a 32-entry tagged BTB broke in cosim.\\nA saturating-counter BHT attacks the much larger forward-branch bubble source\\nwith minimal area (64 flops) and no changes to pipeline bundles.\\n\",\n        \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 32-entry direct-mapped Branch History Table with 2-bit saturating\\ncounters to the IF stage. The table is indexed by PC[6:2] and initialized to\\nstrongly-taken (2'b11) so backward loops are correct immediately without any\\ntraining cost. For every conditional branch, the BHT entry MSB drives\\npredict_taken; unconditional JAL continues to be always predicted taken. In\\nEX stage, each resolved branch writes its actual outcome back to the entry\\nindexed by the branch PC using a standard saturating update rule. This adds\\nonly 64 flops and a few LUTs of combinational logic, does not widen any\\npipeline register, and the BHT read is off the critical instruction-fetch path\\nbecause the PC is known at the start of the cycle while the opcode decode\\n(which selects the BHT result) happens later in parallel.\\n\",\n            \"fitness_delta_pct\": 3,\n        \"fitness_delta_pct\": 3,\n    \"outcome\": \"improvement\",\n    \"fitness\": 347.76,\n    \"delta_pct\": 7.31,\n    \"fmax_mhz\": 146.18,\n    \"cycles\": 4203461,\n    \"lut4\": 10254,\n    \"ff\": 1940,\n    \"error\": null,\n    \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r4s2 (improvement, +7.31%): After a static backward-taken baseline captures the easy loop gains, a minimal 32-entry 2-bit BHT (64 flops) still recovers +7.3% fitness by predicting forward conditional branches; forward-branch direction is the largest remaining dynamic bubble source in CoreMark.\"\n","exit":0,"description":"Extract 32-entry BHT outcome","truncated":false},"title":"Extract 32-entry BHT outcome","time":{"start":1778739683560,"end":1778739683562}},"id":"prt_e25259bf3001Ut0QnTntzdNZkO","sessionID":"ses_1dadf93b3ffeMfaoMLwX4gHiIS","messageID":"msg_e252555c0001SGexqWeybYey8E"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778739684978,"sessionID":"ses_1dadf93b3ffeMfaoMLwX4gHiIS","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"functions.bash:6","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"sed -n '16p' /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | python3 -m json.tool | grep -E 'outcome|fitness|delta_pct|fmax_mhz|lut4|ff|cycles|error'","description":"Extract 128-entry BHT outcome"},"output":"    \"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\",\n        \"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\",\n            \"fitness_delta_pct\": 3,\n        \"fitness_delta_pct\": 3,\n    \"outcome\": \"regression\",\n    \"fitness\": 337.3,\n    \"delta_pct\": -3.01,\n    \"fmax_mhz\": 141.74,\n    \"cycles\": 4202246,\n    \"lut4\": 11315,\n    \"ff\": 2133,\n    \"error\": null,\n    \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r5s2 (regression, -3.01%): A 128-entry BHT regressed CoreMark fitness because the 32-entry table already saturates the benchmark's forward-branch locality, and the larger IF-stage read mux degraded Fmax more than reduced aliasing improved IPC.\"\n","metadata":{"output":"    \"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\",\n        \"motivation\": \"The existing 32-entry 2-bit BHT recovered +7.3% fitness by learning forward\\nbranch directions, but with only 32 entries branches whose lower PC bits\\ncollide alias destructively. In the 6 KB CoreMark working set this is not\\nuncommon, leaving a noticeable fraction of forward-branch bubbles unresolved.\\nExpanding the table to 128 entries (index PC[8:2]) keeps the proven\\nsaturating-counter structure intact while cutting aliasing, at a cost of\\nonly 192 additional flops and minimal LUT overhead.\\n\",\n            \"fitness_delta_pct\": 3,\n        \"fitness_delta_pct\": 3,\n    \"outcome\": \"regression\",\n    \"fitness\": 337.3,\n    \"delta_pct\": -3.01,\n    \"fmax_mhz\": 141.74,\n    \"cycles\": 4202246,\n    \"lut4\": 11315,\n    \"ff\": 2133,\n    \"error\": null,\n    \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r5s2 (regression, -3.01%): A 128-entry BHT regressed CoreMark fitness because the 32-entry table already saturates the benchmark's forward-branch locality, and the larger IF-stage read mux degraded Fmax more than reduced aliasing improved IPC.\"\n","exit":0,"description":"Extract 128-entry BHT outcome","truncated":false},"title":"Extract 128-entry BHT outcome","time":{"start":1778739684976,"end":1778739684977}},"id":"prt_e2525a12d0017nlKbFifboRy0e","sessionID":"ses_1dadf93b3ffeMfaoMLwX4gHiIS","messageID":"msg_e252555c0001SGexqWeybYey8E"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778739686318,"sessionID":"ses_1dadf93b3ffeMfaoMLwX4gHiIS","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"functions.bash:7","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"sed -n '19p' /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | python3 -m json.tool | grep -E 'outcome|fitness|delta_pct|fmax_mhz|lut4|ff|cycles|error'","description":"Extract Gshare outcome"},"output":"    \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\",\n        \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\",\n        \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the proven 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter table, but index it\\nwith pc[6:2] ^ ghr[4:0] instead of pc[6:2] alone. A 5-bit GHR register\\nshifts in actual branch outcomes from EX-stage resolution, so the BHT\\nentry used for prediction is a function of both the branch address and\\nthe recent global control-flow path. To ensure the EX-stage counter\\nupdate writes the same entry that IF read, the GHR value present at\\nfetch time is snapshotted and threaded through the IF/ID and ID/EX\\npipeline bundles. The update rule (strongly-taken init, saturating\\nincrement/decrement) and the static backward-taken / JAL-always-taken\\nbase policy remain unchanged. This costs only 5 flops for the GHR plus\\n5 bits of pipeline state, with negligible combinational delay (a 5-bit\\nXOR on an already-existing mux path).\\n\",\n            \"fitness_delta_pct\": 2,\n        \"fitness_delta_pct\": 2,\n    \"outcome\": \"regression\",\n    \"fitness\": 324.21,\n    \"delta_pct\": -6.77,\n    \"fmax_mhz\": 136.99,\n    \"cycles\": 4225388,\n    \"lut4\": 10358,\n    \"ff\": 1938,\n    \"error\": null,\n","metadata":{"output":"    \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\",\n        \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\",\n        \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the proven 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter table, but index it\\nwith pc[6:2] ^ ghr[4:0] instead of pc[6:2] alone. A 5-bit GHR register\\nshifts in actual branch outcomes from EX-stage resolution, so the BHT\\nentry used for prediction is a function of both the branch address and\\nthe recent global control-flow path. To ensure the EX-stage counter\\nupdate writes the same entry that IF read, the GHR value present at\\nfetch time is snapshotted and threaded through the IF/ID and ID/EX\\npipeline bundles. The update rule (strongly-taken init, saturating\\nincrement/decrement) and the static backward-taken / JAL-always-taken\\nbase policy remain unchanged. This costs only 5 flops for the GHR plus\\n5 bits of pipeline state, with negligible combinational delay (a 5-bit\\nXOR on an already-existing mux path).\\n\",\n            \"fitness_delta_pct\": 2,\n        \"fitness_delta_pct\": 2,\n    \"outcome\": \"regression\",\n    \"fitness\": 324.21,\n    \"delta_pct\": -6.77,\n    \"fmax_mhz\": 136.99,\n    \"cycles\": 4225388,\n    \"lut4\": 10358,\n    \"ff\": 1938,\n    \"error\": null,\n","exit":0,"description":"Extract Gshare outcome","truncated":false},"title":"Extract Gshare outcome","time":{"start":1778739686316,"end":1778739686318}},"id":"prt_e2525a681001wu6vqtkuy7esti","sessionID":"ses_1dadf93b3ffeMfaoMLwX4gHiIS","messageID":"msg_e252555c0001SGexqWeybYey8E"}}
