{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778741370476,"sessionID":"ses_1dac84df8ffeqy1fd7OqLOZiN1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"functions.bash:4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -A 30 '\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r6s2\"' cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","description":"Grep GHR attempt details"},"output":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Add 5-bit GHR gshare indexing to existing 32-entry BHT\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 32-entry bimodal BHT already recovers +7.3% fitness, but destructive\\naliasing among branches that share PC[6:2] limits further gains. A prior\\nattempt to fix aliasing by growing the table to 128 entries regressed -3%\\nbecause the larger read mux hurt Fmax. Gshare attacks the same aliasing\\nproblem without enlarging the table: XORing a 5-bit Global History\\nRegister (GHR) into the index scatters colliding branches while keeping\\nthe 32:1 mux (and thus Fmax) essentially unchanged. Correlated branches\\nin CoreMark (e.g. state-machine checks, nested loop conditionals) also\\nbenefit from history-aware prediction that a plain bimodal table cannot\\nlearn.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the proven 32-entry 2-bit saturating-counter table, but index it\\nwith pc[6:2] ^ ghr[4:0] instead of pc[6:2] alone. A 5-bit GHR register\\nshifts in actual branch outcomes from EX-stage resolution, so the BHT\\nentry used for prediction is a function of both the branch address and\\nthe recent global control-flow path. To ensure the EX-stage counter\\nupdate writes the same entry that IF read, the GHR value present at\\nfetch time is snapshotted and threaded through the IF/ID and ID/EX\\npipeline bundles. The update rule (strongly-taken init, saturating\\nincrement/decrement) and the static backward-taken / JAL-always-taken\\nbase policy remain unchanged. This costs only 5 flops for the GHR plus\\n5 bits of pipeline state, with negligible combinational delay (a 5-bit\\nXOR on an already-existing mux path).\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0.\\nUpdate it on every EX-stage branch resolution by shifting in\\nbht_update_taken (ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_update_taken}).\\nReplace the BHT read index pc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr.\\nDrive the current ghr value into the combinational if_id_t output.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr into the ID/EX register so the snapshot reaches EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr so the counter update\\nwrites the exact entry that was read during fetch.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr field to if_id_t and id_ex_t pipeline bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a 5-bit ghr register initialised to 0.\\nUpdate it on every EX-stage branch resolution by shifting in\\nbht_update_taken (ghr <= {ghr[3:0], bht_update_taken}).\\nReplace the BHT read index pc[6:2] with pc[6:2] ^ ghr.\\nDrive the current ghr value into the combinational if_id_t output.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Capture in.ghr into the ID/EX register so the snapshot reaches EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute BHT update index as in.pc[6:2] ^ in.ghr so the counter update\\nwrites the exact entry that was read during fetch.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 324.21, \"delta_pct\": -6.77, \"vs_baseline\": 14.63, \"fmax_mhz\": 136.99, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4225388, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 10358, \"ff\": 1938, \"seeds\": [137.48, 135.85, 136.99], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-14T04:39:37.400024Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 6, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-14 hyp-20260514-003-r6s2 (regression, -6.77%): Non-speculative GHR update at EX-stage resolution leaves history stale for tightly packed branches, causing the 5-bit XOR to increase destructive aliasing in the 32-entry BHT and regress CoreMark IPC.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260514-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Precompute forwarding selects in ID stage to shorten EX critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The EX-stage critical path currently includes the forward_unit's 5-bit\\naddress comparison, priority encoder, and operand forwarding mux before the\\nALU.  On a LUT-based FPGA these extra logic levels consume precious\\nnanoseconds.  By shifting the forwarding decision into the ID stage\\u2014where\\nthe same comparison is performed against the instructions currently in EX\\nand MEM\\u2014we register the 2-bit select signals into the ID/EX pipeline\\nregister.  This removes the comparison and control generation from the\\nEX-stage datapath without changing pipeline behaviour or IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX-stage critical path currently includes the forward_unit's 5-bit\\naddress comparison, priority encoder, and operand forwarding mux before the\\nALU.  On a LUT-based FPGA these extra logic levels consume precious\\nnanoseconds.  By shifting the forwarding decision into the ID stage\\u2014where\\nthe same comparison is performed against the instructions currently in EX\\nand MEM\\u2014we register the 2-bit select signals into the ID/EX pipeline\\nregister.  This removes the comparison and control generation from the\\nEX-stage datapath without changing pipeline behaviour or IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add fwd_rs1_sel and fwd_rs2_sel (2 bits each) to the id_ex_t bundle.\\nIn id_stage, compute the forwarding selects combinationally by comparing\\nthe current IF/ID instruction's rs1_addr/rs2_addr against the rd and\\nreg_write flags of the instruction currently in EX (the ID/EX register)\\nand the instruction currently in MEM (ex_mem_w), preserving the same\\nEX/MEM-over-MEM/WB priority and x0 guard that forward_unit uses today.\\nRegister these selects into the ID/EX payload.  In ex_stage, remove the\\nforward_unit input ports and use the precomputed in.fwd_rs1_sel /\\nin.fwd_rs2_sel directly in the operand forwarding muxes.  In core.sv,\\nwire ex_mem_w.rd and ex_mem_w.ctrl.reg_write into id_stage for the\\nprecomputation, remove the forward_unit instantiation, and connect the\\nprecomputed selects straight through to ex_stage.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_rs1_sel [1:0] and fwd_rs2_sel [1:0] fields to the id_ex_t struct.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add inputs ex_mem_rd [4:0] and ex_mem_reg_write. Compute next_fwd_rs1/next_fwd_rs2 combinationally by comparing in.instr[19:15] and in.instr[24:20] against reg_q.rd and ex_mem_rd with the same write-enable / x0 guards used by forward_unit. Register the resulting 2-bit values into the ID/EX payload.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the fwd_rs1_sel and fwd_rs2_sel input ports. Use in.fwd_rs1_sel and in.fwd_rs2_sel directly in the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes instead of the former forward_unit-driven selects.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire ex_mem_w.rd and ex_mem_w.ctrl.reg_write into the id_stage instance for precomputation.  Remove the forward_unit instantiation and its wires.  Connect id_ex_w.fwd_rs1_sel and id_ex_w.fwd_rs2_sel directly to ex_stage.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add fwd_rs1_sel [1:0] and fwd_rs2_sel [1:0] fields to the id_ex_t struct.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add inputs ex_mem_rd [4:0] and ex_mem_reg_write. Compute next_fwd_rs1/next_fwd_rs2 combinationally by comparing in.instr[19:15] and in.instr[24:20] against reg_q.rd and ex_mem_rd with the same write-enable / x0 guards used by forward_unit. Register the resulting 2-bit values into the ID/EX payload.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the fwd_rs1_sel and fwd_rs2_sel input ports. Use in.fwd_rs1_sel and in.fwd_rs2_sel directly in the rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes instead of the former forward_unit-driven selects.\\n\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire ex_mem_w.rd and ex_mem_w.ctrl.reg_write into the id_stage instance for precomputation.  Remove the forward_unit instantiation and its wires.  Connect id_ex_w.fwd_rs1_sel and id_ex_w.fwd_rs2_sel directly to ex_stage.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"formal_failed: reg_ch0\\n: pass\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_sw_ch0] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_sw_ch0] summary: Elapsed process time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\nSBY  2:58:03 [insn_sw_ch0] summary: engine_0 (smtbmc bitwuzla) returned pass\\nSBY  2:58:03 [