{"type":"text","timestamp":1778741500223,"sessionID":"ses_1dac84df8ffeqy1fd7OqLOZiN1","part":{"id":"prt_e254144f5001XR0O9GTAVSD3dI","messageID":"msg_e25413130001p8cI3drGorKUG5","sessionID":"ses_1dac84df8ffeqy1fd7OqLOZiN1","type":"text","text":"Wrote the hypothesis file to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260514-003-r9s2.yaml`.\n\n**Chosen angle:** *Speculative gshare with mispredict recovery.*\n\nThe core already has a 32-entry 2-bit BHT (+7.3% fitness) and a static backward-taken/JAL predictor. Prior attempts at a Return Address Stack, JALR ID-stage resolution, and a larger BHT all failed or showed no gain. A prior gshare attempt using **non-speculative** GHR update in EX regressed -6.7% because history was stale for tightly packed branches. This hypothesis fixes that exact failure mode by:\n\n- Adding a 5-bit GHR in IF and XORing it into the existing BHT index.\n- Updating the GHR **speculatively** in IF when a conditional branch is fetched.\n- Snapshotting the GHR into the pipeline bundles so EX can restore it on a mispredict.\n- Keeping the table at 32 entries to avoid the Fmax degradation seen with the 128-entry BHT.\n\nThis targets branch correlation and aliasing without enlarging the array, which is the most promising untried predictor angle left for this core.","time":{"start":1778741495029,"end":1778741500220}}}
